window.PROPAGATION_NPSOT_DATA = [{"Plant_ID": "Toxicodendron radicans", "Scientific Name": "Toxicodendron radicans", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Poison Ivy", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Wear protective gear: gloves, long sleeves, and eye protection to avoid allergic reaction. Refrigerate seeds in moist sand for a few weeks. Sow seeds just beneath the soil surface. Keep it consistently moist and at a warm temperature, around 70°F. Be patient, germination can be unpredictable. — Collection: Collect seeds when they're ripe, typically in late summer to fall. Place them in a sealed container to minimize contact. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Wear protective gear: gloves, long sleeves, and eye protection to avoid allergic reaction. Dip the cut end into rooting hormone. Plant the stem in moist, well-draining soil, ensuring it's stable but not drowning. Give it a few weeks, without poking around. Keep the soil consistently moist. Provide dappled shade or indirect sunlight, much like the plant's natural habitats along riverbanks or woodland edges. Temperature-wise, keep it cool, not cold—somewhere between 60-75°F (15-24°C) during the day and a touch cooler at night. Apply a steady watering schedule—enough to keep the soil moist but not soggy. Overwatering is the equivalent of overfeeding; it's well-intentioned but can lead to a mushy mess. — Collection: Cut stems about 4-6 inches long, with a few leaf nodes, the best spots for root growth. Snip stems at a 45-degree angle, just below a node to maximize rooting potential and moisture absorption.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/102033/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://greg.app/propagate-poison-ivy/#:~:text=When%20it%20comes%20to%20propagation,genetic%20surprise%20seeds%20may%20offer."}, {"Plant_ID": "Acacia angustissima", "Scientific Name": "Acacia angustissima", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Prairie Acacia", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Semi-harwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow outside in the fall. — Collection: Collect in late summer to early fall when seeds are firm, filled out, and dark brown. Allow pods to dry on the plant and break open to collect seeds. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: The primary hurdle is the hard seed coat, which prevents water uptake and germination. Scarification, such as nicking the seed coat with a file or sandpaper, or soaking seeds in hot water (near boiling) for a short period (e.g., 30 seconds) can improve germination rates. After scarification, soaking the seeds in water for 24-48 hours before sowing can further aid germination. Sowing should be done in a well-draining seed starting mix, keeping the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged. Warm temperatures (20-25°C) are beneficial. || Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Propagation through cuttings is also possible with Acaciella angustissima, but success depends on several factors. Cuttings can be prone to fungal diseases and rot if not properly treated. Rooting can be slow and inconsistent. Use a rooting hormone to increase the chances of success. Plant the cuttings in a well-draining, sterile potting mix and maintain high humidity (e.g., using a propagator or covering with a plastic bag). Ensure adequate light but avoid direct sunlight. — Collection: Semi-hardwood cuttings, taken in late spring or early summer, are generally recommended.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/acaciella-angustissima/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ACAN11 2) https://davesgarden.com/guides/pf/go/73443, 3) Wasowski, Sally and Andy, 1991, Native Texas Plants: Landscaping Region by Region. | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-acaciella-angustissima-2/#google_vignette | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-acaciella-angustissima-2/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Acer grandidentatum", "Scientific Name": "Acer grandidentatum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Bigtooth Maple", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Seeds are typically sown as soon as they are collected. Seeds are stratified naturally by planted them in the fall in a thin layer of sand on mulched field beds. Seeds are sown in late September by hand at a depth of 0.25 inches. Seeds are lightly covered and irrigated when soils appear to be drying out on warm days. Desired field density is 18 trees per square foot. Length of Establishment Phase: 1 month after emergence in the spring. — Collection: Seeds are collected during fall months. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: This species is usually very hard to propagate by cuttings, but by placing dark bags over the stems, the tree is forced to grow in darkness — a process called etiolation. Cuttings taken from this etiolated growth root much easier than cuttings taken from stems that grew in full sunlight. The bags will be removed after the tree begins growing in late April or May. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Bigtooth maple exhibits deep physiological dormancy which means that the seed requires a cold stratification treatment of 8 to 16 weeks before it will germinate. Cold stratification is accomplished by storing seed in a moist, aerated medium such as vermiculite or peat moss at temperatures of 34-38° F. Seed should be presoaked for 24 hours before stratification. Maple seed germinates at variable times depending on the seed, temperatures, and duration of chilling. Seeds have a tendency to germinate during stratification, so one way to handle the variation in stratification and germination time is to periodically inspect the seeds and plant only those which have started to germinate. The remaining seeds can be refrigerated and planted later. Stratified seed can be sown in containers or in the field . — Collection: Seed should be selected from healthy trees and can be collected by simply striping them off the branches. Seed can be stored for 1 to 2 years if well dried and held at 34-38° F and 15% moisture in a sealed container (Young et al., 1992).", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/acer-grandidentatum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=aceraceae-acer-2682 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ACGR3 3) https://www.prairiemoon.com/seeds/#/?resultsPerPage=24 | https://www.botanicgardens.org/blog/dark-side-propagating-maples#:~:text=The%20bigtooth%20maple%20Acer%20grandidentatum%20is%20a,soils%20much%20better%20than%20other%20maple%20species.&text=This%20species%20is%20usually%20very%20hard%20to,in%20darkness%20%E2%80%94%20a%20process%20called%20etiolation. | https://extension.usu.edu/cwel/research/propagating-bigtooth-maple"}, {"Plant_ID": "Acer negundo", "Scientific Name": "Acer negundo", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Box Elder", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Seed is imbibed in water overnight. Seeds are dusted with fungicide prior to planting outdoors in the fall where they undergo natural stratification. — Collection: Seed collected in the fall.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/acer-negundo/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=aceraceae-acer-1120"}, {"Plant_ID": "Achillea millefolium", "Scientific Name": "Achillea millefolium", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Common Yarrow", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Root | Bud | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Seed requires one month of cold stratification and direct sunlight for germination. Germination occurs within one or two weeks. — Collection: Collect entire inflorescence and dry before cleaning. Light tan at maturity, seeds mature in late summer and early fall. || Root — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Root cuttings can be propagated by placing them into warm soil in direct sunlight in the spring or fall. || Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: Using a sharp spade, separate the clump into sections, ensuring each division has both roots and shoots. Replant the divisions in well-prepared soil, spacing them appropriately to allow for future growth. — Collection: Divide established yarrow clumps in the early spring or fall when the plant is dormant. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Strip off the lower leaves and make a small cut at the base of the stem. Insert the cuttings into a pot filled with moist rooting mix, ensuring that the nodes are buried. Keep the cuttings in a bright, indirect location and maintain consistent moisture. Use a plastic dome or cover to maintain humidity, if needed. Once the cuttings develop roots (usually within a few weeks), transplant them to your garden bed. — Collection: Yarrow responds well to this during the summer months. Select healthy, non-flowering stems. Cut 4-6 inches below a leaf node", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/achillea-millefolium/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/plantmaterials/mtpmcpg13974.pdf 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ACMI2 | https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/plantmaterials/mtpmcpg13974.pdf | https://nwdistrict.ifas.ufl.edu/hort/2024/02/29/the-art-of-propagating-yarrow-a-guide-to-successful-growth/ | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-achillea-millefolium/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Acmella repens", "Scientific Name": "Acmella repens", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Creeping Spotflower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed | Bud", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Place stem in a moist potting mix to encourage rooting. Roots at the nodes. — Collection: Select healthy stems that are 4 to 6 inches long. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: sow them at a depth of about 1/4 inch. Expect germination within 7 to 14 days, depending on conditions. || Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: Divide plant in early spring or fall by carefully separating root clumps and replanting them in suitable locations.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/acmella-oppositifolia-var-repens/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.aquasabi.com/Acmella-repens-in-Vitro 2) https://greg.app/creeping-spotflower-overview/#:~:text=For%20outdoor%20planting%2C%20focus%20on,in%20the%20warmth%20of%20summer. | https://greg.app/creeping-spotflower-overview/#:~:text=For%20outdoor%20planting%2C%20focus%20on,in%20the%20warmth%20of%20summer."}, {"Plant_ID": "Adiantum capillus-veneris", "Scientific Name": "Adiantum capillus-veneris", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Common Maidenhair Fern", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Root | Spores", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Root — Treatment: Division — Method: Dividing its underground rhizomes, first, trim off to almost ground level most of the older rachis and remove withered fronds. Then dig it up and divide by cutting through with a garden spade or sharp long-edged knife and finally replant the divisions into individual pots, being careful not to plant their crown below soil level, as it is from this point that new fronds will emerge.. || Spores — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow on the surface of a humus-rich sterilized soil. Keep the growing medium always moist by covering with a plastic bag over the pot. Germination should take place within 6 weeks at a temperature of 20-21oC (68-70oF), then transplant the tiny clumps of plantlets where desired. — Collection: Collect the ripe spores from under spore-bearing pinnules (leaflets).", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/adiantum-capillus-veneris/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.plantsrescue.com/posts/adiantum-capillus-veneris 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ADCA | https://www.plantsrescue.com/posts/adiantum-capillus-veneris"}, {"Plant_ID": "Aesculus glabra", "Scientific Name": "Aesculus glabra", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Buckeye", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Sow seeds in the fall. Moist-stratify for 120 days at 41 degrees. — Collection: Seeds dry and shrivel quickly.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/aesculus-glabra/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=AEGL"}, {"Plant_ID": "Aesculus pavia var. flavescens", "Scientific Name": "Aesculus pavia var. flavescens", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Yellow Buckeye", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Root", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seed fresh and untreated in well-drained soil. — Collection: Collect when seeds firm and golden brown || Root — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dormant root cuttings of 3 inches sometimes successfully propagated.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/aesculus-pavia-var-flavescens/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=aepaf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Aesculus pavia var. pavia", "Scientific Name": "Aesculus pavia var. pavia", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Red Buckeye", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Softwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct sow in soil immediately after collection — Collection: As soon as the leathery capsule turns brown and begins to peel back from the firm, golden-brown seeds. Do not allow the seeds to dry out. || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Use sterilized tools to make clean cuts, which helps prevent infection and supports healthy root development. Rooting hormone isn't mandatory, but it gives your cuttings faster root growth. Plant the cuttings in a well-draining medium to avoid the dreaded root rot. Keep the environment humid and the cuttings hydrated to minimize stress and maximize success. For softwood cuttings, bright, indirect light . — Collection: Softwood cuttings should be taken from healthy, disease-free stems during the active growing season, typically from May to July. Ensure the stems have a green hue, indicating they're not too mature.Use sterilized tools to make clean cuts, which helps prevent infection and supports healthy root development.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/aesculus-pavia-var-pavia/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=AEPAP | https://greg.app/propagate-red-buckeye/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Agalinis heterophylla", "Scientific Name": "Agalinis heterophylla", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Prairie False Foxglove", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Place seeds superficially, as they require sufficient light to sprout successfully. Once seedlings establish, transplant them carefully to avoid root disturbance. Ensure to use well-draining soil, providing adequate warmth and moisture to encourage germination.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/agalinis-heterophylla/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Agalinis_heterophylla.html#:~:text=More%20Info%20on%20Prairie%20false,Keep%20authenticity%20in%20nature's%20blueprint."}, {"Plant_ID": "Agave americana", "Scientific Name": "Agave americana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Century Plant", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Offshoots | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Offshoots — Treatment: Division — Method: Replant pups in well draining soil. You’ll need a pair of sharp, clean gardening shears or a knife, gloves (those spines are no joke!), and small pots filled with a well-draining potting mix specifically formulated for succulents and cacti. Choose pups that are at least a few inches in diameter. They should have a healthy root system of their own. Carefully separate them from the mother plant by cutting the connecting tissue as close to the pup as possible. Allow the pups to callous over for a day or two in a dry, shaded area. This helps prevent rot once they are potted. Plant the pups in your prepared pots, ensuring the base sits level with the soil surface. Don’t bury them too deep. Water sparingly until you see new growth. Overwatering is the enemy! Place the pots in a bright location, but avoid direct sunlight until they become established. — Collection: Gently remove small offshoots (pups) in spring or summer. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Lightly press the seeds onto the surface of a well-draining seed starting mix. Don’t bury them. Mist the soil surface and cover the tray with a plastic dome or cling wrap to retain moisture. Place the tray in a bright location, out of direct sunlight, with temperatures around 70-75°F (21-24°C). Germination can be erratic and take anywhere from a few weeks to several months.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/agave-americana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.gardenia.net/plant/agave-americana-century-plant#:~:text=Propagation:%20Agave%20americana%20can%20be,replant%20in%20well%2Ddraining%20soil. | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-agave-americana/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Ageratina altissima", "Scientific Name": "Ageratina altissima", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "White Snakeroot", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Rhizome", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Give 60-day cold treatment before spring sowing. Or the easiest approach is to surface-sow the seeds in fall to early winter, setting them outdoors in a spot protected from mice so they can get a natural chilling period and then germinate when conditions are right in spring. (The winter-sowing approach works very well with this species.) If you sow after January, provide an artificial chilling period of about 2 months. — Collection: Collect seed in the fall, when they begin to be released. || Rhizome — Treatment: Division — Method: Plant immediatelly in well-drained soils of most types, in partial shade. Provide supplemental water until established. — Collection: Divide rhizomes in the spring", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ageratina-altissima/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://openprairie.sdstate.edu/nativeplant/60/#:~:text=Seed%20Collection:Collect%20seed%20in,most%20types'%20Light:%20Partial%20shade 2) https://hayefield.com/product/ageratina-altissima-white-snakeroot/#:~:text=Germination%20Information:%20I%20recommend%20these,description%20as%20well%20before%20ordering. | https://openprairie.sdstate.edu/nativeplant/60/#:~:text=Seed%20Collection:Collect%20seed%20in,most%20types'%20Light:%20Partial%20shade"}, {"Plant_ID": "Ageratina havanensis", "Scientific Name": "Ageratina havanensis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "White Mistflower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Strip off the leaves from the bottom inch or two of the stem to expose the nodes. You can use a mixture of potting soil, perlite, and vermiculite, or simply a seed starting mix. Fill a small pot or tray with the rooting medium and moisten it. Insert your cuttings. Gently make a hole in the rooting medium with a pencil or your finger and insert the bottom end of the cutting. Mist the cuttings and the surrounding air with water. To create a humid environment, you can cover the pot with a plastic wrap or a clear plastic dome. Keep the cuttings in a warm, bright location, but avoid direct sunlight. Patience is key, it can take 2-4 weeks for roots to develop. Check the soil moisture regularly and water when it feels dry. — Collection: Look for strong, green stems that are about 4-6 inches long. Make a clean cut: Use sharp shears or a knife to make a clean, angled cut just below a node (the point where leaves grow). || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Use a sharp knife or garden trowel to divide the plant into several smaller sections, each with its own roots and shoots. Plant the divided sections in individual pots or in the garden, making sure to water them well. — Collection: Carefully remove the plant from its pot, making sure not to disturb the roots too much.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ageratina-havanensis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-ageratina-havanensis/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Allium canadense", "Scientific Name": "Allium canadense", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Meadow Garlic", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump | Seed | Bulb", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: If there are multiple plants growing, dig up the plant and gently tug the plants apart, being careful not to disturb too many of the roots. They may be connected by large root segments which you may need to break to free the plantlet. Pot up the new plant in well-draining soil. Repot the parent plant back into its original location. Some alliums (Allium roseum, A. sphaerocephalon and A. vineale) produce aerial bulbils (small young bulbs produced instead of flowers) in the flower head. These bulbils can be carefully removed and separated. The bulbils can be planted in moist free-draining Can refer to either home-made garden compost or seed/potting compost: • Garden compost is a soil improver made from decomposed plant waste, usually in a compost bin or heap. It is added to soil to improve its fertility, structure and water-holding capacity. Seed or potting composts are used for growing seedlings or plants in containers - a wide range of commercially produced peat-free composts are available, made from a mix of various ingredients, such as loam, composted bark, coir and sand, although you can mix your own. compost about 2.5cm (1in) apart and covered with 1cm (3/8in) layer of compost. It will take several years for them to reach flowering size. — Collection: Check to see if there is more than one plant. In some cases they may still be beneath the soil surface. If you feel confident, you may remove the soil to check for baby plantlets below! || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: It is best to sow ripe ripe seeds as soon as possible. Sow into trays of gritty compost and and cover them with 5mm of grit. Place the containers outside in a shady spot. Alternatively store seeds in a fridge and sow in spring at about 13°C (55°F). Most should germinate within 12 weeks. It will take several years to reach the flowering size. — Collection: Seeds are hard, usually yellow, brown or black, and contained in a seedpod that can be buff colored, white or brown and dry. Ripe seeds usually eject the seedpod easily and naturally. || Bulb — Treatment: Division — Method: Starting plants from bulblets is a convenient method of propagation. Larger bulblets germinate better than smaller ones and retain their viability longer (Krochmal, 1960). Bulblets held in cold storage at 40 degrees F broke dormancy while those stored at room temperature had lower germination percentages. Germination temperature was 69 degrees F. Bulblets held for 3 years at room temperature could not be germinated (Andersen 1968). Allium canadense is easily started from seed in the greenhouse during late winter or early spring. Bulbs can be divided in fall.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/allium-canadense/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://greg.app/plant-care/allium-canadense 2) https://www.rhs.org.uk/plants/allium/growing-guide | https://www.rhs.org.uk/plants/allium/growing-guide | https://warcapps.usgs.gov/PlantID/Species/Details/2043#:~:text=Starting%20plants%20from%20bulblets%20is,can%20be%20divided%20in%20fall."}, {"Plant_ID": "Allowissadula holosericea", "Scientific Name": "Allowissadula holosericea", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Chisos Mountain False Indian Mallow", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Propagate by sowing seeds after bloom decline in well-draining soil. Ensure a warm environment for germination and maintain consistently moist soil. Young plants thrive in partial shade until ready for transplant.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/allowissadula-holosericea/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Allowissadula_holosericea.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Aloysia gratissima", "Scientific Name": "Aloysia gratissima", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Beebrush", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow in pots or seed flats filled with well-drained soil mix, cover lightly, and keep the medium just moist until germination. Seedlings can be pricked out into individual pots and grown on until large enough to survive outdoors. — Collection: Collect seeds in late summer when beginning to dry. Fruit may be slightly crushed and seeds removed by hand. Air-dry before storing in a cool, dry place. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cuttings in rooting hormone. Plant the prepared cutting in a pot filled with a well-draining soil mix, such as a combination of peat moss and perlite. Insert the cutting deep enough so it can stand upright, with at least one or two nodes buried in the soil. Place the pot in a warm, bright location but out of direct sunlight. Cover the pot with a plastic bag or place it under a humidity dome to maintain high humidity and prevent the cutting from drying out. Water sparingly, just enough to keep the soil slightly moist. — Collection: Choose a healthy, non-flowering stem from a mature whitebrush plant. The cutting should be 4-6 inches long and have several sets of leaves. Use a sharp, sterilized knife or pruning shears to make a clean cut just below a leaf node. Remove the lower leaves, leaving two to three sets at the top.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/aloysia-gratissima/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ALGR2 2) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/aloysia-gratissima-whitebrush-grow-care-guide 3) https://earthone.io/plant/aloysia%20gratissima?srsltid=AfmBOopLUHvZyAjE2xc8nfPUmeGopWid4URc0jye6m7KZfFTVxgr8Ztb | 1) https://earthone.io/plant/aloysia%20gratissima?srsltid=AfmBOopLUHvZyAjE2xc8nfPUmeGopWid4URc0jye6m7KZfFTVxgr8Ztb 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Aloysia_gratissima.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Aloysia wrightii", "Scientific Name": "Aloysia wrightii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Wright's Beebrush", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Semi-harwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: The cut ends may be treated with a rooting hormone before being placed in a well-draining soil mix, kept moist but not waterlogged to foster root development. Consistent monitoring and minimal transplanting stress are key to establishing new growth. — Collection: cuttings should be obtained from healthy parent plants, ensuring several nodes are present.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/aloysia-wrightii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Aloysia_wrightii.html#:~:text=More%20Info%20on%20Wright's%20beebrush,Suitable%20temperature%20for%20Wright's%20beebrush"}, {"Plant_ID": "Amblyolepis setigera", "Scientific Name": "Amblyolepis setigera", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Huisache Daisy", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds directly in the ground after the first frost but before the ground freezes. Natural weathering improves germination; seeds lie dormant until spring. Scatter seeds on prepared soil. Press lightly into soil surface. Do not bury deeply — seeds need light for best germination. Optional: Cover lightly with 1/16 inch of soil or fine sand. Let natural rainfall and winter conditions trigger germination in spring. — Collection: Collect seed late in the spring.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/amblyolepis-setigera/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=AMSE 2) https://nativefloraseeds.org/products/huisache-daisy#:~:text=%F0%9F%8C%BE%20Direct%20Sowing%20Outdoors%20%E2%80%93%20Fall%20or%20Spring&text=When:%20After%20the%20first%20frost,conditions%20trigger%20germination%20in%20spring.&text=When:%20After%20danger%20of%20frost,occurs%20in%207%E2%80%9314%20days."}, {"Plant_ID": "Amorpha fruticosa", "Scientific Name": "Amorpha fruticosa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "False Indigo Bush", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Mechanically nick the seed, soak in hot water for 10 minutes, or scarify in concentrated sulfuric acid five to eight minutes. — Collection: Collect in late summer or early fall when the pod turns yellowish brown and begins to dry. Air dry and store in sealed, refrigerated containers for three to five years.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/amorpha-fruticosa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=AMFR"}, {"Plant_ID": "Andropogon ternarius", "Scientific Name": "Andropogon ternarius", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Splitbeard Bluestem", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment, Stratification — Method: Cold stratification (a few weeks of refrigeration) is optional since Splitbeard Bluestem seeds often germinate well without it. In spring, after the last frost, sow your seeds directly into your prepared garden bed. Scatter seeds evenly over the soil surface and lightly rake them in, ensuring good seed-to-soil contact. Keep the soil consistently moist. Germination typically takes 2-4 weeks. — Collection: Snip off the seed heads in the fall when the seed heads are dry and fluffy and store them in a paper bag in a cool, dry place until you’re ready to sow. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Depending on the size of the plant, you can either divide it into smaller sections with a sharp knife or simply pull apart smaller sections with your hands. Make sure each division has at least one shoot and a portion of the root system. Trim any excessively long or damaged roots to encourage healthier growth. Place the divisions in their new locations at the same depth they were growing previously and water in thoroughly. Maintain consistent moisture (but not waterlogged conditions) for the first few weeks. — Collection: In early spring or fall, use a sharp spade or garden fork to carefully lift the entire clump from the ground.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/andropogon-ternarius/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-andropogon-ternarius/ | 1 ) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-andropogon-ternarius/ 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Andropogon_ternarius.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Andropogon virginicus", "Scientific Name": "Andropogon virginicus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Broomsedge", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Bud | Seed | Root", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: With a clean shovel or knife, divide the clump into smaller sections, each containing multiple stems and a healthy root system. Plant these divided sections in their new location, ensuring that the crown (where the stems meet the roots) is just below the soil level. Once planted, water the newly divided broomsedge thoroughly to help establish strong roots. — Collection: The best time to divide broomsedge is in early spring, just as new growth emerges. This gives the newly divided clumps a head start and allows them to establish strong roots before the summer heat sets in. Carefully dig around the perimeter of the established clump. Once it’s loosened, gently lift the entire clump from the soil. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: To boost germination, you can scarify the seeds (lightly nick the seed coat) before sowing them. Sow the seeds in a seed tray filled with well-draining soil, and cover them lightly with a thin layer of soil. Keep the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged, and place the tray in a warm, sunny location. It’s also important to note that broomsedge seeds can take up to a year to germinate! Acclimation is typically accomplished through placement of seedlings outdoors in a protected location for a 1-2 week period prior to transplanting. — Collection: Collect mature seed heads from the plant and allow them to dry completely. Gently crush the seed heads to release the seeds. || Root — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Simply cut a few healthy roots from the mother plant and plant them horizontally in a well-prepared bed of moist soil. Keep the soil consistently moist until the cuttings develop a new shoot, which usually takes about 6-8 weeks. — Collection: This method is best done in late summer.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/andropogon-virginicus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-andropogon-virginicus/ | 1) https://plantiary.com/plant/andropogon-virginicus_4265.html 2) https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=poaceae-andropogon-4014#:~:text=Establishment%20Phase:,after%20placement%20in%20the%20greenhouse.&text=Active%20Growth%20Phase:,fertilizer%20bi%2Dweekly%20until%20hardening.&text=Hardening%20Phase:,week%20period%20prior%20to%20transplanting.&text=References:,%2C%20NC%2027401%2D4901%20USA.&text=Citation:,%2C%20Nurseries%2C%20and%20Genetic%20Resources. 3) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-andropogon-virginicus/#google_vignette | 1) https://plantiary.cm/plant/andropogon-virginicus_4265.html 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-andropogon-virginicus/#google_vignette"}, {"Plant_ID": "Anemone berlandieri", "Scientific Name": "Anemone berlandieri", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Tenpetal thimbleweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Tuber | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Tuber — Treatment: Division — Method: Ensure each division has at least one growing point. Plant the divisions in well-draining soil and water moderately. — Collection: Divide tubers during the dormancy period. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow fresh seeds in well-draining, organic-rich soil. Maintain consistent moisture, avoiding waterlogging. Start seeds in a protected area before transplanting young plants to a partly shaded garden spot, handling the delicate roots gently to ensure healthy growth.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/anemone-berlandieri/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://earthone.io/plant/anemone%20berlandieri | https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Anemone_berlandieri.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Anemone caroliniana", "Scientific Name": "Anemone caroliniana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Carolina Anemone", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Bud", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Choose a well-drained location with partial shade. Amend the soil with compost to enhance drainage and fertility. Sowing the seeds: Scatter seeds sparingly on the soil surface and lightly press them in. No need to bury them deep, as they need light to germinate. Patience, young gardener: Germination typically occurs in spring. Keep the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged. Thin out overcrowded seedlings to provide ample space for growth. — Collection: For best results, sow seeds in late fall or early winter, allowing them to benefit from natural stratification (a period of cold temperatures that stimulates germination). || Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully dig up the clump, ensuring you get a good root system. Using a sharp, clean knife or garden spade, divide the clump into smaller sections, each with healthy roots and shoots. Replant the divisions at the same depth they were growing previously. Water thoroughly and mulch around the base to retain moisture and suppress weeds. — Collection: Divide established clumps in early spring or fall when the plant is dormant.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/anemone-caroliniana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-anemone-caroliniana/ 2) https://greg.app/carolina-anemone-overview/#:~:text=%E2%9C%82%EF%B8%8F%20Division%20of%20Established%20Plants,older%20plants%2C%20promoting%20healthier%20blooms."}, {"Plant_ID": "Anisacanthus quadrifidus var. wrightii", "Scientific Name": "Anisacanthus quadrifidus var. wrightii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Flame Acanthus", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Softwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Seeds are best sown fresh. Seeds can be planted in flats, or outside after the danger of frost has past. Sowing indoors allows for a sturdier plant to withstand mid-summer heat. Plant seeds 1/3 to 1/2 inch deep in a well-drained soil mix. Keep soil moist but not saturated. — Collection: As soon as capsules begin to dry and turn brown but before they split open. Air dry and store in a cool, dry place for one season. || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cuttings in rooting hormone, plant them three inches apart, and give supplemental water. Flame Acanthus cuttings can root within three weeks. — Collection: Take cuttings during early summer or fall. Cut a four to six-inch section below the node, then remove leaves from the bottom half.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/anisacanthus-quadrifidus-var-wrightii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ANQUW | 1) https://coryames.com/flame-acanthus-or-hummingbird-bush-anisacanthus-quadrifidus-wrightii/#:~:text=Cuttings:%20You%20can%20propagate%20Flame,apart%2C%20and%20give%20supplemental%20water. 2) https://www.thespruce.com/hummingbird-bush-care-guide-7496091#:~:text=Remove%20lower%20leaves%2C%20keeping%20between,cutting%20to%20a%20permanent%20position."}, {"Plant_ID": "Aquilegia canadensis", "Scientific Name": "Aquilegia canadensis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Wild Red Columbine", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Cold-moist stratify for 3-4 weeks at 40 degrees or below. Sown in the spring. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct sow in the fall after collection. Seedlings will flower the following year. — Collection: Flowers go to seed approximately 2 weeks after emerging.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/aquilegia-canadensis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=AQCA"}, {"Plant_ID": "Arbutus xalapensis", "Scientific Name": "Arbutus xalapensis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Madrone", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Seeds should be sown in a well-draining soil mix and kept moist until germination. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Cuttings can be taken in late spring or early summer and rooted in a moist, well-draining medium.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/arbutus-xalapensis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ARXA80 2) https://www.fs.usda.gov/database/feis/plants/tree/arbxal/all.html | https://earthone.io/plant/arbutus%20xalapensis"}, {"Plant_ID": "Argemone albiflora", "Scientific Name": "Argemone albiflora", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "White Prickly Poppy", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow the seeds directly in the soil in early spring or fall. Ensure the seeds are lightly covered with soil and kept in a sunny location. The seed usually germinates in 3 - 4 weeks at 15°c. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Sow seeds in spring or autumn. Without smoke or fire treatment some plants will sprout, but there will be some built-in dormancy. To achieve a higher rate of germination, you can start a small smoky fire with pine needles or straw above your seeded area. After the fire burns out, spread the ashes and water them in. Some people have had success buying all-natural smoke flavoring from supermarkets, diluting it with 10 parts water and soaking the seeds in the solution before sowing. If you are starting seeds in flats, you can periodically pass smoky branches underneath. Plant in a well weeded area, and be patient for germination.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/argemone-albiflora/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://earthone.io/plant/argemone%20albiflora 2) https://seedsource.com/white-prickly-poppy/ 3) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Argemone+albiflora#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,15%C2%B0c%5B134%5D. | https://www.grandprismaticseed.com/natives/prickly-poppy#:~:text=Sow%20seeds%20in%20spring%20or,and%20be%20patient%20for%20germination."}, {"Plant_ID": "Aristida purpurea", "Scientific Name": "Aristida purpurea", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Purple Threeawn", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Can be direct sown into the soil outddoors. Best time to sow seeds is during July. It takes about 4 months to grow. Seeds grow roots fast. After 30 days, the roots are approximately 19 inches. Establishment occurs during the warm temperatures of the summer time and with the help of fall time rain. — Collection: Seeds are extremely accessible, can be collected straight from the flowering of the grass. Seeds can be collected once the grass has established flowers (dried). Seeds are hand collected into woven bags from small lots. Storage is done through cold storage at about 33-38 degrees Fahrenheit.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/aristida-purpurea/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://courses.washington.edu/esrm412/protocols/2017/ARPU9.pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Aristolochia coryi", "Scientific Name": "Aristolochia coryi", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Cory's Dutchman's-pipe", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Semi-harwood | Clump | Tuber", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Once collected, the seeds can be sown into trays filled with a loamy seed mix and covered lightly with a thin layer of soil. The trays should be kept in a warm place, with a constant temperature of at least 20°C, and kept moist until germination occurs. — Collection: Collect ripe seeds in the late summer or early autumn before they are dispersed naturally. || Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the lower leaves and apply a rooting hormone. Propagation should take place in a humid environment, either in a propagator with bottom heat (around 70-75°F) or under a humidity dome, using well-draining propagation mix. Misting regularly is crucial to maintain humidity. — Collection: Cuttings should be taken in late summer or early autumn, after the plant has finished its main flush of growth. Cuttings should be approximately 4-6 inches long. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Aristolochia coryi isn’t known for extensive root systems, making successful division challenging. Replant the divisions immediately into well-prepared, well-draining soil. Water thoroughly after planting. — Collection: Division should be undertaken in early spring or autumn during the dormant period. Carefully dig up the entire plant, ensuring minimal disturbance to the root system. Divide the root ball into sections, each with several healthy roots and stems. || Tuber — Treatment: Division — Method: Replant the pieces in a well-draining loamy soil, water lightly, and keep in a cool dry location until new growth appears. — Collection: This should be done during the plant's dormant stage in the late autumn or early winter when the leaves have died back. Dig up the tubers and separate them into smaller pieces, ensuring each piece has a healthy bud.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/aristolochia-coryi/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.botanikks.com/plants/aristolochia-coryi-im-johnston/520723/1 | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-aristolochia-coryi/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Aristolochia serpentaria", "Scientific Name": "Aristolochia serpentaria", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Virginia Dutchman's Pipe", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Root", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Seed best sown in a greenhouse as soon as it is ripe in the autumn. Pre-soak stored seed for 48 hours in hand-hot water and surface sow in a greenhouse. Germination usually takes place within 1 - 3 months at 20°c. Stored seed germinates better if it is given 3 months cold stratification at 5°c[200]. When large enough to handle, prick the seedlings out into individual pots and grow them on in the greenhouse for their first winter. Plant out in late spring or early summer after the last expected frosts. || Root — Treatment: Cutting, Division — Method: Division in autumn. Root cuttings in winter.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/aristolochia-serpentaria/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Aristolochia+Serpentaria#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,cuttings%20in%20winter%5B200%5D."}, {"Plant_ID": "Arnoglossum plantagineum", "Scientific Name": "Arnoglossum plantagineum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Indian Plantain", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Seeds germinate after a period of cold-moist stratification to break dormancy Mix seeds with equal amounts of moist (but not wet) sand, vermiculite, or sterile media. Place mixture in a sealed plastic bag and store in refrigerator at 33-38 degrees F. Stratify for 60 days. Some seeds may sprout in the bag. If so, plant them immediately. Germlination in 30-60 days after treatment. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: A less complicated method is to let nature handle the stratification by sowing seeds directly in the soil in late fall or winter. Seeds will be conditioned by weathering to make germination possible in the spring. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully separate the root clumps and replant them in suitable soil. — Collection: Division is best done in early spring or late fall.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/arnoglossum-plantagineum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.prairiemoon.com/arnoglossum-plantagineum-prairie-indian-plantain#panel-planting 2) https://earthone.io/plant/arnoglossum%20plantagineum 3) https://ferriseeds.com/products/arnoglossum-plantagineum-br-prairie-indian-plantain#:~:text=Growing%20information,days%20after%20the%20warming%20period. | 1) https://www.prairiemoon.com/arnoglossum-plantagineum-prairie-indian-plantain#panel-planting 2) https://earthone.io/plant/arnoglossum%20plantagineum 3) https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=asteraceae-arnoglossum-257 | https://earthone.io/plant/arnoglossum%20plantagineum"}, {"Plant_ID": "Artemisia ludoviciana", "Scientific Name": "Artemisia ludoviciana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "White Sage", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump | Rhizome", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Method: Seeds of white sage can be dormant. If spring seeding or seeding indoors, cold moist stratification (prechill) for 15-60 days can improve establishment. To prechill, put seed in a plastic bag or container with sand, peat, blotter paper, paper towel, cloth, or other medium that can be kept damp, and place in a cold location such as a refrigerator. Planting seed outdoors in the fall will provide natural stratification. Seed should be surface sown or at a very shallow depth (1/8 to 1/4 inch). If starting plants indoors, seed 8-10 weeks prior to transplanting outdoors. Transplant after the danger of frost has passed. Seedlings should be acclimated to weather conditions for 1-2 weeks prior to transplanting outdoors. When determining location and plant spacing for the seedlings, consider that white sage develops rhizomes (underground runners) that allow plants to spread and form colonies. — Collection: The seed is tiny, with over 4 million seeds per pound. Seed is formed in cylindrical heads and is generally ripe from late September to November in the Northern Great Plains. Ripe seeds are grayish brown, smooth, and firm to the touch. Seeds shatter soon after they mature so it is important to monitor ripeness and harvest soon after the seedheads begin to open. Seed can be collected by stripping or crushing the seedheads. Seedheads can also be clipped and stored in a closed environment, such as a paper or cloth bag, to allow the seed to shatter from the heads. To prevent mold growth, seed should be spread out or allowed to surface-dry before storing. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Remove a section of rhizome and cut into pieces. There must be at least one bud on the cut rhizome piece to produce a new plant. The pieces can then be planted outdoors or in pots. It is important to water the rhizome pieces until plant growth is detected. Whole plants can be divided by splitting the plants apart so that each division has a root or rhizome and one or more buds. Each division can then be planted outdoors or potted. Replant the divisions as soon as possible to prevent drying out. Old top growth can be cut off. — Collection: White sage rhizomes can be divided to propagate new plants. To make rhizome cuttings, dig below the soil surface of a plant to find the rhizomes and roots. || Rhizome — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Place the stem in well drained, moist soil to root. Stem cuttings can be more difficult to root than plant or rhizome divisions. — Collection: Stem cuttings can be made by cutting a 4-6 inch stem in spring or early summer. Select a stem that is healthy and free of disease. Cut below the leaf node .", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/artemisia-ludoviciana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/plantmaterials/ndpmcbr14230.pdf | 1) https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/plantmaterials/ndpmcbr14230.pdf 2) https://www.prairiemoon.com/artemisia-ludoviciana-prairie-sage#:~:text=The%20plants%20reach%20heights%20of,for%20many%20Native%20American%20tribes."}, {"Plant_ID": "Asclepias asperula", "Scientific Name": "Asclepias asperula", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Antelope Horn Milkweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Root | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Start indoors after cold stratifying the seeds in a refrigerator for 3-4 weeks. Some individuals may bloom the first year, but they often start blooming after their first winter. Also, seeds can be soaked overnight in water. Cold moist stratification involves chilling the seeds at 40 degrees for up to three months. — Collection: Seeds can be collected in June from established plants or can be ordered online. || Root — Treatment: Cutting, Division — Method: Carefully dig up the plant and separate into smaller sections. Each section should have several shoots and a portion of the root. Replant the sections in well draining soil. Keep the soil moist until the plants become well established. — Collection: Root cuttings can be done in late fall or early spring. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sowing seeds in late fall also allows this exposure to moist cold conditions. Use plastic flats or seedling trays. Fill them 3/4 with potting soil. Scatter the seeds on the soil surface 1/2 inch apart. Cover with 1/4 inch of soil mix. Water thoroughly and place them in a sunny window or under grow lights. Most seeds will germinate in 7-10 days if the flats are maintained at 75 degrees Fahrenheit. After the seeds have germinated and are 3-6 inches tall, they are ready to be transplanted to your garden. Plant the seedlings 6-24 inches apart., depending on the species. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Cut a 4-6 inch section of stem and remove the lower leaves. Dip the cut end of the stem in rooting hormone and plant in a container with moist potting soil. Ensure the cuttings have adequate moisture and light to encourage root development. The transplant to your garden. — Collection: Cuttings can be taken during in late fall or early spring..", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/asclepias-asperula/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.grandprismaticseed.com/natives/antelope-horns-milkweed#:~:text=Direct%20sow%20seeds%20in%20autumn,blooming%20after%20their%20first%20winter. 2) https://monarchbutterflygarden.net/milkweed-for-monarchs/asclepias-asperula-antelope-horns/ 3) https://txmn.org/goodwater/2017/04/19/antelope-horns-milkweed-for-monarchs/ | 1) https://txmn.org/goodwater/2017/04/19/antelope-horns-milkweed-for-monarchs/ 2) https://www.gardenia.net/guide/learn-how-to-plant-care-and-grow-milkweed | 1) https://earthone.io/plant/asclepias%20asperula?srsltid=AfmBOoo9Kbmlw30nA5YMDjK97ITIPfCuPeabxzlOUjAgGysA5m4do9pL 2) https://www.gardenia.net/guide/learn-how-to-plant-care-and-grow-milkweed"}, {"Plant_ID": "Asclepias incarnata", "Scientific Name": "Asclepias incarnata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Swamp Milkweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Root", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Plant seeds in a pot outdoors in the fall, winter or early spring. The wet, cold conditions mimic wild seed propagation in nature and the seeds will germinate in mid spring. Germination is poor at temperatures higher than 85 degrees Fahrenheit. Seedlings should not be transplanted until they have at least one set of true leaves. Allow 4 to 8 weeks inside growing time for seedlings before moving to a cold frame or transplanting outside. Plants can be moved outside once the danger of frost has passed. — Collection: Collect seeds in the fall, when the brown pods are dry and have begun to split. Crack the pods open completely allowing the seeds to dry for one to two weeks in paper bags. Several weevil larvae prey on developing seeds, so look for signs of damage including small entry holes in the pod exuding latex. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Place the seeds in a moist medium and store them in a refrigeratore at 35-38 F, for 4-12 weeks. After stratification, sow the seeds just beneath the soil sureface in seedling trays filled with draining seedling mix. Maintain ambient temperatures between 65 and 75 F, and keep the soil consistently moist. Germination typically occurs within a few weeks. — Collection: Collect seeds in the fall, when the brown pods are dry and have begun to split. Crack the pods open completely allowing the seeds to dry for one to two weeks in paper bags. Several weevil larvae prey on developing seeds, so look for signs of damage including small entry holes in the pod exuding latex. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut ends in rooting hormone to encourage root development. Insert the treated cuttings into a moist medium such as sand or potting soil. Keep the medium consistently moist until the stem develops roots. Roots typically develop within 6-10 weeks. after which the plants can be moved to their permanent location. — Collection: During the summer, choose healthy, green stems approximately 1/3 inch in diameter. Cut the stems under water to prevent air embolism. || Root — Treatment: Division — Method: While division is possible, it's important to note that Swamp Milkweed has a deep taproot. making it sensitive to disturbance. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Good germination results have been reported without stratification by soaking the seed. Soak the seed in hot water (190 degrees Fahrenheit) for 12 hours. Repeat this process two additional times for expected seed germination of 50%. Seed can be placed in cold storage for up to three years. Germination is poor at temperatures higher than 85 degrees Fahrenheit. Seedlings should not be transplanted until they have at least one set of true leaves. Allow 4 to 8 weeks inside growing time for seedlings before moving to a cold frame or transplanting outside. Plants can be moved outside once the danger of frost has passed. — Collection: Collect seeds in the fall, when the brown pods are dry and have begun to split. Crack the pods open completely allowing the seeds to dry for one to two weeks in paper bags. Several weevil larvae prey on developing seeds, so look for signs of damage including small entry holes in the pod exuding latex.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/asclepias-incarnata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/plantmaterials/wvpmcot12252.pdf 2) https://wildseedproject.net/blog/swamp-milkweed#:~:text=To%20grow%20your%20own%20swamp,will%20germinate%20in%20mid%20spring. | 1) https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/plantmaterials/wvpmcot12252.pdf 2) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/asclepias-incarnata-swamp-milkweed 2) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/asclepias-incarnata-swamp-milkweed | https://www.gardenia.net/plant/asclepias-incarnata-swamp-milkweed | https://www.westernnativeseed.com/plant%20guides/ascincpg.pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Asclepias oenotheroides", "Scientific Name": "Asclepias oenotheroides", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Zizotes Milkweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Fall is the best time for planting milkweed seeds. The seeds won't germinate until spring because they require natural freezing and thawing to soften the seed coat so that the embryo plant can grow. This process stops seedlings from emerging in the fall and being killed by winter cold. You can plant the seeds from September 1 up until the soil freezes. Scatter the seeds and use your rake to gently work them into the soil. They will come up in spring when conditions are right for them to grow. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Spring planting takes a little more work because you will need to mimic the natural freezing and thawing cycle. At least six weeks before you are going to plant the seeds in spring, obtain two paper towels, wet them and then wring out excess water. Place one of the paper towels inside a one-gallon, zip-close plastic bag. Scatter the milkweed seeds over this paper towel. Cover the seeds with the second damp paper towel. Zip the plastic bag closed and place it flat in your refrigerator. Leave it undisturbed for at least six weeks. Scatter the seeds and use your rake to gently work them into the soil. When they come up, keep the soil moist until the plants are well established. Other sources recommend sowing milkweed seeds by scattering them on the soil surface 1/4-1/2 inch apart, and then cover with about 1/4 inch of additional soil. Water frequently after planting until plants become established.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/asclepias-oenotheroides/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://dnr.illinois.gov/education/atoz/seedinstr.html#:~:text=Fall%20Planting%20%2D%20Fall%20is%20the%20best%20time%20for%20planting%20milkweed%20seeds."}, {"Plant_ID": "Asclepias texana", "Scientific Name": "Asclepias texana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Milkweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Placing seeds in a moist medium and refrigerating them for 30 days before planting. Once stratified, plant the seeds in a well-draining seed starting mix, barely covering them with soil. Use a light hand when covering the seeds as they need light for germination. You can expect germination to occur within 10-14 days under optimal conditions. Ensure the environment is warm and well-lit to encourage healthy growth. Once seedlings are sturdy enough and risk of frost has passed, transplant them outdoors. Ensure each plant has sufficient space for root growth and access to full sun. — Collection: Collect seeds from mature texas milkweed pods when they begin to split open. Gather the seeds, which should have fluffy, white appendages known as coma. Remove the coma from the seeds if still attached. This can be done manually or by gently blowing them off. Store the seeds in a cool, dry place until ready for sowing. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: For the rooting medium, a mix of perlite and peat moss works wonders. Keep the cuttings in a humid environment, and they should root within 2-4 weeks. By utilizing these propagation techniques, you can easily expand your Texas Milkweed collection and contribute to the beauty of your garden. Next, let’s explore the lifecycle of this remarkable plant. — Collection: Select healthy cuttings that are 4-6 inches long from established plants.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/asclepias-texana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://greg.app/texas-milkweed-overview/#:~:text=To%20propagate%20Texas%20Milkweed%20from,Seedling%20Stage%20%F0%9F%8C%BF 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Asclepias_texana.html | https://greg.app/texas-milkweed-overview/#:~:text=To%20propagate%20Texas%20Milkweed%20from,Seedling%20Stage%20%F0%9F%8C%BF"}, {"Plant_ID": "Asclepias tuberosa", "Scientific Name": "Asclepias tuberosa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Butterfly Milkweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Root | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Root — Treatment: Cutting — Method: In the fall, cut the taproot into 2-inch sections and plant each section vertically, keeping the area moist. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow outdoors in place after frost in the fall, in a cold frame in early spring, or start indoors with bottom heat in late winter (8-10 weeks before average last frost) after 1-month moist stratification to carefully transplant outside later. Using 3-4-inch-deep containers, particularly with separate cells, will allow the roots to grow deeper and seedlings can be more readily transplanted without overly disturbing the roots. Plants will bloom from seed in 2-3 years, and may not transplant well because of their deep taproots. — Collection: Collect seeds after the pods have ripened, but before they have split open. The seeds are wind dispersed, so be careful when gathering to place in a paper or burlap bag to avoid losing them. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Indoors: Cold, moist stratification. Start at least 5 weeks before outdoor night temperatures are reliably in the 10 C (50 F) range. Mix the seed with a slightly moistened, sterile, soil-less growing mix. Put this in a labelled, sealed plastic bag and store in a refrigerator for one day. The next day place this in the freezer for one day. Repeat this for one week, alternating between the fridge and the freezer. After stratifying, plant seed 0.64 cm (1/4 inch) deep in pots. Keep moist but not soggy and very warm (21 C - 70 F). When seedlings are 5 cm (2 inches) tall or more, transplant into the garden spaced 30 cm (1 foot) apart. — Collection: Collect seeds after the pods have ripened, but before they have split open. The seeds are wind dispersed, so be careful when gathering to place in a paper or burlap bag to avoid losing them.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/asclepias-tuberosa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ASTU 2) https://hort.extension.wisc.edu/articles/butterflyweed-asclepias-tuberosa/#:~:text=Propagating%20Butterfly%20Weed,without%20overly%20disturbing%20the%20roots. | 1) https://hort.extension.wisc.edu/articles/butterflyweed-asclepias-tuberosa/#:~:text=Propagating%20Butterfly%20Weed,without%20overly%20disturbing%20the%20roots. 2) https://www.wildflowerfarm.com/asclepias-tuberosa-butterflyweed.html 3) https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/plantguide/pdf/cs_astu.pdf | 1) https://www.wildflowerfarm.com/asclepias-tuberosa-butterflyweed.html 2) https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/plantguide/pdf/cs_astu.pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Asclepias verticilata", "Scientific Name": "Asclepias verticilata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Whorled Milkweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Milkweed seeds need to go through a cold stratification period. Cold stratification is very important for the germination and growth of Milkweed. It helps break the seeds natural dormancy cycle. To do this, we recommend placing Milkweed seed in a damp paper towel or damp sand in a zip lock bag and place in your fridge for 3 – 6 weeks (30 days). Place in an area of the fridge, where it won’t get damaged. We taped ours to the bottom of a refrigerator shelf. Planting In Spring: Once the 30 days are complete, it’s time to plant the cold stratified Milkweed (asclepias) seeds. We recommend planting in 2-4” peat pots. Fill peat pots ¾ of the way with seed starting potting soil and gently add water. Water should be able to drain through the peat pots. Once the soil is damp, place 1-2 cold stratified seeds into each pot. To finish, place 1/4 inch of soil on top of the seed. Planting In Fall: If you're planting Milkweed seed in the fall, let nature do the cold stratification for you! There is no need to place your seeds in the refrigerator before planting, you can plant seeds directly into the soil after there have been a few frosts in your area. This allows for the seeds to remain dormant for the winter and come up in the early spring. Clear away any existing growth and using your index finger to measure, create 1.5\" holes for each Milkweed seed. We recommend spacing seeds about 4-6” apart. Place a seed in each hole and cover. Water thoroughly. Watering: Gently water the planted seed to give additional hydration. The best way to water is from the bottom up. Use a flat pan under the peat pots and add a half inch of water to the bottom of the tray. Don’t over water as it can cause fungus. Water every day or every other day as needed, the best way to test the soil dampness is to touch it. If the soil seems dry then add water; if it’s wet, wait for the soil to dry out to water. Light Requirements: For the next few weeks, make sure the Milkweed is either in a sunny window, in a green house or under a grow light. Milkweed needs lots of sun and warmth to grow. If you’re using a grow light, make sure to lower the bulb closer to the pots or your seedlings may become leggy, as they stretch to the light. In our experiment, this happened to us. Ideally a sturdier stem is better. Cold stratified seeds should germinate and sprout within 10-15 days once planted. In total Milkweed from the day they are cold stratified to growth can take 40 plus days, so be patient! || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Place dry seed (not stratified) in seed starting soil and plant in peat pots under a grow light or in a greenhouse to germinate seeds. The success rate for this is low and more difficult to accomplish. If you choose to use this option it can take months for the seeds to germinate. If you are planting seed outside, we suggest seeding in late fall, and let the Milkweed seed lay on the ground through winter. Milkweed seed will have a long winter of dormancy, so once the sun comes out and the ground warms in the spring, the seeds will germinate on their own.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/asclepias-verticilata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1)) https://www.americanmeadows.com/products/asclepias-whorled-milkweed-wildflower-seeds#:~:text=We%20suggest%20transplanting%20Milkweed%20when,t%20germinate%20over%2085%20degrees. 2) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/asclepias-verticillata#:~:text=surviving%20winter%20conditions.-,How%20to%20Propagate%20Whorled%20Milkweed,18%E2%80%9324%C2%B0C). | 1) https://www.americanmeadows.com/products/asclepias-whorled-milkweed-wildflower-seeds#:~:text=We%20suggest%20transplanting%20Milkweed%20when,t%20germinate%20over%2085%20degrees. 2) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/asclepias-verticillata#:~:text=surviving%20winter%20conditions.-,How%20to%20Propagate%20Whorled%20Milkweed,18%E2%80%9324%C2%B0C)."}, {"Plant_ID": "Asclepias verticillata", "Scientific Name": "Asclepias verticillata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Whorled Milkweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Milkweed seeds need to go through a cold stratification period. Cold stratification is very important for the germination and growth of Milkweed. It helps break the seeds natural dormancy cycle. To do this, we recommend placing Milkweed seed in a damp paper towel or damp sand in a zip lock bag and place in your fridge for 3 – 6 weeks (30 days). Place in an area of the fridge, where it won’t get damaged. We taped ours to the bottom of a refrigerator shelf. Planting In Spring: Once the 30 days are complete, it’s time to plant the cold stratified Milkweed (asclepias) seeds. We recommend planting in 2-4” peat pots. Fill peat pots ¾ of the way with seed starting potting soil and gently add water. Water should be able to drain through the peat pots. Once the soil is damp, place 1-2 cold stratified seeds into each pot. To finish, place 1/4 inch of soil on top of the seed. Planting In Fall: If you're planting Milkweed seed in the fall, let nature do the cold stratification for you! There is no need to place your seeds in the refrigerator before planting, you can plant seeds directly into the soil after there have been a few frosts in your area. This allows for the seeds to remain dormant for the winter and come up in the early spring. Clear away any existing growth and using your index finger to measure, create 1.5\" holes for each Milkweed seed. We recommend spacing seeds about 4-6” apart. Place a seed in each hole and cover. Water thoroughly. Watering: Gently water the planted seed to give additional hydration. The best way to water is from the bottom up. Use a flat pan under the peat pots and add a half inch of water to the bottom of the tray. Don’t over water as it can cause fungus. Water every day or every other day as needed, the best way to test the soil dampness is to touch it. If the soil seems dry then add water; if it’s wet, wait for the soil to dry out to water. Light Requirements: For the next few weeks, make sure the Milkweed is either in a sunny window, in a green house or under a grow light. Milkweed needs lots of sun and warmth to grow. If you’re using a grow light, make sure to lower the bulb closer to the pots or your seedlings may become leggy, as they stretch to the light. In our experiment, this happened to us. Ideally a sturdier stem is better. Cold stratified seeds should germinate and sprout within 10-15 days once planted. In total Milkweed from the day they are cold stratified to growth can take 40 plus days, so be patient! || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Place dry seed (not stratified) in seed starting soil and plant in peat pots under a grow light or in a greenhouse to germinate seeds. The success rate for this is low and more difficult to accomplish. If you choose to use this option it can take months for the seeds to germinate. If you are planting seed outside, we suggest seeding in late fall, and let the Milkweed seed lay on the ground through winter. Milkweed seed will have a long winter of dormancy, so once the sun comes out and the ground warms in the spring, the seeds will germinate on their own.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/asclepias-verticillata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1)) https://www.americanmeadows.com/products/asclepias-whorled-milkweed-wildflower-seeds#:~:text=We%20suggest%20transplanting%20Milkweed%20when,t%20germinate%20over%2085%20degrees. 2) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/asclepias-verticillata#:~:text=surviving%20winter%20conditions.-,How%20to%20Propagate%20Whorled%20Milkweed,18%E2%80%9324%C2%B0C). | 1) https://www.americanmeadows.com/products/asclepias-whorled-milkweed-wildflower-seeds#:~:text=We%20suggest%20transplanting%20Milkweed%20when,t%20germinate%20over%2085%20degrees. 2) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/asclepias-verticillata#:~:text=surviving%20winter%20conditions.-,How%20to%20Propagate%20Whorled%20Milkweed,18%E2%80%9324%C2%B0C)."}, {"Plant_ID": "Asclepias viridis", "Scientific Name": "Asclepias viridis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Green Milkweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Soak seed overnight in water. Cold moist stratification for 14-30 days enhances germination to greater than 60 percent. — Collection: Collect June-July", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/asclepias-viridis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ASVI2"}, {"Plant_ID": "Atriplex canescens", "Scientific Name": "Atriplex canescens", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Four-wing Saltbush", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Method: Seeds must undergo a 10 month period of after-ripening. Gemination can increase by presoaking the fruits and then wringing the water and dissolved salts from the material. Sow in the spring. — Collection: Collect in summer or fall.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/atriplex-canescens/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ATCA2"}, {"Plant_ID": "Baccharis neglecta", "Scientific Name": "Baccharis neglecta", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Poverty Weed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Softwood | Hardwood | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the leaves from the bottom 2-3 inches of the cutting. Fill a pot or seed tray with a well-draining mix like peat moss or perlite. Dip the cut end of each cutting in rooting hormone powder, make small holes in your rooting medium, then gently place the cuttings inside. Keep them moist and humid by watering them regularly and placing a plastic dome or bag over the pot. Allow the cuttings to root for 4-6 weeks before transplanting. — Collection: Choose healthy new growth about 4-6 inches long in early summer when the plant is actively growing. Make sure the cuttings are soft and pliable. Make a clean cut just below a node (the point where leaves grow from the stem). || Hardwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the leaves from the bottom ½ inch of the cutting. Use a mix of sand and potting soil or a pre-made rooting mix. Dip the cut ends in rooting hormone powder or a liquid rooting solution. Plant the cuttings in your rooting medium, making sure to leave at least two nodes above the soil line. Keep the cuttings in a cool, bright spot, maintain consistently damp soil, and allow them to root for a couple of months. — Collection: In late fall or winter when the plant is dormant, choose mature, brown stems from the previous year’s growth. Cut the stems into 6-8 inch lengths, ensuring each piece has at least two nodes. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Plant the seeds in well-draining soil and cover with a thin layer of soil. Water the seeds regularly and keep them in a warm and well-lit location until they germinate. — Collection: Collect the seeds from the plant and allow them to dry out completely.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/baccharis-neglecta/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-baccharis-neglecta/ | https://plantiary.com/plant/baccharis-neglecta_4567.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Baptisia australis var. minor", "Scientific Name": "Baptisia australis var. minor", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Blue Wild Indigo", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump | Softwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Germinates quickly, but does not flower for up to 3 years. — Collection: About six weeks past flowering, the pods should be black and beginning to open. Collect at this time. Comb the seeds from the pod. Mature, viable seeds will be brownish, hard and rounded. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification, Stratification — Method: It is best to sow them in plug trays with large cell sizes (no smaller than 72-cell). Sow one to two seeds per cell when using Jelitto's Gold Nugget or fresh seed, and sow two to three seeds per cell when using regular (untreated) seed. Do not cover them after sowing; it is beneficial to cover them lightly with growing media after the radical has emerged. Germination will occur over a period of two to three weeks with temperatures of 68-75¡ F. From sowing, it will take eight to 10 weeks to produce a transplantable plug when grown at 65 degrees F. — Collection: Germinating seed can be challenging because of its hard seed coat, providing variable results over time. The best results are obtained when using freshly harvested seed. Older seed can be used but will require stratification or scarification prior to sowing and will usually have a significantly lower germination rate compared to fresh seed. Many growers use a hot water soak over night to soften the seed coat and bypass the need for stratification. Jelitto offers baptisia as Gold Nugget seed, which is pretreated to help improve the germination rate and bypasses the need for stratification. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: As soon as plants are removed, trim any broken roots with sharp pruners. Cut apart divisions with a sharp hand saw or sturdy serrated knife. Replant as soon as possible, never letting roots dry, and water in well to settle air pockets. — Collection: Division or transplanting of Baptisia is difficult because of their deep woody root system and should be avoided unless absolutely necessary. Divide in spring or fall when plant is dormant, being careful to avoid breaking new shoots. Dig deeply to get as much root system as possible. || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip cutting in a rooting hormone and insert into a mix of 3 parts composted bark to 1 part peat. Keep humidity around cuttings high with a supported plastic tent. Cuttings should root in about 8 weeks. — Collection: Cuttings should be taken so that at least one set of leaf buds can be inserted below the potting mix surface. Most baptisias root easily in spring when the growth is still relatively soft, but the success rate drops as the stems harden.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/baptisia-australis-var-minor/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=BAAU 2) https://www.hortmag.com/smart-gardening/how-to-harvest-and-grow-the-seeds-of-blue-indigo | https://gpnmag.com/article/baptisia-australis-blue-false-indigo/ | 1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=BAAU 2) https://hgic.clemson.edu/factsheet/baptisia-false-or-wild-indigo/#:~:text=Cuttings%20should%20be%20taken%20so,well%20to%20settle%20air%20pockets. | https://utgardens.tennessee.edu/may-plant-of-the-month-baptisia-false-indigo/#:~:text=Baptisia%20can%20also%20be%20propagated,/ornamentals/%20for%20more%20information."}, {"Plant_ID": "Baptisia australis", "Scientific Name": "Baptisia australis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Wild Blue Indigo", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump | Softwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Germinates quickly, but does not flower for up to 3 years. — Collection: About six weeks past flowering, the pods should be black and beginning to open. Collect at this time. Comb the seeds from the pod. Mature, viable seeds will be brownish, hard and rounded. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: As soon as plants are removed, trim any broken roots with sharp pruners. Cut apart divisions with a sharp hand saw or sturdy serrated knife. Replant as soon as possible, never letting roots dry, and water in well to settle air pockets. — Collection: Division or transplanting of Baptisia is difficult because of their deep woody root system and should be avoided unless absolutely necessary. Divide in spring or fall when plant is dormant, being careful to avoid breaking new shoots. Dig deeply to get as much root system as possible. || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip cutting in a rooting hormone and insert into a mix of 3 parts composted bark to 1 part peat. Keep humidity around cuttings high with a supported plastic tent. Cuttings should root in about 8 weeks. — Collection: Cuttings should be taken so that at least one set of leaf buds can be inserted below the potting mix surface. Most baptisias root easily in spring when the growth is still relatively soft, but the success rate drops as the stems harden. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification, Stratification — Method: It is best to sow them in plug trays with large cell sizes (no smaller than 72-cell). Sow one to two seeds per cell when using Jelitto's Gold Nugget or fresh seed, and sow two to three seeds per cell when using regular (untreated) seed. Do not cover them after sowing; it is beneficial to cover them lightly with growing media after the radical has emerged. Germination will occur over a period of two to three weeks with temperatures of 68-75¡ F. From sowing, it will take eight to 10 weeks to produce a transplantable plug when grown at 65 degrees F. — Collection: Germinating seed can be challenging because of its hard seed coat, providing variable results over time. The best results are obtained when using freshly harvested seed. Older seed can be used but will require stratification or scarification prior to sowing and will usually have a significantly lower germination rate compared to fresh seed. Many growers use a hot water soak over night to soften the seed coat and bypass the need for stratification. Jelitto offers baptisia as Gold Nugget seed, which is pretreated to help improve the germination rate and bypasses the need for stratification.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/baptisia-australis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=BAAU 2) https://www.hortmag.com/smart-gardening/how-to-harvest-and-grow-the-seeds-of-blue-indigo | 1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=BAAU 2) https://hgic.clemson.edu/factsheet/baptisia-false-or-wild-indigo/#:~:text=Cuttings%20should%20be%20taken%20so,well%20to%20settle%20air%20pockets. | https://utgardens.tennessee.edu/may-plant-of-the-month-baptisia-false-indigo/#:~:text=Baptisia%20can%20also%20be%20propagated,/ornamentals/%20for%20more%20information. | https://gpnmag.com/article/baptisia-australis-blue-false-indigo/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Baptisia sphaerocarpa", "Scientific Name": "Baptisia sphaerocarpa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Yellow Wild Indigo", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification, Stratification — Method: When growing in containers, soak the seeds overnight before sowing and germinate at about 70 degrees F. When planting seeds in the ground fall to winter is best. Germination is sporatic (Phillips 1985). Stratification for 10 days and scarification improves germination (Shirley 1994, Steffen 1997). Seedlings are sensitive to overwatering and should be allowed to dry out between waterings. Baptisia benefit from innoculation at planting time with an innoculant specific to Baptisia. Seed burro screens 12/64 > 8/64 x 3/8. — Collection: The seed pods should be collected 1 - 1 1/2 months after flowering (April-August), when they turn brown, and the seeds removed. When infected with beetles, ants or other insects, place the seeds in a plastic bag with a small piece of no-pest-strip for 2 weeks. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: On each cutting, include at least one set of leaf buds to be inserted below the potting mix surface. Dip the cutting into rooting hormone and insert into a mix of 3 parts composted bark to 1 part peat. Keep humidity high around the cuttings to avoid drying out. Cuttings should root in approximately 8 weeks (Russ 2015). — Collection: Take the stem cutting in the spring (late April/early May) when the stem is soft. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Trim any broken roots and divide the plant using a sharp handsaw or knife. Replant quickly before the roots dry, then water around the plant to settle air pockets in the planting hole (Russ 2015). — Collection: Dividing and transplanting of established yellow wild indigo plants is difficult because of their deep woody root system. In the spring, dig deeply around the plant to get as much root system as possible and avoid breaking new shoots.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/baptisia-sphaerocarpa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://warcapps.usgs.gov/PlantID/Species/Details/3249#:~:text=Baptisias%20like%20full%20sun%20but,Habitat 2) https://www.prairiemoon.com/baptisia-sphaerocarpa-large-yellow-wild-indigo#panel-planting 3) https://earthone.io/plant/baptisia%20sphaerocarpa?srsltid=AfmBOoqvHgBHUlOICB_93FMb60V6uEn-pcufVfIVC3C6WGE2eFIezoqQ | https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/plantmaterials/etpmcpg13192.pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Berchemia scandens", "Scientific Name": "Berchemia scandens", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Rattan Vine", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Softwood | Hardwood | Stem | Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut ends in rooting hormone powder and then plant them in a well-draining seed starting mix. Keep the cuttings consistently moist and warm, and you’ll see roots developing within a few weeks. Once the roots are well-established, the cutting can be transplanted into a larger container or planted outdoors. — Collection: In late spring or early summer, choose healthy, non-flowering stems with soft, pliable wood. Cut them into 4-6 inch sections, removing the leaves from the bottom inch or two. || Hardwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove all leaves except for a few at the top. Plant these directly in the ground or in pots. Water well and provide adequate drainage. — Collection: In the late fall or early winter when the plant is dormant, take cuttings from mature, woody stems and cut them into 8-12 inch sections. || Stem — Treatment: Layering — Method: Simply bend a branch down to the ground, burying a section of the stem in the soil. Remove any leaves from the section that will be buried, and make a small incision on the stem where it touches the ground, ensuring it's not completely detached from the parent plant. Secure it with a rock or stake, and the buried stem will eventually develop roots. Once the roots are established, you can carefully cut the new plant away from the mother vine. — Collection: n/a || Seed — Treatment: Scarification, Stratification — Method: Remove the seeds from the fruits and clean them thoroughly to eliminate any flesh or residue. This decreases the likelihood of fungal infection. Stratify the seeds in moist sand or peat for about 60-90 days in a refrigerator. This cold treatment mimics natural winter conditions and helps break seed dormancy. Alternatively, soak the seeds in a container of water for 24 hours to soften the outer seed coat. Sow the seeds in well-drained soil in a sunny to partially shaded location. Plant the seeds at a depth twice the size of the seed itself to ensure optimal germination. Keep the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged. — Collection: Gather mature seeds typically after the fruits have fully ripened and have taken on a dark, almost black color. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Replant the divided sections into well-prepared soil, making sure they are at the same depth as they were before. Water the newly divided plants thoroughly to eliminate any air pockets and encourage root establishment. Maintain regular watering until the plants are well-established. — Collection: Dig up the parent plant carefully, making sure to retain as much root mass as possible. Divide the plant into smaller sections, ensuring each section has a portion of the root system and shoots.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/berchemia-scandens/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-berchemia-scandens/ 2) https://plantiary.com/plant/berchemia-scandens_5162.html | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-berchemia-scandens/ | 1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Berchemia_scandens.html 2) https://plantiary.com/plant/berchemia-scandens_5162.html | https://plantiary.com/plant/berchemia-scandens_5162.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Berlandiera lyrata", "Scientific Name": "Berlandiera lyrata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Chocolate Daisy", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow directly outdoors: In spring, several weeks after last frost date, sow in a sunny garden spot with excellent drainage. Sow 2 inches apart and cover lightly. Keep moist but not soggy while awaiting germination. When seedlings are well established, thin to 6 inches apart so plants have room to mature. Start early indoors: Start seeds indoors about 6 weeks before night temps are above 50°F (10°C). Sow seeds 2 to 3 apart in a container of seed starting mix and cover very lightly. Keep seedbed moist but not soggy while awaiting germination. When outdoor weather is warm and settled both day and night, plant seedlings 6 inches apart in a sunny, well-drained garden spot. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Division in not a recommended method for propagation as the long taproot can be damaged.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/berlandiera-lyrata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.bhg.com/gardening/plant-dictionary/perennial/chocolate-flower/#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Chocolate%20Flower,takes%20up%20to%204%20weeks. 2) https://www.reneesgarden.com/products/daisy-fragrant-chocolate#:~:text=TO%20START%20EARLY%20INDOORS,%2C%20well%2Ddrained%20garden%20spot. | https://plants.ces.ncsu.edu/plants/berlandiera-lyrata/#:~:text=In%20the%20proper%20conditions%2C%20i.e.,long%20taproot%20can%20be%20damaged."}, {"Plant_ID": "Bidens aristosa", "Scientific Name": "Bidens aristosa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Bearded Beggarticks", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Seeds are cold stratified and germinate at 30/15 C. Germination is greater in light than dark.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/bidens-aristosa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=asteraceae-bidens-1900&referer=wildflower"}, {"Plant_ID": "Andropogon gerardii", "Scientific Name": "Andropogon gerardii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Big Bluestem", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Divide during winter dormancy. Dig up divisions from the outside of the clump and transplant them to a new location. Replant the sections at the same depth as the original plant. Keep any newly transplanted grasses consistently moist until they have re-established. — Collection: Depending on how mature the grass is, the cluster of rhizomes can be very difficult to separate and you may need to use a saw or sharp spade to divide them. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Dry stratification as well as cold-moist stratification are recommended for one month to break dormancy. Seeds can be started indoors or sown directly in the garden in late winter or early spring. Sow the seeds at 1/4- to 1/2-inch deep. Keep the seeds consistently moist until they sprout. Be patient, as big bluestem seeds can take up to four weeks to germinate. — Collection: Big bluestem readily produces seeds every year, which can be harvested and planted the following spring. Alternatively, big bluestem seeds can be bought from most garden centers and specialty nurseries. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Plant in fall or spring, barely covering the seeds with Young plants need water their first year, but after that big bluestem becomes very drought tolerant. Big bluestem is a bit slow to establish, but should form a vigorous clump by its third year. soil.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/big-bluestem/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.growveg.com/plants/us-and-canada/how-to-grow-big-bluestem/#:~:text=Sow%20and%20Plant,and%20harvest%20for%20your%20area. 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ANGE 3) https://www.thespruce.com/big-bluestem-plant-profile-4845878#:~:text=Propagating%20Big%20Bluestem,Potting%20and%20Repotting%20Big%20Bluestem | 1) https://www.thespruce.com/big-bluestem-plant-profile-4845878#:~:text=Propagating%20Big%20Bluestem,Potting%20and%20Repotting%20Big%20Bluestem 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ANGE | https://www.growveg.com/plants/us-and-canada/how-to-grow-big-bluestem/#:~:text=Sow%20and%20Plant,and%20harvest%20for%20your%20area."}, {"Plant_ID": "Muhlenbergia lindheimeri", "Scientific Name": "Muhlenbergia lindheimeri", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Big Muhly", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Using your hands or a knife, divide the root clump into smaller sections. Make sure each division has a good amount of roots and several growing points or shoots. Dig holes for each division that are as deep as the root ball and twice as wide. Space the holes approximately 2 to 3 feet apart to allow enough room for lindheimer's muhly to grow. Place each division in a prepared hole, filling in with soil and positioning the plant at the same depth it was initially growing. Firm the soil around the roots carefully to eliminate air pockets. Water the newly planted divisions thoroughly to settle the soil and to help establish them. Keep the soil consistently moist, especially during the first growing season after division to encourage strong root development. — Collection: Thoroughly water the soil around lindheimer's muhly the day before you plan to divide it to make the soil easier to work with and reduce stress on the plant. Carefully dig around the clump of lindheimer's muhly, starting several inches away from the plant base to avoid damaging the root system. Gently loosen the soil and lift the clump out of the ground.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/big-muhly/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Muhlenbergia_lindheimeri.html 2) https://earthone.io/plant/muhlenbergia%20lindheimeri?srsltid=AfmBOoqP1BUmAUyTThAC6DUSDNE6X_xoRR2DzeC3ayVgCqOajPfG-wmK"}, {"Plant_ID": "Bignonia capreolata", "Scientific Name": "Bignonia capreolata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Crossvine", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Softwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow the seeds in containers or directly into the ground in the fall (before the ground freezes) or in the spring after the danger of frost has passed. The seeds do not require extra stratification or special handling (but you should refrigerate them if you don’t plan to plant them right away). Press your seeds 1 to 2 inches into the soil and keep the soil evenly moist as the seeds germinate (typically about 3 to 4 weeks). — Collection: Collect the large, woody capsules from late summer through fall when they are light brown and beginning to dry. Seeds remain viable one year in sealed, refrigerated containers. || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Leave several leaves on the tip of the stem but remove the leaves from the bottom two inches of the stem. Treat the cut end of the stem with rooting hormone to encourage root development. Insert the cut end about 2 inches deep into a moist growing medium. Mist the cutting frequently or slip a plastic bag over the potted cutting to keep it from drying out before it can develop roots. The cutting should take root within six to eight weeks. — Collection: Cut off a healthy, 6- to 8-inch long growing stem (current season’s growth) in spring or early summer.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/bignonia-capreolata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=BICA 2) https://piedmontmastergardeners.org/article/crossvine-a-showstopping-native-vine/#:~:text=Crossvine%20may%20be%20grown%20from,within%20six%20to%20eight%20weeks. 3) https://www.bhg.com/gardening/plant-dictionary/vine/cross-vine/#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Crossvine%20Via,as%20it%20develops%20new%20roots. | 1) https://piedmontmastergardeners.org/article/crossvine-a-showstopping-native-vine/#:~:text=Crossvine%20may%20be%20grown%20from,within%20six%20to%20eight%20weeks. 2) https://www.bhg.com/gardening/plant-dictionary/vine/cross-vine/#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Crossvine%20Via,as%20it%20develops%20new%20roots."}, {"Plant_ID": "Bouteloua gracilis", "Scientific Name": "Bouteloua gracilis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Blue Grama", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct sow seeds into prepared soil in late fall once soil temps are below 50 degrees (usually mid to late November). Can also be planted in winter during natural freeze/thaw cycles and early spring. Plant shallow, no deeper than 1/8 to 1/4 inch deep and lightly rake to work seed in. Plant in full sun. Can take 3 growing seasons to fully establish.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/blue-grama/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.opnseed.com/products/bouteloua-gracilis-blue-grama#:~:text=Direct%20sow%20seeds%20into%20prepared,Plant%20in%20full%20sun. 2) https://www.opnseed.com/products/bouteloua-gracilis-blue-grama#:~:text=Direct%20sow%20seeds%20into%20prepared,Plant%20in%20full%20sun."}, {"Plant_ID": "Boehmeria cylindrica", "Scientific Name": "Boehmeria cylindrica", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Smallspike False Nettle", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: False nettle is very easy to propagate from cuttings. It will readily root in water or soil. When I put cuttings in water for the caterpillars they always grow roots while the caterpillars are eating. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Start indoors 6-8 weeks before last frost. Surface sow False Nettle seeds and keep the seeds and the seedlings very moist. The plants are very tiny upon emerging so you may want to use a mist bottle to keep from damaging them. A plastic top would help keep in the moisture. Growth is slow until they reach about 1-2 inches at which time they will take off. When planting outdoors, space the plants about 2 feet apart. Plant them out into their permanent positions in late spring or early summer, after the last expected frosts. — Collection: Stored the seeds in a cool dry area or in the refrigerator until you are ready to plant – this aids germination. We store our seeds in cold storage. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Division in spring. Very easy, larger divisions can be planted straight into their permanent positions whilst smaller clumps are best potted up and kept in a cold frame until they are growing away well.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/boehmeria-cylindrica/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.joyfulbutterfly.com/product/false-nettle/#:~:text=From%20seed:%20start%20indoors%206,False%20Nettle%20native%20range | https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Boehmeria+cylindrica#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,they%20are%20growing%20away%20well."}, {"Plant_ID": "Boltonia diffusa", "Scientific Name": "Boltonia diffusa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Doll's Daisy", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump | Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: This type of propagation is relatively simple; you will need a clean shovel, mulch, fresh soil (any kind will do, though it does need to be well-draining), compost, and pots (only necessary if you will be saving divided plants for transporting elsewhere), Using a shovel, dig up your existing plant. Start from the outside and work your way in to avoid damaging the rhizome roots. Once you have worked it up out of the ground, lay it out. Start to tease apart the roots with your gloved fingers. Once the roots are untangled, separate your plant into segments, ensuring that each one has at least one thick root section with eyes. Prepare your pot(s) or new planting site(s) with amended, well-draining soil. You can either bring in new soil or simply amend your existing soil with compost to complete this task. Then, plant your divided rhizomes about an inch under the soil surface and water thoroughly. Apply a thick layer of mulch over the new planting to protect it from cold weather as it acclimates to its new home. Then, enjoy watching it sprout the following growing season. — Collection: Division is best done in spring or fall (after the plant has entered dormancy, but before it has begun its new spring growth) Plants generally need division every 3 to 4 years. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Seed collected from cultivars is unlikely to produce plants like its parents. Boltonia seeds germinate in 7 to 8 weeks at 60°F (15°C). — Collection: Allow flowers to dry on the plant if you want to collect seed for replanting. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Make a hole in your planting medium by pushing your pencil into the soil. Dip the end of the stem in rooting hormone, and plant it in your pot. Fill in soil around the cutting to support it, but do not pack it down too much. Moisten with water, and ensure that the pot has good drainage. Your pot should be kept in warm, sunny conditions indoors (and not in direct sunlight). Water whenever your soil is dry under the top layer. After about four to six weeks have passed, your cutting should be rooted. When you notice new growth, you'll know you have roots. Keep your new plant in an area with bright light (though not direct sunlight) and temperatures between 55 and 70 degrees Fahrenheit. Ensure that the soil stays moist, but not wet, until the next spring, when you can transplant it to its new home. Ensure that the last frost of the year has occurred before doing this, as it can seriously damage your new plant. — Collection: In early summertime, choose the plant that you'd like to propagate. Ensure that this plant has had a good watering the night before, as this will improve the chances your cutting will take root. Cut one or more 6 inch portion(s) of the end of a non-blooming branch and strip the leaves off of the lower half. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Boltonia seeds need to be cold-stratified in order to germinate. This can be accomplished by filling a plastic bag or other sealable container with moistened peat moss or sand, and placing the seeds within the substrate. Place the container/bag in the refrigerator for 60 days. After this period has passed, remove the seeds. Place your seeds in lukewarm water for six hours. Viable seeds will sink to the bottom, and non-viable seeds will float to the top. You can discard any seeds that float. Water your prepared seed tray or pot filled with soil, and ensure that good drainage is occurring. Place your seeds on top of the soil of the seed tray, and sprinkle soil over them. Water with your spray bottle, taking care to not dislodge any of the small seeds. Place your tray in a warm area that receives bright, indirect light. A greenhouse is the most ideal climate, but a planting tray inside a window will do as well. Germination usually takes between 3 and 4 weeks from sowing. Once you begin to see seedlings sprout and they are able to be handled, transplant them to their own individual 3-inch pots, filled with the same potting medium as described in Step 1. Loosen the seedlings from the potting medium by digging down with the tines of your fork about an inch and a half, gently working the seedling up until it is out. Then, replant the seedling in its individual pot. Keep the seedling's potting medium moist, but not wet, by spraying the soil with your spray bottle. Keep your new plant in an area with bright light (though not direct sunlight) and temperatures between 55 and 70 degrees Fahrenheit. Ensure that the soil stays moist, but not wet, until the next spring (after the danger of frost has passed), when you can transplant it to its new home. — Collection: The seed heads on Boltonia plants are pretty easy to spot, they're large and dangle from the branches, left behind after flowers have faded. Cut them off of the plant, placing them in a paper bag. Harvest as many as you can, and place the paper bag in a dry, cool, dark area. They will begin to split open and release the seeds contained inside. Once they have been released, take them out of the bag and put them in a container so you can work with them.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/boltonia-diffusa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://harvesttotable.com/how-to-grow-boltonia/#Boltonia_propagation 2) http://www.theeyrye.com/boltonia.html 3) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Boltonia_diffusa.html 4) https://greg.app/boltonia-overview/ | 1) https://harvesttotable.com/how-to-grow-boltonia/#Boltonia_propagation 2) https://greg.app/boltonia-overview/ | 1) http://www.theeyrye.com/boltonia.html 2) https://greg.app/boltonia-overview/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Bothriochloa barbinodis", "Scientific Name": "Bothriochloa barbinodis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Cane Bluestem", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Bud", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Cane bluestem is typically easy to germinate with no pretreatment necessary (Gucker 2011). In lab and field settings germination rates are generally 75% or higher (Gucker 2011). Seeds germinated at 25°C (77°F) show the highest germination rates of 88-93% (Gucker 2011). Abrupt temperature changes and seeds kept at lower and higher temperatures had lower germination rates of 0-76% (Gucker 2011). — Collection: Seeds are collected when they form a white fluffy fan at the top of the culms and when they readily detach from the plant. Gently collect seed tufts by hand, removing them from the culms. || Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully dig around the clump, ensuring you lift the entire root system. Using a sharp spade or garden knife, divide the clump into smaller sections, each with a good amount of roots and shoots. Replant the divided sections immediately in prepared garden beds, spacing them according to the desired density and watering them in thoroughly. While drought-tolerant once established, Cane Bluestem benefits from regular watering during its first year, especially during hot, dry periods. — Collection: The best time to divide Cane Bluestem is in early spring when new growth begins to emerge. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Cane Bluestem seeds benefit from a period of cold stratification to improve germination rates. You have two options: Direct Sowing: In the late fall, sow seeds directly into prepared garden beds after the first frost. This allows them to undergo natural cold stratification over winter. Indoor Sowing: For an early spring start, mimic natural stratification by mixing the seeds with damp vermiculite in a sealed plastic bag and storing them in the refrigerator for 6-8 weeks. Sow the chilled seeds in seed trays filled with a well-draining seed starting mix, lightly covering them with soil. Cane Bluestem thrives in full sun to partial shade and well-draining soil. Keep the soil consistently moist until the seedlings are established. Expect germination to occur within 2-4 weeks after sowing indoors or in the spring for direct-sown seeds. — Collection: The optimal time to collect Cane Bluestem seeds is in the fall when the fluffy, silver seed heads mature. Snip the seed heads with sharp shears and store them in a paper bag in a cool, dry location until you’re ready to sow.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/bothriochloa-barbinodis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://rngr.net/npn/propagation/protocols/bothriochloa-barbinodis-bothriochloa#:~:text=Propagation%20Collection:,Propagation%20Processing/Propagule%20Characteristics: | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-bothriochloa-barbinodis/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Bothriochloa laguroides", "Scientific Name": "Bothriochloa laguroides", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Silver Bluestem", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: In mid March to mid April, sow seeds outside in cells or in the ground. Lightly cover with soil. The seed do not need pretreatment, but they germinate best when they are exposed to large temperature swings (70-90 F with nights 34-45 F). Seeds will germinate in 2-7 weeks. — Collection: Timing is key. Harvest mature seeds from existing plants in late summer or early fall when the seed heads turn a light tan color. Gently rub the seed heads between your palms to release the seeds. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Using a sharp spade or garden knife, carefully lift the entire clump of grass from the ground. Depending on the size of the clump, you can divide it into sections, ensuring each section has a healthy amount of roots and shoots. Choose a sunny location with well-drained soil for your new divisions. Dig holes slightly larger than the root balls and space them 12-18 inches apart to allow for future growth. Water thoroughly after planting. — Collection: Ideally, divide Silver Bluestem in early spring, just as new growth emerges. This allows the divisions ample time to establish themselves before the heat of summer.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/bothriochloa-laguroides-ssp-torreyana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://frontrange.wildones.org/wp-content/images/sites/105/2020/10/Bothriochloa-laguroides-ssp.-torreyana-.pdf 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-bothriochloa-laguroides/ | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-bothriochloa-laguroides/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Bouteloua curtipendula", "Scientific Name": "Bouteloua curtipendula", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Sideoats Grama", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Division is best done in early spring or fall. Ensure that each division has a healthy root system. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sown directly in the soil in the spring or fall. — Collection: In early fall, after the spikes turn brown, just run your hand along the stalk and strip the oats. You now have a handful of viable seed.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/bouteloua-curtipendula/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://earthone.io/plant/bouteloua%20curtipendula?srsltid=AfmBOoo-JejmFcoo0QnNe3pOSOJ3aPytyyNLOQzJHIruCyVt9ahfTKYR | 1) https://growitbuildit.com/sideoats-grama-bouteloua-curtipendula/ 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=BOCU"}, {"Plant_ID": "Bouteloua eriopoda", "Scientific Name": "Bouteloua eriopoda", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Black Grama", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Bud | Cutting", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow the seeds about 1/4 inch deep in well-prepared soil for optimal germination. — Collection: Collect when the seed heads turn brown. Once harvested || Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: Separate the clumps carefully and replant them immediately to encourage healthy growth — Collection: The best time to do this is in early spring or fall || Cutting — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Place them in a rooting medium made of a mix of peat and perlite for the best results. — Collection: Select healthy stems that are 4-6 inches long", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/bouteloua-eriopoda/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://greg.app/black-grama-overview/#:~:text=%F0%9F%8C%8D%20Environmental%20Benefits,the%20biodiversity%20of%20its%20ecosystem."}, {"Plant_ID": "Bouteloua rigidiseta", "Scientific Name": "Bouteloua rigidiseta", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Grama", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: The best times to propagate texas grama are during the cooler, moist periods of spring and autumn. Utilizing division as the propagation method, these seasons offer optimal temperatures and adequate light levels that support root establishment and growth without the stress of extreme heat or potential drought conditions prevalent in summer. Once divided, the sections should be planted promptly at the same depth they were originally growing to encourage successful establishment. Regular watering and minimizing transplant shock by keeping the soil moist will help the new plantlets thrive. — Collection: Separate the parent plant into smaller clumps, ensuring that each new section has a healthy root mass and several shoots.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/bouteloua-rigidiseta/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Bouteloua_rigidiseta.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Brickellia eupatorioides", "Scientific Name": "Brickellia eupatorioides", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "False Boneset", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds indoors in late winter or early spring, or directly outdoors in the garden after the last frost. Use a well-draining seed starting mix and fill seed trays or pots with drainage holes. Sprinkle seeds onto the surface and cover lightly with soil. Maintain consistent moisture, but avoid overwatering. Provide bright, indirect light. When seedlings have developed their second set of true leaves, transplant them into individual pots or directly into the garden, spacing them 18-24 inches apart. — Collection: Collect healthy seeds from mature plants after flowering. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end in rooting hormone powder. Insert cuttings into a rooting medium like a mixture of perlite and vermiculite, or a specialized rooting formula. Maintain consistent moisture and provide bright, indirect light. Covering with a plastic bag helps to create a humid environment. After a few weeks, the cutting should start to root and you can gradually remove the plastic bag. When cuttings have established roots, typically within 4-6 weeks, transplant them into individual pots or directly into the garden, spacing them 18-24 inches apart. — Collection: Cuttings offer a faster and Take cuttings in late spring or early summer when the plant is actively growing. Choose healthy, non-flowering stems with several nodes (where leaves emerge). Cut a 3-4\" section of stem just below a node, remove the bottom leaves.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/brickellia-eupatorioides/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-brickellia-eupatorioides/ 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Brickellia_eupatorioides.html | 1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-brickellia-eupatorioides/ 2) https://plantiary.com/plant/brickellia-eupatorioides_4294.html?"}, {"Plant_ID": "Bouteloua dactyloides", "Scientific Name": "Bouteloua dactyloides", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Buffalograss", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Seeds should be cold-moist stratified at 40 degrees for six weeks. Requires light for germination. Old seed germinates better than young seed. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Let nature handle the stratifying through a dormant seeding, sowing seeds on the surface of a weed-free site in late fall or winter. Seeds will be conditioned by weathering to make germination possible in subsequent growing seasons.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/buffalograss/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=BODA2 | https://www.prairiemoon.com/buchloe-dactyloides-buffalo-grass-cultivar#panel-planting"}, {"Plant_ID": "Andropogon glomeratus", "Scientific Name": "Andropogon glomeratus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Bushy Bluestem", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump | Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Divide during winter dormancy. Divide clumps with roots attached and liberal amounts of root-laden soil onto wet mineral soils in late winter or early spring. The plants should be spaced at 18 inches because the rate of spread is slow. Spread is generally less than 0.2 feet per year in unconsolidated sediment. — Collection: Carefully dig around the clump, ensuring you don’t damage the root system. Using a sharp spade or garden knife, divide the clump into smaller sections, each containing a healthy portion of roots and shoots. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: When planting from seed, do so when ground is no longer frozen in spring and after the date of the last projected frost. Sow seeds on the surface, pressing them lightly without burying them. These seeds need light to germinate. They will germinate in a few weeks. Keep weeds away from seeds and young seedlings, as they compete with the grass for nutrients and water. Keep growing seeds moist, but not soggy, until they have some growth. While bushy bluestem seed will tolerate in poor soils, the best initial growth is in moist soil. When growing as a landscape plant, mulch helps hold in moisture. Place the mulch about 3 inches (8 cm.) thick, but don’t let it touch the stems. If started indoors, Gradually Introduce them to the Outdoors: Once the danger of frost has passed and your seedlings have developed a robust root system, it’s time to harden them off. This process involves gradually acclimating the young plants to outdoor conditions. — Collection: Seeds are produced 6-8 weeks from when the culms are produced || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip stems in rooting hormone, and planted in moist, well-draining soil. Ensure they receive consistent moisture until roots develop. — Collection: Cuttings can be taken from young stems in the summer.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/bushy-bluestem/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/plantguide/pdf/pg_angl2.pdf 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ANGL2 3) chrome-extension://efaidnbmnnnibpcajpcglclefindmkaj/ https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-andropogon-glomeratus/?print=pdf | 1) https://www.gardeningknowhow.com/ornamental/foliage/bushy-beardgrass/what-is-bushy-beardgrass.htm 2) https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/plantguide/pdf/pg_anvi2.pdf | https://mygardenchannel.com/care-guide-to-bushy-bluestem-grass/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Callicarpa americana", "Scientific Name": "Callicarpa americana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "American Beautyberry", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Softwood | Hardwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sowing the cleaned seeds lightly in a greenhouse kept just above 40 degrees in November. They will germinate in January and February, and are ready to plant outside under shade by April. — Collection: Each berry contains at least 2 to 3 seeds that are 1/16 inch long. To propagate by seed, plant the whole berry after crushing it between your fingers to expose the seeds, or process the berries to separate the seeds from the fruit. Berries can be placed in a blender with water. After mixing, allow the liquid to sit. Viable seeds will sink to the bottom, and everything else can be skimmed off the top and blended again. Do this until the seeds are adequately separated. Drain the seeds and allow them to dry before storing. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Cold stratification for 1 month || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Softwood tip cuttings should be taken from \"early May through June, just after the first flush of growth but before the plant has flowered.\" The cuttings should be 4 to 5 inches long with the leaves from the bottom half removed. Treat the cuttings with rooting hormone (5,000 ppm) and place gently in your rooting material. Roots should begin to grow within 1 to 2 weeks. || Hardwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Hardwood cuttings should be 5 to 8 inches long, treated with rooting hormone (10,000 ppm), and placed under intermittent mist. While we don't think that putting cuttings directly in the ground will work very well, you may successfully separate large clumps of mature plants in the winter.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/callicarpa-americana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) How To Grow Native Plants of Texas And The Southwest by Jill Nokes 2) https://www.epicgardening.com/american-beautyberry/#:~:text=Propagating%20From%20Cuttings,to%204%20weeks%20to%20root. 3) https://www.fnps.org/assets/pdf/pubs/callicarpa_americana_beautyberry.pdf | 1) How To Grow Native Plants of Texas And The Southwest by Jill Nokes 2) https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/factsheet/pdf/fs_caam2.pdf | 1) How To Grow Native Plants of Texas And The Southwest by Jill Nokes 2) https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/factsheet/pdf/fs_caam2.pdf 3) https://theplantnative.com/plant/american-beautyberry/#:~:text=Can%20I%20grow%20American%20Beautyberry%20by%20cuttings?,your%20garden%202%20months%20later! 4) https://www.epicgardening.com/american-beautyberry/#:~:text=Propagating%20From%20Cuttings,to%204%20weeks%20to%20root."}, {"Plant_ID": "Callirhoe involucrata", "Scientific Name": "Callirhoe involucrata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Winecup", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Use a hot-water scarification treatment. Using wet heat is an effective method for many small-seeded species with hard impermeable seed coats as it provides a rapid, uniform treatment, and results of the treatment can easily be seen within a few hours. Thickness of the seed coat may vary somewhat among sources, so it is a good idea to dissect a few seeds and examine the thickness of seed coats from each lot to help determine duration of the wet-heat treatment.Seeds are added to boiling water for only 5 to 10 s and then immediately transferred to a vat of cold water, which allows them to quickly cool and prevents embryo damage. The seeds imbibe in the cool water for 1 d and are ready for sowing without further treatment. We direct sow seeds to individual Ray Leach 164-ml (10-in3) containers and lightly cover. Seed in the fall, raking into loose topsoil to ensure good seed/soil contact. Winecups like sun and a well-drained site. Flowers the second year. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: The easiest way to do this is winter sowing, where you basically plant the seeds outside in pots or some container, covered up to maintain moisture. So now you just need to plant the seeds into a small pot, six pack, or whatever you wish to grow them in. Then I plant them approximately 1/8” (3mm) deep, and then set outside in the Winter or early Spring, covered by a small plastic dome. Since winter can be rough weather, I secure the dome both twine and duct tape. Once the plants are outside, you just need to wait until the temperatures warm up. If you suspect that it will get very warm, say 70F (18C) or more, then you may want to consider removing the dome that day, or moving the plant into the shade. I must admit that I have had seedlings/seeds get ‘cooked’ by being in direct sunlight but protected by a dome. Now depending on what container you have your seedlings in will determine when you need to transplant your seedlings to larger pots, or wait until you plant out in the ground.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/callirhoe-involucrata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=CAIN2 2) https://muse.jhu.edu/article/168297#:~:text=Seed%20Propagation,-Seeds%20have%20physical&text=Seeds%20are%20added%20to%20boiling,containers%20and%20lightly%20cover... | 1) https://growitbuildit.com/callirhoe-involucrata-how-to-grow/#:~:text=Winecup%20Flowers%20needs%20to%20have,both%20twine%20and%20duct%20tape. 2) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Callirhoe+involucrata#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,the%20main%20clump%5BK%5D."}, {"Plant_ID": "Callirhoe leiocarpa", "Scientific Name": "Callirhoe leiocarpa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Tall Poppymallow", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds in the fall, a few weeks before the first expected frost. This allows the seeds to naturally stratify over the winter. Scatter the seeds evenly over the soil surface. Lightly press them into the soil or cover them with a thin layer of soil (about 1/ inch deep). Water the seeds gently but thoroughly. Keep the soil consistently moist until the seeds germinate. Or sow seeds in the spring, after the last expected frost following the same procedure. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Rub the seeds between coarse sandpaper to remove the outer husk before planting. Sow outdoors in late summer or early fall about 1/8 inch deep. Or simply soak the Callirhoe Leiocarpa seed in water overnight and direct sow 1/4\" below the surface of the soil in Fall or Spring || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Soak the Wine Cup seed in water overnight, then mix the seed with moist sand and store it in the refrigerator for 30 days before planting. After the last frost of spring, sow the treated seed 1/4\" below the surface of the soil.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/callirhoe-leiocarpa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://nativefloraseeds.org/products/wine-cup | 1) https://hort.extension.wisc.edu/articles/winecups-callirhoe-involucrata 2) https://www.everwilde.com/store/Wine-Cup-Wildflower-Seeds.html#:~:text=HOW%20TO%20GROW,Poppymallow%2C%20Palmleaf%20poppymallow%2C%20Cowboy%20Rose"}, {"Plant_ID": "Oenothera berlandieri", "Scientific Name": "Oenothera berlandieri", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Sundrops", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Outdoors: Sow fresh seed directly in the garden in the fall. Tag the location of the seed and monitor through spring to ensure you don’t miss out on the tiny seedlings. Indoors: Prepare a well-draining seed-starting mix. Fill seed trays or small pots with the mix, ensuring there are drainage holes to prevent waterlogging. Scatter the seeds evenly over the soil surface and lightly press them into the soil. Cover them with a thin layer of fine sand or vermiculite. Water gently to moisten the soil without displacing the seeds. Place the seed trays or pots in a warm, bright location. Maintain consistent moisture in the soil but avoid overwatering. Seeds should germinate within 2-4 weeks. Once the seedlings have developed a few true leaves and are sturdy enough to handle, gradually acclimate them to outdoor conditions by hardening off. Transplant them into the garden bed or larger containers, spacing them appropriately. — Collection: Collect mature seeds from berlandier's sundrops by harvesting seed pods once they have turned brown and begun to split open naturally. The seed is small and may be hard to collect. Shake the dry seed pods over a sheet of paper placed directly under the plant in the garden to aid with seed collection. Ensure seeds are fully dry before storing them. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Place cuttings in a lightly moistened potting mix over low bottom heat. Place the plants under a mist system or cover them with a transparent cover and lightly mist them once or twice a day. Don’t allow the soil to dry completely, but ensure it doesn’t stay saturated. — Collection: Take cuttings of new growth in early spring. Remove the bottom leaves of the cuttings", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/calylophus-berlandieri/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Oenothera_berlandieri.html 2) https://www.bhg.com/how-to-plant-and-grow-creeping-sundrops-8385437#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Sundrops,it%20doesn't%20stay%20saturated. | https://www.bhg.com/how-to-plant-and-grow-creeping-sundrops-8385437#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Sundrops,it%20doesn't%20stay%20saturated."}, {"Plant_ID": "Calyptocarpus vialis", "Scientific Name": "Calyptocarpus vialis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Horseherb", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the lower leaves from the cutting, leaving a couple of sets at the top. Water Propagation: Place the cuttings in a jar or glass with water, ensuring the leaf nodes (bumps on the stem where leaves grow) are submerged. Change the water every few days. Roots should appear in 1-2 weeks. Soil Propagation: Plant the cuttings in a well-draining potting mix, burying the bottom leaf node. Keep the soil consistently moist. — Collection: Taking cuttings is arguably the easiest and most efficient way to propagate straggler daisies. Using clean, sharp shears, take 3-4 inch stem cuttings from healthy, non-flowering stems. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: HOW TO EASILY “SEED” AN AREA: Simply find a fast growing, blooming stand of Horseherb and mow it periodically using a lawnmower with a grass catcher attachment. Then thinly spread the Horseherb catchings (clippings) onto the area to be planted. Let the clippings dry for a few days then water or let the next rainfall germinate the very small seed which were collected during mowing. Horseherb will establish itself in stony, shady areas where grass will not grow well. NOTE: Horseherb DOES NOT kill or crowd out grasses; the grass thins or dies and the Horseherb covers the bare spots! — Collection: Though this species may be propagated by seed, it is rarely done because the seeds are difficult to collect in quantity. Seeds are rarely if ever commercially available. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Divide the plant during repotting by separating the root ball into smaller sections and planting them individually", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/calyptocarpus-vialis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-calyptocarpus-vialis/ 2) https://earthone.io/plant/calyptocarpus%20vialis | https://www.plantanswers.com/Articles/HorseherbOrStragglerDaisy.asp#:~:text=Horseherb%20(Calyptecarpus%20vialis)%20is%20not,planted%20all%20over%20the%20area. | https://earthone.io/plant/calyptocarpus%20vialis"}, {"Plant_ID": "Campsis radicans", "Scientific Name": "Campsis radicans", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Trumpet Creeper Vine", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratify 30-60 days at 41-50 degrees — Collection: Gather ripe capsules when they turn brown but before they dry and split open (between 2-3 months after flowering). Remove seeds from pod, air dry,", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/campsis-radicans/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=CARA2"}, {"Plant_ID": "Capsicum annuum", "Scientific Name": "Capsicum annuum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Chile Pequin", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Soak the seeds of capsicum annuum var. conoides in lukewarm water overnight to enhance germination. This softens the seed coat and prompts the germination process. Plant the seeds of capsicum annuum var. conoides in a well-draining seed starting mix, approximately 1/4 inch deep. Cover lightly with soil, and gently water the mix, keeping it evenly moist but not waterlogged. Keep the seed trays in a warm location (about 70-85°F or 21-29°C) with indirect light. Capsicum annuum var. conoides seeds typically germinate in 7-14 days under optimal conditions. Once the seedlings of capsicum annuum var. conoides emerge, provide them with stronger light, such as a sunny window or a grow light. Water them regularly to keep the soil moist, and begin fertilizing with a balanced, diluted fertilizer every two weeks. — Collection: Choose high-quality seeds of capsicum annuum var. conoides, ensuring they are disease-free and harvested from mature fruits. This ensures a better germination rate and healthier seedlings. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow the seeds indoors 6-8 weeks before the last frost date. Keep the soil warm and moist until germination occurs, then transplant the seedlings outdoors or into larger pots.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/capsicum-annuum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Capsicum_annuum_var._conoides.html | https://earthone.io/plant/capsicum%20annuum?srsltid=AfmBOopwiyJ5NopHi3f5dyXvaZ2aWP6vqH3PC9D5ZTMPiXBVq36oP3Xo"}, {"Plant_ID": "Carex blanda", "Scientific Name": "Carex blanda", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Creek Sedge", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Dig Carefully: Using a shovel or garden fork, carefully dig around the perimeter of the Carex blanda clump you wish to divide. Lift the Clump: Gently lift the entire clump out of the ground, ensuring you get as much of the root system as possible. Divide the Clump: Look for natural divisions within the clump and gently pull or tease apart the sections. Aim for divisions with a healthy root system and at least 3-4 shoots. You can also use a sharp, clean knife to separate stubborn clumps. Replant the Divisions: Prepare your planting area with well-draining soil amended with compost. Plant the divisions at the same depth they were growing originally, water them thoroughly, and apply a thin layer of mulch to help retain moisture. Watering: Maintain consistent moisture, especially during the first few weeks after propagation. Avoid overwatering, which can lead to root rot. Sunlight: Place your new plants or divisions in an area with partial to full shade, mimicking their preferred natural environment. — Collection: Early spring, just as new growth emerges, is the prime time for dividing Carex blanda. The plant is energized after winter dormancy, making it more resilient and adaptable to the process. Fall: Dividing in early fall, before the first frost, is also an option. However, it’s crucial to give the divisions ample time to establish themselves before winter sets in. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow them directly outdoors in prepared seedbeds or start them indoors in a well-draining seed-starting mix. Ensure consistent moisture and provide light shade. Germination can be slow and erratic. Watering: Maintain consistent moisture, especially during the first few weeks after propagation. Avoid overwatering, which can lead to root rot. Sunlight: Place your new plants or divisions in an area with partial to full shade, mimicking their preferred natural environment. — Collection: Collect ripe seeds in late summer or fall.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/carex-blanda/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-carex-blanda/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Carex brevior", "Scientific Name": "Carex brevior", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Short-beak Sedge", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct sow either in late fall or early spring. Plant the seed just below the surface of the soil, compacting the soil very firmly. For spring planting, mix the seeds with moist sand and store in the refrigerator for 60 days before planting. Keep the soil lightly moist until germination, since this seed cannot germinate in dry soil. Water seedlings regularly until they become established. Though it will grow in nearly any soil type, this grass prefers dry, sandy, or rocky soil. It eventually spreads by rhizomes. — Collection: At the end of the season, the seed heads will begin to turn from green to brown. Remove them as soon as they ripen to their mature brown color, and spread them out to dry. Thresh them to separate the seed from the stems. Store the seed in a cool, dry place. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: 60 Days Cold Stratification.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/carex-brevior/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.everwilde.com/store/Carex-brevior-Seed.html | 1) https://www.fellabees.com/shop/p/r3fdxulqv6erhczfxbeg066pg9x19t 2) https://www.bluestemnatives.com/product-page/seeds-carex-brevior-shortbeak-sedge"}, {"Plant_ID": "Carex cherokeensis", "Scientific Name": "Carex cherokeensis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Cherokee Sedge", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Seed is planted into round cell greenhouse flat liners with 38 cells per flat that have been filled with coarse processed bark and composted pine bark growing medium. Seed is surface sown at a rate of 3-5 seeds per cell and lightly covered with starter sized, 1/16\" - 1/8\" diameter, granite poultry grit to combat damping off diseases. Prepared flats are lightly hand watered to slightly moisten the growing medium and cold stratified at 35 degrees Fahrenheit for a minimum of 30 days. Stratified seed is placed in a greenhouse maintained under natural lighting and at a minimum temperature of 70 degrees Fahrenheit. Soil moisture is maintained during germination by bottom watering. Flats are placed in shallow trays that permit water levels around the flats to be maintained at approximately a one inch depth. Germination typically occurs 10- 14 days after placement in the greenhouse. After germination,flats are removed from the trays of water and placed on greenhouse benches. Seedlings are maintained in a greenhouse environment 4-6 months to promote development of a plug with at least 6 inches of top growth and a dense, fibrous root system suitable for mechanical transplanting.Watering is reduced to overhead hand watering once daily. Seedlings receive a water soluble complete fertilizer bi-weekly until hardening. Acclimation is typically accomplished through placement of seedlings outdoors in a protected location for a 2-4 week period prior to transplanting.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/carex-cherokeensis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/plantmaterials/wvpmcmt9842.pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Carex crus-corvi", "Scientific Name": "Carex crus-corvi", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Ravensfoot Sedge", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Seeds germinate after a period of cold moist stratification. Mix seeds with an equal amount of moist sand, or vermiculite. Place mixture in a sealed plastic bag. Store in the refrigerator (33-38 degrees Fahrenheit. Stratify for 60 days. Avoid rapid or frequent changes in temperature or humidity and protect against rodents. If sprouting occurs before this plant immediately. Sow seeds shallowly, no deeper than the width of the seed and keep seedlings carefully weeded. Periodic watering is helpful to establish seedlings. Native perennial plants can be slow-growing. An adequate root system with supporting top growth is the first priority. Full flowering happens once a mature plant is established. Outdoor sowing between late fall and early spring is a practical and efficient technique that allows seeds to germinate in their natural timeframe. When outdoor sowing, it is good practice to plant on a weed-free site, clear of vegetation. The requirements for each species vary, but a good rule of thumb is to plant the seed no deeper than the width of the seed. Species with very small seeds should be surface-sown, then firmly pressed to make sufficient contact with the soil. Cover with burlap to keep the area from drying out. If you expect to move the plants once mature, it works best to sow the seed into rows. Mark the rows well and keep weed free and well thinned. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Propagated through division by separating rhizomes with roots. Select vigorous segments for replanting to ensure quick, reliable growth in moist to wetland habitats, promoting overall health and thriving conditions.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/carex-crus-corvi/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.prairiemoon.com/PDF/Germination-Codes-and-Seed-Starting-Basics-Brochure.pdf 2) https://www.prairiemoon.com/carex-crus-corvi-crowfoot-fox-sedge#panel-planting | https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Carex_crus-corvi.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Carex emoryi", "Scientific Name": "Carex emoryi", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Emory Sedge", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump | Seed | Stem | Rhizome", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Replant the divisions immediately to minimize stress on the plants. Trim any damaged or long roots to encourage quicker establishment. Ensure each division has a healthy portion of roots and shoots. Prepare planting holes in a suitable location with well-drained, moist soil. Place each division into its hole, ensuring the crown is at soil level, and backfill with soil. Water the divisions thoroughly after planting to settle the soil around the roots. Maintain consistent moisture but avoid waterlogging. The newly separated clumps will grow into individual, full-sized plants within a growing season. — Collection: Emory's sedge can be optimally propagated in spring and autumn through division. Avoid extreme summer heat or winter cold to ensure successful propagation. Begin by carefully digging up the mature plant. Use a garden fork or spade to avoid damaging the root system. Separation Gently shake off excess soil from the roots. Locate natural divisions or offsets in the clump and use a sharp, clean knife or spade to separate these sections. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow them in spring, ensuring the soil remains moist to encourage germination. Germination typically takes between 14 to 30 days under optimal conditions. Keep an eye on moisture levels, as consistent watering is crucial for successful sprouting. The seedling stage lasts about 4-6 weeks. During this time, the young plants establish their roots and begin to grow. — Collection: Collect mature seeds in late summer or early fall. Harvest the seeds once the spikes have fully matured and turned brown. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Plant the stem in a moist potting mix, ensuring that the lower nodes are buried in the mix. Cover the pot with clear plastic to maintain humidity and place in a warm, bright location. Water the new plant regularly and remove the plastic once it has rooted and is producing new growth. — Collection: Identify mature, healthy stems that have not yet blossomed. Cut a small section of stem that includes a few leaves and roots. || Rhizome — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Plant the cuttings in a tray or pot filled with a soil mix. Keep the soil mix moist and place the container in a shaded area. Once the new plants have established a strong root system, they can be transplanted into individual pots or directly into the ground. — Collection: Cut the rhizomes in sections measuring about 2 to 3 inches long.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/carex-emoryi/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1 ) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Carex_emoryi.html 2) https://greg.app/emorys-sedge-overview/ 3) https://www.botanikks.com/plants/carex-emoryi-dewey/539285/1 | 1) https://greg.app/emorys-sedge-overview/ 2) https://www.botanikks.com/plants/carex-emoryi-dewey/539285/1 | https://plantiary.com/plant/carex-emoryi_4682.html | https://www.botanikks.com/plants/carex-emoryi-dewey/539285/1"}, {"Plant_ID": "Carex leavenworthii", "Scientific Name": "Carex leavenworthii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Leavenworth's Sedge", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Spring is the ideal time for sowing Leavenworth's Sedge seeds, specifically after the last frost. Under optimal conditions, expect germination to take between 14 to 30 days. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: To maintain healthy growth, divide clumps every 2 to 3 years, ideally in early spring or fall. This involves carefully separating the clumps and replanting them to encourage robust development. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: For cutting propagation, select healthy stems that are 4 to 6 inches long. Use a well-draining potting mix as the rooting medium to ensure successful growth.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/carex-leavenworthii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://greg.app/leavenworths-sedge-overview/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Rosa carolina", "Scientific Name": "Rosa carolina", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Carolina Rose", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Do not allow the seeds to dry out. Remove seeds from pulpy hip. Seeds require stratification, 3 months at 40 degrees. — Collection: Collect seeds as soon as the hips have turned red in the late summer or early fall.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/carolina-rose/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ROCA4"}, {"Plant_ID": "Carya illinoinensis", "Scientific Name": "Carya illinoinensis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Pecan", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Softwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Seeds are best sown in a cold frame as soon as they are ripe. Pecan seeds show delayed germination and require a period of cold stratification. Seeds should be stratified at 36-41º F for thirty to sixty days and then followed by incubation at room temperature. The seedlings should be transplanted when they are large enough to handle and planted in deep pots to accommodate the taproot. Put the plants in their permanent positions as soon as possible, preferable during the first summer, and give them some protection from the cold for the first winter. Pecan requires a frost-free period of 6 to 9 months for nuts to be produced and mature. The trees require 1 to 2 inches of rain per week during the growing season. || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the severed end of the cutting in 1 percent IBA (indolebutyric acid) rooting talc or rooting hormone. Flick the stem to knock loose the excess talc. Insert the pecan cutting to half its length into the moistened perlite. Shake the pot gently to settle the perlite against the stem. Drizzle water around the cutting to further settle it. Place the pecan cutting outdoors where it will receive light shade and shelter from the wind. Choose a spot with no midday sun or western sun. This kind of sunlight will desiccate the cutting. One of the keys is if you had a misting sprinkler that was on a timer to come on twice during the day. Preferably not allowing the water droplets to stay on the leaves overnight. A light mist over the pecan cutting with a spray bottle twice a day will prevent drying out. Moisten the perlite whenever you mist the cutting, so it never fully dries out. If you close this area in a mini-greenhouse keep in mind that the pecan cutting will be susceptible to a variety of diseases. Roots of your cutting should appear in 6 to 8 weeks by lightly tugging on the stem and feeling for resistance. Fill a 5-inch peat pot with perlite or vermiculite. Pour water into the pot until the perlite is saturated and the sides of the pot feel moist. Transplant the rooted pecan cutting into a 1-gallon container filled with garden soil. A south-facing wall will be the best location to place your new plant to protect your plant from the winter winds. Water your pecan cutting only if the weather is dry for longer than two weeks. Transplant your 1-year-old plant into your garden in the spring. — Collection: Take cuttings in late spring or early summer when the tree is no longer dormant. Gather a 6-inch-long tip cutting from a healthy side branch. Select one with a pliant, ¼-inch-thick stem and plenty of foliage. Avoid branches with blossoms. Sever the cutting 1/16-inch below a mature leaf using bypass shears or utility knife or grafting knife. Before making the cut, dip the blade in rubbing alcohol, which stops diseases. Make the cut slightly angled to expose a larger portion of the inner flesh. Pull off all the leaves along the lower half of the cutting.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/carya-illinoinensis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/plantguide/pdf/pg_cail2.pdf 2) https://hort.ifas.ufl.edu/database/lppi/sp070.shtml#:~:text=Time%20of%20year%20to%20graft,and%20stored%20at%2035%20F. 3) https://hort.ifas.ufl.edu/database/lppi/sp070.shtml | 1) https://hort.ifas.ufl.edu/database/lppi/sp070.shtml#:~:text=Time%20of%20year%20to%20graft,and%20stored%20at%2035%20F. 2) https://www.times-gazette.com/story/lifestyle/2019/04/29/a-stroll-through-garden-starting/5316186007/ 3) https://hort.ifas.ufl.edu/database/lppi/sp070.shtml"}, {"Plant_ID": "Castilleja indivisa", "Scientific Name": "Castilleja indivisa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Indian Paintbrush", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow the seeds in the fall or early spring directly into the soil. Ensure the seeds are lightly covered with soil and keep the area moist until germination. Plant in well-drained soils in full sun. Surface sow or 1/8\". Gently raking them in will provide even better results. If possible, gently water them in after sowing and continue to keep them damp until they are established. — Collection: Seeds can be collected in midsummer for early spring flowering species and in late summer for mid-elevation species. High elevation species are collected during fall.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/castilleja-indivisa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.texasbluebonnetseeds.com/paintbrush.htm 2) https://earthone.io/plant/castilleja%20indivisa 3) https://muse.jhu.edu/pub/3/article/181532/pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Castilleja purpurea", "Scientific Name": "Castilleja purpurea", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Prairie Paintbrush", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow fresh seeds in well-drained soil, ensuring they receive sufficient light for germination. Maintain consistent moisture without waterlogging. Once seedlings are large enough, carefully transplant them to their final location to minimize root disturbance. — Collection: Collect seeds from downy indian paintbrush immediately after the seed capsules mature and begin to open. Use gloves to handle plants, as they can sometimes irritate the skin. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Place the collected seeds in a sealed plastic bag with moistened sand or vermiculite to stratify in a refrigerator. Stratify for approximately 60-90 days to simulate winter conditions, which helps to break seed dormancy. Remove the seeds from stratification. Prepare a well-draining soil mix in a container with ample organic matter. Ensure the container has good drainage holes. Sow the stratified seeds on the soil surface, as downy indian paintbrush seeds need light to germinate. Gently press them into the surface without covering them with soil. Mist lightly to keep the seeds moist without washing them away. Germination and Early Care Place the container in a location with partial sunlight and maintain consistent moisture, but avoid waterlogging. Germination should occur in about 2-3 weeks under optimal conditions. Indian Paintbrush? After germination, allow downy indian paintbrush seedlings to grow sufficiently until they are large enough to handle. Transplant them carefully to a more permanent location with similar soil and light conditions. Downy indian paintbrush prefers well-drained soils and can tolerate partial shade to full sunlight. Regular watering is crucial during dry periods, but care should be taken not to overwater, to avoid root rot. Gradually acclimate the plants to outdoor conditions by increasing their exposure to direct sunlight and varying temperatures. — Collection: Collect seeds from downy indian paintbrush immediately after the seed capsules mature and begin to open. Use gloves to handle plants, as they can sometimes irritate the skin.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/castilleja-purpurea/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Castilleja_purpurea.html | https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Castilleja_purpurea.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Ceanothus herbaceus", "Scientific Name": "Ceanothus herbaceus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Redroot", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Seed propagation is best done in the fall. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Cuttings can be taken in the spring or early summer. Ensure the cuttings are kept in a humid environment until they root.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ceanothus-herbaceus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://earthone.io/plant/ceanothus%20herbaceus"}, {"Plant_ID": "Carex planostachys", "Scientific Name": "Carex planostachys", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Cedar Sedge", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Best results were achieved by fall-sowing directly in the soil. — Collection: Seed heads can be clipped or easily hand-stripped when seed is mature, brown, and starting to shatter in late May / early June. Remaining seeds can be spread out to air dry out of direct sunlight.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/cedar-sedge/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/plantmaterials/orpmcmt9962.pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Celtis pallida", "Scientific Name": "Celtis pallida", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Spiny Hackberry", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Seedling", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Best sown as soon as it is ripe in a cold frame. Stored seed is best given 2 - 3 months cold stratification and then sown February/March in a greenhouse. Germination rates are usually good, though the stored seed might take 12 months or more to germinate. The seed can be stored for up to 5 years. As soon as they are large enough to handle, prick the seedlings out into individual pots. The leaves of seedlings often have a lot of white patches without chlorophyll, this is normal and older plants produce normal green leaves. Grow the seedlings on in a cold frame for their first winter, and plant them out in the following late spring or early summer. Give them some protection from the cold for their first winter outdoors. || Seedling — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Seeds that will be planted soon (1-3 days) after collection may be planted with the fruit (pulp) intact, with favorable germination. Scarification is also recommended for increasing germination of spiny hackberry. Germination as high as 62% has been obtained using a combination of mechanical scarification, gibberellic acid, and heat/chill treatments. — Collection: The seeds of spiny hackberry should be cleaned from the fruit after collection if planting will be delayed. Care should be taken when drying cleaned seeds, as this species is especially susceptible to molding.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/celtis-ehrenbergiana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Celtis+pallida#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,Cuttings 2) https://apps.cals.arizona.edu/arboretum/taxon.aspx?id=1065 | https://www.ckwri.tamuk.edu/plant/granjeno"}, {"Plant_ID": "Celtis laevigata", "Scientific Name": "Celtis laevigata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Hackberry", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratify 60-90 days at 41 degrees. Plant seeds ½ inch deep in a moist, loose, and well-drained bed.6 It is beneficial to mulch the seedbed with straw and leaves. If planted directly in the fall, establishment is between 3-5 months. If stratified seeds are planted in the spring or summer, establishment is about 12 weeks. — Collection: Pick mature fruits in late summer until winter. Air-dry with pulp on or soak overnight and rub pulp off on screen. The seeds can be depulped by wet maceration. Depulping is not essential, but it has been reported to aid germination (1). Average germinative capacity is reported to be 55 percent for sugarberry. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Sugarberry can be propagated by cuttings (7). Small stumps sprout readily, and there is some sprouting from root collars of fire-damaged seedlings and saplings.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/celtis-laevigata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=CELA 2) https://www.srs.fs.usda.gov/pubs/misc/ag_654/volume_2/celtis/laevigata.htm#:~:text=Seeds%20should%20be%20stratified%20in,fire%2Ddamaged%20seedlings%20and%20saplings. 3) chrome-extension://efaidnbmnnnibpcajpcglclefindmkaj/ https://courses.washington.edu/esrm412/protocols/2011/CELA.pdf | https://www.srs.fs.usda.gov/pubs/misc/ag_654/volume_2/celtis/laevigata.htm#:~:text=Seeds%20should%20be%20stratified%20in,fire%2Ddamaged%20seedlings%20and%20saplings."}, {"Plant_ID": "Celtis reticulata", "Scientific Name": "Celtis reticulata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Netleaf Hackberry", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Softwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Following pulp removal, all hackberry species should be cold-stratified at 5°C in a moist media to break dormancy. Stratification for 90-120 days is effective. Sow seed in a seedbed or open frame in autumn. — Collection: Berries are collected by hand in September-December. If it is early in the season and fruits are still moist, spread the berries to prevent mold. If it is later in the season, no additional drying is necessary. Pulp removal is recommended to increase germination rates. To remove flesh from berries for storage or planting, wash under running water in a semi-fine sieve to remove pulp. Let seed dry completely. || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove lower leaves and dip the cut end in rooting hormone. Plant cuttings in a well-draining soil mix and keep them consistently moist. Roots should develop within 6 to 8 weeks, after which the cuttings can be transplanted into larger containers or outdoor beds. — Collection: Can be propagated by softwood cuttings taken in early summer. Take 6-inch cuttings from young, vigorous shoots.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/celtis-reticulata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://rngr.net/npn/propagation/protocols/celtis-ehrenbergiana-celtis#:~:text=Foothills%20and%20mesas%201%2C500%2D3%2C000,winnowing%20to%20remove%20berry%20debris. 2) https://harvesttotable.com/how-to-grow-celtis-hackberry/#:~:text=Where%20to%20plant%20Celtis%20%E2%80%93%20Hackberry%20*,soil.%20Celtis%20will%20grow%20in%20alkaline%20soil. 3) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/celtis-occidentalis#:~:text=Propagation%20by%20Cuttings,and%20keep%20them%20consistently%20moist. | https://www.gardenia.net/plant/celtis-occidentalis#:~:text=Propagation%20by%20Cuttings,and%20keep%20them%20consistently%20moist."}, {"Plant_ID": "Plectocephalus americanus", "Scientific Name": "Plectocephalus americanus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "American Basketflower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Choose a location that receives full sun and has well-drained soil. Avoid areas prone to waterlogging, as American basket-flower does not tolerate waterlogged conditions. No special treatment is required for the seeds, however, ensuring that the they are fresh can enhance germination rates. Sow the seeds directly into the prepared site. Lightly cover them with a thin layer of soil—no more than 1/4 inch deep. After sowing, gently water the area, ensuring the soil is moist but not waterlogged. Continue to provide water whenever the top inch of soil becomes dry. Once seedlings are visible and a few inches tall, thin them to about 12 to 18 inches apart. This spacing allows ample room for growth and air circulation, which is crucial for healthy development. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end into rooting hormone to encourage root growth. Plant your cuttings in a pot filled with rooting medium (a mixture of perlite and peat moss works well). Water regularly and keep the cuttings in a warm, humid environment. — Collection: The best time to take cuttings is in the late spring or early summer. Select healthy, non-flowering stems with new growth. Cuttings should be about 4-6 inches long with several nodes (points where leaves grow). Using sharp, clean pruning shears, remove leaves from the bottom half of the cutting.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/centaurea-americana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Plectocephalus_americanus.html 2) https://www.rareseeds.com/blog/post/how-to-grow-basketflower-seeds?srsltid=AfmBOorAcfkS1E03MiEt8HYkZdnLEZY8a57Mr6Q_nZtzfF3U7Q5M6IrG | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-plectocephalus-americanus/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Centrosema virginianum", "Scientific Name": "Centrosema virginianum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Spurred Butterfly Pea", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Scarify seeds: pre-soak for 12 hours in warm water and sow in a greenhouse in the spring. Prick out the seedlings into individual pots once they are large enough to handle and plant out in the summer. Ensure a warm, humid environment for germination, provide moderate light, and maintain moisture. Transplant seedlings when sturdy, placing them in supportive locations. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Ensure that cuttings have at least a few nodes and are placed in a moist, well-draining medium. — Collection: Cuttings can be taken during the growing season.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/centrosema-virginianum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://practicalplants.org/wiki/centrosema_virginianum/#:~:text=Propagation,plant%20out%20in%20the%20summer. 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Centrosema_virginianum.html | https://earthone.io/zh/plant/centrosema%20virginianum"}, {"Plant_ID": "Cephalanthus occidentalis", "Scientific Name": "Cephalanthus occidentalis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Buttonbush", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Buttonbush can be started from seeds sown outdoors in fall, immediately after the round brown seed pods are collected from plants. Successful seedlings will appear in late spring once temperatures are warm enough. — Collection: Collections of seed can be made as soon as the fruiting heads turn reddish-brown, usually in October. Light pressure on the fruit will break them into separate seeds. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end into rooting hormone and shake off any excess. Root the cuttings directly in moist ground where you want the plants to grow. Or fill a small pot with moist soil and poke a hole into the soil with your finger. Slide the cutting into the hole and firmly press the soil around the cutting. Place the cutting in an area with bright, indirect lighting and keep the soil moist. Roots should develop in a couple of weeks. Once roots form and new growth appears, you can transplant the cutting to its permanent location. Once the potted seedlings are at least a year old, transfer them to the garden, spaced about 3 feet apart. — Collection: In spring, soon after new growth appears, select a stem that is around 4 to 6 inches long. It should have a node and some leaves on it. Using a sharp, clean knife, cut the stem below a node. Remove any lower leaves, keeping only the upper leaves.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/cephalanthus-occidentalis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.growveg.com/plants/us-and-canada/how-to-grow-buttonbush/#:~:text=Buttonbush%20can%20be%20started%20from,want%20the%20plants%20to%20grow. | 1) https://www.thespruce.com/buttonbush-growing-guide-5323850#:~:text=Propagating%20Buttonbush,a%20purchased%20packet%20of%20seeds. 2) https://www.growveg.com/plants/us-and-canada/how-to-grow-buttonbush/#:~:text=Buttonbush%20can%20be%20started%20from,want%20the%20plants%20to%20grow. 3) https://www.thespruce.com/buttonbush-growing-guide-5323850#:~:text=Propagating%20Buttonbush,a%20purchased%20packet%20of%20seeds."}, {"Plant_ID": "Ceratophyllum demersum", "Scientific Name": "Ceratophyllum demersum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Coontail", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: No special treatment is needed—simply float the cuttings in water, and they will continue growing. — Collection: Extremely easy to propagate by taking cuttings from the stem or simply breaking off a segment of the very brittle stem. Stem fragments with lateral buds also develop into new plants throughout the season.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ceratophyllum-demersum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://en.aqua-fish.net/plants/ceratophyllum-demersum# 2) https://dnr.maryland.gov/waters/bay/documents/sav/coontail.pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Cercis canadensis var. canadensis", "Scientific Name": "Cercis canadensis var. canadensis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Eastern Redbud", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Hardwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Eastern Redbud seeds are tough nuts to crack. Scarification helps; soak them in hot water for 24 hours to soften the shell. Follow up with stratification at 3-5°C for 5-8 weeks to mimic winter and kickstart germination. Spring is your starting gun for sowing Eastern Redbud seeds. This season offers a full stretch of growing time, ensuring your seedlings can bulk up before winter. — Collection: Timing is crucial when collecting Eastern Redbud seeds. Aim for late summer when pods darken, extending possibly into November. Local seeds are your best bet for hardiness. Once collected, dry them thoroughly and store in a cool place. || Hardwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Rooting hormone gives cuttings a growth edge. Dip the nodes for 5-7 seconds, then plant with good drainage. Patience is key; expect to transplant your rooted redbuds by next fall. Gradually introduce your cuttings to more direct sunlight. Transplant when they're sturdy enough to handle the real world. A snug pot with room to grow and well-draining soil will make for a happy redbud. — Collection: Choose healthy branches with several nodes. A node is where growth will sprout. Robust cuttings are your friends. Early spring is also the sweet spot for taking hardwood cuttings. This timing allows cuttings to establish roots throughout the growing season, setting the stage for strong development.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/cercis-canadensis-var-canadensis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://greg.app/propagate-eastern-redbud/ 2) https://www.wildflower.org/expert/show.php?id=4357&frontpage=true | https://greg.app/propagate-eastern-redbud/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Cercis canadensis var. texensis", "Scientific Name": "Cercis canadensis var. texensis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Redbud", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the lower leaves from the cuttings, leaving two or three at the top. Optionally, dip the cut end of the cutting in a rooting hormone powder to encourage root development and protect against fungal infections. Fill a pot with a sterile, well-draining potting mix, such as a mix of peat and perlite. Make holes in the potting medium with a stick or your finger, then insert the bottom end of the cuttings into the holes. Gently firm the soil around the cuttings to provide support and eliminate air pockets. Cover the pot with a clear plastic bag or place it in a humidity dome to maintain high humidity around the cuttings. Ensure the plastic does not touch the leaves by supporting it with sticks or a frame. Place the setup in indirect light. Keep the soil moist but not waterlogged. In about 4-6 weeks, check for root growth by gently tugging on the cuttings. Once the roots are established, gradually acclimate the young plants to normal conditions before transplanting them into larger pots or permanent locations outdoors. — Collection: Choose healthy, non-flowering stems from the current year's growth of texas redbud. The cuttings should be about 4-6 inches in length with several leaf nodes. Use a clean, sharp pruning shear to make the cuts just below a node. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Grow in deep, fertile, moist but well-drained soil in full sun or dappled shade.Propagate by sowing seed in containers in a cold frame in autumn. — Collection: Harvest pods as soon as they begin to dry to reduce insect damage.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/cercis-canadensis-var-texensis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Cercis_canadensis_var._texensis.html | 1) https://www.rhs.org.uk/plants/309065/cercis-canadensis-var-texensis-texas-white/details 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=CECAT"}, {"Plant_ID": "Cercocarpus montanus", "Scientific Name": "Cercocarpus montanus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Mountain Mahogany", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Some sources recommend scarification for 10-20 minutes in concentrated sulfuric acid followed by 5-10 minutes || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Deplumed seeds should be soaked in water for thirty minutes before sowing. Stratification may then be necessary for 30 days at 41 degrees.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/cercocarpus-montanus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=CEMO2"}, {"Plant_ID": "Chamaecrista fasciculata", "Scientific Name": "Chamaecrista fasciculata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Partridge Pea", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Root | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Plant them in the fall. They need to overwinter in the ground. Though they germinate in late spring. — Collection: Collect seeds when they mature in August. Once the flower has faded, watch for the pods to ripen and turn brown. These pods contain the seeds. Carefully collect the pods before they dry and shatter, ensuring you don’t lose precious seeds. Air dry for one week in cloth bags. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Partridge Pea have a hard seed coat that needs scarification. This process mimics the natural breakdown of the seed coat in nature and allows water and oxygen to penetrate. While there are several methods for scarification, you can simply use sandpaper to gently abrade the seed coat. Alternatively, you can soak the seeds in water for 24 hours before planting. Partrige Pea seeds are best sown directly in the ground. Choose a sunny location with well-drained soil as this plant thrives in warm, sunny conditions. You can sow the seeds indoors, but it’s best to transplant them outdoors after the last frost. Plant the seeds about 1/4 inch deep and 6 inches apart. Water thoroughly and keep the soil moist until germination occurs, which usually takes 10-14 days. Thin seedlings as needed to ensure proper spacing. Once your seedlings have established, regular watering is essential, especially during dry periods. However, ensure that the soil doesn’t become waterlogged, which can lead to root rot. — Collection: Collect seeds when they mature in August. Once the flower has faded, watch for the pods to ripen and turn brown. These pods contain the seeds. Carefully collect the pods before they dry and shatter, ensuring you don’t lose precious seeds. Air dry for one week in cloth bags. || Root — Treatment: Division — Method: Plant in the ground immediately and water ( moist, but not soggy). — Collection: A sharp knife or spade is your scalpel. Look for multiple shoots and a healthy root system; these are non-negotiables for each division. Gently tease apart the root ball, or go in with a clean cut. Late spring or early summer is your window for this operation, ensuring a smooth transition during transplanting. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Plant in moist, but not soggy soil. — Collection: Early summer is prime time for taking cuttings, just before the heat turns up. Snip a healthy stem, dip it in rooting hormone if you're feeling extra, and plant it like it's the last one on Earth.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/chamaecrista-fasciculata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://seedsource.com/partridge-pea/ 2) https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=fabaceae-chamaecrista-1297 3) https://nativefloraseeds.org/products/partridge-pea | 1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-chamaecrista-fasciculata/ 2) https://nativefloraseeds.org/products/partridge-pea 3) https://greg.app/propagate-partridge-pea/#:~:text=Harvesting%20Partridge%20Pea%20seeds%20at,to%20fall%20is%20your%20window. | https://greg.app/propagate-partridge-pea/#:~:text=Harvesting%20Partridge%20Pea%20seeds%20at,to%20fall%20is%20your%20window."}, {"Plant_ID": "Chaptalia texana", "Scientific Name": "Chaptalia texana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Silverpuff", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully separate the offsets from the parent plant and replant them in suitable soil. — Collection: Propagate in the spring. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Take cuttings from healthy, non-flowering shoots, planted in well-draining soil. Consistent moisture and rooting hormone enhance success, while careful root handling during transplanting promotes robust growth.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/chaptalia-texana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://earthone.io/plant/chaptalia%20texana?srsltid=AfmBOooq630Q_hxUbdpDd17Tmjw6CI57wIUHdtL4IjJ_mnJsbJFKyskH | https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Chaptalia_texana.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Chasmanthium latifolium", "Scientific Name": "Chasmanthium latifolium", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Inland Sea Oats", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Indoors: Plant seed 0.64 cm (1/4 inch) deep in pots. Keep moist but not soggy and very warm (21 C - 70 F). When seedlings are 5 cm (2 in.) tall, transplant into the garden spaced 30 cm (1 ft.) apart. Outdoors: Sow seed 0.64 cm (1/4 inch) deep outdoors in either late fall or early spring. — Collection: Collect seed in fall. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Best germination can be achieved with a short period of cold, moist stratification. Sow outdoors by March or stratify with moist sand/potting soil in the refrigerator for 2 to 4 weeks. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Moisten soil. Gently remove clumps. Tease apart roots and divide into smaller clumps. Replant in new location immediately. Kee moist but not soggy until they appear to be well established. — Collection: Best to do in the spring while it is cool to put less stress on plants and allow roots to develop before dormancy in the winter.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/chasmanthium-latifolium/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://wwhttps://www.wildflowerfarm.com/chasmanthium-latifolium-northern-sea-oats.html#:~:text=Plant%20seed%200.64%20cm%20(1,30%20cm%20(1%20ft.) | https://mowildflowers.net/chasmanthium-latifolium--river-oats-/#:~:text=Seed:%20Best%20germination%20can%20be,for%202%20to%204%20weeks. | Claire Sorenson, NPSOT member observation."}, {"Plant_ID": "Cheilanthes alabamensis", "Scientific Name": "Cheilanthes alabamensis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Alabama Lipfern", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Rhizome | Spores", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Rhizome — Treatment: Division — Method: Gently separate clumps of the fern and replant them in new locations, ensuring each division has roots and fronds. — Collection: The best time to divide your ferns is in spring or early fall when the plant is actively growing. || Spores — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Scatter the collected spores on a moist, sterile medium and cover them lightly to encourage germination. Reaching maturity takes approximately 1-2 years, depending on various factors like light and moisture. The growth rate is moderate, which means patience is key as you nurture your fern. — Collection: Harvest spores from mature fronds when they are ready, usually indicated by a change in color.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/cheilanthes-alabamensis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://greg.app/alabama-lip-fern-overview/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Chilopsis linearis", "Scientific Name": "Chilopsis linearis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Desert Willow", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Softwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Best if direct sown fresh into well-drained soil. Planting the seeds too deep is detrimental because desert willow seeds need light to germinate. Seeds will germinate in one to three weeks but only expect about 40% of the seeds to be viable. Seeds germinate at temperatures between 70°F and 80°F within a 1- to 2-week period. Transplant your seedlings to a larger pot once seedlings produce two sets of leaves and are four inches tall. This pot should be big enough to allow space to grow. Place outside for a month to harden up and allow to acclimate to the outdoors. You can then plant or keep in the container to allow to grow for the first year to plant the following year. — Collection: Gather seeds from late summer through autumn, when the pods have dried and turned brown, but before they split open to release feathery seeds. Spread out the pods for drying, beat them lightly, and shake seeds free of the pods. Store seed in a cool, dry place until planting. || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: The use of rooting hormones enhances the probability of successful propagation. Maintain a slight dampness in the soil rather than letting it become waterlogged. Root development takes 4 to 6 weeks. The process of transplantation happens when roots develop properly. Propagation reaches optimal results during warm summer periods. Correct sun exposure combined with adequate ventilation results in better survival results. Young plants acquire maximum benefits from periodic deep water applications. The procedure protects biological variety and establishes robust plant development. Plants grown from spring cuttings will produce a well-rooted five-gallon plant in one year. — Collection: Start with softwood cuttings that measure 6 to 8 inches in length.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/chilopsis-linearis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://legacylandscaper.com/desert-willow-chilopsis-linearis/#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Desert%20Willow,and%20establishes%20robust%20plant%20development. 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=CHLI2 3) https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/plantguide/pdf/pg_chli2.pdf 4) https://johndenson.com/desert-willow-chilopsis-linearis/#:~:text=Growing%20Desert%20Willows%20from%20Seed,the%20Southwest%20by%20Jill%20Nokes. 5) https://www.thespruce.com/desert-willow-growing-guide-5210875#:~:text=Propagating%20desert%20willow%20by%20seed%20is%20the%20preferred%20and%20easiest,to%20plant%20the%20following%20year. | 1) https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/plantguide/pdf/pg_chli2.pdf 2) https://legacylandscaper.com/desert-willow-chilopsis-linearis/#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Desert%20Willow,and%20establishes%20robust%20plant%20development. 3) https://johndenson.com/desert-willow-chilopsis-linearis/#:~:text=Growing%20Desert%20Willows%20from%20Seed,the%20Southwest%20by%20Jill%20Nokes. 4) https://www.thespruce.com/desert-willow-growing-guide-5210875#:~:text=Propagating%20desert%20willow%20by%20seed%20is%20the%20preferred%20and%20easiest,to%20plant%20the%20following%20year."}, {"Plant_ID": "Chrysactinia mexicana", "Scientific Name": "Chrysactinia mexicana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Damianita", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow directly in the ground in spring. — Collection: Collect the dry flower heads after the blooming period.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/chrysactinia-mexicana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=CHME3"}, {"Plant_ID": "Cirsium texanum", "Scientific Name": "Cirsium texanum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Thistle", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Root", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: For seed propagation, sow the seeds in well-draining soil and keep them moist until germination. || Root — Treatment: Division — Method: For root division, carefully separate the roots and replant them in suitable soil.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/cirsium-texanum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://earthone.io/plant/cirsium%20texanum 2) https://seedsource.com/texas-thistle/ | https://earthone.io/plant/cirsium%20texanum"}, {"Plant_ID": "Cissus trifoliata", "Scientific Name": "Cissus trifoliata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Sorrelvine", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Collection: Take cuttings in spring or summer.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/cissus-trifoliata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Cissus_trifoliata.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Clematis crispa", "Scientific Name": "Clematis crispa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Swamp Leatherflower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: A 60-180 day period of cold-moist stratification at 33-40 degrees aids in the germination of stored seeds. Sow in spring", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/clematis-crispa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=CLCR"}, {"Plant_ID": "Clematis drummondii", "Scientific Name": "Clematis drummondii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Virgin's Bower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: To stratify, place seeds in a moist media 1-5°C for 60-180 days. — Collection: Seeds can be collected when fruits are brown and soft white plume-like styles are effortlessly removed from the plant with seeds attached. Pinch seed plumes with your fingers to collect them. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Clematis drummondii propagation by seed is relatively simple. Soak in water 24 hours before sowing and sow after last frost. — Collection: Seeds can be collected when fruits are brown and soft white plume-like styles are effortlessly removed from the plant with seeds attached. Pinch seed plumes with your fingers to collect them. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Propagate by cuttings which will root from nodes with less success.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/clematis-drummondii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=clematis-drummondii-clematis 2) https://www.borderlandsplants.org/product-page/old-man-s-beard-seed-clematis-drummondii | https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=CLDR"}, {"Plant_ID": "Clematis pitcheri", "Scientific Name": "Clematis pitcheri", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Purple Leatherflower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Moist stratify at 41 degrees for 60-90 days. Can take a long time to germinate. — Collection: Gather seeds when they are no longer green but before the cluster of achenes completely dries and drops the seeds to the ground.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/clematis-pitcheri/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=CLPI"}, {"Plant_ID": "Clematis texensis", "Scientific Name": "Clematis texensis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Scarlet Leatherflower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Soak the seeds of scarlet leather flower in lukewarm water for 24 hours prior to sowing. This hydration helps break the seed's dormancy and encourages germination. Sow seeds immediately in well-drained soil, providing a structure for scarlet leather flower to climb, or in pots with a well-draining soil mix such as a mixture of potting soil, perlite, and peat moss. Ensure the containers have adequate drainage holes. Sow the seeds on the surface of the soil and press them gently into the soil but do not cover them completely, as they require light to germinate. Mist lightly to keep the soil moist. — Collection: For best results, collect seeds once pods have ripened, ensuring careful handling as they're delicate || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Moist stratify at 41 degrees for 60-90 days before planting in spring. — Collection: Gather seeds when they are no longer green but before the cluster of achenes completely dries and drops the seeds to the ground. They remain viable up to two years without refrigeration. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the leaves from the bottom half of the stem and dip the cut end in rooting hormone. Place the cutting in a pot filled with well-draining soil or a mix of perlite and peat. Keep the soil moist but not waterlogged and place the pot in a shaded area with indirect sunlight. Mist the cutting daily with water to prevent it from drying out and cover the pot with plastic wrap to create a humid environment. After 3-4 weeks, check for roots by gently tugging the stem. Once roots have formed, transplant the cutting into a larger pot or directly into the ground. — Collection: Take a cutting of a mature stem in the early summer, making sure it has at least two nodes and the stem is about 6 inches in length. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: For water propagation, avoid using transparent containers. Place the stem in water, and once roots appear, add hydroponic fertilizer. When roots are 5-7 cm long, transfer to soil. For soil propagation, plant deeply in soil without fertilizer. After propagation, avoid exposing to bright light. Gradually increase light exposure to help the plant adapt to gentle light. Maintain high humidity and a temperature of 18-25°C. || Stem — Treatment: Layering — Method: Stem layering is mentioned, but there are no details available at this time. We will add more information as it becomes available.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/clematis-texensis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Clematis_texensis.html | https://gonzalesmastergardeners.org/uploads/7/2/5/4/72540621/clematis_texensis.pdf | https://plantiary.com/plant/clematis-texensis_6341.html | https://plantingo.com/plant-care-guide/clematis-texensis-buckley/3579"}, {"Plant_ID": "Cocculus carolinus", "Scientific Name": "Cocculus carolinus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Carolina Snailseed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the lower leaves, leaving only the top set. Dip the cut end in rooting hormone (optional) and plant the cuttings in a pot filled with a well-draining mix of perlite and peat moss. Keep the soil consistently moist and cover the pot with a plastic bag to create humidity. After several weeks, once roots have developed, carefully transplant the cuttings into individual pots or directly into the ground. — Collection: The optimal time for taking cuttings is late spring or early summer when the vine is actively growing. Select healthy stems about 4-6 inches long that have at least two sets of leaves and cut just below a leaf node. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Seeds benefit from cold stratification, mimicking their natural winter dormancy. Place the seeds in a moist paper towel inside a sealed plastic bag and refrigerate for 6-8 weeks. Propagation can be easily done by seed planted after the last expected frost. Seeds may also be sown indoors in spring, after the last frost, in seed trays or small pots filled with well-draining potting mix. Place them about 1/4 inch deep and keep the soil consistently moist. Once seedlings develop a few sets of true leaves, they can be transplanted outdoors in a sunny or partially shaded location with well-drained soil. The plant will not usually produce fruit for the first few years after planting. — Collection: Seeds are produced on the female plant. The \"moonseeds\" ripen in the fall, turning a beautiful deep purple. Collect berries and extract the seeds, ensuring to remove any pulp.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/cocculus-carolinus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-cocculus-carolinus/ | 1) https://worldplants.ca/display.php?id=9677# 2) https://plants.ces.ncsu.edu/plants/cocculus-carolinus/ 3) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-cocculus-carolinus/ 4) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-cocculus-carolinus/ 5) https://www.gardeningknowhow.com/ornamental/vines/moonseed-vine/growing-carolina-moonseed-for-birds.htm"}, {"Plant_ID": "Colubrina texensis", "Scientific Name": "Colubrina texensis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Hog Plum", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Semi-harwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratification at 41 degrees for 30-40 days. — Collection: Gather fruit as it turns black-brown, but before it splits apart. If the pulp is still fleshy, it should be removed or allowed to dry on the seed. Fruit collected later in the season is usually dry enough to store intact with the seed. || Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end in rooting hormone powder or gel to stimulate root development. Insert the treated cuttings into a well-draining propagation medium, such as a mix of perlite and peat moss. Ensure the nodes are buried but keep the leaves above the surface. Place the cuttings in a warm, humid environment with indirect light. Maintain a humidity level of around 80% using a plastic cover or misting system to prevent the cuttings from drying out. Water the cuttings regularly to keep the soil moist but not waterlogged. After roots have developed in 6-8 weeks, gradually acclimate the cuttings to outdoor conditions before transplanting them into the garden or larger pots. — Collection: Gather healthy, disease-free semi-hardwood cuttings from about 4-6 inches long. Ensure each cutting has at least 2-3 nodes and remove the leaves from the lower half. Make a clean cut just below a node.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/colubrina-texensis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=COTE6 | https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Colubrina_texensis.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Commelina erecta", "Scientific Name": "Commelina erecta", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Dayflower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Start seeds indoors 6-8 weeks before the last expected frost. Sow them lightly in a seed-starting mix and keep them consistently moist. A warm, sunny windowsill is ideal for germination, which usually takes 2-3 weeks. Once the seedlings are sturdy and all danger of frost has passed, transplant them outdoors in a well-drained location. — Collection: Collect seeds from mature flowers in late summer or early fall. You’ll recognize them as small, brown capsules. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: While not mandatory, dipping the cut end in rooting hormone can encourage faster root development. Plant the cuttings in a well-draining potting mix and keep the soil consistently moist. Keep in a location with bright, indirect sunlight. Roots usually develop in a few weeks. Once you see new growth, you can transplant your rooted cuttings outdoors. — Collection: Take stem cuttings about 4-6 inches long from healthy, non-flowering stems in spring or summer. Strip off the lower leaves, leaving a few at the top.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/commelina-erecta/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-commelina-erecta/ 2) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/commelina-erecta#:~:text=Virtually%20pest%20and%20disease%20free,Americas%2C%20Africa%20and%20western%20Asia. | 1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-commelina-erecta/ 2) https://sharonsflorida.com/plants-page/native-wildflowers/whitemouth-dayflower/#:~:text=Propagation,watered%20until%20it%20is%20established."}, {"Plant_ID": "Commelina virginica", "Scientific Name": "Commelina virginica", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Virginia Dayflower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seed March in a greenhouse. The seed usually germinates in 4 - 5 weeks at 20°c[164]. When they are large enough to handle, prick the seedlings out into individual pots plant them out in late spring or early summer, after the last expected frosts. Or seeds can be sown directly into the substrate where they are to grow. The soil ought to be kept consistently moist after sowing to encourage germination. It is important to distribute the seeds evenly to avoid overcrowding, which may hinder development. Seedlings typically emerge without the need for any special treatment, ready to add their bright blue blossoms to your garden’s palette. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Prepare the Plant: Water the dayflower thoroughly a few hours before division. Gentle Excavation: Carefully dig up the clump, ensuring you get a good portion of the root system. Divide and Conquer: Using your hands or a sharp, clean knife, separate the plant into smaller sections. Ensure each section has a healthy root system and several stems. Replant and Rejoice: Replant the divisions at the same depth they were previously growing, water thoroughly and watch them thrive. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Choose Wisely: Select healthy, non-flowering stems in spring or early summer. Make the Cut: Cut a 4-6 inch piece of stem just below a leaf node. Prepare the Cutting: Remove the leaves from the bottom inch of the stem. Root Hormone (Optional): Dipping the cut end in rooting hormone can encourage faster root development. Potting Time: Plant the cutting in a moist, well-draining potting mix. Humidity Boost: Cover the pot with a plastic bag or humidity dome to create a warm, moist environment. Be Patient: It may take several weeks for roots to develop. Once rooted, you can transplant them to a larger pot or outdoors. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Requires 30 days cold moist stratification, sow in early spring Difficult; sporadic germination, better germination results when planted directly into garden soil; may take two years to germinate/", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/commelina-virginica/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Commelina+virginica#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,Very%20easy%5B200%5D. 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Commelina_virginica.html#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Virginia%20dayflower?&text=Virginia%20dayflower%20is%20a%20vibrant,blossoms%20to%20your%20garden's%20palette. | 1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-commelina-virginica/ 2) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Commelina+virginica#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,Very%20easy%5B200%5D. | https://www.hungryhookfarm.com/product/seeds-commelina-virginica/285"}, {"Plant_ID": "Condalia hookeri", "Scientific Name": "Condalia hookeri", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Bluewood Condalia", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Semi-harwood | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove all leaves from the bottom two nodes and dip the cut ends into rooting hormone. Plant the cuttings in a well-draining rooting mix and maintain consistently moist soil. — Collection: Take 4-6 inch cuttings from semi-hardwood stems in late summer or early fall. The ideal cutting should have at least three nodes (places where leaves or branches grow) and a healthy green tip. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Scarify the seeds (lightly scratch the outer surface with a knife) to help with germination. Sow the seeds in a seed tray filled with well-draining soil, ensuring consistent moisture and warm temperatures. Provide a humid environment by covering your cuttings with a plastic dome or using a propagator. You can also mist the cuttings regularly. Avoid direct sunlight during the initial stages of propagation, especially for cuttings. A bright, indirect light environment is ideal. Keep the soil consistently moist but not soggy. Avoid letting the soil dry out completely, as this can hinder rooting. — Collection: Collect ripe seeds from mature plants and store them in a cool, dry place until the following spring.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/condalia-hookeri/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-condalia-hookeri/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Conoclinium coelestinum", "Scientific Name": "Conoclinium coelestinum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Blue Mistflower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Give them at least three weeks in 35°F (2°C). Then sow them on clean, moist soil and press seeds into the soil surface so they have good soil contact, but don’t bury them. Keep the seeds warm and lightly moist until they germinate in approximately one to two weeks. Alternatively, sow them outdoors in fall in areas with substantial winters. If sowing the seeds indoors, transplant the seedlings to a protected outdoor location once the weather has warmed and continue to keep them moist. When the seedlings are several inches tall, transplant them to their permanent location. Seeds started in early spring are capable of blooming by the fall of their first year. If they don’t have enough time to bloom in their first year, they will certainly bloom in their second year of growth. — Collection: Seeds can be allowed to dry out before sowing. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove any leaves from the lower third to half of the stem, leaving a few pairs of healthy leaves at the top. Place the cutting into a cup of water so the bare stem (not the leaves) is submerged. Most of your stem cuttings should form roots within a few weeks, and these successful cuttings can then be transplanted into pots or permanent in-ground locations. — Collection: Take a four to six-inch cutting from a fresh, healthy stem. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Examine the clump for natural divisions, using your fingers or a sharp knife to separate the blue mistflower into smaller sections. Each section should have a good amount of roots and some top groLook over the roots of each division, trimming away any that are damaged or dead. Aim to create a compact, healthy root system that will establish quickly when replanted. wth. Plant each division at the same depth it was growing at originally, spacing them appropriately for the expected size at maturity. Fill in around the roots with soil amended with compost, and firm the soil gently to remove air pockets. Water the new divisions thoroughly to settle the soil and ensure that there are no air gaps around the roots. The water also provides necessary hydration to help the roots recover and grow. Over the next few weeks, monitor the blue mistflower closely for signs of water stress or sun scorch, adjusting your care routine as necessary to encourage healthy growth. — Collection: Carefully dig around the perimeter of the blue mistflower's clump, ensuring you are deep enough to avoid cutting through the root system. Gently lift the entire clump out of the ground. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Seeds germinate readily without pretreatment and fill plug trays within a few weeks. Seedlings grown in communal flats or multiple seedlings per plug can easily be barerooted for transplanting. — Collection: Collect seeds when fruit tissue turns dark brown to grey and is dry; avoid collecting when fruits moist and do not dislodge easily from plant to ensure seed maturity. Seeds germinate readily without pretreatment and fill plug trays within a few weeks. Seedlings grown in communal flats or multiple seedlings per plug can easily be barerooted for transplanting.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/conoclinium-coelestinum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.epicgardening.com/blue-mistflower/ 2) https://www.joyfulbutterfly.com/product/blue-mistflower-seeds-conoclinium-coelestinum/#:~:text=How%20to%20Start%20Blue%20Mistflower,a%20mature%20plant%20to%20propagate. | https://www.epicgardening.com/blue-mistflower/ | https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Conoclinium_coelestinum.html#:~:text=A%20sharp%20knife%20or%20pruning,Rooting%20hormone | https://longleafpine.fnpschapters.org/data/uploads/propagation-manual-for-fl-panhandle-native-plants/conoclinum-coelestinum.pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Coreopsis basalis", "Scientific Name": "Coreopsis basalis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Golden Tickseed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/coreopsis-basalis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://seedsource.com/golden-wave/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Coreopsis grandiflora", "Scientific Name": "Coreopsis grandiflora", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Common Coreopsis", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump | Seed | Stem | Root", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Lay the plant on its side and carefully tease apart the root ball. Identify healthy sections with leaves, stems, and roots. Use a sharp, clean tool to cut the plant into smaller sections, each with a robust root system. Handle the roots gently to avoid damage. Make a hole in a sunny spot, matching the depth and width of the root ball. Plant each division at the same depth it was previously growing. Water well to settle the soil and keep the soil consistently moist as they establish. — Collection: Look for plants that are crowded or have multiple offsets. Water the plant a day before to reduce transplant shock. Gently remove the plant from the ground, ensuring you preserve the root system. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow in spring or autumn, directly in the garden or under cover. in well-drained loosened soil. Cover the seeds with a very thin layer of soil—no more than 0.5 cm. Keep the soil consistently moist until germination, which typically takes 2 to 3 weeks. Once seedlings emerge, before planting, ensure they receive plenty of sunlight and water them regularly. Thin the seedlings to about 15 cm apart to give them room to grow. — Collection: Wait for the flower heads to dry on the plant. Gently shake or rub the heads to release the seeds. Store the seeds in a paper envelope in a cool, dry place until you're ready to sow them. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end into rooting hormone to boost root growth. Plant the cutting in well-draining soil, burying at least one node to foster root emergence. Keep the soil consistently moist, but be wary of overwatering which can lead to rot. Provide bright, indirect light and maintain a warm environment to encourage rooting. — Collection: Select stems that are vigorous and disease-free, with several sets of leaves, but non-flowering. Use sterilized shears to make a clean, angled cut just below a leaf node. Remove the lower leaves to expose additional nodes, which can increase rooting potential. || Root — Treatment: Cutting — Method: To plant the cuttings,dip the cut ends in rooting hormone to boost growth potential. Plant the cuttings in a well-draining soil mix, positioning them vertically with the straight cut (top) end slightly above the soil surface. Water the soil to a consistent moisture level, not too soggy or too dry. Place the pots in a warm area with indirect light. Keep an eye on moisture levels; roots need to stay hydrated but not waterlogged. Patience is key—roots can take several weeks to develop. Once you feel resistance when gently tugging on the cutting, it's a sign that roots are forming. — Collection: Look for roots that are about as thick as a pencil and exhibit a healthy vigor. Use clean, sharp tools to cut sections, aiming for lengths between 3 to 4 inches. Make a straight cut near the crown and an angled cut at the other end to remember which way is up. Clean the roots gently but thoroughly to remove soil and debris. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: If planting seeds in the Spring or Summer, the seeds need 2-4 weeks of cold/wet stratification. It will be 10-15 days with Sunlight and 60-80 day to maturity.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/coreopsis-grandiflora/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://greg.app/propagate-coreopsis-grandiflora/ | 1) https://greg.app/propagate-coreopsis-grandiflora/ 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-coreopsis-grandiflora/ | https://whitwamorganics.com/products/large-flowered-tickseed-coreopsis-grandiflora#:~:text=Coreopsis%20needs%20regular%20watering%20throughout,weeks%20of%20cold/wet%20stratification."}, {"Plant_ID": "Coreopsis lanceolata", "Scientific Name": "Coreopsis lanceolata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Lanceleaf Coreopsis", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Bud | Seed | Softwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: Division should be used on plants that are a couple of years old. Divide the basal rosettes. Carefully dig up the entire plant, leaving the roots as intact as possible. With a sharp trowel or a garden knife, cut the clump into smaller sections. Discard the woody center of the plant. Each of the remaining sections should have several healthy roots. Replant the sections in a sunny location with excellent drainage, at the same depth as the original plant. Keep the new plants well-watered until they are established and show new growth. — Collection: Best done in winter or early spring. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sown in Spring. Seeds of this species benefit from light and KNO3 enrichment for germination. — Collection: Nutlets are mature and ready for collection about four weeks after the flowers wither. Watch the inner series of bracts; when they begin to darken, it is time to collect. Remove chaff and store || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Take softwood cuttings of the basal rosette. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: The seeds require 30 days of cold stratification to break their dormancy. This can be done in two ways. In late winter, sow the seeds outdoors in containers or an outdoor weed-free seedbed. Or you can place the seeds in a sealed plastic bag with a damp paper towel and store them in a refrigerator at 33 to 40 degrees Fahrenheit for 1 month before planting them in garden soil or in pots. Plant the seeds about 1/8 inch deep just below the soil surface; they need light to germinate. When the seedlings are 2 inches tall, you can transplant them into the garden after all danger of frost has passed.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/coreopsis-lanceolata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=COLA5 2) https://www.thespruce.com/coreopsis-lanceolata-7255292#:~:text=After%20two%20to%20three%20years,established%20and%20show%20new%20growth. 3) https://edis.ifas.ufl.edu/publication/EP058 | 1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=COLA5 2) https://www.fnps.org/assets/pdf/pubs/coreopsis_lanceolata_lanceleaftickseed_3_0.pdf 3) https://edis.ifas.ufl.edu/publication/EP058 | https://www.fnps.org/assets/pdf/pubs/coreopsis_lanceolata_lanceleaftickseed_3_0.pdf | 1) https://www.thespruce.com/coreopsis-lanceolata-7255292#:~:text=After%20two%20to%20three%20years,established%20and%20show%20new%20growth. 2) https://brightlanegardens.com/native-plants/plant-glossary/native-perennials/lanceleaf-coreopsis-coreopsis-lanceolata/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Coreopsis tinctoria", "Scientific Name": "Coreopsis tinctoria", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Plains Coreopsis", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sown in the fall. Seeds need light to germinate. Seeds germinate within 21 to 28 days, so water them regularly. — Collection: Seed heads form at the site of a dead or dying flower. If the seed head is already dry, pluck it and crush it between your fingers to harvest the seed, which you can plant the following spring. If the seed head has not dried, cut about 6 inches of the stem it is on and hang it upside down in a warm, dry place until it dries. Then, crush it to harvest the seed. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: With a garden trowel, divide the plant into several sections, each with its own roots, being careful not to damage the roots. Plant each division in the garden immediately and water well. — Collection: Use a spade to lift an entire perennial coreopsis plant and root ball from the ground. Choose a mature plant that is at least two years old. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove all the leaves except for those at the top of the cutting. Dip each cutting into rooting hormone and insert it into a pot of vermiculite or perlite until only the top leaves are showing. Moisten the planting medium, and place the pot in a bright, warm place. Check for roots in two or three weeks by gently tugging a leaf. After the cuttings develop a healthy root system, they can be planted in the garden. — Collection: Cut a 4- to 6-inch piece of stem beneath a node at a 45°F angle.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/coreopsis-tinctoria/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.bhg.com/gardening/plant-dictionary/perennial/coreopsis/#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Coreopsis,seed%2C%20cuttings%2C%20or%20division. 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=COTI3 3) https://www.ugaoo.com/blogs/gardening-basics/how-to-grow-coreopsis-plant | https://www.bhg.com/gardening/plant-dictionary/perennial/coreopsis/#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Coreopsis,seed%2C%20cuttings%2C%20or%20division."}, {"Plant_ID": "Cornus drummondii", "Scientific Name": "Cornus drummondii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Roughleaf Dogwood", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Semi-harwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Roughleaf Dogwood seeds require a period of cold stratification to mimic natural winter conditions and break their dormancy. Place the seeds in a moistened paper towel inside a sealed plastic bag, and store them in the refrigerator for 60-90 days. After stratification, sow the seeds in a seed-starting mix, pressing them gently into the soil. Keep the soil consistently moist and place the seed tray in a bright location, out of direct sunlight. Germination can take several weeks to a few months. Once the seedlings are large enough to handle, transplant them into individual pots or directly into your garden. — Collection: Collect ripe fruits (drupes) in the fall. The fruits will be small, white, and clustered together. Gently crush the fruits and separate the seeds. Clean any remaining fruit pulp from the seeds. || Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end of the stem in rooting hormone powder to encourage faster root development. Fill a small pot with a well-draining potting mix. Create a small hole in the center and gently insert the cutting. Water thoroughly. Cover the pot with a clear plastic bag or use a propagation dome to maintain humidity and warmth. This will help create a greenhouse-like environment for the cutting. Place the pot in a bright location, but out of direct sunlight. Check the moisture regularly and mist the cutting to maintain humidity. Within a few weeks, you should start to see new growth, a sign that roots are developing. Once the cutting shows significant root development (usually within 6-8 weeks), you can transplant it into a larger pot or directly into your garden. — Collection: The best time for taking cuttings is late spring or early summer when the plant is actively growing. Select a healthy stem that’s around 4-6 inches long and free from any damage or disease. Look for a stem with new growth, as this indicates active hormones that will aid in root development. Using sharp, sterilized pruning shears, make a cut just below a leaf node (the point where a leaf emerges from the stem). Remove the leaves from the bottom third of the cutting.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/cornus-drummondii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=CODR 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-cornus-drummondii/ | 1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-cornus-drummondii/ 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Cornus_drummondii.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Corydalis curvisiliqua", "Scientific Name": "Corydalis curvisiliqua", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Curvepod", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: The seeds will germinate after a short dormancy period; they can be planted during the fall or early spring. — Collection: Collect seeds from mature Corydalis curvisiliqua plants in late spring. Ensure the seeds are fully ripe and dry before storage. This step is vital to ensure high germination rates and avoid fungal growth. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Each cutting should be 4-6 inches long, with at least two nodes, to ensure successful propagation. — Collection: Take cuttings from healthy growth, ideally during early spring, when the plant is actively growing. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Use a sharp spade to separate the tubers, ensuring each section has roots and shoots. This method rejuvenates older plants and encourages vigorous growth. — Collection: Divide mature Corydalis curvisiliqua clumps in early spring.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/corydalis-curvisiliqua/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.illinoiswildflowers.info/prairie/plantx/lb_corydalis.htm 2) https://seedsource.com/scrambled-eggs/ 3) https://www.forwardplant.com/plant-info/corydalis-curvisiliqua/ | https://www.forwardplant.com/plant-info/corydalis-curvisiliqua/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Cotinus obovatus", "Scientific Name": "Cotinus obovatus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "American Smoketree", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Semi-harwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow direct in soil in the spring. May take two springs to sprout. — Collection: To collect seeds before wind dispersion, clip the entire fruiting panicle from the tree in late April. Collect enough to compensate for a high percentage of infertile seed. Air-dry before storing or planting. When dried, fuzzy panicle are easily detached. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Scarify in a 20-40 minute concentrated sulfuric acid treatment. Or soak them for 12 hours, change the water, then soak them for another 12 hours. After that, allow the seeds to dry in the open air. After all danger of frost is over, plant the seeds in well-drained, sandy soil in a sunny spot in the garden. Press each seed 3/8 inch (1 cm.) into the soil, a good distance apart. Irrigate gently and keep the soil moist. Be patient. Propagating a smoke tree by seed can take up to two years before you see growth. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Moist stratification for 150 days. Follow with 60-80 days of stratification at 38-41 degrees. || Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the lower leaves, then strip off a little bark on the bottom end of the cutting and dip the wound in root hormone. Prepare a pot with a good draining growing medium. Place stakes in the corners of your pot then cover it with a plastic bag. Keep the medium moist. When they start rooting, transfer them to a larger pot. — Collection: Taken in spring after flowering. The wood should not be the new growth. It should snap cleanly when you bend it. Take cuttings about the length of your palm during summer. Take them early in the day when the plant is full of water.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/cotinus-obovatus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=COOB2 | 1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=COOB2 2) https://www.gardeningknowhow.com/ornamental/trees/smoke-tree/smoke-tree-propagation-methods.htm"}, {"Plant_ID": "Crataegus crus-galli", "Scientific Name": "Crataegus crus-galli", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Cockspur Hawthorn", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Softwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: It should be warm stratified for 3 months at 15°c and then cold stratified for another 3 months at 4°c. It may still take another 18 months to germinate. It is best to pot up the seedlings as soon as they are large enough to handle and grow them in individual pots for their first year, planting them out in late spring into nursery beds or their final positions. When growing larger quantities, it might be best to sow them directly outdoors in a seedbed, but with protection from mice and other seed-eating creatures. Grow them in the seedbed until large enough to plant out, but undercut the roots if they are to be left undisturbed for more than two years. || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Ensure that cuttings and seedlings of cockspur hawthorn receive sufficient light, as inadequate light can weaken plants and decrease the chances of successful propagation. Applying bottom heat to cuttings can promote quicker root development, which is critical for the successful propagation of cockspur hawthorn. Employ a well-draining rooting medium to maintain proper moisture levels and prevent rot in cuttings of cockspur hawthorn. — Collection: Can be taken in early summer. Choose a disease-free, vigorous parent plant for obtaining cuttings or to ensure the best start for propagation. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Scarify the seed before stratifying it might reduce this time. Fermenting the seed for a few days in its own pulp may also speed up the germination process. It is best to pot up the seedlings as soon as they are large enough to handle and grow them in individual pots for their first year, planting them out in late spring into nursery beds or their final positions. When growing larger quantities, it might be best to sow them directly outdoors in a seedbed, but with protection from mice and other seed-eating creatures. Grow them in the seedbed until large enough to plant out, but undercut the roots if they are to be left undisturbed for more than two years. — Collection: Another possibility is to harvest the seed 'green' (as soon as the embryo has fully developed but before the seedcoat hardens. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow it immediately in a cold frame. If timed well, it can germinate in the spring. If you are only growing small quantities of plants. It is best to pot up the seedlings as soon as they are large enough to handle and grow them in individual pots for their first year, planting them out in late spring into nursery beds or their final positions. When growing larger quantities, it might be best to sow them directly outdoors in a seedbed, but with protection from mice and other seed-eating creatures. Grow them in the seedbed until large enough to plant out, but undercut the roots if they are to be left undisturbed for more than two years.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/crataegus-crus-galli/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Crataegus+crus-galli#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation&text=Stored%20seed%20can%20be%20very,for%20more%20than%20two%20years. 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Crataegus_crus-galli.html | 1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Crataegus_crus-galli.html 2) https://earthone.io/plant/crataegus%20crus-galli"}, {"Plant_ID": "Crataegus viridis", "Scientific Name": "Crataegus viridis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Green Hawthorn", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Semi-harwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Strip the leaves from the lower half of each cutting while leaving a few leaves at the top for photosynthesis. Before planting, dip the cut end in a rooting hormone powder to promote root development and protect against fungus. Fill pots or trays with a moistened mix of 50% peat and 50% perlite to ensure good drainage. Insert the cuttings into the medium up to their halfway point, firming the soil around them to eliminate air pockets. Cover the potted cuttings with a plastic bag or place them in a humidity dome to maintain a humid atmosphere around them. This helps prevent moisture loss during the rooting process. Position the pots in indirect sunlight and keep the soil consistently moist but not wet. Rooting can take several weeks; after which, begin checking for root development by gently tugging on the cuttings. If there's resistance, roots have likely formed. — Collection: Cut 4-6 inch sections from the current season's growth using clean, sharp pruning shears. The lower cut should be just below a node, and the upper cut just above a node.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/crataegus-viridis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Crataegus_viridis.html 2) https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=rosaceae-crataegus-1220"}, {"Plant_ID": "Croton capitatus", "Scientific Name": "Croton capitatus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Goatweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Can be propagated by seeds. Sow the seeds in well-draining soil in a sunny location. The best time to propagate is in the spring when temperatures are moderate. Keep the soil slightly moist until the seeds germinate.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/croton-capitatus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://earthone.io/plant/croton%20capitatus?srsltid=AfmBOooneGgcx48X7zvpGgkqmX_UaEUn6KAkdFwnCW8wj0oUhLfV6a7i"}, {"Plant_ID": "Croton fruticulosus", "Scientific Name": "Croton fruticulosus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Bush Croton", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed | Semi-harwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Make the Cut: Use clean, sharp scissors to cut just below a leaf node. Prepare the Cutting: Remove the lower leaves, leaving only a couple at the top. Rooting Hormone (Optional): Dip the cut end in rooting hormone to encourage faster root growth. Plant the Cutting: Place the cutting in a well-draining potting mix, burying it about an inch deep. Water and Cover: Water the cutting lightly and cover it with a plastic bag or a clear container to maintain humidity. Wait for Roots: Keep the cutting in bright, indirect light and check for roots in about 4-6 weeks. — Collection: Choose a healthy stem from the parent plant that is at least 4-6 inches long. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Soil Preparation: Use a well-draining potting mix in a seed tray or small pots. Sowing Seeds: Scatter the seeds on the surface and lightly press them into the soil. Watering: Mist the soil gently to moisten it without over-saturating. Light and Temperature: Place the tray in a warm area with bright, indirect light. Germination Time: Expect germination to occur within 2-4 weeks, depending on conditions. — Collection: Obtain fresh seeds from a reliable source. || Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Essential for taking clean, precise cuttings from bush croton. Sharp shears minimize damage to mother plant tissues and cutting stems, promoting quick healing and reducing the risk of infection. Important for encouraging root development on cuttings of bush croton. Rooting hormones can increase the success rate of cuttings by stimulating root growth, essential for the propagation process. Facilitate the organization and protection of cuttings during the rooting phase. Trays with cell inserts help maintain optimal spacing and proper drainage, preventing rot and promoting healthy root development in bush croton. Crucial for maintaining high humidity levels around bush croton cuttings. This tool helps prevent dehydration and allows the cuttings to focus energy on root production rather than water uptake. Used to maintain consistent moisture levels around bush croton cuttings without over-saturating the growing medium. Misting ensures proper hydration, which is crucial for successful root initiation. — Collection: Collect spring or summer.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/croton-fruticulosus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://greg.app/bush-croton-overview/#:~:text=Propagating%20with%20Cuttings,in%20about%204%2D6%20weeks. | https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Croton_fruticulosus.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Cucurbita foetidissima", "Scientific Name": "Cucurbita foetidissima", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Buffalo Gourd", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed | Bud", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Method: It has developed a highly efficient method of asexual propagation by producing roots along its vines when they are in contact with moist sand or soil, principally during periods of summer rains. Make your cut with a sterilized tool just below a node, where the leaf bids adieu to the stem. Rooting hormones are not essential but highly recommended. They give your cuttings a head start in the rooting race. After dipping the cut end into this magic powder, plant your cutting in a well-draining soil mix. Keep the soil moist, but not soggy. Cover with a plastic dome or bag for that tropical humidity, but let it breathe—cuttings appreciate a little fresh air too. — Collection: Selecting the right stem cuttings for propagation is like picking the best players for your team. Opt for stems that scream health: vibrant leaves, no signs of pests or diseases,. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Germination temperature range is between 15 °C and 37 °C with an optimum at 25 °C. The maximum depth for a successful germination is 12 cm. The germination is possible in a pH range from 2.2 (germination rate 15%) up to pH 8 (germination rate 90%). sow early to mid spring in a greenhouse in a rich soil. Germination should take place within 2 weeks. Sow 2 or 3 seeds per pot and thin out to the best plant. Grow them on fast and plant out after the last expected frosts, giving them cloche or frame protection for at least their first few weeks if you are trying them outdoors. — Collection: Selecting the right seeds is crucial for successful Buffalo Gourd propagation. Opt for seeds that are plump, shiny, and free from imperfections, as these traits often indicate good health and viability. It's like picking the best athletes for your team; you want the ones that show promise of great performance. || Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: With a clean, sharp tool, divide the plant into sections. Ensure each has a fair share of roots and shoots. Plant each division in a well-prepped hole, mixing in some organic matter to give the soil a little pep. Keep the depth consistent with their previous growing conditions to avoid any growth stunts. Water the root balls generously before they settle into their new homes. Place them in bright, indirect light and keep the soil moist but not soggy. — Collection: First, hydrate your plant thoroughly to make the roots more flexible. Gently unearth the plant, keeping the root ball intact.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/cucurbita-foetidissima/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://cucurbit.info/1978/07/the-versatility-of-the-feral-buffalo-gourd-cucurbita-foetidissima-hbk/#:~:text=It%20has%20developed%20a%20highly,permalink. | 1) https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cucurbita_foetidissima#:~:text=Germination%20temperature%20range%20is%20between,2.5%20m%20(8.2%20ft). 2) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Cucurbita+foetidissima#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,you%20are%20trying%20them%20outdoors. 3) https://seedsource.com/buffalo-gourd/ 4) https://greg.app/propagate-buffalo-gourd/ | https://greg.app/propagate-buffalo-gourd/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Cylindropuntia imbricata", "Scientific Name": "Cylindropuntia imbricata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Cholla", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: From woody stem cuttingsFrom softwood cuttingsAllow cut surface to callous over before planting || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct sow after last frost. — Collection: Unblemished fruit must be significantly overripe before harvesting seed; clean and dry seeds. Properly cleaned, seed can be successfully stored.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/cylindropuntia-imbricata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://davesgarden.com/guides/pf/go/66650"}, {"Plant_ID": "Cylindropuntia leptocaulis", "Scientific Name": "Cylindropuntia leptocaulis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Christmas Cactus", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds in early spring in a well-drained compost. Grow them on in the greenhouse for at least their first two winters. Plant out into permanent positions in late spring or early summer", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/cylindropuntia-leptocaulis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://temperate.theferns.info/plant/Cylindropuntia+leptocaulis#:~:text=Seed%20%2D%20sow%20early%20spring%20in,Very%20easy%2C%20rooting%20quickly."}, {"Plant_ID": "Cynanchum laeve", "Scientific Name": "Cynanchum laeve", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Honeyvine", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end of the stem in rooting hormone powder. Plant the stem cutting in a well-draining potting mix. Water the cutting thoroughly and place it in a bright location but out of direct sunlight. Cover the pot with a plastic bag or a clear plastic container to create a humid environment. Keep the soil moist but not waterlogged. After a few weeks, the plant should start producing new growth, which indicates that it has rooted. Once the root system is well-established, remove the plastic cover and care for the plant as usual. — Collection: Choose a healthy stem from the plant and cut a section that is 3-4 inches long. Remove the leaves from the bottom half of the stem. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Since Honeyvine Milkweed seeds have a hard outer coat, they benefit from a period of cold stratification. This can be achieved by placing the seeds in a damp paper towel in a plastic bag and refrigerating them for several weeks. After stratification, provide consistent moisture and warmth by covering the area with a thin layer of mulch. Gently scatter seeds on a well-prepared soil in the desired location. Press the seeds lightly into the soil, ensuring good soil-to-seed contact. Germination may occur over several weeks to months. As the seeds sprout, nurture the seedlings by keeping the soil evenly moist and offering protection from extreme weather.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/cynanchum-laeve/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://plantiary.com/plant/cynanchum-laeve_1225.html | https://plantflowerseeds.com/products/cynanchum-laeve-honeyvine-sandvine-climbing-milkweed-10-seeds#:~:text=Only%2048%20items%20in%20stock,or%20I%20cancel%2C%20if%20permitted.&text=Cynanchum%20laeve%2C%20or%20Honeyvine%20Milkweed,the%20intricate%20balance%20of%20nature."}, {"Plant_ID": "Cynanchum racemosum", "Scientific Name": "Cynanchum racemosum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Talayote", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Talayote can be propagated via stem cuttings placed in well-draining soil. Keep cuttings moist but avoid overwatering. Using rooting hormone aids success. After rooting, provide moderate watering and sufficient sunlight. Careful transplanting is essential, along with regular monitoring for pests and diseases.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/cynanchum-racemosum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Cynanchum_racemosum.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Dalea aurea", "Scientific Name": "Dalea aurea", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Golden Dalea", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Sow in early spring in a greenhouse. The seed has a hard seedcoat and benefits from scarification before sowing in order to speed up and improve germination. This can usually be done by pouring a small amount of nearly boiling water on the seeds (being careful not to cook them!) and then soaking them for 12 - 24 hours in warm water. By this time they should have imbibed moisture and swollen - if they have not, then carefully make a nick in the seedcoat (being careful not to damage the embryo) and soak for a further 12 hours before sowing. When they are large enough to handle, prick the seedlings out into individual pots and plant them out into their permanent positions in the summer. — Collection: Allow pods to dry on plant; break open to collect seeds || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut base of the cutting into a rooting hormone powder to promote root development and reduce the risk of disease. Fill a small pot with a well-draining propagation mix (e.g., a mixture of perlite and peat moss). Make a hole in the medium with a pencil or similar tool, and insert the cutting. Firm the soil gently around the cutting to ensure good contact. Water the cutting thoroughly but avoid waterlogging the soil. Maintain a humid environment by covering the pot with a plastic bag or placing it in a propagation dome. Ensure the bag or dome has ventilation holes to prevent fungal growth. Place the pot in a warm location with indirect light. Monitor the moisture level and humidity, ensuring the soil remains moist but not overly wet. In 4-6 weeks, check for root development by gently tugging the cutting. Once roots have established, transplant the cutting to its final location with well-draining soil. Golden prairie clover thrives in full sun to partial shade and requires moderate watering until it is well-established. Afterward, it is relatively drought-tolerant. Regularly check for pests and diseases, and provide minimal fertilization, as golden prairie clover generally prefers nutrient-poor soils. — Collection: Select healthy, semi-hardwood cuttings from the parent plant, preferably around 4-6 inches long. Ensure the cutting includes at least a couple of nodes, and remove the leaves from the lower half, leaving a few at the top.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/dalea-aurea/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://temperate.theferns.info/plant/Dalea+aurea#:~:text=Propagation,/plant/Dalea+aurea%3E 2) https://davesgarden.com/guides/pf/go/68331 | https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Dalea_aurea.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Dalea candida", "Scientific Name": "Dalea candida", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "White Prairie Clover", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Pre-soak for 12 hours in warm water to soften hulls. Sow in early spring in a greenhouse approx 1/16 inch deep. at a temperature of 65-70 degrees Fahrenheit. Keep seeds moist until germination. Seeds will germinate in 14-30 days. When they are large enough to handle, prick the seedlings out into individual pots and plant them out into their permanent positions in the summer.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/dalea-candida/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Dalea+candida+oligophylla#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,in%20the%20summer%5B200%5D. 2) https://www.outsidepride.com/seed/clover-seed/white-prairie-clover-seed.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Dalea compacta", "Scientific Name": "Dalea compacta", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Compact Prairie Clover", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Sow in early spring in a greenhouse. The seed has a hard seedcoat and benefits from scarification before sowing in order to speed up and improve germination. This can usually be done by pouring a small amount of nearly boiling water on the seeds (being careful not to cook them!) and then soaking them for 12 - 24 hours in warm water. By this time they should have imbibed moisture and swollen - if they have not, then carefully make a nick in the seedcoat (being careful not to damage the embryo) and soak for a further 12 hours before sowing. When they are large enough to handle, prick the seedlings out into individual pots and plant them out into their permanent positions in the summer[ || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end of the stem into rooting hormone powder and plant the cutting in a container filled with well-draining soil mix. Water the cutting and place it in a warm, bright location with filtered sunlight to encourage rooting. Keep the soil moist but not waterlogged, and mist the cutting regularly to maintain humidity. After a few weeks, check for signs of new growth, which indicate the cutting has rooted. Once the roots have developed fully, transplant the new plant into a larger pot or into a garden bed. — Collection: Select healthy stem cuttings that are around 6 inches long and have at least two leaves. Remove any leaves that are closer to the bottom of the cutting, leaving only the topmost two leaves.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/dalea-compacta/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://temperate.theferns.info/plant/Dalea+compacta#:~:text=Propagation,/plant/Dalea+compacta%3E 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Dalea_compacta.html#:~:text=Care%20Guide%20for%20Compact%20prairie%20clover&text=It%20thrives%20with%20deep%2C%20infrequent,for%20optimal%20growth%20and%20establishment. | https://plantiary.com/plant/dalea-compacta_19380.html#:~:text=Propagation:%20You%20can%20propagate%20Dalea%20Compacta%20through,the%20seeds%20directly%20in%20the%20garden%20or"}, {"Plant_ID": "Dalea formosa", "Scientific Name": "Dalea formosa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Feather Dalea", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Semi-harwood | Softwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Seeds should be sown in well-draining soil and kept in a warm, sunny location. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Cuttings can be taken in the spring or early summer and rooted in sandy soil. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Seeds benefit from soaking in warm water for 12-24 hours to soften the seed coat. If they have not swollen, try pricking with a needle, careful to not damage the embryo. Sow in a well drained mix, and keep slightly moist until seedlings appear. || Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Cuttings taken in late spring or early summer may root under mist with bottom heat. This process can be tricky. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: In the fall, sow your seeds directly into the ground. Cover them lightly with soil and water them gently. You can also start seeds indoors in seed trays a few weeks before the last frost. Dalea Formosa seeds can take several months to germinate. Keep the soil evenly moist and provide adequate sunlight. — Collection: After flowering, the plant produces seed pods. These pods will turn brown and dry, eventually releasing the tiny, dark brown seeds. Collect these seeds and store them in a cool, dry place. || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the leaves from the bottom inch or two of the stem and make a diagonal cut at the base. Dip the cut end in a rooting hormone to enhance root development. Plant your cuttings in a well-draining potting mix. Keep them moist and provide a humid environment by covering them with a plastic dome or bag. Place your cuttings in a bright, indirect light location. Within a few weeks, you should see roots emerging from the cuttings. Once the roots are about an inch long, you can gradually acclimate the new plants to outdoor conditions. — Collection: Take softwood cuttings from new growth in the spring or summer. Select healthy stems about four inches long. || Stem — Treatment: Layering — Method: Within a few months, new roots should develop where the branch is buried. Once the new plant has established roots, you can sever it from the mother plant and transplant it to its own location. — Collection: Select a flexible branch and bend it to the ground. Pin the branch in place with a wire or rock and bury the section in the soil.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/dalea-formosa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://earthone.io/plant/dalea%20formosa | 1) https://temperate.theferns.info/plant/Dalea+formosa#:~:text=Propagation,/plant/Dalea+formosa%3E 2) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/dalea-formosa-indigobush-grow-care-guide#:~:text=Sow%20in%20a%20well%20drained,can%20be%20pruned%20out%20cleanly. | https://www.gardenia.net/plant/dalea-formosa-indigobush-grow-care-guide#:~:text=Sow%20in%20a%20well%20drained,can%20be%20pruned%20out%20cleanly. | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-dalea-formosa/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Dalea frutescens", "Scientific Name": "Dalea frutescens", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Black Dalea", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Softwood | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Fresh seeds need a scarification process. Soak the seeds in warm water for 24 hours to soften their hard outer shell, which improves germination rates. Fill seed trays or pots with a well-draining seed starting mix. Sow the seeds 1/8 inch deep and cover them lightly with soil. The growing period needs continuously moist conditions to produce robust root systems. Moisten the soil gently with a fine spray, and keep it consistently damp but not waterlogged until germination occurs, usually within 2-3 weeks. Once seedlings have developed true leaves and are strong enough to handle, transplant them into a sunny location with well-draining soil, spacing them about 12-18 inches apart. — Collection: Choose healthy, viable seeds from a reputable source to ensure they are disease-free and capable of germination. || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: A rooting hormone treatment increases the likelihood of successful propagation for cuttings. Plants that become well-established have good resistance to dry conditions while needing very little care. Plants positioned in sunny areas with light, sandy, or rocky soil conditions develop into healthy specimens. — Collection: Cuttings made from softwood during early spring or summer seasons. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: The process of dividing mature plants works provided that each portion contains solid root development. The right spacing between plants creates ventilation that minimizes disease risks.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/dalea-frutescens/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Dalea_lasiathera.html 2) https://legacylandscaper.com/black-dalea-dalea-frutescens/#:~:text=Propagates%20by%20seeds%20and%20occasionally,resistant%20to%20deer%20herbivore%20consumption. | https://legacylandscaper.com/black-dalea-dalea-frutescens/#:~:text=Propagates%20by%20seeds%20and%20occasionally,resistant%20to%20deer%20herbivore%20consumption."}, {"Plant_ID": "Dasylirion texanum", "Scientific Name": "Dasylirion texanum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Sotol", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Offshoots", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Texas Sotol propagation involves sowing seeds in well-draining soil with consistent moisture, avoiding waterlogging for successful germination. An ideal environment with indirect sunlight and protection from extreme conditions is essential for healthy seedling growth. Or sow spring in a greenhouse. When they are large enough to handle, prick the seedlings out into individual pots and grow them on in the greenhouse for at least their first winter. Plant them out into their permanent positions in late spring or early summer, after the last expected frosts. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Place the cut leaf section in a warm, dry location out of direct sunlight. Allow the cut end to callus over for a few days to prevent rot when planted. Fill a pot with a well-draining sandy soil mix, ideally suited for succulent or desert plants. Ensure adequate drainage to prevent water retention. Once the cut end has callused, plant the cutting about 2 inches deep in the prepared potting mix. Position the cutting standing upright as it naturally grows. Water the cutting sparingly, just enough to moisten the soil. Place the pot in a location that receives bright, indirect sunlight. Avoid overwatering to prevent rot. After propagation, maintain minimal watering of texas Sotol, allowing the soil to dry completely between watering sessions. Provide texas Sotol with bright, indirect sunlight and protect from extreme temperatures. — Collection: Select a healthy, mature leaf from texas Sotol. Using a sharp, sterilized knife, cut a 6-8 inch section from the leaf. Ensure the cutting includes some of the base tissue to improve rooting chances. || Offshoots — Treatment: Division — Method: Applying a rooting hormone to the offsets can encourage stronger root development, resulting in better establishment of texas Sotol. Ensure that propagated texas Sotol receives ample sunlight to maintain strong growth and vitalization, without being subject to intense midday heat. Water texas Sotol sparingly and allow the soil to dry out between watering to mimic its natural desert habitat, promoting healthy root systems. — Collection: Propagation by dividing offsets has high success rates. Carefully remove offsets from the parent texas Sotol and allow the cut surface to callus before planting.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/dasylirion-texanum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Dasylirion_texanum.html 2) https://temperate.theferns.info/plant/Dasylirion+texanum#:~:text=Seed%20%2D%20sow%20spring%20in%20a,after%20the%20last%20expected%20frosts. 3) https://earthone.io/plant/dasylirion%20texanum?srsltid=AfmBOopemcMIKrrhesxxBLfhtMVbgdtI_wglnazkcVwFVnEEeF42lmBG | https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Dasylirion_texanum.html#:~:text=Texas%20Sotol%20is%20a%20resilient,root%20development%20without%20promoting%20rot."}, {"Plant_ID": "Datura wrightii", "Scientific Name": "Datura wrightii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Angel Trumpet", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Bud | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Bud — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Before planting, nick them with a file or pocketknife and plant them 5 to a one-gallon pot filled with a sandy soil media in spring (after frost danger is past or with frost protection). If more than one seed germinates, thin out all but one seedling. Allow it to grow until the roots have spread throughout the pot and transplant into a well-drained location during the growing season. Water it intermittently until established during the first year. The following year it should be able to make it on native rainfall. You may spur its growth with supplemental irrigation, but its form and flowering may be adversely affected by excess irrigation. — Collection: Collect seeds from dried pods in the fall. Seedpods are globe-shaped and very spiny. These split open when ripe to release several, semicircular, flattened, yellow-brown seeds. Use caution if attempting to propagate this plant from seeds because the toxin is concentrated in the seeds. Use caution in handling or storing seeds for fruits, and especially keep away from children or pets. For propagating by seed: || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Ensure the cuttings have at least one node and place them in a well-draining soil mix. — Collection: Cuttings can be taken during the growing season.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/datura-wrightii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://extension.arizona.edu/sites/extension.arizona.edu/files/barnesm/SacredDatura.pdf 2) https://calscape.org/Datura-wrightii-(Sacred-Datura) | https://earthone.io/plant/datura%20wrightii?srsltid=AfmBOorO3RwoTHokzrMwwSTP86bI1b2JxD2UssjxjgfR8jtG59hSKuaP"}, {"Plant_ID": "Delphinium carolinianum", "Scientific Name": "Delphinium carolinianum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Prairie Larkspur", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sown in fall or spring. — Collection: Seeds are formed dry in a pod, which call for close observation in order to collect before they are thrown out.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/delphinium-carolinianum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=DECA3"}, {"Plant_ID": "Desmanthus illinoensis", "Scientific Name": "Desmanthus illinoensis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Illinois Bundleflower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: First scarify the seed. Rub the seed between two pieces of sandpaper, make a small nick through the seedcoat, or tumble or shake it with coarse sand and then sow the mixture into your prepared seed bed. Bundleflower may be seeded alone at a depth of ½ inch on heavier moister soils or up to 1 inch deep on dryer sandier soil types. Planting into a prepared seed bed with mulch would increase the chance of establishment. Planting in the early to mid spring time would provide optimum moisture conditions for the seedlings. Broadcast planting would require a 50 to 100 percent increase in the amount of seed used. The seed should also be inoculated with the correct inoculant to cause nodulation of the plants root system. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct sow seeds into prepared soil in late fall once soil temps are below 50 degrees (usually mid to late November). Can also be planted in winter during natural freeze/thaw cycles and early spring. Plant shallow, no deeper than 1/8 to 1/4 inch deep and lightly rake to work seed in. Plant in full sun to partial shade. Can take 3 growing seasons to fully establish.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/desmanthus-illinoensis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) m https://sharpseed.com/illinois-bundleflower/#:~:text=Establishment,of%20the%20plants%20root%20system. 2) https://www.grandprismaticseed.com/natives/illinois-bundleflower#:~:text=Bundleflower%20is%20also%20a%20good,bean%20family%20plants%20have%20grown. 3) https://warcapps.usgs.gov/PlantID/Species/Details/1846#:~:text=Propagation%20by%20seed%20is%20best,be%20harvested%20with%20a%20combine. 4) https://www.electricveg.com/fabaceae/desmanthus-illinoensis.html | Direct sow seeds into prepared soil in late fall once soil temps are below 50 degrees (usually mid to late November). Can also be planted in winter during natural freeze/thaw cycles and early spring. Plant shallow, no deeper than 1/8 to 1/4 inch deep and lightly rake to work seed in. Plant in full sun to partial shade. Can take 3 growing seasons to fully establish."}, {"Plant_ID": "Dichondra carolinensis", "Scientific Name": "Dichondra carolinensis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Carolina Ponyfoot", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: The best time to propagate carolina ponyfoot via sowing is in spring. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the lower leaves, leaving only a few at the top. Dip the cut end in rooting hormone powder and plant in moist potting soil. Keep the soil moist and place the cutting in indirect light. Over time, roots should begin to form and the cutting will begin to grow. — Collection: Take cuttings from mature, healthy specimens about 4-6 inches long, with several leaves.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/dichondra-carolinensis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Dichondra_carolinensis.html | https://plantiary.com/plant/dichondra-carolinensis_3777.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Digitaria californica", "Scientific Name": "Digitaria californica", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Arizona Cottontop", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Root", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Gently crush the dried seed heads to release the seeds. Prepare a container with a suitable planting mix, ensuring good drainage. Sow the seeds on the surface of the planting mix, lightly pressing them into the soil. Moisten the planting mix gently, either by misting with water or using a fine spray nozzle. Place the container in a warm, well-lit area, preferably under a grow light or in a greenhouse. Ensure the soil remains consistently moist but not waterlogged. Germination may take a few weeks to several months, depending on the conditions and the plant's natural dormancy period. Once the seedlings have developed a few sets of true leaves, transplant them into individual pots or into the desired planting location. — Collection: When seeds are mature is usually indicated by a change in color from green to brown. Carefully collect the seed heads or stalks by clipping or cutting them from the plant. Place the seed heads or stalks in a paper bag or envelope to dry for a few weeks until they become brittle. || Root — Treatment: Division — Method: Prepare a planting site with well-draining soil and sufficient sunlight. Gently divide the plant by separating the root ball into smaller sections, making sure each section has enough roots and shoots. Transplant the divided sections into individual pots or directly into the intended growing area. Water the newly divided plants thoroughly and regularly until they establish themselves. — Collection: Carefully dig up the plant, ensuring that the roots remain intact.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/digitaria-californica/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://seedsource.com/az-cottontop/ 2) https://plantiary.com/plant/digitaria-californica_33166.html | https://plantiary.com/plant/digitaria-californica_33166.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Diospyros texana", "Scientific Name": "Diospyros texana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Persimmon", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed | Seedling", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Plant in well-draining soil, maintaining consistent moisture and warmth while avoiding overwatering. Patience is essential, as root development may take time. — Collection: Select healthy, semi-hardwood segments with leaf nodes. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Germinates readliy from fresh seed. Sow seed with some patience. They often benefit from time and weathering for good germination. Seedling trees will begin flowering within five to six-years but it will take approximately 10-years for the flaking bark to appear. — Collection: Collect fully ripe, black fruit clean off pulp to prevent mold. Air-dry seeds and store in sealed, refrigerated containers. Cold-moist storage will induce dormancy and delay germination. || Seedling — Treatment: Transplant — Method: In home gardens, you can transplant small volunteer seedlings to other areas while they are still young. Seedling trees will begin flowering within five to six-years but it will take approximately 10-years for the flaking bark to appear.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/diospyros-texana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Diospyros_texana.html#:~:text=Water:%20Texas%20persimmon%20is%20drought,root%20development%20may%20take%20time. 2) https://earthone.io/plant/diospyros%20texana?srsltid=AfmBOoquJUt6LI2L9CHrd97zIfhPl4WjyLUOiTLqH8M5jm-glOVC2vrk | 1) https://hort.ifas.ufl.edu/trees/DIOTEXA.pdf 2) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/diospyros-texana-texas-persimmon 3) https://earthone.io/plant/diospyros%20texana?srsltid=AfmBOoquJUt6LI2L9CHrd97zIfhPl4WjyLUOiTLqH8M5jm-glOVC2vrk 4) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=DITE3 | 1) https://hort.ifas.ufl.edu/trees/DIOTEXA.pdf 2) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/diospyros-texana-texas-persimmon"}, {"Plant_ID": "Diospyros virginiana", "Scientific Name": "Diospyros virginiana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Common Persimmon", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Root | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratify seeds in moist peat for 30-60 days at 36-41 degrees. Or the simplest method is to sow seed in situ, or in a nursery bed, in the fall. If you have a large quantity of seed this method works great, but for smaller quantities I opt for the refrigerator method. Seedlings grow slowly. American persimmon trees grown from seed, however, can take anywhere from 4-8 years to bear. — Collection: Fruit ripens to bright orange in late Septemter to November. Clean fruit immediately to prevent mold and fermentation. Air-dry seeds and store in sealed, refrigerated containers. || Root — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Bury root cuttings in moist sand over winter and lift when shoot is well developed. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Single-node stem (leaf-bud) cuttings collected from root suckers root much better than longer cuttings from the same source. Rooting at the early stage of the growing season results in a much higher rooting rate than that obtained in cuttings rooted at later stages of the growing season.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/diospyros-virginiana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=DIVI5 2) https://thefruitnut.com/storing-and-stratifying-american-persimmon-seeds/#:~:text=Step%20%231:,Moist%20but%20not%20soaked. | https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=DIVI5 | https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0304423817307744#:~:text=kaki%20(Hejazi%20et%20al.%2C,(2013)."}, {"Plant_ID": "Distichlis spicata", "Scientific Name": "Distichlis spicata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Saltgrass", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump | Root", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Soak seeds for 24 hours in water and plant in spring or early summer. The seeds can be sown directly on the surface of the soil or in containers of well-draining medium such as perlite and peat moss. Sow seeds shallowly (about ¼ inch deep) and keep the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged. Germination can be erratic and may take anywhere from a few weeks to a couple of months. Highest germination seems to come with 50 degree night and 105 degree day temperature regimes. — Collection: Collect seeds directly from mature plants in the fall. Look for plump, dry seed heads that are easily dislodged. Rub them over a sieve to clean from chaff. Keep dry and store in a refrigerator. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Replant each division promptly to avoid drying out the roots. Applying rooting hormone to the cut root sections can significantly boost root development in new divisions. Choose a sunny location with well-drained soil. Plant the divisions at the same depth they were originally growing. Water them in thoroughly. — Collection: Carefully dig around the base of a healthy clump. Use a shovel or garden fork to lift the entire clump from the ground. Gently tease apart the grass into smaller sections, ensuring each division has a good amount of roots attached. || Root — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Plant in a well-draining soil mix about 2.5 cm deep and water regularly. The new plants can be transplanted once they have developed their second set of leaves. — Collection: The roots of the plant need to be about 5 cm long and 0.5 cm in diameter. The cuttings can be taken in late fall or winter.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/distichlis-spicata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-distichlis-spicata/ 2) https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=poaceae-distichlis-586 3) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=DISP | 1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-distichlis-spicata/ 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Distichlis_spicata.html | https://www.botanikks.com/plants/distichlis-spicata-l-greene-var-divaricata-beetle/566270/1"}, {"Plant_ID": "Dyschoriste linearis", "Scientific Name": "Dyschoriste linearis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Snakeherb", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Take cuttings from healthy stems with multiple leaf nodes, cut at a diagonal. Use rooting hormone for quick root growth and plant in well-draining soil. Maintain consistent moisture and provide indirect sunlight for strong root development and vigorous growth.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/dyschoriste-linearis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Dyschoriste_linearis.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Tripsacum dactyloides", "Scientific Name": "Tripsacum dactyloides", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Eastern Gamagrass", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: For best results, sow seeds in late fall to early winter. This allows the seeds to undergo natural stratification, a period of cold-moist conditions that breaks their dormancy and promotes germination come spring. Sowing the Seeds: Scatter seeds on the surface of prepared soil, ensuring good seed-to-soil contact. Since gamagrass seeds are light-sensitive, avoid burying them too deeply. Patience, Young Padawan: Germination can take anywhere from a few weeks to a couple of months. During this time, keep the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged. — Collection: Once pollination has occurred the flowers will fall from the spikelets. Place a mesh bag (like the kind you buy garlic in), over the seed head. As the yellow corn-like seeds dry up, they will fall into the bag and can be planted immediately. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Transplant the divisions into their new homes, ensuring the crown of the plant (where the roots meet the shoots) is level with the soil surface. Water well but water deeply and less frequently to encourage deep root development. — Collection: In late spring or early summer, choose established plants that are at least 3-4 years old. Using a sharp spade or shovel, carefully dig around the perimeter of the clump you wish to divide. Once loosened, gently separate the clump into smaller sections, ensuring each division has a good amount of roots and shoots.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/eastern-gamagrass/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.fnps.org/assets/pdf/pubs/tripsacum_dactyloides_easterngamagrass_3_0.pdf 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-tripsacum-dactyloides/ | 1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-tripsacum-dactyloides/ 2) https://earthone.io/plant/tripsacum%20dactyloides"}, {"Plant_ID": "Echinacea angustifolia", "Scientific Name": "Echinacea angustifolia", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Black Samson", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Sow 1/4 inch deep in clean, form, seed bed, late fall, in the field or sow seed in flats following cold-moist stratification. For best results, cold-moist stratification in plastic bag in refrigerator for two to four months. They should germinate within two weeks after treatment. Field grown plants may be lifted in early spring for transplanting. Plants and seeds must be well watered until the plants are 1+ years old. Seed germination is usually slow and poor, often yielding only 50% germination rates without treatment. — Collection: Mature heads may be clipped from plants. Harvest seeds in late fall. Collect seed that falls easily out of the dried flower head. Seed that is hard to remove is usually bad and difficult to germinate. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Etherol treatment (1mM solution on paper towels in the refrigerator for 2 weeks} Seeds should germinate in two weeks after treatment. Seeds can be sown directly into an outdoor seedbed in fall or early spring, but the soil needs to be well prepared. Plant seeds just under the soil surface spacing them two inches apart. Keep the bed moist and weed-free. When seedlings emerge (at least 21 days), thin to the recommended spacing mentioned above. Plants and seeds must be well watered until the plants are 1+ years old. Seed germination is usually slow and poor, often yielding only 50% germination rates. without treatment. — Collection: Mature heads may be clipped from plants. Harvest seeds in late fall. Collect seed that falls easily out of the dried flower head. Seed that is hard to remove is usually bad and difficult to germinate.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/echinacea-angustifolia/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=asteraceae-echinacea-1349 2) https://openprairie.sdstate.edu/nativeplant/11/#:~:text=Germination:%20Etherol%20treatment%20(1mM%20solution,Downloads:%203%20see%20details 3) / https://newcropsorganics.ces.ncsu.edu/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Echinacea-Angustifolia.pdf?fwd=no | 1) https://openprairie.sdstate.edu/nativeplant/11/#:~:text=Germination:%20Etherol%20treatment%20(1mM%20solution,Downloads:%203%20see%20details 2) https://newcropsorganics.ces.ncsu.edu/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Echinacea-Angustifolia.pdf?fwd=no"}, {"Plant_ID": "Echinocactus texensis", "Scientific Name": "Echinocactus texensis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Horsecrippler Cactus", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Offshoots", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Seed can be sown in well drained soil. || Offshoots — Treatment: Transplant — Method: Offshoots can be carefully removed and planted once they have dried out for a few days.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/echinocactus-texensis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.gardenia.net/plant/echinocactus-texensis-horse-crippler-cactus-grow-care-guide#:~:text=during%20extreme%20cold.-,Uses,cactus%20is%20highly%20drought%2Dtolerant."}, {"Plant_ID": "Echinocereus reichenbachii", "Scientific Name": "Echinocereus reichenbachii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Lace Cactus", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Use fine-grain sandpaper or a file to gently abrade the seeds, which possess a tough outer layer. Scarification boosts water absorption and aids the germination process. This mild rubbing only removes a portion of the seed coat, improving germination rates without harming the seed embryo. Plant in well-draining cactus mix soil to ensure good air circulation and proper water runoff. This soil blend prevents water accumulation around the roots. Containers with drainage holes are essential to prevent excessive moisture. Use plastic bags or a humidity dome to cover seed trays to maintain a high moisture environment, which is crucial for the germination of Lace Hedgehog Cactus seeds. — Collection: Wait for the fruit to mature and starting to dry and shrivel; this is when seeds are ripe for the picking. Use a sharp, sterile knife or scalpel to precisely detach seed pods from the hedgehog cactus without harming plant tissue. A keen blade ensures a clean cut, lessening plant stress and enhancing recovery and regrowth periods. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Successfully rooting cuttings from this cactus can be challenging, but stem cuttings provide faster results and this method maintains the parent plant's characteristics. Allow the cut end to callous over for several days to a week to prevent rot. This step is crucial for giving your cutting the ability to fend off root rot and infection. Then plant in a well-draining, barely moist potting mix and maintain a warm and dry environment during the rooting process. Excessive watering can lead to rot. Roots develop within a month, after which you can begin regular watering. Seeing new growth from the cutting indicates that it has successfully rooted and is growing. — Collection: Take cuttings from mature stems during the growing season (spring or early summer). Look for stems that are healthy and have a semi-hardwood consistency. About 4-6 inches in length is ideal, with several leaf nodes — the spots where roots will emerge. Use sharp, sterilized scissors or pruners to remove an offset stem with a clean, angled cut at the base just below a node. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Allow the cut ends of both the mother plant and the offsets to callous over for a few days before planting them in a well-draining potting mix. — Collection: Division works well for established clumps. This works best in spring as growth resumes. Carefully separate offsets (pups) from the mother plant with roots attached using a sharp, sterilized knife or blade. Damage to the mother plant or the offsets can occur if done improperly. Offsets should be of sufficient size before separation to ensure viability. Ignore the runts; bigger offsets mean a head start. || Stem — Treatment: Grafting — Method: Use grafting tape to hold the pair in place, like a botanical bandage. Keep them warm and dry and soon, they'll grow together as one. Patience is key; it's a slow dance, not a quickstep. — Collection: Choose a rootstock that's vigorous and disease-resistant, ensuring it's a good fit for your scion. (the upper part of the combined plant). Make sure the scion and rootstock are the same diameter for a seamless connection. The flat graft is ideal for cacti. Make a clean cut with a sharp sterile knife to slice the rootstock smoothly.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/echinocereus-reichenbachii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.forwardplant.com/care/propagate/echinocereus-reichenbachii/ 2) https://greg.app/propagate-lace-hedgehog-cactus/ 3) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ECRE | 1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-echinocereus-reichenbachii/ 2) https://greg.app/propagate-lace-hedgehog-cactus/ 43 https://plantiary.com/plant/echinocereus-reichenbachii_636.html | 1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-echinocereus-reichenbachii/ 2) https://greg.app/propagate-lace-hedgehog-cactus/ | https://greg.app/propagate-lace-hedgehog-cactus/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Echinocereus triglochidiatus", "Scientific Name": "Echinocereus triglochidiatus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Claret Cup Cactus", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Offshoots | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Offshoots — Treatment: Division — Method: Transplant the offsets immediately in loose, well-draining soil. Set seedlings or divisions 12 to 24 inches apart, positioned slightly above ground level to prevent waterlogging. Tamp the soil firmly to stabilize each plant, and wait a week before the first watering. Thereafter, water only when the top two to three inches of soil are dry. — Collection: Offsets, aka daughters or pups, are stems that grow beside a parent stem. Divide them in the spring to start new plants. Wear thick gloves. Use a clean garden shovel to dig around and about four to six inches below the outer cylinders in the mound. Use your fingers to gently separate the desired number of stems from the parent. Each must have roots attached. Tamp the soil back around the parent mound. || Offshoots — Treatment: Division — Method: Allow the offset to dry for a few days to form a callus, then plant it in well-draining soil. — Collection: Carefully remove a healthy pup from the base of the parent plant using sterilized tools. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Note that many sources do not recommend propagating this succulent using seeds because it is slow-growing, and germination can take several weeks to months. Here is a detailed method to try. In spring, fill a seed tray three-quarters of the way with moist cactus and succulent potting mix. Surface sow several seeds per cell. Cover the tray with clear plastic wrap and place it in bright, indirect sunlight. The plastic creates a greenhouse effect, and there is no need to water. When the seeds sprout, remove the wrap and keep the soil evenly moist but not soggy. Allow the seedlings to grow until they are at least an inch tall and have spines. Thin them to one per cell. Alternatively you can scatter a few seeds over moist garden soil every 12 to 24 inches. Do not bury them. Maintain even moisture without oversaturation. — Collection: Remove the seeds from the ripe reddish fruit. Wear protective gloves to avoid contact with any remaining spines.Gently twist the fruit to detach it and slice the fruit in half. Scoop out the flesh and place it in a mesh strainer. Use the back of a spoon to press the pulp through the strainer and retain the seeds. Rinse the seeds well and spread on a clean paper towel in a single layer to dry out. Store the dry seeds in an airtight jar in a cool, dry place until the following spring; they don’t require cold stratification.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/echinocereus-triglochidiatus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://gardenerspath.com/plants/succulents/grow-claret-cup-cactus/ | 1) https://planetdesert.com/products/claret-cup-cactus-echinocereus-triglochidiatus 2) https://earthone.io/plant/echinocereus%20triglochidiatus | 1) https://gardenerspath.com/plants/succulents/grow-claret-cup-cactus/ 2) https://gardenbeast.com/echinocereus-triglochidiatus-guide/ 3) https://succulentsnetwork.com/echinocereus-triglochidiatus-claret-cup-cactus/ 4) https://guzmansgreenhouse.com/growing-claret-cup-cactus/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Echinodorus berteroi", "Scientific Name": "Echinodorus berteroi", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Upright Burhead", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Offshoots | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: The dry nutlets containing the seeds can be sown in any kind of container (aquarium, vase, ...) with water and a substrate, e.g. a mixture of sand and loam. They will float at first, but then they sink to the ground by and by. The seeds inside the nutlets germinate after varying periods of time. The seedlings then are best cultivated submersed in order to get larger, more decorative plants. Young plants cultivated emersed stay smaller and form flower stalks early on. || Offshoots — Treatment: Division — Method: Often daughter rosettes may form, which can be separated from the mother plant when they have grown strong enough. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Upright burhead can be propagated through cuttings from healthy, non-flowering shoots. A clean cut below a node enhances root development. Using rooting hormone and a well-draining soil mix is recommended. Maintain consistent moisture, warmth, and provide indirect light to support successful rooting.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/echinodorus-berteroi/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.flowgrow.de/db/aquaticplants/echinodorus-berteroi 2) https://fishy.wiki/en/plants/alismataceae/echinodorus-berteroi.phtml 3) https://pts.lifeasible.com/echinodorus-berteroicellophane-sword-item-1144.html | 1) https://www.flowgrow.de/db/aquaticplants/echinodorus-berteroi 2) https://fishy.wiki/en/plants/alismataceae/echinodorus-berteroi.phtml | https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Echinodorus_berteroi.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Echinodorus cordifolius", "Scientific Name": "Echinodorus cordifolius", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Creeping Burhead", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Offshoots", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Offshoots — Treatment: Division — Method: Echinodorus cordifolius", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/echinodorus-cordifolius/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.gardenia.net/plant/echinodorus-cordifolius#:~:text=Can%20be%20propagated%20by%20cutting,help%20keep%20the%20plant%20smaller."}, {"Plant_ID": "Ehretia anacua", "Scientific Name": "Ehretia anacua", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Sandpaper Tree", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Anaqua seeds benefit from a period of cold stratification. Place the seeds in a moist paper towel within a sealed plastic bag and store them in your refrigerator for 6-8 weeks. Plant the stratified seeds in well-draining soil, about ½ inch deep. Keep the soil consistently moist, and within a few weeks, you should see your Anaqua seedlings emerge. — Collection: In late summer, Anaqua trees bear small, orange-brown fruits. Collect fully ripe fruits that easily detach from the branch. Gently crush the fruits and rinse away the pulp to reveal the small, brown seeds within. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end of the cutting in rooting hormone to encourage root development. Insert the cutting into a well-draining potting mix. Cover the pot with a clear plastic bag to create a humid environment. Keep the soil consistently moist and be patient; it can take several weeks for roots to establish. — Collection: Take cuttings in late spring or early summer from new growth. Look for healthy, semi-hardwood cuttings, about 6-8 inches long. Remove the leaves from the lower half of the cutting.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ehretia-anacua/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=EHAN 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-ehretia-anacua/ | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-ehretia-anacua/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Elephantopus carolinianus", "Scientific Name": "Elephantopus carolinianus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Carolina Elephantsfoot", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Bulb", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Surface sow and press into soil. Cool temperatures to germinate. well-draining soil. Keep the soil moist, and in about 2 to 4 weeks, you should see germination. || Bulb — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully separate the bulbs and replanting them immediately to ensure they thrive. — Collection: Aim to do this every 3 to 4 years in early spring.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/elephantopus-carolinianus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.clayandlimestone.com/2020/09/elephantopus-carolinianus.html#:~:text=Habitat:%20Low%20woods%2C%20ravines%2C,%2C%20moist%20thickets%2C%20open%20woods.&text=Propagation:%20Germination%20%2D%20Very%20Easy:,Cool%20temperatures%20to%20germinate. 2) https://greg.app/carolina-elephants-foot-overview/#:~:text=%F0%9F%8C%B1%20Seed%20Propagation,weeks%2C%20you%20should%20see%20germination. 3) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Elephantopus_carolinianus.html#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Carolina%20elephantsfoot?&text=Carolina%20elephantsfoot%20is%20effectively%20propagated,itself%20and%20thrive%20in%20gardens. | https://greg.app/carolina-elephants-foot-overview/#:~:text=%F0%9F%8C%B1%20Seed%20Propagation,weeks%2C%20you%20should%20see%20germination."}, {"Plant_ID": "Elymus canadensis", "Scientific Name": "Elymus canadensis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Prairie Wildrye", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct sow seeds into prepared soil in late fall once soil temps are below 50 degrees (usually mid to late November). Can also be planted in winter during natural freeze/thaw cycles and early spring. Plant shallow, no deeper than 1/8 to 1/4 inch deep and lightly rake to work seed in. Plant in full sun to partial shade. Can take 3 growing seasons to fully establish. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Seeds benefit from cold stratification. It is best to plant in the fall to allow seeds to naturally stratify under the snow. Spring-planted seeds can be cold-and-moist stratified for 60 days in a refrigerator. Soil contact is important when sowing seeds, so avoid planting over heavy litter. Raking seed into the soil produces better results, but seeds will also grow if spread on the soil surface.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/elymus-canadensis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.opnseed.com/products/elymus-canadensis-nodding-wild-rye#:~:text=Direct%20sow%20seeds%20into%20prepared,growing%20seasons%20to%20fully%20establish. | https://bwsr.state.mn.us/sites/default/files/2023-02/Featured%20Plant%20March%202023%20Canada%20wildrye%20II%20Accessible.pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Elymus interruptus", "Scientific Name": "Elymus interruptus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Wildrye", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Seeds benefit from cold stratification. It is best to plant in the fall to allow seeds to naturally stratify under the snow. Spring-planted seeds can be cold-and-moist stratified for 60 days in wet sand in a refrigerator. Plant ¼\" deep; germination usually occurs in 2–4 weeks after stratification. — Collection: Clip mature seed heads July through September when they begin to dry, turn brown and seeds come off with slight pressure. Place in a paper bag and allow to finish drying for 1–2 weeks in a cool, dry place. Rub the seed heads between your hands or against a fine screen to release seeds.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/elymus-interruptus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.briansnativeplants.com/elymus-hystrix 2) https://bwsr.state.mn.us/sites/default/files/2023-02/Featured%20Plant%20March%202023%20Canada%20wildrye%20II%20Accessible.pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Elymus virginicus", "Scientific Name": "Elymus virginicus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Virginia Wildrye", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: \"The seed requires no stratification or treatment, and typically produce greater than 85% germination (NRCS, 2009). For best results, prepare a clean, firm, weed free seedbed by disking, harrowing, and firming the seedbed with a cultipacker or roller prior to establishment. Rain or irrigation may also be used to settle and firm the field. If possible, allow an initial flush of weeds before planting, and treat with a non-selective, broad spectrum herbicide such as glyphosate in the 2-4 leaf stage. This will help reduce early weed pressure, and, may be done multiple times before planting if severe weed competition is anticipated. Seed should be planted in early spring (in the northern plains) or fall at a depth of approximately ¼ to ½ inch in heavy soils, and up to 1 inch deep in sandy soils (NRCS, 2009). Adequate soil moisture is critical for establishment of healthy stands. Seed should be drilled at 10-15 pure live seed (PLS) pounds per acre or broadcast at 20 PLS pounds per acre, when a monoculture is desired. Mixtures should be adjusted accordingly based on the desired concentration of plants. Virginia wildrye has approximately 96,000 seeds p\" || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Elymus virginicus seeds need at least 30 days of cold moist stratification prior to sowing. Highest germination rate in cool soil. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: On favorable sites, this species reproduces vegetatively at the base by tillering, forming large clumps that become more vigorous so long as good conditions persist. Vigorous clumps will produce numerous upright stems. It does not spread long distances vegetatively, instead relying on seeds to this end.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/elymus-virginicus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/plantguide/pdf/pg_elvi3.pdf | https://www.bluestemnatives.com/product-page/seeds-elymus-virginicus-virginia-wild-rye#:~:text=Stratification%20Codes&text=Seed%20should%20germinate%20when%20sown%20in%20a%20warm%20location.&text=Hot%20water%20treatment:%20Bring%20water,seed%20with%20a%20thick%20seedcoat.&text=(%23%20of%20days%20of%20cold,a%20refrigerator%2C%20NOT%20the%20freezer.&text=Sow%20on%20the%20surface%20of,these%20seeds%20are%20very%20small.&text=These%20seeds%20need%20a%2060,90%20day%20cold%2C%20moist%20period.&text=These%20seeds%20need%20a%2060-90%20day%20cold%2C%20moist%20period,60-90%20day%20moist%20period.&text=Highest%20germination%20rate%20in%20cool%20soil.,-H&text=Seeds%20need%20scarification:%20One%20way,also%20called%20for%2C%20scarify%20first.&text=Legume%20Inoculant%20(more%20info%20next%20year).&text=Legume%20seeds%20(more%20info%20next%20year).&text=Parasitic%20species%20which%20needs%20a%20host%20plant.&text=Plant%20fresh%20seed%20or%20keep%20seed%20moist.&text=Best%20results%20when%20seed%20sown,fall%20for%20a%20natural%20winter. | https://bplant.org/plant/752#:~:text=Growth%20slows%20during%20the%20hotter,livestock)%2C%20or%20regular%20mowing."}, {"Plant_ID": "Engelmannia peristenia", "Scientific Name": "Engelmannia peristenia", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Engelmann's Daisy", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Rosette", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seed direct in the soil in the fall. — Collection: Collect seed in June. || Rosette — Treatment: Transplant — Method: Engelmannia has a long taproot and is best transplanted in winter during its rosette stage.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/engelmannia-peristenia/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ENPE4"}, {"Plant_ID": "Equisetum hyemale spp. affine", "Scientific Name": "Equisetum hyemale spp. affine", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Horsetail", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully dig around the perimeter of the rough horsetail clump you wish to divide. Gently loosen the soil and lift the clump out of the ground, minimizing root damage. Rinse the soil from the roots of the rough horsetail clump to get a clear view of the root system and identify natural divisions. Divide the rough horsetail clump into sections using your hands or a sharp knife. Make sure each division has a portion of the root system as well as several stems. Trim any damaged or excessively long roots to encourage new growth and ease the replanting process. Choose an appropriate location for the new rough horsetail divisions that replicates its natural growing conditions. Rough horsetail thrives in moist, well-drained soil and can tolerate both full sun and partial shade. Plant each rough horsetail division at the same soil depth as it was previously growing. Space the divisions according to their expected mature size. Once the rough horsetail divisions are in the ground, water them thoroughly to settle the soil around the roots and eliminate any air pockets.Apply a layer of organic mulch around the newly planted rough horsetail divisions to retain moisture, regulate soil temperature, and suppress weeds. Keep an eye on the newly planted rough horsetail to ensure they establish well. Provide water as needed, especially during periods of drought or if you observe the soil drying out. — Collection: Identify a healthy, mature rough horsetail plant that shows signs of vigorous growth. Look for a clump that has multiple stems and ensure that it has not been affected by pests or diseases. Clean your gardening tools with a solution of bleach and water to prevent the spread of disease. You will need a sharp shovel or spade for dividing the plant. Thoroughly water the soil around the rough horsetail clump a day before dividing to ease the extraction process and minimize stress on the plant.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/equisetum-hyemale/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Equisetum_hyemale.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Eragrostis hirsuta", "Scientific Name": "Eragrostis hirsuta", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Big Top Lovegrass", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Propagate by division in early spring.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/eragrostis-hirsuta/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://plants.ces.ncsu.edu/plants/eragrostis-hirsuta/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Eragrostis intermedia", "Scientific Name": "Eragrostis intermedia", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Plains Lovegrass", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Ensure each division has roots and replant at the original soil depth while keeping the soil moist. This method preserves genetic fidelity and increases landscape presence. — Collection: Propagated through division, ideally during cooler times.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/eragrostis-intermedia/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Eragrostis_intermedia.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Eragrostis secundiflora", "Scientific Name": "Eragrostis secundiflora", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Red Lovegrass", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Bud", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Start by soaking them for 24 hours before planting. This simple step helps kickstart the germination process, which thrives at an optimal temperature of 70°F (21°C). Red lovegrass is best started using greenhouse grown transplants, planted on bedded rows. Seedlings grow and mature quickly and will produce a marketable crop in the year of planting. When cleaned to caryopses seed quality and active germination are very high (≥ 90%) because of this only small amounts of seed is needed to produce a sufficient number transplant to establish production fields. — Collection: Seed harvest is possible using a variety of methods and implements. Seed ripens indeterminately, and a Woodward Flail-Vac Seed Stripper (Ag-renewal, Inc., Weatherford, Oklahoma) can collect the ripe seed crop without damaging or eliminating the ability to make subsequent harvests of the stand as later flowering florets mature. However, majority of the seed crop will hold well on the plants after complete maturity allowing for combine harvest. An additional benefit of combining is the removal of unfilled florets which increases seed harvest purity. In well managed, irrigated fields, 2-3 harvests can be expected per year. The first harvest is typically in May, with the last harvest in October. Potential seed yields per acre have been calculated at 10 PLS lbs. per acre on 36” bedded rows with a plant population of 14,000 plants per acre. || Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully separate the clumps and replant them immediately to ensure they establish well in their new locations.. — Collection: The best time for this is in early spring or fall, when the plant is less stressed.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/eragrostis-secundiflora/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://plants.sc.egov.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/plantguide/pdf/pg_erso.pdf 2) https://greg.app/red-lovegrass-overview/#:~:text=Elevate%20your%20garden%20with%20Red,reduce%20the%20risk%20of%20disease. | https://greg.app/red-lovegrass-overview/#:~:text=Elevate%20your%20garden%20with%20Red,reduce%20the%20risk%20of%20disease. 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Eragrostis_secundiflora.html#:~:text=A%20distinctive%20warm%2Dseason%20grass,its%20characteristic%20red%2Dhued%20panicles."}, {"Plant_ID": "Eragrostis spectabilis", "Scientific Name": "Eragrostis spectabilis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Purple Lovegrass", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Lovegrass seed can be sown either indoors in the late winter or directly outside. The ornamental grass seed is small, press the seed into the soil but do not cover it. Keep the Purple Love Grass seed moist until germination. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Assemble the necessary tools including a sharp spade or knife, pots, potting soil, and water. Ensure all tools are clean to prevent the spread of disease to purple lovegrass. Gently tease apart the root clump into smaller sections using your hands or cut through with the spade or knife. Each section should have a good amount of roots and several shoots. Fill pots with potting soil and plant the divided sections of purple lovegrass, ensuring that the roots are well spread out and that the soil level is the same as it was when the plant was in the ground. Water the newly potted sections of purple lovegrass thoroughly to settle the soil around the roots and eliminate air pockets. Place the pots in a location where purple lovegrass will receive appropriate amounts of sunlight and maintain consistent moisture in the soil without overwatering. Keep an eye on the new purple lovegrass plants for signs of growth or stress. Adjust care as needed to ensure healthy root and shoot development. — Collection: Choose a time when purple lovegrass is actively growing but not during the heat of the day to avoid excessive stress on the plant. Carefully dig around the base of purple lovegrass to lift the entire clump from the ground with minimal root disturbance. Shake off any loose soil.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/eragrostis-spectabilis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.outsidepride.com/seed/ornamental-grass/love-grass/love-grass-purple.html#:~:text=Purple%20love%20grass%20(Eragrostis%20spectabilis)%20is%20a,in%20winter%20to%20prepare%20for%20spring%20growth 2) https://www.rpseeds.co.uk/products/eragrostis-spectabilis-purple-love-grass-seeds#:~:text=GROWING%20GUIDE,soil%20in%20a%20sunny%20position. | https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Eragrostis_spectabilis.html#:~:text=Purple%20lovegrass%20is%20typically%20propagated%20through%20division%2C,well%2Ddraining%20soil%20are%20crucial%20for%20healthy%20growth."}, {"Plant_ID": "Eragrostis trichodes", "Scientific Name": "Eragrostis trichodes", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Sand Lovegrass", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Seeds are placed in cold moist stratification for 14 days. Germination occurs at 30D/20N C alternating temperature cycle. Dry storage of spring germinating seeds resulted in 62% germination. Heating pretreatment resulted in 100% germination. Pretreatment with potassium nitrate resulted in 63% germination. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sowing outdoors: seedbed preparation should provide a weed free, firm surface on which to plant. Since seed sze is small the planting depth should be 2.5 to 5 mm to allow seedling emergence. Neoteric seed of E. trichodes often shows considerable dormancy. This quality may be considered desirable for range seedings since seedlings continue to emerge over a longer period of time (Ahring et al. 1963). Sowing indoors: Direct sow either in late fall or early spring. Press the Eragrostis Trichodes seed into the surface of the soil, compacting the soil very firmly. . Keep the soil lightly moist until germination. Water seedlings occasionally until they become established. Mature plants tolerate heat and drought well, since they prefer dry and sandy soil. This plant readily spreads and reseeds itself, and can grow very quickly in good conditions. It makes an excellent choice for erosion control, as well as being a beautiful ornamental grass. — Collection: At the end of the season, the seed heads will begin to ripen and turn color. Strip the seed from the stem, and separate the seed from the plant material. Store the sand love grass seeds in a cool, dry place.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/eragrostis-trichodes/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=poaceae-eragrostis-1770#:~:text=General%20Distribution:,Citation: | 1) https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/plantguide/pdf/pg_ertr3.pdf 2) https://www.everwilde.com/store/Eragrostis-trichodes-Seed.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Erigeron modestus", "Scientific Name": "Erigeron modestus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Prairie Fleabane", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Soak the harvested seeds in water for about 24 hours to help soften the seed coat and enhance germination rates. Fill seed trays or small pots with a well-draining potting mix. Sow the soaked seeds on the surface and lightly press them into the soil. Avoid covering the seeds with too much soil. Moisten the soil with a gentle spray of water. Keep the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged during the germination period, which typically takes a few weeks. Once seedlings have grown a few true leaves and are strong enough to handle, transplant them into individual pots or directly into the garden, spacing them appropriately to allow room for growth. — Collection: Collect seeds from mature plains fleabane plants. Ensure that the seeds are fully ripened and dry before collection for optimal germination.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/erigeron-modestus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Erigeron_modestus.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Erigeron philadelphicus", "Scientific Name": "Erigeron philadelphicus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Philadelphia Fleabane", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Bud", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Seeds can be sown in the spring. — Collection: Plants self sow freely when in suitable positions. Multiple harvests may be necessary since ripening varies over a period of weeks. Small scale plots can be harvested using handheld vacuum sucking off seeds from plants as they ripen1. || Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: To divide, carefully dig up the plant and separate the root clumps, then replant them in suitable locations. — Collection: Division is best done in the fall or early spring. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Cold-moist stratification of 90-120 days before seed will germinate. — Collection: When seed is dormant", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/erigeron-philadelphicus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://earthone.io/plant/erigeron%20philadelphicus | https://courses.washington.edu/esrm412/protocols/2017/ERPH.pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Eriogonum longifolium var. longifolium", "Scientific Name": "Eriogonum longifolium var. longifolium", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Longleaf Buckwheat", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Bud | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Best sown as soon as it is ripe in the autumn in a sandy compost in a greenhouse. Sow stored seed in early spring in a warm greenhouse. As soon as they are large enough to handle, prick the seedlings out into individual pots and grow them on in the greenhouse for at least their first winter. Plant out in late spring or early summer, after the last expected frosts. || Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: Division has to be done with care because the plant resents root disturbance. Try to obtain divisions from around the edges of the plants without digging up the whole clump. Tease the divisions out with as much root on them as possible and pot them up. Grow them on in light shade in the greenhouse until they are rooting well and plant them out in the summer. — Collection: Division in early spring. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Cuttings of greenwood with a heel in the summer.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/eriogonum-longifolium-var-longifolium/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Eriogonum+longifolium#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,in%20the%20summer%5B200%5D."}, {"Plant_ID": "Eryngium hookeri", "Scientific Name": "Eryngium hookeri", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Hooker's Eryngo", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Use fresh seeds sown in well-draining soil, lightly covered to retain humidity. Maintain consistent moisture without overwatering, and ensure sunny conditions for germination,", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/eryngium-hookeri/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Eryngium_hookeri.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Eryngium leavenworthii", "Scientific Name": "Eryngium leavenworthii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Leavenworth Eryngo", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Fill a seed tray with a well-draining soil mix, such as a sandy potting mix. Scatter the seeds evenly on the surface and cover them very lightly with soil. Spritz the surface gently with water to keep it lightly moist but not waterlogged. Consistent moisture during germination is crucial. Place the seed tray in a location that receives indirect light and maintains a temperature of around 60-70°F (15-21°C) which is optimal for germination. Watch for seedling emergence, which typically occurs within a few weeks. Once seedlings are large enough to handle, thin them out to avoid overcrowding and promote stronger growth. — Collection: Start by collecting ripe seeds from mature leavenworth's eryngo plants. Allow them to dry completely to enhance germination rates. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Germination can be slow, and the seeds benefit from stratification. Sow pre-moistened flats and seal them in plastic bags in late winter. Refrigerate for two to three weeks. Then move the flats outdoors to a shady location after all threat of frost has passed. Transplant as seedlings appear, which usually takes two to three weeks.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/eryngium-leavenworthii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Eryngium_leavenworthii.html | 1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Eryngium_leavenworthii.html 2) https://www.westcoastseeds.com/blogs/wcs-academy/how-to-grow-eryngium"}, {"Plant_ID": "Eryngium yuccifolium", "Scientific Name": "Eryngium yuccifolium", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Rattlesnake Master", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Root | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Root — Treatment: Division — Method: Mature plants can be divided in late spring or early fall and planted in the ground. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct sow seeds in spring to avoid the need to transplant at all. Prior to sowing, provide the rattlesnake master seeds with simulated cold stratification. Keep the seeds in a plastic bag with some sand in the refrigerator for two months before planting. If you’re sowing in fall, broadcast them in your desired area and wait for them to germinate in spring. — Collection: Collect seed in fall when the seed heads have turned brown. Tap the seed out of the heads and air-dry, || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Cold-moist stratify at 40 degrees for 2 months. Sown in the spring. — Collection: Collect seed in fall when the seed heads have turned brown. Tap the seed out of the heads and air-dry,", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/eryngium-yuccifolium/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ERYU | 1) https://www.epicgardening.com/rattlesnake-master/#:~:text=Propagation,them%20to%20germinate%20in%20spring. 2) https://www.everwilde.com/store/Eryngium-yuccifolium-WildFlower-Seed.html 3) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ERYU"}, {"Plant_ID": "Euonymus atropurpureus", "Scientific Name": "Euonymus atropurpureus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Wahoo", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Seed must be stratified. Some texts say a single stratification at 32-50 degrees for 90-120 days is appropriate. Others say double stratification is necessary 90 days warm and 60 days cool.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/euonymus-atropurpureus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=EUAT5"}, {"Plant_ID": "Eupatorium serotinum", "Scientific Name": "Eupatorium serotinum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Late Boneset", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully separate the root clumps and replant them. — Collection: Divide in early spring. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Take 4-6 inch cuttings, remove the lower leaves, and plant them in a moist rooting medium. — Collection: Take stem cuttings in late spring to early summer.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/eupatorium-serotinum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://earthone.io/plant/eupatorium%20serotinum"}, {"Plant_ID": "Eustoma exaltatum ssp. russellianum", "Scientific Name": "Eustoma exaltatum ssp. russellianum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Bluebell", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: The seed is exceptionally small and somewhat difficult to germinate. The best results have come from surface seeding (since the seed requires light for germination) in flats at approximately 70 75 degrees. Field seeding can be done in spring or fall, however, spring germination usually results in the vegetative growth overwintering and not flowering until the second summer. Fall germination should produce flowers the first season. — Collection: Collect seed when seeds inside the capsule are black.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/eustoma-exaltatum-ssp-russellianum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=EUEXR"}, {"Plant_ID": "Eustoma exaltatum", "Scientific Name": "Eustoma exaltatum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Small Bluebell", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Stage 1 (10-12 days): Maintain soil temperature at 20 to 22˚C. Keep media evenly moist but not saturated. Do not cover or bury the seed. Light is required for germination. Stage 2 (14-21 days): Maintain soil temperature at 20 to 22°C. Reduce moisture levels once radicals emerge. Allow the soil to dry out slightly before watering to control algae growth. Irrigate early in the day so foliage is dry by nightfall. Stage 3 (28-35 days): Maintain soil temperature at 18 to 20°C. Allow media to dry thoroughly between irrigations. Avoid extreme wilting, which can induce rosetting. Stage 4 (7 days): Maintain soil temperature at 17 to 18°C. Allow media to dry thoroughly between irrigations. Avoid permanent wilting, which can induce rosetting. Do not hold the plugs until rootbound as this induces rosetting. Transplant should be when the seedlings reach a height of 5 cm. Seedling grows very slowly, 4 leaves will develop in about 2 months. It blooms about 5 months after sowing. — Collection: Collect seed in June, when seeds inside capsule are black. Eustoma exaltatum are usually grown from seed, which should be sown in early spring. Seeds should be planted in a moist mixture of moss and peat. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: For cuttings, take a healthy stem cutting, dip it in rooting hormone, and plant it in a moist, well-draining medium.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/eustoma-exaltatum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://travaldo.blogspot.com/2021/05/eustoma-exaltatum-seaside-gentian-care-and-culture.html 2) https://earthone.io/plant/eustoma%20exaltatum?srsltid=AfmBOorMKnualL8J_GzvaCNouptqDtRoddH9fYYabUNKHmk_MHdzZ35q 3) https://www.wildflower.org/expert/show.php?id=6237&frontpage=true | https://earthone.io/plant/eustoma%20exaltatum?srsltid=AfmBOorMKnualL8J_GzvaCNouptqDtRoddH9fYYabUNKHmk_MHdzZ35q"}, {"Plant_ID": "Eysenhardtia texana", "Scientific Name": "Eysenhardtia texana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Kidneywood", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Softwood | Semi-harwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Texas kidneywood germinates best when temperatures fall between 68–86º F and when there is about 12 hours of daylight. Colder temperatures have been known to reduce germination, whereas higher temperatures tend to reduce the survival of new seedlings. However, Texas kidneywood has been known to germinate with no light and temperatures from 59–104º F. Young plants may do better in light shade until they become better established. — Collection: Seedpods should be harvested when they have turned brown and dry. Seeds are kidney-shaped, slightly-plump, and light to darker brown when matured. Seeds or pods should be dried at room temperature for several days before storing. It is recommended that seeds or pods be fumigated and stored at cold temperatures. || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Cuttings 4 to 6\" long should be taken in the summer and early fall. A rooting hormone should be used to facilitate root growth. Cuttings tend to root in 3 to 4 weeks. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Soaking in warm water overnight will help to soften the hard seed coat. Sow in well drained, gritty mix, and keep barely moist until germination. || Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: May root with mist and bottom heat. — Collection: Take cuttings in late spring or summer.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/eysenhardtia-texana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.ckwri.tamuk.edu/plant/texas-kidneywood#:~:text=Texas%20kidneywood%20can%20be%20grown%20from%20seed,There%20is%20about%2012%20hours%20of%20daylight 2) https://plants.sc.egov.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/factsheet/pdf/fs_eyte.pdf | https://www.ckwri.tamuk.edu/plant/texas-kidneywood#:~:text=Texas%20kidneywood%20can%20be%20grown%20from%20seed,There%20is%20about%2012%20hours%20of%20daylight | https://www.gardenia.net/plant/eysenhardtia-texana-texas-kidneywood-grow-care-guide"}, {"Plant_ID": "Fleischmannia incarnata", "Scientific Name": "Fleischmannia incarnata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Pink Thoroughwort", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow the seeds in seed trays or small pots filled with seed-starting mix. Keep the soil moist and warm. Expect seeds to germinate within a few weeks, though it may take longer. Once seedlings develop a few true leaves, you can gently move them into larger containers or the garden. — Collection: Allow seedheads to dry on plants; remove and collect seeds. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove any leaves that would be submerged in water. Fill a jar or container with clean water, ensuring it’s deep enough to submerge the cut end of the stem. Change the water frequently to prevent algae growth. Root development can take a few weeks or even months. Once the cutting has developed a healthy root system, you can gently pot it in well- draining soil. — Collection: Choose a healthy, non-flowering stem from your Fleischmannia. The ideal time for this is in spring or early summer when the plant is actively growing. Make a clean, angled cut just below a node (where a leaf or branch grows). || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Plant each division in a well-prepared container or garden bed, ensuring the roots are spread out and the crown of the plant is at or slightly above soil level. — Collection: The best time for division is usually in early spring or late summer when growth is active. Gentle Excavation: Carefully dig up the clump and gently separate it into smaller divisions. Each division should have its own roots and healthy aerial growth.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/fleischmannia-incarnata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Fleischmannia_incarnata.html#:~:text=Water:%20Pink%20slender%2Dthoroughwort%20thrives,handling%20and%20growing%20medium%20quality 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-fleischmannia-incarnata/?amp=1&print=pdf | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-fleischmannia-incarnata/?amp=1&print=pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Forestiera pubescens", "Scientific Name": "Forestiera pubescens", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Elbowbush", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Plant seeds in moist soil in the fall or prior to February for natural stratification. For spring planting in May, seeds must be stratified for 30 days in moist sand at 38 degrees Fahrenheit. — Collection: Harvest fruit when it has turned dark purple in late summer. Cut them open to retrieve seeds. Rinse seeds to remove any flesh that is still attached, and then leave them out to dry. Store in ventilated bags or containers in cool, dry place. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Make a hole in your planting medium by pushing your pencil into the soil. Dip the end of the stem in rooting hormone, and plant it in your pot. Fill in soil around the cutting to support it, but do not pack it down too much. Moisten with water, and ensure that the pot has good drainage. Your pot should be kept in warm, sunny conditions indoors (and not in direct sunlight). Water whenever your soil is dry under the top layer. After about four to six weeks have passed, your cutting should be rooted. — Collection: Ensure that this plant has had a good watering the night before, as this will improve the chances your cutting will take root. Cut one or more 6 inch portion(s) of the end of a non-blooming branch and strip the leaves off of the lower half.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/forestiera-pubescens/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=fopup#: 2) https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/factsheet/pdf/fs_fopu2.pdf 3) https://www.theeyrye.com/forestiera.html | https://www.theeyrye.com/forestiera.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Rhamnus caroliniana", "Scientific Name": "Rhamnus caroliniana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Carolina Buckthorn", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Plant immediately with fruit in tact and squished, not dried. — Collection: Collect seeds in fall when fruits have turned dark purple. Clean off pulp if seed is to be saved. Seeds to be sown should not be dried, as this induces dormancy.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/frangula-caroliniana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=CHLI2"}, {"Plant_ID": "Fraxinus texensis", "Scientific Name": "Fraxinus texensis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Ash", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratify in moist sand or perlite for 30-60 days at 41 degrees F.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/fraxinus-albicans/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=FRAL3"}, {"Plant_ID": "Fraxinus berlandieriana", "Scientific Name": "Fraxinus berlandieriana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Mexican Ash", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratify in moist sand or perlite for 30-60 days at 41 degrees.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/fraxinus-berlandieriana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=FRBE"}, {"Plant_ID": "Fraxinus pennsylvanica", "Scientific Name": "Fraxinus pennsylvanica", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Green Ash", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stored seeds require warm-moist stratification for 60 days, followed by 120 days at 32-41 degrees. It usually germinates in spring Prick out the seedlings into individual pots when they are large enough to handle and grow them on in a cold frame for their first winter. Plant them out into their permanent positions or a nursery bed in late spring or early summer of the following year. If you have sufficient seed then it is possible to sow it directly into an outdoor seedbed, preferably in the autumn. Grow the seedlings on in the seedbed for 2 years before transplanting either to their permanent positions or to nursery beds. — Collection: The seed is best harvested green - as soon as it is fully developed but before it has fully dried on the tree. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Fresh seed can then be sown immediately in a cold frame. It usually germinates in spring. — Collection: The seed is best harvested green - as soon as it is fully developed but before it has fully dried on the tree. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Make a clean cut with a sharp knife or pruning shears just below a node (where leaves grow). The ideal length is 6-8 inches. Remove the leaves from the bottom two inches of the cutting. Dip the cut end in a rooting hormone powder to stimulate root development. Plant the cuttings in a moist rooting medium, like a mixture of peat moss and perlite. Ensure the cuttings are planted at least an inch deep, leaving the top leaves exposed. Cover the pot with a plastic dome or bag to create a humid environment, which promotes root growth. Place the pot in a bright, indirect light location. Regularly check the moisture levels and keep the medium consistently moist. It can take a few weeks to a few months for roots to develop. Once new growth appears, you know the rooting process is successful! — Collection: In late summer or early fall, select healthy, mature branches that are about the thickness of a pencil.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/fraxinus-pennsylvanica/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=FRPE 2) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Fraxinus+pennsylvanica 3) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-fraxinus-pennsylvanica/ | https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Fraxinus+pennsylvanica | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-fraxinus-pennsylvanica/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Funastrum crispum", "Scientific Name": "Funastrum crispum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Wavyleaf Twinevine", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the leaves from the bottom half of the cutting to prevent rot. Optionally, dip the cut end in rooting hormone to promote faster root development. Fill a small pot with a well-draining soil mix. Insert the cut end of the stem into the soil, ensuring at least one node is buried. Water lightly to settle the soil. Place the pot in a warm, bright area with indirect sunlight. Maintain consistent moisture by misting the soil lightly without making it soggy. Covering the pot with a plastic bag can help retain humidity, but ensure adequate airflow to prevent mold. After the plant has rooted and starts showing new growth, gradually acclimate it to normal humidity levels by removing any covering. Keep the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged. Wavy-leaf twinevine thrives in bright, indirect light and prefers well-draining soil. Prune regularly to encourage a bushier growth habit and support its twining nature by providing a structure for it to climb. — Collection: Choose a healthy, mature stem from wavy-leaf twinevine with at least two or three sets of leaves. Make sure the stem is free of diseases and pests. Use a clean, sharp knife or pruning shears to cut a 4-6 inch section of the stem just below a node, where the leaves attach. Ensure the cut is clean and even.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/funastrum-crispum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Funastrum_crispum.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Funastrum cynanchoides", "Scientific Name": "Funastrum cynanchoides", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Fringed Twinevine", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Cold-wet stratification: label a sandwich-sized ziplock bag with the name of the milkweed and date, then fill it about 3/4 full with sand, decomposed granite, or another abrasive media. Add enough water to make the sand very wet – you should see the sheen of water when you squish the bag. Add the seeds – however many you want to plant – to the mixture and place the baggie on the top shelf of your fridge, where you can move it a couple of times daily. Plant after a month has passed. — Collection: Collect after seed pod has split.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/funastrum-cynanchoides/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://store.underwoodgardens.com/vining-milkweed-seeds-funastrum-cynanchoides/f1213/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Gaillardia aestivalis", "Scientific Name": "Gaillardia aestivalis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Lanceleaf Blanketflower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct sow int he soil. — Collection: The seeds are generally ripe September. Remove the seeds from the heads by rubbing then shake through a screen to remove chaff. Seed viability remains high for several years with proper storage.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/gaillardia-aestivalis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://warcapps.usgs.gov/PlantID/Species/Details/3810#:~:text=The%20seeds%20are%20generally%20ripe,with%20competition%20from%20tall%20plants. 2) https://www.plantdelights.com/products/gaillardia-aestivalis-var-winkleri-grape-sensation?srsltid=AfmBOoq0NBE-FUWoQVWYZ_RXFMM6Gou62WnFimkVfb8s1M-pPX26nqUb"}, {"Plant_ID": "Gaillardia pulchella", "Scientific Name": "Gaillardia pulchella", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Firewheel", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: After flowering ceases, allow seeds to completely mature before mowing for reseeding or collecting to plant in a new area. Look for heads with no dried petals persisting. Since G. pulchella is an annual, it is essential that this species be allowed to reseed for an abundant display the following year. — Collection: After flowering ceases, allow seeds to completely mature before mowing for reseeding or collecting to plant in a new area. Look for heads with no dried petals persisting. Since G. pulchella is an annual, it is essential that this species be allowed to reseed for an abundant display the following year. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: To increase vigor and extend the life of perennial forms, divide plants every 2 to 3 years in spring or fall.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/gaillardia-pulchella/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.fnps.org/assets/pdf/pubs/gaillardia_pulchella_blanketflower.pdf 2) https://earthone.io/plant/gaillardia%20pulchella 3) https://www.everwilde.com/store/Gaillardia-pulchella-WildFlower-Seed.html?srsltid=AfmBOoro0jIuuIulclMN62ztHi9T2qtX6dCiZ3slb87ME-onl8ccFzza | https://www.gardendesign.com/plants/gaillardia.html#:~:text=Dividing:,years%20in%20spring%20or%20fall."}, {"Plant_ID": "Garrya ovata", "Scientific Name": "Garrya ovata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Mexican Silktassel", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Use a well-draining potting mix rich in organic matter. Sterilize the soil to kill any pathogens that could hinder seed germination or cutting establishment. Sow seeds shallowly in the prepared trays, covering them lightly with soil. Maintain a consistent temperature and moisture level to encourage germination. — Collection: Gather seeds from healthy, mature Garrya ovata plants during late spring. Ensure seeds are dry and free from any mold or pests before planting.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/garrya-ovata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.forwardplant.com/plant-info/Garrya_ovata/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Gelsemium sempervirens", "Scientific Name": "Gelsemium sempervirens", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Carolina Jessamine", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Rhizome | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Layering — Method: Carolina jasmine roots fairly readily. An easy method is to layer one of the long runners while it is attached to the mother plant. You can actually almost weave it in and out of the soil, so that one long sprout could give you 3-5 new plants. Place a rock or brick over the part under the soil to keep it from bouncing up, and you should have rooted plants within a month or two. Once rooted, cut them apart and transplant. || Rhizome — Treatment: Division — Method: Remove the excess soil from the rhizomes, and then cut them into pieces, making sure that each rhizome has at least one bud on it. Bury the rhizomes in the ground to about the same depth they were planted when you dug them up, and water well. Continue to water twice a week throughout winter. In spring, you should see some above-ground activity. — Collection: Start by digging up your jessamine in September or October. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Start indoors in late winter, or outdoors in late spring when the soil is warm. — Collection: If you want to collect a few seeds to start new plants, pick in fall after the seeds have turned brown. Air-dry for three or four days. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Cutting type: stem tip Time of year to take cuttings: Summer Cutting maturity: softwood Rooting hormone: IBA TALC 3000 PPM Rooting environment: intermittent mist Time to rooting: 10-12 weeks", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/gelsemium-sempervirens/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.uaex.uada.edu/yard-garden/in-the-garden/reference-desk/vines/carolina-jessamine.aspx#:~:text=Carolina%20jasmine%20roots%20fairly%20readily,cuttings%20to%20be%20semi%2Dhardwood. 2) https://gardenerspath.com/plants/vines/grow-carolina-jessamine/ 3) https://hort.ifas.ufl.edu/database/lppi/sp170.shtml#:~:text=Common%20name(s):%20Carolina,1/2%20way%20through%20stem | https://gardenerspath.com/plants/vines/grow-carolina-jessamine/ | https://www.gardeningknowhow.com/ornamental/vines/carolina-jessamine/growing-carolina-jessamine.htm#:~:text=Carolina%20Jessamine%20propagation%20can%20occur,%2D3.6m)%20at%20maturity. | https://hort.ifas.ufl.edu/database/lppi/sp170.shtml#:~:text=Common%20name(s):%20Carolina,1/2%20way%20through%20stem"}, {"Plant_ID": "Geum canadense", "Scientific Name": "Geum canadense", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "White Avens", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds directly in the soil in September and April. — Collection: Seed Collection: Collect seed in June.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/geum-canadense/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=GECA7"}, {"Plant_ID": "Glandularia bipinnatifida", "Scientific Name": "Glandularia bipinnatifida", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Prairie Verbena", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Prepare a well-draining soil mix, typically a blend of standard potting soil and sand or perlite to enhance aeration and drainage. Sow the seeds evenly across the surface of the soil mix, lightly pressing them in, but do not cover them completely as they require light for germination. Moisten the soil carefully using a fine mist spray to avoid displacing the seeds. Maintain consistent moisture levels without saturating the soil. Place the seed tray in a warm, well-lit area, but out of direct sunlight. Maintain a temperature around 70°F (21°C) to encourage germination, which typically occurs within 2-3 weeks. — Collection: Collect the nutlets in summer and fall when they separate into fours. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Mature plants produce rooted starts from stems. Two-inch tip cuttings should be treated with a 1:10 liquid rooting hormone. Place under intermittent mist for approximately 8 days. After root initiation occurs remove from mist and keep soil evenly moist until rooting has finished. — Collection: Cuttings can be harvested any time plant is actively growing. Remove inflorescence from cutting material.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/glandularia-bipinnatifida/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://openprairie.sdstate.edu/nativeplant/197/#:~:text=Seed%20collection:%20Collect%20the%20nutlets,Mesic%20to%20dry%2C%20drought%20tolerant. 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Glandularia_bipinnatifida_var._latilobata.html | 1) https://openprairie.sdstate.edu/nativeplant/197/#:~:text=Seed%20collection:%20Collect%20the%20nutlets,Mesic%20to%20dry%2C%20drought%20tolerant. 2) https://plantselect.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Verbena-bipinnatifida.pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Gleditsia triacanthos", "Scientific Name": "Gleditsia triacanthos", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Honey Locust", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Summary: Preferred temperature for germination: 70-85 degrees F Time required for germination: 6-8 weeks. Method: Bring water just to boiling in a heat-proof container (water volume should be 3 to 4 times the volume of the seeds you are treating). Remove water from heat source and let stand for one minute (if you have a thermometer, water temperature should be about 190°F). Pour seeds into hot water. Then allow water to cool to room temperature. Remove seeds after they begin to swell; seeds can be allowed to swell up to 3 times their normal size. Plant seeds immediately after boiling water treatment; do not store. Alternatively, vigorously rub the seeds on a piece of medium or fine sandpaper or a file, then plant. Fill your pot or other container with soil or potting mix; water thoroughly, let the soil settle, and refill to bring the soil level up to within 1/2\" to 1\" of the top. Be sure that holes in the pot are adequate to allow quick drainage of extra water. Plant seeds in moist soil 1/2\" to 3/4\" deep and cover with soil. Seed orientation does not matter. More than one seed can be planted in a pot to ensure that at least one germinates (space well apart). A clear plastic bag or plastic wrap can be placed loosely over the top of the pot to help keep moisture and warmth in. Puncture the plastic in several places to allow some heat to escape. Place the pot on a waterproof tray or dish in a sunny spot. Keep away from radiators or heat registers that might get the germinating seeds too warm. Germination and shoot emergence should take 10 to 14 days (could take up to 21 days). Remove plastic as soon as shoot emerges and snip off the weakest shoot with scissors if both seeds germinate. Water before and after germination when the soil just below the surface begins to dry. Soil should remain moist but not waterlogged. If the tree remains in the pot for longer than a month or so you should use a liquid fertilizer solution occasionally to keep it healthy. Follow directions on the fertilizer package. Plant in the fall or the next spring (tree can over-winter with its pot buried in the garden). Near planting time if tree has been inside move outside to a protected location to \"harden off\". Dig a hole as deep as the pot and 2-3 times as wide. Then carefully remove the pot and place the intact root ball in the hole, backfilling with native soil around the sides and tamping gently. Water thoroughly and care-for as you would any other tree. — Collection: Time of year to collect seed: Autumn || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Cuttings can be taken from young, healthy branches and rooted in a well-draining soil mix. Propagation is best done in the spring or early summer. Mix a low-fertility rooting medium of 50-percent sterile perlite and 50-percent peat moss. Fill your container to 1 inch below its lip. Water the medium so it remains evenly moist during potting. Strip the leaves from the cutting's lower half to keep them from contaminating the rooting medium and to minimize the cutting's transpiration, or water loss. Sprinkle a small pile of rooting hormone powder into a saucer. Make a shallow indentation in the pile with a florist's stick. Dip the base of the cutting into the shallow indentation and tap it to remove the excess. Dispose of the leftover powder. Insert a florist's stick into the growing medium to a depth of half the cutting's length. Using this premade hole prevents the rooting powder from rubbing off when you pot the cutting. Position the cutting in the container with the cut end down. Gently tamp medium around the edge of the hole. Water again if your container is less than 3 inches deep. Cover the cutting with a clear glass jar to provide essential humidity and room to grow. Inserting florist's sticks in the medium around the cutting, sliding a clear plastic bag up over the sticks and tying it shut also works. Move the container to an area with indirect light. Lift or open the covering for two minutes every other day to ventilate the plants and mist the medium with the spray bottle of water. Watch the cutting for the new growth, indicating root development. When you're satisfied it can be moved, slowly remove the rooting medium until the cutting lifts without resistance. Transfer it to a container of regular potting soil in bright light away from direct sun. Continue regular watering and gradually increase the honey locust's sun exposure as it grows. — Collection: Harvest your branch cutting on an early spring or summer morning while the tree is actively growing. Carry a dark plastic bag containing two wet paper towels with you. Look for a branch with healthy twigs that break easily when bent. Make a sharp cut just beneath a leaf, 4 to 5 inches from the branch's growing tip. Store the cutting in the wet paper towels inside the dark plastic bag to keep it moist before potting.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/gleditsia-triacanthos/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://hort.ifas.ufl.edu/database/lppi/sp176.shtml#:~:text=Common%20name(s):%20Honey,for%20germination:%206%2D8%20weeks 2) https://extension.usu.edu/forestry/files/resources/plant-and-take-care-of-honeylocust-tree.pdf | 1) https://earthone.io/plant/gleditsia%20triacanthos 2) https://www.weekand.com/home-garden/article/grow-honey-locust-branch-18057279.php"}, {"Plant_ID": "Gomphrena haageana", "Scientific Name": "Gomphrena haageana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Rio Grande Globe Amaranth", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Propagate by sowing seed at 60-65 degrees Fahrenheit in early spring. Sow seeds outdoors after all danger of frost has passed, or indoors 6-8 weeks prior to the last spring frost. Pinch young plants to promote bushiness.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/gomphrena-haageana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.gardenia.net/plant/gomphrena-haageana-strawberry-fields"}, {"Plant_ID": "Gomphrena serrata", "Scientific Name": "Gomphrena serrata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Gomphrena Weed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow the seeds in well-draining soil in a sunny location. Keep the soil moist until germination, which typically occurs within 1-2 weeks.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/gomphrena-serrata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://earthone.io/plant/gomphrena%20serrata?srsltid=AfmBOoqv37i3EiSXo3Jdez8gvfaJVeJ6Mfbtbqg505GKft52zqcQOhm2"}, {"Plant_ID": "Gonolobus suberosus", "Scientific Name": "Gonolobus suberosus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Anglepod Milkvine", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Select a healthy stem, ideally one with a few leaf nodes. Aim for a length of 4-6 inches. Trim the cutting just below a leaf node and remove the lower leaves. This allows the cutting to focus energy on root development. Use a well-draining mix of peat moss, perlite, and vermiculite, or simply moist perlite. Dip the cut end of the stem cutting in rooting hormone powder (optional). Plant the cutting in the rooting medium, ensuring the leaf nodes are above the soil line. Keep the rooting medium consistently moist. Place the pot in a warm, bright location out of direct sunlight. You should see roots developing within a few weeks. Once the roots are well established, you can transplant your new Gonolobus suberosus to a larger pot with well-draining soil. — Collection: Use sterilized scissors or a sharp knife to prevent the spread of diseases. Takie a healthy section of stem, removing the lower leaves, and rooting it in a suitable substrate. The best time for stem cuttings is during the growing season, typically from spring to early summer. This is when the plant is actively growing and rooting hormones are present. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Start by soaking seed in water for 24 hours. This simple step helps kickstart the germination process. For the best results, maintain a temperature of 70°F (21°C) during germination. This warm environment encourages healthy sprouting and sets the stage for robust growth.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/gonolobus-suberosus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-gonolobus-suberosus/ | https://greg.app/gonolobus-suberosus-overview/#:~:text=To%20propagate%20Gonolobus%20suberosus%20from,the%20stage%20for%20robust%20growth."}, {"Plant_ID": "Grindelia lanceolata", "Scientific Name": "Grindelia lanceolata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Narrowleaf Gumweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow autumn or spring in a cool greenhouse and only just cover the seed. Prick out the plants into individual pots when they are large enough to handle and plant them out into their permanent positions in early summer. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Division as new growth commences in the spring. Very easy, larger clumps can be replanted direct into their permanent positions, though it is best to pot up smaller clumps and grow them on in a cold frame until they are rooting well. Plant them out in the spring. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Propagation is easiest from seed, and germination rates are generally high. Achenes placed under a thin layer of soil on wet filter paper at ambient temperature and diffuse light germinate at around 70%, but an 8-day cool pretreatment at 46°F can raise these rates slightly. Germination usually occurs at 2 to 3 weeks at 50–60°F. Seed can be propagated in containers and transplanted, or sown directly on-site in the fall or spring, though October plantings tend to produce higher yields with lower irrigation requirements. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Place a sheet of sandpaper (medium grit) with the sandy side up in a beer or soda box (one with short sides) on a smooth or hard surface. Place the seeds to be scarified on the sandpaper. Now rub the seeds between the sandpaper for about ½ to 1 minute to wear holes in the impermeable surface of the seed. A second method that works well with about 1/3 to 1 cup of seeds is to place the seeds in a blender and hit the low speed touch blend button several times. Let the blender speed almost reach the maximum of its low setting. The following are some general steps to follow when germination seeds indoors. 1. Use flats, pots, or trays that are about three inches deep. There should be drainage holes in the bottoms of the containers. The containers should be new or else used containers should be soaked in 10% Clorox solution. 2. Fill the container to the top with a moist soil less growing medium and level off. Use a germination mix if possible that contains small particles. There are many soil less mixes on the market that contain predominantly peat moss and vermiculite. The important thing they lack is weed seeds and the fungi that cause damping off of the seedlings. 3. Using a board, hand, or other flat surface mash the loose potting mixture down about ¼ to ½ inch below the top of the container. 4. Sow seeds on the surface of the mix. Small seeds can be evenly scattered over the surface. Shaking them from a saltshaker may help. Larger seeds can also be scattered on the surface or planted in rows. 5. Cover the seeds to a depth that is about twice their diameter. Very small seeds like cardinal flower need no covering at all. The same fine particle germinating mix or fine sifted sphagnum or peat moss can be used to cover seeds. 6. Clearly label and date the seeds in a way that the writing will not be washed away by water. 7. Large and small seeds can be watered from above with a watering can that dispenses small drops. Large droplets tend to splash the seeds around a lot. It is often recommended that small seeds be watered from below by placing a container in a pan of water and letting the mix soak up the water. 8. Many people lay a piece of glass or plastic over the surface of the container to keep the seeds moist until they just begin to germinate. If this is done, don’t keep the seeds in direct sunlight or they may become too warm. The 3 inches of germination mix holds enough water to keep the surface moist during most of a 24 hr period without the use of a glass or plastic covering. This is assuming the air is still and sunlight is not intense.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/grindelia-lanceolata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Grindelia+lanceolata#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,Cuttings. | https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/plantguide/pdf/pg_grca.pdf | www.missouribotanicalgarden.org/Portals/0/Shaw%20Nature%20Reserve/PDFs/horticulture/Propagation.pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Gutierrezia sarothrae", "Scientific Name": "Gutierrezia sarothrae", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Snakeweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds in the spring in a greenhouse and only just cover the seed. Prick the plants out into individual pots as soon as they are large enough to handle, using deep pots to accommodate the tap root. Grow on for the first winter in a greenhouse and plant out into their permanent positions in late spring or early summer. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Cut sections appr — Collection: Take cuttings of half-ripe wood, July/August. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Soak the seeds in water for about 24 hours before sowing. This helps to soften the seed coat, encouraging germination. Ensure the water is at room temperature to prevent shocking the seeds. Plant the seeds in a seed tray filled with well-draining soil. Cover them lightly with soil, and ensure consistent moisture by misting with water. Place the tray in a location with indirect sunlight.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/gutierrezia-sarothrae/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Gutierrezia+sarothrae#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,July/August%20in%20a%20frame. 2) https://earthone.io/plant/gutierrezia%20sarothrae?srsltid=AfmBOoprfaMvK1fFkqRWd0pIjwkv_Od5gAhAOxpGHs6qoOsKYkPxj3mm | 1) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Gutierrezia+sarothrae#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,July/August%20in%20a%20frame. 2) https://www.forwardplant.com/plant-info/Gutierrezia_sarothrae/ | https://www.forwardplant.com/plant-info/Gutierrezia_sarothrae/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Bouteloua hirsuta", "Scientific Name": "Bouteloua hirsuta", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Hairy Grama", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: o effectively propagate hairy grama, a hardy perennial grass, employ division, a method well-suited for its growth habit. With a robust root system, gardeners should separate mature clusters into smaller bunches during the plant's active growth phase, ensuring each new segment contains a healthy section of roots. Careful handling is essential to maintain root integrity and encourage swift establishment in well-draining soil. Regular watering post-division aids in recovery and resilience, setting a foundation for vigorous new growth.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/hairy-grama/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Bouteloua_hirsuta.html#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Hairy%20grama?&text=To%20effectively%20propagate%20hairy%20grama,foundation%20for%20vigorous%20new%20growth."}, {"Plant_ID": "Helenium amarum", "Scientific Name": "Helenium amarum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Bitter Sneezeweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow spring in a greenhouse. When they are large enough to handle, prick the seedlings out into individual pots and plant them out in early summer. If you have sufficient seed it would be worthwhile trying a sowing in situ outdoors in mid to late spring. Fall sowing allows them to experience a period of cold stratification, which improves germination. Scatter seeds thinly across the prepared soil and lightly cover them with a thin layer of soil. Water thoroughly after sowing, ensuring the soil remains consistently moist. Germination can take several weeks, so practice patience. Once seedlings emerge, thin them out to give each plant enough space to thrive. Aim for a spacing of 12-18 inches between plants. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully dig up the plant and gently divide it into smaller sections, ensuring each section has healthy roots and foliage. Transplant the newly divided plants into prepared beds with well-drained soil and water them thoroughly. — Collection: After the plant has finished flowering, choose a healthy and well-established clump.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/helenium-amarum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Helenium+amarum#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,in%20mid%20to%20late%20spring. 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-helenium-amarum/?print=pdf 3) https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Helenium_amarum.html | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-helenium-amarum/?print=pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Helianthus annuus", "Scientific Name": "Helianthus annuus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Common Sunflower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Bud", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow them 1 inch deep and 6 inches apart in well-draining soil. Full sun is non-negotiable. Water well and watch for sprouts in 7 to 10 days. Thinning may be necessary; keep the robust seedlings. — Collection: Wait for the head to brown and the back to yellow. Protect your future seeds from birds with netting or bags. Once ready, cut the head and shake out the seeds or rub them free. Dry them on a towel before storing in a cool, dry place. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: ip the cut end in rooting hormone and plant in a sandy peat mix. Keep it humid and wait for roots to form in a few weeks. Transition your rooted cuttings gradually to outdoor conditions. Start with indirect light, increasing exposure over time. Patience is key; roots need time to establish before facing the full brunt of the sun. — Collection: Choose a healthy stem, 4-6 inches long, preferably in the morning. Strip the lower leaves to expose nodes. A sharp cut ensures a clean start. || Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: Remove the plant, tease apart the root ball, and ensure each new plant has a fair share of roots. Replant promptly in fresh soil and water well. — Collection: Timing is everything. Spring or early fall is ideal for division. This gives your sunflowers a chance to settle in without the stress of extreme temperatures. Observe your plants for signs of recovery and growth, adjusting care as needed.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/helianthus-annuus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://greg.app/propagate-common-sunflower/#:~:text=Division%20Propagation,growth%2C%20adjusting%20care%20as%20needed."}, {"Plant_ID": "Helianthus hirsutus", "Scientific Name": "Helianthus hirsutus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Hairy Sunflower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Bud", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: You can direct sow seeds in prepared garden beds after the last frost or start them indoors 6-8 weeks before your last frost date. Sow seeds about ¼ – ½ inch deep in well-draining soil. — Collection: Wait until the flower head has fully matured in late summer and dried on the plant. The petals will have fallen off, leaving behind a seed-filled disc. Cut off the flower head, leaving a few inches of stem attached. Look for plump, dark-colored seeds to ensure viability. Hang the flower heads upside down in a dry, well-ventilated area for a few weeks. This allows the seeds to fully dry out and become ready for storage or planting. Once the flower heads are completely dry, gently rub or shake them to release the seeds. Separate any remaining debris or plant material from the seeds using a sieve or your fingers. || Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: Use a sharp, clean knife or garden spade to divide the clump into smaller sections. Each section should have a healthy set of roots and shoots. Replant the divisions at the same depth they were originally growing, ensuring adequate spacing. Water thoroughly. — Collection: Early spring or fall, when the plant is dormant, is the ideal time for division. Carefully dig up the entire clump, ensuring you get as much of the root system as possible.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/helianthus-hirsutus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-helianthus-hirsutus/ 2) https://livetoplant.com/how-to-propogate-helianthus-plant-the-right-way/ | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-helianthus-hirsutus/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Helianthus maximiliani", "Scientific Name": "Helianthus maximiliani", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Maximilian Sunflower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: If growing indoors, it’s best to do cold, moist stratification. Start at least 5 weeks before outdoor night temperatures are reliably in the 10 C (50 F) range. Mix the seed with a slightly moistened, sterile, soil-less growing mix. Put this in a labelled, sealed plastic bag and store in a refrigerator for one day. The next day place this in the freezer for one day. Repeat this for one week, alternating between the fridge and the freezer. After stratifying, plant seed 0.32 cm (1/8 inch) deep in pots. Keep moist but not soggy and very warm (21 C - 70 F). When seedlings are 5 cm (2 inches) tall or more, transplant into the garden spaced 30 cm (1 foot) apart. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: In late fall through to mid-winter fill plastic pots with a slightly moistened, sterile, soil-less growing mix. Plant seed 0.32 cm (1/8 inch) deep in pots and label the pots. Place them outdoors in an area where they will experience the snow and cold of winter. The seed will germinate in the pots in spring as the weather warms up. Be sure to water the pots regularly in spring and once the plants are 5 cm (2 inches) tall, transplant them into your garden.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/helianthus-maximiliani/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflowerfarm.com/helianthus-maximiliani-maximilians-sunflower.html#:~:text=Indoors:%20Cold%2C%20moist%20stratification.,transplant%20them%20into%20your%20garden. 2) https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/plantguide/pdf/pg_hema2.pdf | 1) https://www.wildflowerfarm.com/helianthus-maximiliani-maximilians-sunflower.html#:~:text=Indoors:%20Cold%2C%20moist%20stratification.,transplant%20them%20into%20your%20garden. 2) https://earthone.io/plant/helianthus%20maximiliani?srsltid=AfmBOooK2F7kpWAp0KXoNXfff8sQ0SPVIaGNgwz3vxNCf1AYowJXOrKO"}, {"Plant_ID": "Heliotropium curassavicum", "Scientific Name": "Heliotropium curassavicum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Seaside Heliotrope", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Seeds can be sown in the spring || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Ensure the cuttings are placed in a well-draining soil mix and kept in a warm, bright location. — Collection: Cuttings can be taken during the growing season.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/heliotropium-curassavicum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://earthone.io/plant/heliotropium%20curassavicum?srsltid=AfmBOoqUDP9RELh6-3k3USnsKjii3nzIxvBhrZd4qYnRr3RdWjcOeHHf 2) https://store.theodorepayne.org/products/heliotropium-curassavicum-salt-heliotrope-seed | https://earthone.io/plant/heliotropium%20curassavicum?srsltid=AfmBOoqUDP9RELh6-3k3USnsKjii3nzIxvBhrZd4qYnRr3RdWjcOeHHf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Hesperaloe parviflora", "Scientific Name": "Hesperaloe parviflora", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Red Yucca", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Offshoots | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Offshoots — Treatment: Transplant — Method: Select a location with full sun and well-drained soil. Space harvested “pups,” at least 2-3 feet apart to allow for mature growth; young plants may be small, but they will spread relatively quickly. — Collection: Established plants will eventually develop offsets or “pups” that grow to the side of the plant. To propagate, dig up the offsets and replant them. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Presoak seeds overnight before planting 2 seeds per cell or plant. Once seedlings sprout, ensure they receive plenty of light by placing them on a sunny windowsill or positioning them 3-4 inches below fluorescent plant lights that are switched on for 16 hours daily and off for 8 hours at night. Adjust the lights as the plants grow taller. Avoid using incandescent bulbs as they generate excessive heat. Remember, most plants need a period of darkness to thrive, so do not keep the lights on for 24 hours. Transplant into garden when temperatures are consistently warm. Before transplanting seedlings into the garden, it's essential to \"harden them off\". This involves acclimating young plants to outdoor conditions by placing them in a sheltered outdoor area for about a week. Initially, shield them from strong winds and direct sunlight. If there's a risk of frost overnight, either cover the plants or bring them indoors, then return them outside in the morning. This hardening off method helps strengthen the plant's cell structure, minimizing transplant shock and sun damage. Space plants 48 - 60 inches apart in garden.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/hesperaloe-parviflora/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://dallascountymastergardeners.org/red-yucca-hesperaloe-parviflora/#:~:text=Propagation%20&%20Planting:,they%20will%20spread%20relatively%20quickly. | https://www.outsidepride.com/resources/planting/redyucca-planting/#:~:text=Presoak%20seeds%20overnight%20before%20planting,for%208%20hours%20at%20night."}, {"Plant_ID": "Heterotheca canescens", "Scientific Name": "Heterotheca canescens", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Hoary False Goldenaster", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Clean the seeds by removing any plant debris. If applicable, stratify the seeds by placing them in a moist medium such as peat moss or sand and refrigerate for 4-6 weeks to break dormancy. Prepare a well-draining soil mix, preferably sandy or loamy. Fill seed trays or pots with this mix and ensure it is moist but not waterlogged. Sow the seeds thinly on the soil surface. Lightly press them into the soil without burying them deeply. Cover with a thin layer of soil or vermiculite if needed, and mist lightly with water. Place the trays or pots in a location with indirect light and maintain consistent moisture by lightly misting the surface as needed. Monitor for germination, which typically occurs within 14-21 days. After the seeds have germinated and seedlings are established, gradually acclimate hoary false goldenaster to outdoor conditions by placing them in a sheltered area and gradually exposing them to more sunlight. Once strong enough, transplant seedlings into a well-draining location with full sunlight. Water regularly but avoid overwatering, as hoary false goldenaster prefers slightly drier conditions. — Collection: Collect seeds from mature hoary false goldenaster flowers. Ensure the seeds are fully ripened and dry before gathering. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds directly in the garden after the last frost. Seeds germinate best in moist soil under warm temperatures. This plant prefers full sun to partial shade and well-drained soil. Look for a sunny spot with loose, fertile soil to ensure your seedlings thrive. Scatter seeds thinly across the chosen area and lightly cover them with soil. Gently water the area to encourage germination. Germination will occur in approximately 2 weeks. Once seedlings emerge, thin them to about 6-12 inches apart, leaving the strongest plants to grow. This allows for better air circulation and promotes healthy growth. — Collection: Collect seeds when flower heads turn white and fluffy. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Separate established plants into smaller portions. Dig up a mature plant and gently divide it into sections, ensuring each division has healthy roots. Replant immediately and water as needed until roots are established. — Collection: The best time to divide Heterotheca canescens is in the spring or fall. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Cut a 4-6 inch stem just below a leaf node and remove the lower leaves. Dip the cut end in rooting hormone and plant it in a well-draining potting mix. — Collection: Take stem cuttings in late spring or early summer.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/heterotheca-canescens/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Heterotheca_canescens.html#:~:text=Hoary%20false%20goldenaster%2C%20commonly%20found%20in%20sunny%2C,conditions%20is%20crucial%20to%20prevent%20root%20rot. | 1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-heterotheca-canescens/ 2) NPSOT Austin member input | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-heterotheca-canescens/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Heterotheca subaxillaris", "Scientific Name": "Heterotheca subaxillaris", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Camphorweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Self-seed prolifically.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/heterotheca-subaxillaris/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://plantiary.com/plant/heterotheca-subaxillaris_5301.html#:~:text=Heterotheca%20Subaxillaris%20is%20best%20grown%20in%20well%2Ddrained,the%20soil%20is%20between%206.0%20and%207.5."}, {"Plant_ID": "Hibiscus laevis", "Scientific Name": "Hibiscus laevis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Halberd Leaf Hibiscus", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Containers: Soaking them in water for 12 to 24 hours before sowing and/or providing extra warmth from a heat mat can help to speed germination. Fill a container with moistened potting soil. Pack the soil firm, but leave a 1/2″ (12 mm) gap at the top. The soil should be moist, not wet. If you squeeze a handful, only a couple of drops of water should fall out. Plant the Hibiscus laevis seeds 1/4″ deep (6 mm). TIP – use a pencil to make the hole. Set the container in a location that receives morning sun and afternoon shade. This is a very important step, as the afternoon shade will help ensure that the seeds, and eventual seedlings won’t dry out in hot afternoon sun. Germination should occur in Spring as evening temperatures warm up. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct sow: Soaking them in water for 12 to 24 hours before sowing and/or providing extra warmth from a heat mat can help to speed germination. It helps to have a disturbed or somewhat barren area. Otherwise more established plants could shade out the tiny seedlings. In very wet areas, like the edge of a newly installed pond or disturbed area near water, you can just press seed into the soil, and lightly cover it with nearby dirt. If the area is somewhat uneven or fairly disturbed, you may even be able to just broadcast then walk on the seed. The first year of Hibicus laevis’s life will be establishing a strong taproot system. The foliage may grow a couple of feet, but it will probably just resemble a green leafy bush. But by the second year of life, it will produce at least one flowering stalk (perhaps more). By the 3rd year, the plant should be fully mature, putting out 4-8 stalks with multiple flowers.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/hibiscus-laevis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://growitbuildit.com/hibiscus-laevis-halbred-leaf-rose-mallow/#:~:text=The%20soil%20should%20be%20moist,pencil%20to%20make%20the%20hole. 2) https://hayefield.com/product/hibiscus-laevis-smooth-rose-mallow/#:~:text=Germination%20Information:%20Sow%20these%20seeds,description%20as%20well%20before%20ordering."}, {"Plant_ID": "Hibiscus moscheutos ssp. lasiocarpos", "Scientific Name": "Hibiscus moscheutos ssp. lasiocarpos", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Woolly Rose Mallow", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds just beneath the soil surface as they require light for germination. To ensure success, use a well-draining soil mix and maintain consistent moisture without waterlogging. A warm environment promotes optimal growth, so consider starting indoors if temperatures fluctuate. Once seedlings are sturdy enough, transplant them to their final location, carefully handling their delicate roots. — Collection: The fruit harvest time is usually in late fall, one month after blooming. At that point, its sepals are fully developed, turning dark purple before the lower leaves start falling. The fruits can be cut off from the stem base with sharp scissors after the morning dew is dry. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Plant the cutting in moist soil and keep it in a warm, bright location until roots develop. The cutting should begin forming roots within five weeks. Transplant the cutting into a larger container or directly in the garden after its roots are formed. — Collection: For stem cuttings, take a 6-inch cutting from a healthy plant in late spring or early summer. Remove any of the cutting's lower leaves before placing it in a container filled with 1 part peat and 3 parts sand. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Prepare the seeds by soaking them in warm water for one to 24 hours before planting. This breaks their dormancy, allowing the process of germination to begin. Use a sharp knife to lightly nick the seed on one edge. This allows maximum water penetration after planting. Start seeds inside about 12 weeks before the last frost, transplanting seedlings after the danger of frost has passed. Place seeds 1/4 inch deep in a container or pot filled with potting mix. Place in a sunny, warm area. Keep the soil moist. Seeds take 14 to 30 days to start sprouting.Alternately, gardeners can sow seeds directly in the garden in fall or after the danger of frost has passed in spring. When sowing seeds or planting young hibiscus moscheutos plants outdoors, select a sunny planting area with nutrient-rich, well-draining soil. — Collection: Gather seeds once the flowers fade. Gardeners can pinch the seed head off and place it in a cool, dry location to dry the seeds; or, let the pods dry on the plant before breaking them open to collect the seeds. Store seeds in a cool, dry spot until you are ready to plant them. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Separate the plant into three or four smaller plants by spreading the roots apart and pulling or cutting clumped areas apart. Remove any discolored or eroded roots. Plant the newly divided hibiscus moscheutos in holes that are as deep as the roots and wide, or wider than the spread of the roots. Cover with nutrient-rich soil and keep evenly moist. — Collection: Dig a trench around the plant's drip line, severing roots. Use a shovel to place an angled cut down and under the plant. Repeat the angled cutting around the outer edge of the drip line until you can lift the plant up from its hole.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/hibiscus-moscheutos-ssp-lasiocarpos/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Hibiscus_moscheutos_subsp._lasiocarpos.html#:~:text=Propagation%20Time:%20Mid%20spring%2C%20Late,carefully%20handling%20their%20delicate%20roots. | 1) https://earthone.io/plant/hibiscus%20moscheutos 2) https://www.weekand.com/home-garden/article/propagate-hibiscus-moscheutos-18065491.php | https://www.weekand.com/home-garden/article/propagate-hibiscus-moscheutos-18065491.php"}, {"Plant_ID": "Hilaria belangeri", "Scientific Name": "Hilaria belangeri", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Curly Mesquite", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Bud", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Start by soaking them for 24 hours before planting. This simple step boosts germination rates, and for optimal results, maintain a temperature of around 70°F (21°C). || Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully digging up and separating clumps. The best time for this technique is either early spring or fall, ensuring the plants have time to recover and thrive in their new locations. — Collection: Divide roots while the grass is dormant. Although some say to divide during the growing season has a higher success rate. Spreading by stolons is the main method of reproduction in the plant because it is often sterile and rarely forms seeds.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/hilaria-belangeri/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://greg.app/curly-mesquite-overview/#:~:text=%F0%9F%8C%B1%20Seed%20Propagation,F%20(21%C2%B0C). | 1) https://greg.app/curly-mesquite-overview/#:~:text=%F0%9F%8C%B1%20Seed%20Propagation,F%20 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=HIBEB#:~:text=Propagation&text=Description:%20Propagate%20by%20seed%20or,while%20the%20grass%20is%20dormant.1%C2%B0C). 3) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Hilaria_belangeri.html#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Curly%2Dmesquite?&text=Endemic%20to%20arid%20regions%2C%20curly,complications%20of%20seed%20germination%20obstacles. 4) https://www.spadefootnursery.com/grasses-grasslike-plants/hilaria-belangeri"}, {"Plant_ID": "Hilaria jamesii", "Scientific Name": "Hilaria jamesii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "James' Galleta", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Bud | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully separate healthy mature clumps during periods of active growth, ensuring each division has ample root structure and top growth. Replant the divisions promptly, maintaining appropriate soil moisture. Choose a sunny spot with well-draining soil. — Collection: The prime time to transplant is from the heart of spring into its waning weeks, to leverage the soil warmth and optimal growth conditions. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds in spring in a greenhouse. Only just cover the seed. When they are large enough to handle, prick the seedlings out into individual pots and grow them on in the greenhouse for at least their first winter. Plant them out into their permanent positions in late spring or early summer, after the last expected frosts. — Collection: Seed viability and germination are generally poor.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/hilaria-jamesii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Hilaria_jamesii.html | 1) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Hilaria+jamesii# 2) https://www.fs.usda.gov/database/feis/plants/graminoid/plejam/all.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Hydrocotyle verticillata", "Scientific Name": "Hydrocotyle verticillata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Whorled Marshpennywort", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Propagated through runners or lateral shoots that develop from the main plant. eparate the plant into smaller sections, each with roots and leaves, and replant them in moist soil. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Can also be propagated by taking stem cuttings and planting them. cut a healthy stem with leaves and place it in water or moist soil until roots develop.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/hydrocotyle-verticillata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.aquaticplants.co.za/product-page/hydrocotyle-verticillata#:~:text=It's%20generally%20easy%20to%20care%20for%20and,is%20not%20required%20but%20can%20be%20beneficial 2) https://earthone.io/plant/hydrocotyle%20verticillata"}, {"Plant_ID": "Hypericum hypericoides", "Scientific Name": "Hypericum hypericoides", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "St. Andrew's-cross", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds directly in the garden any time after danger of frost has passed. Alternatively, get a head start and plant them indoors a few weeks before the last expected frost. Be patient, as germination takes one to three months. — Collection: Fruits are capsules that burst open upon maturity and contain dozens to hundreds of tiny brown seeds. Collect fruit when brown and dry, but before they open. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove leaves from the lower half of the cutting to expose a section of the stem. Dip the cutting ends in rooting hormone before planting them in a well-draining soil mixture. Keep the soil consistently moist and provide dappled sunlight until the cuttings establish a strong root system. — Collection: Cuttings should be taken from healthy mature plants in autumn or early winter. Cut a stem that is 4-6 inches long. Ensure the cutting has several sets of leaves. The best cuttings come from the ends of branches that have not flowered yet. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully dig up the plant, separate the roots, and replant the divisions in the desired location. — Collection: In early spring or late fall, divide established plants.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/hypericum-hypericoides/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.gardeningknowhow.com/edible/herbs/st-johns-wort/growing-st-andrews-cross-plant.htm 2) https://longleafpine.fnpschapters.org/data/uploads/propagation-manual-for-fl-panhandle-native-plants/hypericum-hypericoides.pdf | https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Hypericum_hypericoides.html | https://thecameronteam.net/st-andrews-cross-native-plant-guide/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Hypericum sphaerocarpum", "Scientific Name": "Hypericum sphaerocarpum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Roundseed St. John's-wort", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Let nature handle the stratifying through a dormant seeding, sowing seeds on the surface of a weed-free site in late fall or winter.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/hypericum-sphaerocarpum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.prairiemoon.com/hypericum-sphaerocarpum-round-fruited-st-johns-wort"}, {"Plant_ID": "Hypoxis hirsuta", "Scientific Name": "Hypoxis hirsuta", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Yellow Star-grass", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Tuber | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Tuber — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully separate the tubers, ensuring that each section has a healthy amount of roots and shoots. Plant them in individual pots with well-draining soil. Or Choose a location with partial shade and well-drained soil. Plant the divisions in the ground at the same depth they were originally growing, water them thoroughly, and mulch around the base to retain moisture. — Collection: Best done during the dormancy period. Carefully dig around the plant, ensuring you get a good portion of the root system. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Direct sow in the fall, pressing the tiny seeds in the surface of rich soil and sprinkling a very thin layer of soil on top; this seed needs light to germinate. Mixing the seed with a small amount of sand may help in seed distribution. For spring planting, mix the seed with moist sand and store it in the refrigerator for 60 days before planting. To start indoors, sow seeds in a flat, keeping the soil lightly moist and at a temperature of 65-70 degrees F until germination, which will be slow and irregular. germination can take anywhere from a few weeks to a couple of months. Transplant seedlings outdoors as soon as they can safely be handled. — Collection: After blooming, this plant will produce a small pod that eventually splits to explosively release its small black seeds. To save the seeds, either bag the ripening pods with small pieces of fabric to capture the falling seed or remove the pods just before they split. Spread the pods out to dry, keeping in mind that they will need to be covered since they may still split to release their seeds. Store the cleaned seed in a cool, dry place.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/hypoxis-hirsuta/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://earthone.io/plant/hypoxis%20hirsuta 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-hypoxis-hirsuta/ | 1) https://www.everwilde.com/store/Hypoxis-hirsuta-WildFlower-Seed.html 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-hypoxis-hirsuta/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Ibervillea lindheimeri", "Scientific Name": "Ibervillea lindheimeri", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Balsam Gourd", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Propagates usually from seeds that must be sown in the spring and will germinate at about 20° C. The seedlings' caudex forms below ground and will grow much faster if left underground for some years. Warm temperatures are crucial for germination. Once germinated, handle seedlings carefully during transplanting and provide adequate light, gradually acclimatizing them to outdoor conditions before final planting. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the lower leaves. Put the cutting in a pot with a moist substrate and rinse it regularly until the branch roots in several weeks. — Collection: cut a healthy 4-inch (10 cm) long mature stem.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ibervillea-lindheimeri/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://myplantin.com/plant/763 2) https://www.llifle.com/Encyclopedia/SUCCULENTS/Family/Cucurbitaceae/31787/Ibervillea_lindheimeri#:~:text=Pest%20and%20disease:%20Bugs%2C%20mealy,left%20underground%20for%20some%20years. 3) https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Ibervillea_lindheimeri.html | https://myplantin.com/plant/763"}, {"Plant_ID": "Ilex decidua", "Scientific Name": "Ilex decidua", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Possumhaw Holly", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Hardwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Seeds germinate best if planted immediately after collection. They may be pretreated with double-stratification but the essential element seems to be time. Once internal conditions in the seed are right (it may take years), it will germinate. Double stratification consists of warm moist conditions for 30-60 days followed by a cold moist stratification of 60-90 days. || Hardwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Strip the leaves from the bottom half of the stem. Dip the cut end in a rooting hormone and plant it in a mixture of half perlite and half peat moss, maintaining high humidity conditions. Once cuttings have rooted, pot them individually in a well-draining potting mix. Plant them outdoors when they are well-established and the risk of frost has passed. — Collection: Use 4-6 inch stem cuttings taken in late winter or early spring when the plant is dormant. Be sure to select healthy, mature wood from the previous season’s growth. Make sure the cut is made just below a node.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ilex-decidua/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ILDE 2) https://scnps.org/plants/ilex-decidua/ | 1) https://dallascountymastergardeners.org/possumhaw-holly-ilex-decidua/ 2) https://plantiary.com/plant/ilex-decidua_4104.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Ilex vomitoria", "Scientific Name": "Ilex vomitoria", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Yaupon Holly", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: 30-60 days treatment at 68-86 degrees followed by 60-90 days of 41 degrees. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow immediately after collection.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ilex-vomitoria/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ILVO"}, {"Plant_ID": "Sorghastrum nutans", "Scientific Name": "Sorghastrum nutans", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Indiangrass", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Seed is damp stratified by mixing it with equal amounts of vermiculite and lightly dampening in a plastic bag or container. Store this seed for 3-4 months in a cold room of 34-36 degrees F. Sow seeds indoors: Start at least 4 weeks before outdoor night temperatures are reliably in the 10 C (50 F) range. Plant seed 0.64 cm (1/4 inch) deep in pots. Keep moist but not soggy and very warm (21 C - 70 F). When seedlings are 5 cm (2 in.) tall, transplant into the garden spaced 30 cm (1 ft.) apart. Seeds sown outdoors: Outdoors: Sow seed 0.64 cm (1/4 inch) deep outdoors in either late fall or early spring. — Collection: Collect seed in fall.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/indiangrass/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=SONU2 2) https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=poaceae-sorghastrum-288&referer=wildflower#:~:text=Seed%20is%20damp%20stratified%20by,Establishment%20Phase: 3) https://www.wildflowerfarm.com/sorghastrum-nutans-indiangrass.html#:~:text=Indoors:%20No%20pre%2Dtreatment%20necessary,late%20fall%20or%20early%20spring."}, {"Plant_ID": "Indigofera miniata", "Scientific Name": "Indigofera miniata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Scarlet Pea", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Place cutting in water until roots start to emerge. — Collection: Cut a stem just below a node. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Coastal indigo propagates best through fresh seeds in well-draining, organic-rich soil. Lightly covering seeds enhances soil contact for germination. Maintain consistent moisture without overwatering, and ensure ample sunlight post-germination for optimal growth. — Collection: Collect seed in late summer, fall when pods turn brown.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/indigofera-miniata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://earthone.io/plant/indigofera%20miniata?srsltid=AfmBOopnFQkgPSQVbkC-hkpO5prze78IH5GRxGsFQQC1xmXLTSESZlme 2) https://beach-landscaping.com/groundcover-and-vines-coastal-indigo/#:~:text=Botanical%20name:%20indigofera%20miniata,Invasive%20species:%20yes | 1) https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Indigofera_miniata.html 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=inmi"}, {"Plant_ID": "Ipomoea cordatotriloba", "Scientific Name": "Ipomoea cordatotriloba", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Purple Bindweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: For seed propagation, sow the seeds in a well-draining soil mix in spring. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: For stem cuttings, take cuttings from healthy plants and root them in water or a moist soil mix. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Germinating Ipomoea cordatotriloba, or tievine, seeds involves a few essential steps to ensure successful propagation of this fast-growing vine. Start by scarifying the seeds by gently scratching or nicking the seed coat. Scarification aids in water absorption, promoting quicker and more uniform germination. Following scarification, soak the seeds in warm water for about 24 hours to further facilitate hydration. After this period, sow the seeds in well-draining soil, covering them lightly. Maintain consistent moisture during the germination period and provide a warm environment, as Ipomoea cordatotriloba thrives in tropical conditions. Germination usually occurs within a few weeks. Once the seedlings have developed a few sets of leaves, they can be transplanted into their final outdoor location.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ipomoea-cordatotriloba/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://earthone.io/plant/ipomoea%20cordatotriloba 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-ipomoea-cordatotriloba/?print=pdf | 1) https://plantflowerseeds.com/products/ipomoea-cordatotriloba-tievine-10-seeds?srsltid=AfmBOoq_x_yrm2z1FlNEkFfjuTMJWq89P0WfixxbX-XEvwIZcxSJK0XN 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-ipomoea-cordatotriloba/?print=pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Ipomoea leptophylla", "Scientific Name": "Ipomoea leptophylla", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Bush Morning Glory", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Pre-soak the seed for 12 hours in warm water, or scarify the seed, and sow in individual pots in a greenhouse in early spring. The seed usually germinates in 1 - 3 weeks at 22°c. Plants are extremely resentful of root disturbance, even when they are quite small, and should be potted up almost as soon as they germinate[219]. Grow them on in the greenhouse for at least their first winter then plant them out into their permanent positions in late spring or early summer, after the last expected frosts.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ipomoea-leptophylla/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Ipomoea+leptophylla#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,Layering. 2) https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/plantmaterials/kspmcpg12295.pdf 3) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Ipomoea_leptophylla.html#:~:text=Bush%20morning%20glory%20is%20a%20hardy%20perennial,so%20maintain%20consistent%20watering%20during%20this%20stage."}, {"Plant_ID": "Ipomoea lindheimeri", "Scientific Name": "Ipomoea lindheimeri", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Lindheimer's Morning Glory", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Lindheimer's morning glory propagates effectively through sowing. Scarifying seeds enhances water absorption, promoting uniform germination. soak ca. 24-48 h in lukewarm water, Sow in well-draining soil, keeping it moist but not waterlogged, in a warm environment. This method yields diverse, vigorous offspring.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ipomoea-lindheimeri/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Ipomoea_lindheimeri.html 2) https://www.sunshine-seeds.de/Ipomoea-lindheimeri-45841p.html?language=en"}, {"Plant_ID": "Ipomopsis rubra", "Scientific Name": "Ipomopsis rubra", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Standing Cypress", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sown in the fall. Since it is a biennial, it is recommended that you plant two consecutive years in order to produce flowering stalks each year. — Collection: After flowering ceases, allow seeds to completely mature before removing for reseeding or collecting seed to plant in a new area.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ipomopsis-rubra/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=IPRU2"}, {"Plant_ID": "Iresine rhizomatosa", "Scientific Name": "Iresine rhizomatosa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Wood Amaranth", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end in rooting hormone, tapping off any excess. You can root your Iresine cutting either by placing it in clean water until roots form and then potting it or by putting the fresh cutting directly into the soil. Create a hole in the moist potting mix and gently insert the cutting. Lightly firm the soil around it. Cover the pot with a clear plastic bag or use a humidity dome to trap moisture. Place your cutting in a bright spot, out of direct sunlight. Keep the soil consistently moist but not soggy. In 2-3 weeks, you should see new growth, indicating successful rooting. Once the roots are established, typically after 4-6 weeks, you can transplant your new Iresine rhizomatosa into individual pots or directly into the garden. — Collection: Spring and early summer are ideal for taking cuttings, as the plant is actively growing. Choose healthy, non-flowering stems and make a clean cut about 4-6 inches long, just below a leaf node. Remove the lower leaves, leaving 2-3 leaves at the top. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Using your hands or a clean, sharp knife, carefully divide the clump into smaller sections, ensuring each section has a good amount of roots and shoots. Plant each division into its own pot or directly into the garden, using well-draining soil. Water thoroughly and provide shade for a few days while it adjusts. — Collection: If you have a mature Iresine rhizomatosa that has formed a dense clump, division is another excellent propagation method. Early spring is the best time to divide your plant, just as new growth emerges. Carefully dig up the entire plant, ensuring you get as much of the root system as possible.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/iresine-rhizomatosa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-iresine-rhizomatosa/ 2) https://plnts.com/en/care/houseplants-family/iresine 3) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Iresine_rhizomatosa.html | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-iresine-rhizomatosa/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Juglans microcarpa", "Scientific Name": "Juglans microcarpa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Little Walnut", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratify for 60-120 days at 34-41 degrees. Sow in spring. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Remove husks. It is not necessary to remove shell. Sow immediately in fall — Collection: Collect nuts in fall or winter when husks begin to turn black and split open.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/juglans-microcarpa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=JUMI"}, {"Plant_ID": "Juniperus ashei", "Scientific Name": "Juniperus ashei", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Ashe Juniper", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Seed can be sown outdoors in fall. Germlination is poor, sow a large number of seeds. — Collection: Collect seeds from late summer through fall when it has turned its ripe color. Seed can be extracted by running the fruits through a macerator. Thoroughly dry and clean seeds to avoid mold and overheating.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/juniperus-ashei/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=JUAS"}, {"Plant_ID": "Juniperus virginiana", "Scientific Name": "Juniperus virginiana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Eastern Red Cedar", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratify at 41 degrees for 30-120 days. Sown in the spring. — Collection: Collect seeds from late summer through fall when it has turned its ripe color. Thoroughly dry and clean seeds to avoid mold and overheating. If not planting immediately, air dry before storing || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sown in the fall. Germination often poor so large quantity of seed needed. — Collection: Collect seeds from late summer through fall when it has turned its ripe color. Thoroughly dry and clean seeds to avoid mold and overheating. If not planting immediately, air dry before storing", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/juniperus-virginiana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=JUVI"}, {"Plant_ID": "Justicia americana", "Scientific Name": "Justicia americana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Water Willow", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Root | Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Root — Treatment: Division — Method: Divide and transplant in another area or in a pot. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds in the spring. Peat pots provide an ideal environment for american water-willow seedlings, promoting healthy root development. Peat pots can be planted directly into the soil, reducing root disturbance. This feature is crucial for american water-willow, which may have delicate root systems that could be damaged during transplanting. Spread the seeds evenly across the surface of the prepared soil. Lightly press the seeds into the soil but do not bury them deeply, as they require light to germinate effectively. Cover the seed trays with a clear plastic lid or wrap to maintain a high humidity environment. Place in indirect sunlight and ensure the soil remains consistently moist. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the lower leaves and dip the bottom of the stem in rooting hormone. Plant the cutting in a container filled with moist potting soil and cover with a plastic bag or dome. Place the container in a well-lit area, but avoid direct sunlight. — Collection: Take a stem cutting in spring or summer that is at least 6 inches long and has 2-4 nodes", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/justicia-americana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "Experience from NPSOT Austin member, Claire Sorenson. | https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Justicia_americana.html | 1) https://plantiary.com/plant/justicia-americana_12002.html 2) https://www.botanikks.com/plants/justicia-americana-l-vahl/517769/1"}, {"Plant_ID": "Justicia pilosella", "Scientific Name": "Justicia pilosella", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Hairy Tube-tongue", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: From herbaceous stem cuttings. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct sow outdoors in fall or in spring after last frost. — Collection: Allow pods to dry on plant; break open to collect seeds.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/justicia-pilosella/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://davesgarden.com/guides/pf/go/75169"}, {"Plant_ID": "Krameria lanceolata", "Scientific Name": "Krameria lanceolata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Trailing Ratany", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Use a small, triangular, fine-toothed file to create a groove that penetrates the capsule just to the point that the seed inside becomes visible. The seed is tan and fills the capsule, so don’t blithely file away through the capsule into the seed. Holding the capsule firmly with small needle-nose pliers saves getting numerous stabs from the spines. Be careful of crushing the capsule and the seed within. Empty capsules became apparent when the file groove opened into an empty space. Floating in water seems to be a way to separate empty from viable capsules, with viable seeds sinking quickly, but more information is needed. Plant the seeds in a well-draining soil mix. The seeds are reported to require light for germination, so don’t bury them too deep. germination can be slow and erratic, sometimes taking several months. In my case, using six fresh seeds collected 2 days prior (some taken from the plant, others from the ground where they had fallen), the six seeds all germinated within 2 weeks. Three germinated outside in potting soil medium and three germinated indoors in damp vermiculite (before I could get them into cold stratification). K. lanceolata is reported to be an obligate semi-parasite, forming haustoria on the roots of a broad range of host plants. In pots it may be necessary to include one or more other native plants. The wild plants providing my seeds are growing among primarily Nolina lindheimeriana and Aristida purpurea. — Collection: Collect seed in summer when fruit is brown and sharp. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end in a rooting hormone to encourage root development. Plant the cuttings in a well-draining potting mix and place them in a humid environment. A propagation box or covering the pot with a plastic bag can help retain moisture. Once the cuttings have developed a strong root system, they can be transplanted into individual pots or directly into the ground. — Collection: Take cuttings in the spring or early summer from healthy, new growth.Choose stems that are about 4-6 inches long and remove the lower leaves.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/krameria-lanceolata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=KRLA 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-krameria-lanceolata/?print=print 3) https://beetlesinthebush.com/2009/08/07/friday-flower-krameria-lanceolata/ 4) Tom Heger, NPSOT member, personal growing experience. | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-krameria-lanceolata/?print=print"}, {"Plant_ID": "Lantana horrida", "Scientific Name": "Lantana horrida", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Lantana", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Root", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Start lantana seeds indoors 6 to 8 weeks before you plan to transplant them outdoors. Soak seeds for 12-24 hours in clean, warm water to soften the seed coat. Fill small, individual pots to within ½ inch (1 cm) of the top with soilless seed starting medium and moisten the medium with water. Lay one or two seeds in the center of each pot and cover them with 1/8 inch (3 mm) of soil. If more than one seedling emerges, clip out the weakest plant with a pair of scissors. Keep the soil consistently moist and at a steady temperature between 70 and 75 F (21-24 C) day and night. A good way to maintain the moisture is to place the pots in a clear plastic bag. You can keep temperatures steady with a heat mat. While the pots are in the bag, keep them away from direct sunlight. Check the pots often and remove the bag as soon as the seedlings emerge. Be patient, and don't give up hope if your seedlings don't sprout right away. Even under ideal conditions, you can expect germination to take 6 to 8 weeks. — Collection: Collect seeds as soon as the fruit has filled out and turned dark. Air dry with pulp on or clean before storage. Store in sealed, refrigerated containers. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Prepare a small pot of seed starting mix or a half-and-half mixture of peat moss and perlite. Moisten the mix with water and make a hole 2 inches (5 cm) deep in the center of the pot with a pencil. Coat the lower 2 inches (5 cm) of the cutting with rooting hormone. (Though rooting hormone is not essential, it may help to speed the process). Place the cutting in the hole, firming the medium around the base so it stands up straight. Place three or four craft sticks in the soil near the edge of the pot. Space them evenly around the pot. Put the potted cutting in a plastic bag and seal the top. The craft sticks will keep the bag from touching the cutting. Each cutting should be watered well at planting, and kept consistently moist throughout the following weeks. Check occasionally to make sure the soil is moist, but otherwise leave the cutting undisturbed until you see signs of new growth. Rooting takes three to four weeks. After two weeks, you can check the plants by gently tugging at the base of each cutting. Any resistance will indicate that the plants have been successfully rooted. Remove the cutting from the bag and place it in a sunny window until you are ready to transplant it outdoors. — Collection: Take cuttings of new growth in spring. Cut 4-inch (10 cm) tips from the stems and remove the lower leaves from the cutting, leaving only the uppermost 1-2 sets of true leaves at the top. || Root — Treatment: Division — Method: Texas Lantana may also be propagated by digging the root ball and dividing it into smaller sections for re-planting.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/lantana-urticoides/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=LAUR2 2) https://www.gardeningknowhow.com/ornamental/flowers/lantana/how-to-propagate-lantana.htm | https://www.gardeningknowhow.com/ornamental/flowers/lantana/how-to-propagate-lantana.htm | https://dallascountymastergardeners.org/texas-lantana/#:~:text=Minimal%20care%20is%20required%20for,require%20staking%20or%20other%20support."}, {"Plant_ID": "Lepidium virginicum", "Scientific Name": "Lepidium virginicum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Peppergrass", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow the seeds into a high-quality potting mix and water deeply to encourage germination. Keep the pots somewhere that is warm and keep the soil moist. Once sprouted, you’ll need to harden off the seedlings once they have a set of true leaves. Don’t put them outside without hardening off or you risk killing your plants. When you direct sow the seeds outside, plant the seeds 8-12 inches apart; they grow fast, so you can thin later. In ideal conditions, peppergrass plants can get bushy, so leave space for them to grow. Simply cover the seeds with 1/2 inch of dirt and water deeply. These seeds germinate quickly, typically within 4-8 days. You’ll practically be able to watch them grow.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/lepidium-virginicum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.canativeseeds.com/product/lepidium-virginicum-pepperweed-/872https://morningchores.com/growing-peppergrass/ 2) https://www.canativeseeds.com/product/lepidium-virginicum-pepperweed-/872 3) https://earthone.io/plant/lepidium%20virginicum 4) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Lepidium_virginicum.html#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Virginia%20pepperweed?&text=Virginia%20pepperweed%20is%20best%20propagated,drainage%20to%20promote%20healthy%20growth."}, {"Plant_ID": "Leptochloa dubia", "Scientific Name": "Leptochloa dubia", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Green Sprangletop", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct seed in the ground. Seed should be placed 1⁄4 to 1⁄2 inch deep. Seedbed preparation should begin the year prior to spring planting to reduce weed problems during the first year of establishment. Work the site as necessary during the summer or early fall prior to establishment to create a firm weed-free seedbed. Work should be completed in the fall to allow time for the soil to settle and accumulate moisture.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/leptochloa-dubia/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://sharpseed.com/green-sprangletop/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Leucaena retusa", "Scientific Name": "Leucaena retusa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Goldenball Leadtree", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: The Goldenball Lead Tree can be propagated through seeds, which are usually soaked for a few hours before planting to improve germination. Seedlings can be established in nurseries before being transplanted into the field.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/leucaena-retusa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.innovationgrounds.com/goldenball-leadtree/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Leucophyllum frutescens", "Scientific Name": "Leucophyllum frutescens", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Cenizo", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Softwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Seeds can be started immediately in the greenhouse or directly in the garden any time after the season's last spring frost. Press seeds lightly into the soil and water regularly until germination occurs. Then, reduce watering, allowing the soil to dry out between waterings. — Collection: Collect the tiny seeds before the seed capsule dries completely and splits open, and store the seeds in a cool and dry place, such as the refrigerator. || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the end in rooting powder and place it in a pot with well-draining potting soil in a bright place with indirect light. Water the potting mix lightly and spritz the plants regularly with water. Don’t let the soil dry completely, but avoid keeping it fully saturated. Cover the pot with clear plastic or spritz the plants several times throughout the day until root growth begins. Rooting can take a few weeks to several months. — Collection: Softwood and semi-hardwood cuttings taken from the current year's growth. After blooming ends in summer, but you can also take hardwood cuttings while the plant is dormant in late fall or winter. Cut 4 to 6 inches from the tip of a stem. Remove the foliage from the bottom half of the stem cutting.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/leucophyllum-frutescens/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.bhg.com/how-to-plant-and-grow-texas-sage-8286146#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Texas%20Sage,day%20until%20root%20growth%20begins. 2) https://comalmg.org/focus-on-a-native-32/#:~:text=Cenizo%20propagation%20can%20be%20done,Plants%20are%20commonly%20available%20commercially. | 1) https://www.bhg.com/how-to-plant-and-grow-texas-sage-8286146#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Texas%20Sage,day%20until%20root%20growth%20begins. 2) https://www.gardeningknowhow.com/ornamental/shrubs/texas-sage/rooting-texas-sage-cuttings.htm 3) https://comalmg.org/focus-on-a-native-32/#:~:text=Cenizo%20propagation%20can%20be%20done,Plants%20are%20commonly%20available%20commercially. 4) https://www.missouribotanicalgarden.org/gardens-gardening/your-garden/help-for-the-home-gardener/advice-tips-resources/visual-guides/propagating-plants-by-cuttings#:~:text=Many%20plants%20will%20root%20from,rot%20if%20kept%20too%20wet."}, {"Plant_ID": "Liatris aspera", "Scientific Name": "Liatris aspera", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Tall Blazing Star", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Blazing star seed usually germinates readily. Four to six weeks of cold, moist stratification is helpful. Sow the stratified seed ¼ inch deep into transplanting containers two months before the last frost freeze date and grow in the greenhouse. Takes 5.5 months to grow out seedling transplants under greenhouse conditions. Seedlings will be ready for transplanting when they become root bound with vigorous root growth and small corm. Place plants in a shade house for approximately two weeks to harden off before transplanting. Transplant the seedlings at 8 inch intervals into rows in a firm, weed free seedbed. — Collection: Harvest seed in October. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Divide the corms so each one has a growth point. Treat the corms with fungicide and store in slightly moist sphagnum peat moss at 28-30°F for 10 weeks of cold storage before replanting the following spring. Do not allow the corms to thaw and refreeze or dry out during cold storage. After freezing, the corms can be stored up to 2 weeks at 40-45°F before replanting. Plant corms 1” deep into a firm, weed free seedbed using a planting rate of no more than 4 corms per square foot. Water corms as needed for the first three weeks after planting to provide a moderately moist soil and promote sprouting. Afterwards, allow the soil to dry between waterings as a constantly saturated soil will promote root rot development. — Collection: Divide corms of older tall blazing star plants in the fall after stem die-back.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/liatris-aspera/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://mowildflowers.net/liatris-aspera-rough-blazing-star-1/#:~:text=Liatris%20aspera%20(Rough%20Blazing%20Star) 2) https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/plantguide/pdf/pg_lias.pdf | https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/plantguide/pdf/pg_lias.pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Liatris punctata", "Scientific Name": "Liatris punctata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Gayfeather", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratify 3 months at 40 degrees. Sow following spring. — Collection: Wait until the flower heads on the entire stalk have turned fluffy tan before collecting. Bring the stalks inside to air-dry then shake or brush the nutlets from the heads. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Lightly nick with knife. Sow in fall.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/liatris-punctata-var-mucronata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=LIPUM2"}, {"Plant_ID": "Lindera benzoin", "Scientific Name": "Lindera benzoin", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Spicebush", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratify for 90-120 days at 41 degrees. Some texts say double stratification (a month of warm stratification followed by 3 months of cool stratification) is necessary. — Collection: Collect seeds in late summer through October when the fruit has turned red. Seeds must be cleaned before storing.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/lindera-benzoin/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=LIBE3"}, {"Plant_ID": "Lindheimera texana", "Scientific Name": "Lindheimera texana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Yellowstar", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow or scatter seed on bare soil in non-turf areas in November. Rosettes will grow slowly over winter, and quickly after February. To grow indoors in trays, scatter the seeds across the surface of the prepared soil. Gently press them into the top layer of the soil without covering them, as they need light to germinate. Maintain consistent moisture in the soil, but avoid waterlogging. Germination typically occurs within two to three weeks. — Collection: Seed can be collected in May.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/lindheimera-texana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.gardenstylesanantonio.com/plants/lindheimer-daisy/# 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Lindheimera_texana.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Lithospermum incisum", "Scientific Name": "Lithospermum incisum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Narrowleaf Puccoon", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Root", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Method: Soak seeds in hot (135 degrees) water overnight, and plant immediately. || Root — Treatment: Division — Method: Take 2-inch cutting. Treat cuttings with hormones and plant in soil in the fall.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/lithospermum-incisum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=LIIN2"}, {"Plant_ID": "Lobelia cardinalis", "Scientific Name": "Lobelia cardinalis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Cardinal Flower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: This species requires or benefits from a three month period of cold-moist stratification in the refrigerator. — Collection: As seeds approach maturity, the capsule opens slightly at its top. Check capsules at both upper and lower portions of the stalk. || Stem — Treatment: Layering — Method: Stem rooting, by bending a stem down into the mud and fastening it with a rock or sticks.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/lobelia-cardinalis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=LOCA2"}, {"Plant_ID": "Lonicera albiflora", "Scientific Name": "Lonicera albiflora", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "White Honeysuckle", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratification for two to three months at 40 degrees. — Collection: Collect seeds in late summer to early fall when berries turn ripe color. Clean immediately to avoid fermentation and overheating.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/lonicera-albiflora/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=LOAL"}, {"Plant_ID": "Lonicera sempervirens", "Scientific Name": "Lonicera sempervirens", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Coral Honeysuckle", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Softwood | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the bottom sets of leaves and dip the cut end in rooting hormone. Insert the cutting in a small pot filled with damp potting mix, deep enough so the two nodes are buried. Place the pot with the cutting in bright light away from direct sunlight. Keep it moist. As new growth appears, check for root growth by gently tugging, if there is resistance, roots have formed. Leave it in the pot and keep it well=watered for at least another month before transplanting it into the landscape in the fall. — Collection: Using sharp pruners, cut a 6-inch piece of softwood vine, ideally with two nodes near the cut end and two sets of leaves at the tip of the cutting. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratification for two to three months at 40 degrees. Pant the seeds on small pots filled with well-draining, damp potting mix. Cover the seeds lightly. Place a clear dome or plastic bag or over the seeds to retain moisture. Keep the soil moist. Once the seeds have germinated, remove the cover. — Collection: Collect seeds in late summer to early fall when berries turn ripe color. Clean immediately to avoid fermentation and overheating. Store in sealed containers at 34-38 degrees.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/lonicera-sempervirens/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.thespruce.com/coral-honeysuckle-guide-5190661 | 1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=lose 2) https://www.thespruce.com/coral-honeysuckle-guide-5190661"}, {"Plant_ID": "Ludwigia octovalvis", "Scientific Name": "Ludwigia octovalvis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Mexican Primrose Willow", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Offshoots", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: For optimal growth, use well-draining soil that stays moist but not waterlogged. Seeds should be gently pressed into soil and kept in a bright, warm location to encourage germination. Consistent moisture during this stage is crucial. Young plants must be hardened off before transplanting outdoors to acclimatize them to the natural environment. Carefully monitoring for pests and diseases during the early stages of development will ensure a healthy start. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove any lower leaves to prevent them from rotting in the water. Place the cutting in a separate container with water or directly plant it in the substrate. Within a few weeks, roots should start to grow, and a new plant will form. — Collection: Simply cut a healthy stem with a sharp, sterile pair of scissors or pruning shears. Make sure the cutting is at least a few inches long and has a few leaves. || Offshoots — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Side shoots are another method of propagation that involves removing and replanting the small shoots that grow from the main stem. Plant the shoots in the substrate, ensuring that the roots are properly buried. With proper care, the shoots will establish themselves as individual plants. — Collection: Shoots can be carefully detached from the parent plant using your fingers or a pair of tweezers.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ludwigia-octovalvis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Ludwigia_octovalvis.html#:~:text=Key%20care%20points%20include%20ensuring,be%20invasive%20in%20favorable%20conditions. | https://blog.cantonaquatics.com/aqua-eden-chronicles/the-ultimate-guide-to-propagating-ludwigia-repens#:~:text=Simply%20cut%20a%20healthy%20stem,plant%20it%20in%20the%20substrate."}, {"Plant_ID": "Lupinus texensis", "Scientific Name": "Lupinus texensis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Bluebonnet", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Scarification will hasten germination. Put seeds in the freezer overnight and then douse with boiling water to crack seedcoats. Soaking seeds overnight is also effective. Drain water, add rhizobium, and plant. — Collection: Allow the bluebonnet to reseed itself by leaving the seed pods intact on the plant until they turn from yellow to brown.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/lupinus-texensis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=LUTE"}, {"Plant_ID": "Lycium berlandieri", "Scientific Name": "Lycium berlandieri", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Berlandier's Wolfberry", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Semi-harwood | Softwood | Suckers", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Mash the very wet berries with a potato masher, fork, and/or fingers to separate pulp. Follow with a wet ferment for one week in a gallon jar. Water winnow and rinse through No. 20 sieve.It may be possible to skip the fermenting step and simply separate the pulp after mashing. Rock tumblers can also be used to separate the pulp from the seeds (Dreeson 2004). Cleaned seeds should be stored in cool, dry, airtight containers ~5°C (Bonner and Karrfalt 2008). Germination rates of some Lycium sp. increase with cold stratification, although it varies between species and some do not require stratification (Bonner and Karrfalt 2008). Untreated Lycium andersonii seeds have germination rates between 68% and 94% while Lycium barbarum seeds need 60-120 days of cold stratification in moist sand at 5°C to achieve germination results of 74% (Bonner and Karrfalt 2008). sow early spring in a greenhouse. Germination is usually good and fairly quick. Prick out the seedlings into individual pots when they are large enough to handle and grow them on in the greenhouse for their first winter. Plant out in late spring or early summer. Pinch out the shoot tips of the young plants in order to encourage bushy growth[78]. Cuttings of half-ripe wood, 5 - 10cm with a heel if possible, July/August in individual pots in a frame. — Collection: Collect mature berries by hand. || Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: You can take a 4-5 inch long cutting, remove the leaves from the lower two-thirds of the stem, and dip the cuttings in rooting hormone. — Collection: The best time to take cuttings is during the spring season when the new stems have developed. || Suckers — Treatment: Division — Method: The suckers can be planted out direct into their permanent positions. — Collection: Division of suckers in late winter.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/lycium-berlandieri/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=LYBE 2) https://rngr.net/npn/propagation/protocols/lycium-berlandieri-lycium#:~:text=Mash%20the%20very%20wet%20berries,(Bonner%20and%20Karrfalt%202008). 3) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Lycium+berlandieri#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,Layering. 4) https://www.fs.usda.gov/database/feis/plants/shrub/lycber/all.html#:~:text=Stratified%20seeds%20of%20other%20wolfberry,establishment%20of%20other%20woody%20species. | 1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=LYBE 2) https://www.fs.usda.gov/database/feis/plants/shrub/lycber/all.html#:~:text=Stratified%20seeds%20of%20other%20wolfberry,establishment%20of%20other%20woody%20species. | 1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=LYBE 2) https://www.fs.usda.gov/database/feis/plants/shrub/lycber/all.html#:~:text=Stratified%20seeds%20of%20other%20wolfberry,establishment%20of%20other%20woody%20species. 3) https://www.botanikks.com › plants › lycium-berlandieri | 1) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Lycium+berlandieri#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,Layering. 2) https://www.fs.usda.gov/database/feis/plants/shrub/lycber/all.html#:~:text=Stratified%20seeds%20of%20other%20wolfberry,establishment%20of%20other%20woody%20species."}, {"Plant_ID": "Lygodesmia texana", "Scientific Name": "Lygodesmia texana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Skeleton Plant", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end of each cutting into a rooting hormone. Fill a pot with a well-draining soil mix, typically one designed for cacti and succulent, suits the growing conditions of Texas Skeleton Weed. Plant the cuttings about 2 inches deep in the soil, ensuring that the leaves are above the soil surface. Place the pot in a location that receives indirect sunlight, as Texas Skeleton Weed thrives best under partial sun exposure. Keep the environment around the plant humid, by misting it daily, but not the leaves directly. Initially, water the soil lightly just to keep it slightly moist, not soggy; over-watering can lead to rot issues. Reduce watering frequency once signs of new growth appear, adapting to a more infrequent watering schedule suitable for a drought-tolerant species. — Collection: Collect stem cuttings from healthy, mature plants. Ensure that each cutting is about 4-6 inches long and includes several leaves. A clean, sharp knife or pruners should be used to make a clean cut just below a leaf node.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/lygodesmia-texana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Lygodesmia_texana.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Lythrum alatum", "Scientific Name": "Lythrum alatum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Winged Loosestrife", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: divide mature plants in early spring or fall. Ensure the new divisions have adequate moisture to establish roots. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct sow winged loosestrife seeds in late fall; since they need light to germinate, plant them on the surface of the soil.This purple loosestrife seed can also be started indoors 6-8 weeks before planting in the spring. — Collection: After the flowers fade, a slender pod will develop. Since the tiny seeds easily blows away, shake the seed out of the pods as soon as they open. Store the winged loosestrife seed in a cool, dry place. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: For spring planting, mix the Lythrum Alatum seeds with moist sand and store them in the refrigerator for 60 days before planting. Keep the soil lightly moist until germination. Plant the stratified seeds in early spring. Use a well-drained seed starting mix in pots or trays. Sprinkle the seeds lightly on the surface of the soil and barely cover them with a thin layer of soil or vermiculite. Place the pots or trays in a location that receives indirect light and maintains a consistent temperature. Keep the soil moist but not waterlogged. Germination should occur within 3-4 weeks. Once the seedlings have developed a couple of sets of true leaves and are sturdy enough, transplant them to individual pots or directly into the garden. Ensure the transplantation is done on a cloudy day or in the evening to reduce stress on the young plants. — Collection: After the flowers fade, a slender pod will develop. Since the tiny seeds easily blows away, shake the seed out of the pods as soon as they open. Store the winged loosestrife seed in a cool, dry place.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/lythrum-alatum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://earthone.io/plant/lythrum%20alatum | 1) https://www.everwilde.com/store/Lythrum-alatum-WildFlower-Seed.html 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Lythrum_alatum.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Maclura pomifera", "Scientific Name": "Maclura pomifera", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Osage Orange", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Hardwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Soak seeds in water for 24 hours before planting to improve germination. Sow seeds directly outdoors or in containers, covering lightly with soil. — Collection: Seed should be collected from the fruit in the fall. || Hardwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Root cuttings in well draining soil mix under warm, humid conditions. — Collection: Taken in late winter or early spring.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/maclura-pomifera/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://earthone.io/plant/maclura%20pomifera 2) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/maclura-pomifera#:~:text=Cuttings%20*%20Take%20hardwood%20cuttings%20in%20late,well%2Ddraining%20soil%20mix%20under%20warm%2C%20humid%20conditions."}, {"Plant_ID": "Berberis trifoliolata", "Scientific Name": "Berberis trifoliolata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Agarita", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Hardwood | Suckers", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: The seeds need a cold stratification of two to three months. Therefore, it can be sown through summer or autumn and the seeds then germinate in spring. As it is a Perennial plant, it doesn't need to be sown yearly and has a very long lifespan. Green seed (harvested when the embryo has fully developed but before the seed case has dried) should be sown as soon as it is harvested and germinates within 6 weeks. Plant them out in late spring or early summer and consider giving them some protection from the cold for their next winter. — Collection: Best sown as soon as it is ripe in a greenhouse. Growers report that Agarita grown from seed will take a minimum of three years to produce a 5-gallon plant. The seedlings as well seem to be quite particular about their soil conditions. || Hardwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Root dormant hardwood cuttings. Cut 5-6 inches in length, apply rooting hormone, and keep under mist. — Collection: Take cuttings in winter from the previous year's growth. || Suckers — Treatment: Division — Method: Whilst they can be placed direct into their permanent positions, better results are achieved if they are potted up and placed in a frame until established. — Collection: Divide suckers in spring.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/mahonia-trifoliolata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Berberis_trifoliolata#:~:text=The%20plant%20can%20be%20reproduced,therefore%20relatively%20resistant%20to%20pathogens. 2) https://www.ensembletexas.com/agarita-mahonia-trifoliolata/#:~:text=Propagation:,I%20will%20report%20back! 3) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Mahonia+trifoliolata#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,Leaf%20cuttings%20in%20the%20autumn. | https://www.ensembletexas.com/agarita-mahonia-trifoliolata/#:~:text=Propagation:,I%20will%20report%20back! | https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Mahonia+trifoliolata#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,Leaf%20cuttings%20in%20the%20autumn."}, {"Plant_ID": "Malvaviscus arboreus", "Scientific Name": "Malvaviscus arboreus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Turk's Cap", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Turk's Cap will germinate promptly from fresh, untreated seeds planted outside after danger of frost is past. Germination of Turk's Cap is inhibited by cold temperatures. Cover the seeds no deeper than 1/4 - 1/2 inches. — Collection: Allow to dry whole and then crush the desiccated fruit with a rolling pin. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: The cuttings should be 4 to 6 inches long with leaves from the bottom halves removed, Dip the cut end in rooting hormone, and plant it in a well-draining soil mix. Keep the soil moist and place the cutting in a warm, bright location until roots develop. — Collection: Take cuttings in the spring or early summer. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Large clumps of Turk's Cap may easily be separated in early spring and transplanted to a new site. Be sure to water well.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/malvaviscus-arboreus-var-drummondii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=MAARD#:~:text=Propagation%20Material:%20Root%20Division%20%2C%20Seeds,inches%20after%20the%20last%20frost. | 1) https://earthone.io/plant/malvaviscus%20arboreus 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=MAARD#:~:text=Propagation%20Material:%20Root%20Division%20%2C%20Seeds,inches%20after%20the%20last%20frost."}, {"Plant_ID": "Marshallia caespitosa", "Scientific Name": "Marshallia caespitosa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Barbara's Buttons", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump division", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Fall Sowing (Outdoors): For a natural approach, sow seeds directly outdoors in fall. This mimics the plant’s natural life cycle, allowing seeds to experience winter’s chill for optimal germination come spring. Late Winter/Early Spring (Indoors): If starting seeds indoors, aim for late winter or early spring, about 6-8 weeks before the last expected frost. Choose a location with well-draining soil and full sun to light shade. Loosen the soil and remove any weeds. Scatter seeds evenly over the prepared area and lightly press them into the soil, ensuring good seed-to-soil contact. Do not bury the seeds deeply, as they require light for germination. Water gently but thoroughly, keeping the seedbed consistently moist but not waterlogged. || Clump division — Treatment: Division — Method: Divide established Barbara’s Buttons plants in early spring or fall when the soil is moist but not waterlogged. Carefully dig up the entire clump, ensuring you get as much of the root system as possible. Gently tease apart the plant into smaller sections, each with a healthy set of roots and shoots. Replant the divisions at the same depth they were originally growing, water them well, and keep the soil consistently moist until they are established.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/marshallia-caespitosa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-marshallia-caespitosa/ 2) https://greg.app/barbaras-buttons-overview/#:~:text=%F0%9F%8C%B1%20Seed%20Propagation,within%207%20to%2014%20days."}, {"Plant_ID": "Marsilea macropoda", "Scientific Name": "Marsilea macropoda", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Bigfoot Waterclover", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: To encourage germination, a moist, well-draining substrate is essential, providing a habitat similar to its natural aquatic or semi-aquatic environment. Careful monitoring of moisture levels ensures optimal conditions for spore development, without over-saturating and risking fungal growth. Sow spores on the surface, as they require light to germinate. Be patient, as the germination process for hairy waterclover can take longer than typical garden plants. — Collection: Hairy waterclover is effectively propagated through sowing its spores, which are akin to seeds in flowering plants. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Divide plant and repot or plant immediately in ground.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/marsilea-macropoda/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Marsilea_vestita.html# | https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=MAMA9"}, {"Plant_ID": "Marsilea vestita", "Scientific Name": "Marsilea vestita", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Hairy Water Clover", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Root", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Root — Treatment: Division — Method: Divide plant and report or plant soil immediately.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/marsilea-vestita/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=MAVE2"}, {"Plant_ID": "Matelea biflora", "Scientific Name": "Matelea biflora", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Purple Milkweed Vine", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Germinating Matelea biflora seeds can be a rewarding process. Start by scarifying the seeds to break their hard seed coat, which mimics natural seed dispersal conditions. You can do this by gently rubbing the seeds with sandpaper or carefully nicking them with a knife. Next, soak the scarified seeds in warm water for 24 to 48 hours to soften them. After soaking, plant the seeds in a well-draining potting mix, covering them with a thin layer of soil. Maintain a consistent temperature of around 70 to 75°F (21 to 24°C) and provide indirect light. Keep the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged, using a spray bottle to mist the surface as needed. Germination may take several weeks to a few months, so be patient. Once the seedlings have grown large enough to handle, transplant them into individual pots or your desired garden location. Matelea biflora seeds require some care and patience, but with the right conditions, you can successfully grow this beautiful native plant. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratify the seeds for 30 days in a cool, moist environment. This mimics natural conditions and helps improve germination rates. After stratification, sow the seeds in well-draining soil, covering them lightly to protect them from excessive moisture. — Collection: Start by collecting seeds from mature pods, ensuring they are fully developed. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Cut the stems to a length of 4-6 inches. Then, place them in a rooting medium and maintain humidity until roots develop, which can take a few weeks. This method allows you to create new plants from existing ones, ensuring a vibrant garden. — Collection: Begin by selecting healthy stems that have at least two nodes, as these will provide the best chance for root development.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/matelea-biflora/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://plantflowerseeds.com/products/matelea-biflora#:~:text=Germinating%20Matelea%20biflora%20seeds%20can,grow%20this%20beautiful%20native%20plant. | https://greg.app/matelea-biflora-overview/#:~:text=Start%20by%20collecting%20seeds%20from,depending%20on%20the%20growing%20conditions."}, {"Plant_ID": "Matelea reticulata", "Scientific Name": "Matelea reticulata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Pearl Milkweed Vine", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Root", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Plant seeds in well-draining soil, about 1/4 inch deep.. Ensure the soil is loose and rich in organic matter. Keep the soil moist but not soggy. — Collection: Collect seeds from mature pods. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end in rooting hormone for better success. Place the cutting in moist soil and cover it lightly. Keep the soil consistently moist until roots develop, which usually takes a few weeks. — Collection: Choose stems that are healthy and free from disease. Cut a 4-6 inch section below a node. || Root — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully remove the plant from the ground. Gently divide the root ball into sections. Replant each section in its own spot. — Collection: This method is best done in early spring or fall when the plant is not actively growing.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/matelea-reticulata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=MARE4 2) https://greg.app/green-milkweed-vine-overview/ | https://greg.app/green-milkweed-vine-overview/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Maurandella antirrhiniflora", "Scientific Name": "Maurandella antirrhiniflora", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Snapdragon Vine", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow them indoors in a seed tray filled with a well-draining seed starting mix. Keep the soil consistently moist and provide them with bright, indirect light. Once seedlings develop their first set of true leaves, they can be gently transplanted into individual pots. — Collection: Harvest seeds from mature seed pods after the flowers fade. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: The best time to propagate Maurandella antirrhiniflora is in the early spring or late summer, when the plant is actively growing. Remove the leaves from the bottom inch or two and dip the cut end in rooting hormone for an extra boost. Plant the cuttings in a good quality potting mix, keeping the soil consistently moist. Cover the pot with a plastic dome or humidity dome to help retain moisture and encourage root development. With consistent care, you’ll see new roots emerge within a few weeks. Provide your cuttings with bright, indirect light. Don’t let the soil dry out completely, but avoid overwatering. The soil should be consistently moist, but not soggy. — Collection: Snip a healthy stem section from your existing Maurandella antirrhiniflora plant. Choose non-flowering stems, ideally about 4-6 inches long.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/maurandella-antirrhiniflora/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-maurandella-antirrhiniflora/?print=pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Melampodium leucanthum", "Scientific Name": "Melampodium leucanthum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Blackfoot Daisy", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: It can be directly seeded outdoors one to two weeks after the last frost in spring after the soil temperature reaches at least 70°F. Barely cover the seeds with soil, as they need light to germinate. Keep the soil moist. Seedlings will appear in one to two weeks, after which you can thin them 10 to 15 inches apart, depending on the cultivar. You can also start the seeds indoors in pots or seed trays about six weeks before the last expected frost date to get a head start on the growing season. — Collection: Easily self-seeds or collect seeds from dry seed heads. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end in rooting hormone powder. Plant the cutting in a well-draining potting mix and water thoroughly. Place in a warm, bright spot with indirect sunlight and keep the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged. Watch for new growth and roots in 4-6 weeks. Once the cutting is established, it can be transplanted into a larger container or outdoors into a garden bed. — Collection: Take stem cuttings in the spring or early summer from healthy parent plants. Use a sterile, sharp blade to make a clean cut at a 45-degree angle just below a leaf node. Remove any leaves from the lower half of the stem", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/melampodium-leucanthum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.bhg.com/gardening/plant-dictionary/annual/melampodium/#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Melampodium,start%20on%20the%20growing%20season. | https://plantiary.com/plant/melampodium-leucanthum_1074.html#:~:text=To%20propagate%20this%20plant%2C%20you,outdoors%20into%20a%20garden%20bed."}, {"Plant_ID": "Melica mutica", "Scientific Name": "Melica mutica", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Two-flower Melic Grass", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Separate plants ensuring adequate roots and shoots, then place in well-prepared soil with consistent moisture. Space divisions to allow growth and monitor for pests and diseases to promote healthy establishment of twoflower melicgrass. — Collection: Divide during active growth.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/melica-mutica/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Melica_mutica.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Melochia pyramidata", "Scientific Name": "Melochia pyramidata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Pyramid Flower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds in well-prepared, fertile, well-draining soil. Maintain consistent moisture and provide warmth and sunlight to promote growth. Early care is crucial for developing healthy, robust plant. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Cuttings can be taken during the growing season and rooted in a suitable medium.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/melochia-pyramidata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Melochia_pyramidata.html#:~:text=Pyramid%20flower%20(Melochia%20pyramidata)%20%2D%20PictureThis&text=Pyramid%20flower%20(Melochia%20pyramidata)%20is,be%20identified%20during%20this%20period.&text=Vascular%20plants-,Snap%20a%20photo%20for%20instant%20plant%20ID%2C%20gaining%20quick%20insights,uses%2C%20and%20symbolism%2C%20etc. 2) https://earthone.io/plant/melochia%20pyramidata?srsltid=AfmBOoq8j7Qtme3NMsO-at6WLinChO9HeL8e7SqEhz0WuH5Il8u8EjmI | https://earthone.io/plant/melochia%20pyramidata?srsltid=AfmBOoq8j7Qtme3NMsO-at6WLinChO9HeL8e7SqEhz0WuH5Il8u8EjmI"}, {"Plant_ID": "Menodora heterophylla", "Scientific Name": "Menodora heterophylla", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Low Menodora", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Clean and dry the seeds thoroughly. Remove any debris or plant material to prevent mold and disease. Prepare a well-draining soil mix by combining equal parts potting soil, sand, and perlite. Fill seed trays or small pots with the soil mix. Place the seeds on the surface of the soil mix and lightly press them in. Cover with a thin layer of soil or sand, ensuring good soil-to-seed contact. Mist the soil with water to keep it evenly moist but not waterlogged. Place the trays or pots in a warm, bright area with indirect sunlight. Monitor moisture levels and mist as needed until germination occurs. — Collection: Harvest mature seeds from existing low menodora plants. Look for brown, dry seed capsules that easily release seeds when gently crushed. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Menodora seeds benefit from a period of cold, moist stratification to break their dormancy. In late fall or winter, mix the seeds with a moist (not soggy) seed starting mix or vermiculite. Place the mixture in a sealed plastic bag and store it in the refrigerator (33-40°F) for 4-6 weeks. After stratification, sow the seeds in seed trays or pots filled with a well-draining seed starting mix. Press the seeds gently onto the surface, but avoid burying them deeply, as they require light to germinate. Keep the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged. Misting the surface with water can prevent disturbing the small seeds. Place the seed trays in a bright location, but out of direct sunlight. A temperature around 70-75°F is ideal for germination. Menodora seeds can take 2-4 weeks (or even longer) to germinate. Be patient and continue to provide consistent moisture and light. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Select healthy, non-flowering stems for your cuttings. Aim for sections that are at least 4-6 inches long. Using sharp, sterilized pruning shears, make a clean cut just below a leaf node (the point where a leaf attaches to the stem). Remove the leaves from the lower third of the cutting to prevent them from rotting in the soil. Dip the cut end of the stem in rooting hormone to encourage faster and stronger root development. Plant the cuttings in small pots filled with a well-draining potting mix. Keep the potting mix moist. Covering the cuttings with a plastic bag or dome will create a humid environment that promotes rooting. — Collection: The best time to take cuttings is in the spring or early summer when the plant is actively growing.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/menodora-heterophylla/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Menodora_heterophylla.html#:~:text=Harvest%20mature%20seeds%20from%20existing,Watering%20and%20germination 2) https://www.botanikks.com/plants/menodora-heterophylla-moric-ex-dc/559367/1 | 1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-menodora-heterophylla/ 2) https://www.botanikks.com/plants/menodora-heterophylla-moric-ex-dc/559367/1"}, {"Plant_ID": "Menodora longiflora", "Scientific Name": "Menodora longiflora", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Showy Menodora", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Prepare well-draining soil mixed with sand or perlite to imitate the natural arid environment of showy menodora. Fill seed trays or pots with this soil mix. Sow the seeds on the soil surface and lightly press them down, barely covering them with soil. Maintain a light, uniform moisture by misting the soil frequently. Place the trays or pots in a bright location with indirect sunlight. Maintain a temperature range of 65-75°F (18-24°C) to support germination, which should occur in 2-3 weeks. — Collection: Harvest seeds from mature, healthy showy menodora plants. Look for dry, brown fruits to ensure seeds are fully developed. Clean the seeds by removing any remaining fruit pulp. Allow them to dry completely in a shaded location to prevent mold. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Begin by soaking Menodora longiflora seeds in lukewarm water for 24 hours to enhance germination. Use a well-draining soil mix, such as a blend of sand and peat moss, and sow seeds on the surface. Lightly press them into the soil without covering them, as light aids their germination. Or plant in a pot with a damp, well-draining medium. Maintain humidity by covering with a plastic dome or clear plastic bag, and ensure the medium remains moist but not soggy. Place in a location with indirect sunlight to promote rooting and growth. — Collection: Harvest seeds from mature, healthy showy menodora plants. Look for dry, brown fruits to ensure seeds are fully developed. Clean the seeds by removing any remaining fruit pulp. Allow them to dry completely in a shaded location to prevent mold. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the leaves from the lower half of the cutting to prevent rot and dip the cut end in rooting hormone powder before planting. Plant in a pot with a damp, well-draining medium. Maintain humidity by covering with a plastic dome or clear plastic bag, and ensure the medium remains moist but not soggy. Place in a location with indirect sunlight to promote rooting and growth. — Collection: Select healthy, non-flowering stems from the parent plant for cuttings. Cut each stem to about 4-6 inches in length, ensuring that there are several leaf nodes present.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/menodora-longiflora/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Menodora_longiflora.html#:~:text=Showy%20menodora%20thrives%20well%20in,gardeners%20in%20achieving%20robust%20growth. | https://www.forwardplant.com/plant-info/menodora-longiflora/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Merremia dissecta", "Scientific Name": "Merremia dissecta", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Alamo Vine", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Root", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Sand or nick the seed coat to allow water to enter the seeds. 2. Soak the seeds for 24 hours. 3. Sow the seeds in moderately fertile, well-drained soil in pots or outdoors if the temperatures are 60 degrees F or warmer. Put them in an area in full sun or light shade. 4. Cover the seeds with a thin layer of soil. 5. Water the seeds. 6. Fertilize the seeds. 7. Water the plants during dry periods. A trellis, arbor or pergola can be used to support the vines.. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: If desired, dip the cut end of the stem in rooting hormone powder to promote root growth. Fill a small pot with well-draining soil, such as a mixture of sand and peat moss. Create a small hole in the soil with your finger or a pencil. Insert the stem cutting into the hole, making sure to bury at least one node under the soil. Gently press the soil around the stem to hold it in place and water the cutting well. Place the pot in a warm, bright location, but out of direct sunlight. Keep the soil moist but not waterlogged and mist the cutting daily to increase humidity. After a few weeks, new growth should appear, indicating that the plant has successfully rooted. Once it has grown enough, the cutting can be transplanted into a larger pot or planted outdoors in a suitable location. — Collection: Start by selecting a healthy, mature Merremia Dissecta plant. Carefully cut off a stem of the plant using a sharp, sterilized garden knife or scissors. Make sure that the stem you have selected has several nodes, which are points on the stem where leaves or buds emerge. Remove the lower leaves from the stem, leaving only a few on the top. || Root — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Root cuttings can be taken when parts of the vine have touched the ground and started to set out roots", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/merremia-dissecta/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://floridaseeds.net/products/cutleaf-morning-glory-merremia-dissecta-organic-10-fresh-seeds-free-us-shipping | https://plantiary.com/plant/merremia-dissecta_5590.html | https://sharonsflorida.com/plants-page/native-vines/noyau-vine/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Meximalva filipes", "Scientific Name": "Meximalva filipes", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texasfan", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Fill a seed tray or small pots with seed-starting mix. Place the container in a warm, sunny spot, preferably a greenhouse or indoors under a grow light. Meximalva filipes seeds typically germinate within 10-14 days. Once seedlings develop their first true leaves, you can transplant them to individual pots or directly into your garden. — Collection: After the Meximalva filipes flowering, carefully collect the seeds from dried seedpods. Ensure they are fully mature and dry before storing in a cool, dry place. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Applying a rooting hormone to the cut end can improve success rates. Place the cuttings in a pot filled with a well-draining potting mix. Moisten the soil and create a mini-greenhouse by covering the pot with a plastic bag or dome. Keep the soil consistently moist and provide bright, indirect light. It can take a few weeks for roots to develop, so patience is crucial. — Collection: Select strong, healthy stems from your existing Meximalva filipes that have grown about 6-8 inches long. Using a sharp knife or pruning shears, make a clean, straight cut about a quarter inch below a leaf node (the area where a leaf emerges from the stem). Remove any leaves that will be below the soil line. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Scarify the seeds lightly by rubbing them with sandpaper to promote better water absorption. Prepare a well-draining soil mix consisting of equal parts sand, perlite, and peat moss. Fill small pots or a seed-starting tray with the soil mix, and lightly moisten it with water. Plant the prepared seeds 1/4 inch deep in the soil mix. Space the seeds adequately to allow for ample room for growth. Lightly cover the seeds with soil and gently water to settle the soil. Place the pots or tray in a warm, sunny location. Maintain a consistent temperature between 70-75°F (21-24°C). Keep the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged. Germination should occur in 2-3 weeks. Once the seedlings have developed at least two sets of true leaves, carefully transplant them into individual pots with a similar soil mix. Gradually acclimate them to outdoor conditions by placing them outside for a few hours each day over a period of one week. — Collection: Collect seeds from mature texasfan plants. Ensure the seeds are dry and free from any mold or damage.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/meximalva-filipes/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-meximalva-filipes/ | 1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-meximalva-filipes/ 2) https://www.montana.edu/extension/broadwater/blog-article.html?id=21879 | https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Meximalva_filipes.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Mimosa strigillosa", "Scientific Name": "Mimosa strigillosa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Powderpuff", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Mimosa strigillosa is easily propagated by placing tip cuttings in a glass of water or placing them directly into potting soil. Or find sections that have begun to set roots at the nodes. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: The seed coating is impervious to water so it should be scarified (rubbed using a nail file or lightly rubbed with sandpaper) to ensure germination.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/mimosa-strigillosa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=MIST2 2) https://floridanativegarden.wordpress.com/2017/04/14/a-short-bit-on-sunshine-mimosa-mimosa-strigillosa/#:~:text=Mimosa%20strigillosa%20is%20easily%20propagated,anytime%20during%20its%20growing%20season."}, {"Plant_ID": "Mirabilis albida", "Scientific Name": "Mirabilis albida", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "White Four O'Clock", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow the seeds in well-draining soil in the spring. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Take a healthy stem cutting and plant it in moist soil. Keep the soil moist until the cutting establishes roots.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/mirabilis-albida/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://earthone.io/plant/mirabilis%20albida?srsltid=AfmBOoqqnZw_ONtkCk2J74geDcBGyiifbTqj2i8Ie8wz_Ms2Ey9Lrd01"}, {"Plant_ID": "Mirabilis linearis", "Scientific Name": "Mirabilis linearis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Narrowleaf Four O'Clock", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Use a well-draining soil mix in a container or a designated area in your garden. Ensure the soil is loose and airy to facilitate root growth. Plant the seeds about 1/4 inch deep in the soil. Space them approximately 2 inches apart to allow ample growth space. After sowing, water the soil gently but thoroughly to ensure the seeds are moist. Avoid over-watering as this can displace the seeds or lead to rot. Keep the soil consistently moist and watch for seedlings to emerge. This usually happens within 2-3 weeks. Provide partial sunlight until the seedlings are well established. — Collection: Choose healthy seeds from a mature narrowleaf four o'clock plant. Ensure the seeds are dry and free from any signs of mold or damage.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/mirabilis-linearis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Mirabilis_linearis.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Mirabilis nyctaginea", "Scientific Name": "Mirabilis nyctaginea", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Wild Four O'clock", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Soak the seeds in room temperature water for 24 hours to soften the hard seed coat and promote germination. Fill a seed tray or pots with a well-draining potting mix. A mix that is rich in organic material but allows for good drainage works best for wild four o'clock. Plant the soaked seeds 1/4 inch deep into the potting mix, ensuring they are spaced out evenly. Cover lightly with the soil without compacting it firmly. Water the sown seeds gently to moisten the soil without causing the seeds to dislodge or the soil to wash away. Place the seed tray or pots in a warm location with indirect light. Wild four o'clock seeds require warmth and indirect sunlight to germinate properly. Expect seeds to germinate within two to three weeks. Once seedlings emerge, ensure they have sufficient light to prevent them from becoming leggy. When seedlings have grown large enough and have developed true leaves (not just the initial seed leaves or cotyledons), they are ready to be transplanted. — Collection: Choose healthy, mature seeds from a robust wild four o'clock plant. Healthy seeds increase the chances of successful propagation. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: You can sow seeds directly into the garden after the last frost, or start them indoors 6-8 weeks before the anticipated last frost date. Plant seeds about ½ inch deep in well-draining soil. With consistent moisture and warm temperatures (around 70°F), you can expect to see sprouts emerge in 1-3 weeks. If starting indoors, harden off the seedlings by gradually introducing them to outdoor conditions before transplanting them into the garden after the last frost. — Collection: After the blooms fade, you’ll notice small, black, peppercorn-like seeds. Allow these to dry completely on the plant before collecting. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dipping the cut end in rooting hormone (while optional) can encourage faster root development. Plant the prepared cutting in a pot filled with a well-draining potting mix. Cover the pot with a plastic bag or humidity dome to retain moisture. Be patient! It can take several weeks for roots to develop. You can check for roots by gently tugging on the cutting. If you feel resistance, your cutting is likely taking root. Once your cutting has rooted well, you can transplant it into a larger pot or directly into the garden. — Collection: The best time for cuttings is in the spring or early summer when the plant is actively growing. Choose a healthy, non-flowering stem that’s about 4-6 inches long. Use a sharp, clean knife or pair of shears to make a cut just below a leaf node. Remove the leaves from the bottom inch or two of the stem.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/mirabilis-nyctaginea/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Mirabilis_nyctaginea.html 2) https://plants.ces.ncsu.edu/plants/mirabilis-jalapa/#:~:text=Four%2Do'clock%20can%20be,and%20will%20regrow%20in%20spring. | 1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-mirabilis-nyctaginea/ 2) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Mirabilis+nyctaginea#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,comes%20into%20growth%5B200%5D. | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-mirabilis-nyctaginea/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Monarda citriodora", "Scientific Name": "Monarda citriodora", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Horsemint", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Offshoots | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow mid to late spring in a cold frame. Germination usually takes place within 10 - 40 days at 20°c. When large enough to handle, prick the seedlings out into individual pots and plant them out into their permanent positions in early summer. The seed can also be sown in situ in late summer in areas where the winters are not too severe and will produce larger plants. || Offshoots — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Pot them up into individual pots and keep them in light shade in a cold frame or greenhouse until they are rooting well. Plant them out in the summer. — Collection: Harvest the shoots with plenty of underground stem when they are about 8 - 10cm above the ground. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Clump division can be done in spring or autumn. Replant immediately.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/monarda-citriodora/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Monarda+citriodora#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,Division%20in%20spring%20or%20autumn."}, {"Plant_ID": "Monarda fistulosa", "Scientific Name": "Monarda fistulosa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Beebalm", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Division — Method: Remove the lower leaves and all flower or seed heads and insert the stems into a sand and perlite-rooting medium. Bury each cutting up to the first node. Place the cuttings in an enclosed area and mist them several times a day. In 4 to 5 weeks the cuttings should be well rooted and can be transplanted to pots. Then outplant the plants in the garden in the early autumn. — Collection: Take stem tip cuttings, 3-4 inches long, any time from May to August. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: 5 month outdoor stratification for material grown in the Outdoor Nursery. A 30 day cold moist stratification was used in the refrigerator for greenhouse grown material. This species is reported to have up to a 97% germination rate in the presence of light. Media is kept slightly moist during germination. Initial germination appeared uniform and occurred following several days of temperatures at 70 degrees F or above during the day. Root and shoot development occurs rapidly following germination. 4 to 6 true leaves were evident 3 weeks after germination. Plants reached root tightness in containers in 3 months. — Collection: Seeds are hand collected in fall when capsules turn tan and papery. Seeds are black at maturity. Capsules are collected in paper bags and are kept in a well ventilated drying shed prior to cleaning. Seeds ripen 2 months after plant blooms. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Seeds can also be broadcast on a weed-free surface from January to mid-May in sunny locations. Once the seeds germinate seedlings should be watered during extended dry period. During the first summer of full growth mow the area 3 to 5 times to keep the plants between 8 and 4 inches tall. Mowing also reduces weeds. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Large divisions can be planted out direct into their permanent positions. We have found that it is better to pot up the smaller divisions and grow them on in light shade in a cold frame until they are well established before planting them out in late spring or early summer.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/monarda-fistulosa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) chrome-extension://efaidnbmnnnibpcajpcglclefindmkaj/ https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/plantguide/pdf/cs_mofi.pdf 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=MOFI 3) https://warcapps.usgs.gov/PlantID/Species/Details/2628#:~:text=Propagation%20by%20seeds%20is%20easy,and%20fertilizing%20(Phillips%201985). 4) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Monarda+fistulosa#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,late%20spring%20or%20early%20summer. | 1) https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=lamiaceae-monarda-95#:~:text=Ecotype:,refrigerator%20for%20greenhouse%20grown%20material. 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=MOFI 3) https://warcapps.usgs.gov/PlantID/Species/Details/2628#:~:text=Propagation%20by%20seeds%20is%20easy,and%20fertilizing%20(Phillips%201985). | 1) https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/plantguide/pdf/cs_mofi.pdf 2) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Monarda+fistulosa#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,late%20spring%20or%20early%20summer. | https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Monarda+fistulosa#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,late%20spring%20or%20early%20summer."}, {"Plant_ID": "Monarda punctata", "Scientific Name": "Monarda punctata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Spotted Beebalm", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Spotted beebalm seeds should be sown indoors 8-10 weeks before your average last frost date. Surface sow these tiny seeds. Sprinkle a group of five seeds in each planting cell. When your seedlings are one inch tall, thin them to one seedling per cell. They can be transplanted outside after the threat of frost has passed in the spring. Space plants at least 12 inches apart to give them room to grow. Alternatively, you can directly sow your seeds two to four weeks before your last frost date. Directly sow seeds by broadcasting them over the surface of the soil. Water them in lightly. Keep the soil evenly moist until the seeds germinate. You should see germination within two weeks. Then, thin seedlings to at least 12 inches apart. — Collection: When the flowers fade, they will die back and be replaced by seed heads. When the seed heads are fully mature, cut them off and spread them over a clean, dry surface to air dry for several days. Once the seed heads are fully dried, place them into a paper bag and shake. The seeds will fall to the bottom of the bag. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the foliage from the bottom inch of the cutting. Remove flower heads from the cutting as well. You want the cutting to focus its energy on producing new roots, not flowers. Place your monarda cutting directly into the soil, and it should form new roots within a week or two. If you see new growth, this is a good sign that your cutting has taken root. Cuttings can then be planted into your garden. — Collection: Propagate spotted bee balm by taking stem tip cuttings. Make sure that your cuttings are at least three to four inches long, and || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Large divisions can be planted out direct into their permanent positions. We have found that it is better to pot up the smaller divisions and grow them on in light shade in a cold frame until they are well established before planting them out in late spring or early summer. — Collection: Division in spring or autumn.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/monarda-punctata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.epicgardening.com/spotted-bee-balm/ 2) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Monarda+punctata#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,late%20spring%20or%20early%20summer. 3) https://www.gardeningknowhow.com/ornamental/flowers/how-to-grow-horsemint | 1) https://earthone.io/plant/monarda%20punctata 2) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Monarda+punctata#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,late%20spring%20or%20early%20summer. 3) https://www.gardeningknowhow.com/ornamental/flowers/how-to-grow-horsemint"}, {"Plant_ID": "Morus rubra", "Scientific Name": "Morus rubra", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Red Mulberry", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Hardwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Crush fruit in hand, and allow the pulp to decompose within sand or a soil medium over the summer and fall outdoors within a container with drainage. Continue winter stratification in that container before sowing the seeds with the sand or soil medium in the spring compressed onto the surface. With proper pot size (.5 gallon or 1 gallon) and fertilizer they should reach at least 4 feet as first year saplings. Can be stratified in a refrigerator at 40 degrees F, for 2-3 months. Germination will occur in 1-3 weeks. The germination environment temperature is 86 degrees F during the dayand 68 degrees F at night. Beds need mulch and half shade. — Collection: Collect fruit early summer. || Hardwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip cuttings in rooting hormone: IBA Quick Dip 12000 PPM. Soil temperature for est rooting: 70-80 degrees F — Collection: Take cuttings in the summer.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/morus-rubra/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://lovenativeplants.com/blog/redmulberry#:~:text=Propagation%20Tips:%20Collect%20fruit%20around,feet%20as%20first%20year%20saplings. 2) https://woodlanders.net/products/morus-rubra#:~:text=Propagation:%20Morus%20rubra%20can%20be,late%20spring%20or%20early%20summer. 3) https://hort.ifas.ufl.edu/database/lppi/sp258.shtml | https://hort.ifas.ufl.edu/database/lppi/sp258.shtml"}, {"Plant_ID": "Muhlenbergia capillaris", "Scientific Name": "Muhlenbergia capillaris", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Gulf Muhly", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Choose a mature and robust pink muhly grass that is free from pests and diseases. This ensures the best chance of successful propagation. Clean and sterilize all tools such as shovels or spades, pots, and potting soil to prevent the spread of disease. Set up a workspace with good lighting and access to water. Thoroughly water the pink muhly grass the day before dividing to ensure it is well-hydrated which makes the division process less stressful for the plant. Gently dig around the outskirts of pink muhly grass's root system, being careful to minimize damage. Lift the entire plant from the soil using a spade or fork. Using your hands or a sharp knife that has been sterilized, divide the root ball into sections. Ensure each division has a good amount of roots and several shoots. Trim any excessively long or damaged roots to promote healthy growth. However, be sure to leave enough roots to sustain the divided plants. Fill pots with a well-draining potting mix or prepare a spot in the garden with similar conditions to the original planting site. Make sure the site has good drainage and airy soil. Plant each division of pink muhly grass at the same depth it was originally growing. The crown of the plant should be at soil level, not buried deeply. Water thoroughly after planting. Keep the soil around pink muhly grass divisions consistently moist but not waterlogged. Provide shade if necessary for the first few weeks to reduce stress on the new plants. Keep an eye on the pink muhly grass divisions for signs of new growth, typically within a few weeks. Watch for any pests or disease and treat as necessary. — Collection: Can propagate by division every three years. The optimal time periods to propagate pink muhly grass through division are early spring and autumn. These seasons offer cooler temperatures and sufficient light for root establishment, avoiding the stress of summer heat. Spring propagation allows a full growing season ahead, while autumn gives the plant time to establish before winter. Both periods have typically higher soil moisture, which aids in root development for new pink muhly grass plants. || Seed — Method: Seeds can be sown directly outdoors in late winter or early spring when the risk of frost has passed, as Pink Muhly Grass germinates best with some exposure to cold temperatures. Alternatively, start seeds indoors in seed trays filled with a well-draining germination mix, placing them on the surface of the soil and lightly pressing them in without covering them, as they need light to germinate. Keep the soil moist but not waterlogged. — Collection: begin with seed collection in late fall or early winter once the seeds have matured. Collect seeds by gently clipping the seed heads from the plant and allow them to dry. Once dry, thresh the seeds to separate them from chaff.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/muhlenbergia-capillaris/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=MUCA2 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Muhlenbergia_capillaris.html#:~:text=What%20Is%20the%20Best%20Time,new%20pink%20muhly%20grass%20plants. 3) https://dallascountymastergardeners.org/muhlenbergia-capillaris-pink-muhly-grass/ | https://dallascountymastergardeners.org/muhlenbergia-capillaris-pink-muhly-grass/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Muhlenbergia dubia", "Scientific Name": "Muhlenbergia dubia", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Pine Muhly", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Start in cool weather. Low germination rate. — Collection: Collect seed in late fall, winter.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/muhlenbergia-dubia/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=MUDU"}, {"Plant_ID": "Muhlenbergia schreberi", "Scientific Name": "Muhlenbergia schreberi", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Nimblewill", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump | Softwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds directly outdoors in late spring or early summer when the soil is consistently warm. Choose a sunny spot with well-drained soil. Lightly rake the surface to create a fine seedbed. Sprinkle the seeds sparingly, then gently cover them with a thin layer of soil. Keep the soil consistently moist but not soggy. Seeds will typically germinate within a few weeks. Once seedlings are a few inches tall, thin them to ensure adequate space for growth. You can transplant those you thinned to new locations. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully dig up the clump. Use a sharp knife or spade to divide the mass into smaller sections, each with a healthy root system and several shoots. Plant these divisions immediately in prepared beds or containers, ensuring that the crown (where the roots meet the stem) is just below the soil surface. Water thoroughly. — Collection: Early spring or late summer, when the grass is actively growing, is ideal for division. || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Apply a rooting hormone to the cut end. Pot the cuttings in a well-draining rooting mixture, keeping only the nodes submerged. Place a humidity dome over the pot or cover it with a plastic wrap to create a humid environment. Keep the rooting mix consistently moist and monitor for signs of new growth, which will indicate successful rooting. After a few weeks, the cutting should be ready to transplant. — Collection: Take softwood cuttings in late spring or early summer when the grass is actively growing. Choose a healthy, non-flowering stem. Use sharp pruning shears to cut a 4-6 inch section, ensuring at least two nodes (where leaves emerge) are included. Remove the bottom leaves.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/muhlenbergia-schreberi/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-muhlenbergia-schreberi/ 2) https://plants.ces.ncsu.edu/plants/muhlenbergia-schreberi/#:~:text=In%20the%20fall%2C%20attractive%20panicles,Tags: | 1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-muhlenbergia-schreberi/ 2) https://gardeningsolutions.ifas.ufl.edu/plants/ornamentals/muhly-grass/#:~:text=As%20the%20plants%20age%2C%20they,contact%20your%20county%20Extension%20office. | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-muhlenbergia-schreberi/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Nassella leucotricha", "Scientific Name": "Nassella leucotricha", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Wintergrass", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Bud | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Plant directly in soil. Under optimal conditions, expect germination within 7 to 14 days. — Collection: Wait until the seed heads turn brown before harvesting. || Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: Ensure each clump is at least 6 inches in diameter for successful replanting. — Collection: The best time for division is early spring or fall || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Aim for a length of 4 to 6 inches and place them in a well-draining potting mix to encourage root development. — Collection: Take healthy stem cuttings.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/nassella-leucotricha/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://greg.app/texas-wintergrass-overview/#:~:text=%F0%9F%8C%9E%20Texas%20Wintergrass%20thrives%20in,inches%20to%20encourage%20healthy%20growth."}, {"Plant_ID": "Nemastylis geminiflora", "Scientific Name": "Nemastylis geminiflora", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Prairie Celestials", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Bulb | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Bulb — Treatment: Division — Method: Separate bulbs with care, replant in well-drained soil, in a sunny location. Place each corm 2-3 inches deep and 6-8 inches apart. Maintain adequate moisture to support rooting. — Collection: After the foliage has yellowed and died back in late summer or early fall, carefully dig up your Prairie Celestial plants. You’ll find small, bulb-like structures clustered around the base of the original corm. These are the new corms, ready to grow into new plants. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Seeds can be somewhat slow to germinate. Don’t despair if you don’t see sprouts immediately in the spring. Be patient and maintain consistent moisture, and you will be rewarded with delicate seedlings. Prairie Celestial seeds benefit from a period of cold stratification to mimic natural winter conditions. In fall, sow the seeds directly in your garden or in pots filled with a well-draining seed starting mix. Gently press the seeds into the soil, but avoid burying them too deep. Over winter, the cold temperatures will work their magic, preparing the seeds for germination in the spring. — Collection: Keep a watchful eye on your plants in late spring or early summer as the flowers fade. You’ll notice small seed capsules developing where the blooms once were. Allow these capsules to dry completely on the plant, turning brown and papery. Once dry, carefully collect the capsules and extract the small, black seeds within.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/nemastylis-geminiflora/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Nemastylis_geminiflora.html#:~:text=Propagation:%20Prairie%20pleatleaf%20can%20be,Hydrangea%20macrophylla 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-nemastylis-geminiflora/ | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-nemastylis-geminiflora/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Nemophila phacelioides", "Scientific Name": "Nemophila phacelioides", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Baby Blue Eyes", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Baby Blue Eyes do well sown from seed, with about 12 inches of spacing. — Collection: Seeds can be collected by tying a bag to the flower head. With pollination, slightly elongate-spherical, green, two-part capsules form, and turn light brown with maturity. Before summer’s heat, the capsules split open and small rough, brown seeds are released.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/nemophila-phacelioides/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nemophila_phacelioides#:~:text=Cultivation,bag%20to%20the%20flower%20head. 2) https://earthone.io/plant/nemophila%20phacelioides?srsltid=AfmBOopD5nCKxIIb2D15NB1TwjX2TLD1FldLfu-3WQDFHwOrSVnJxgwj 3) https://anps.org/2016/05/02/know-your-natives-large-flower-baby-blue-eyes/ 4) https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Nemophila_phacelioides.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Neptunia pubescens", "Scientific Name": "Neptunia pubescens", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Tropical Puff", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Nick the seed tips and soak for about 8 hours before planting.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/neptunia-pubescens/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://hawthornhillwildflowers.blogspot.com/2020/06/tropical-puff-neptunia-pubescens.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Nolina lindheimeriana", "Scientific Name": "Nolina lindheimeriana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Devil's Shoestring", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Use a well-draining seed starting mix and moisten thoroughly. Plant seeds about half an inch deep and cover lightly. Provide bottom heat (around 70-75°F) and bright indirect light. Germination can take anywhere from a few weeks to several months. Once seedlings develop a few true leaves, thin them out to give each one enough space to grow. — Collection: Look for seed pods turning brown and dry in late summer or fall. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Using a sharp, sterilized knife, carefully divide the clumps, ensuring each section has a good root system. Plant each division in a well-draining potting mix and water thoroughly. Nolina lindheimeriana, true to its desert origins, can be a bit slow-growing. Don’t worry if your propagation efforts don’t show immediate results. Keep providing proper light, watering sparingly, and be patient. — Collection: As your Nolina lindheimeriana matures, it may develop offsets or \"pups\" at the base. The ideal time for division is during the plant’s active growing season in spring or early summer. Carefully dig up the entire plant, ensuring you don’t damage the roots.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/nolina-lindheimeriana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-nolina-lindheimeriana/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Nolina texana", "Scientific Name": "Nolina texana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Beargrass", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Plant seeds in cold frame or greenhouse in late January (cool weather). Seedlings do best if transplanted into 4-6 inch pots and given light shade the first season. — Collection: Collect seed when pods begin to dry.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/nolina-texana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=NOTE"}, {"Plant_ID": "Nyctaginia capitata", "Scientific Name": "Nyctaginia capitata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Devil's Bouquet", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Bud", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Begin by soaking seeds in water for 24 hours. This simple step helps to soften the seed coat, promoting better germination. Next, sow the seeds at a depth of 1/4 inch in well-draining soil. Under warm conditions, expect germination to take about 2-3 weeks, so keep an eye on them! || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Use a rooting medium made of equal parts perlite and peat moss. With proper humidity control, the cuttings should root in about 2-4 weeks, giving you new plants to nurture — Collection: Select healthy stems that are 4-6 inches long. This ensures you’re starting with strong material that has the best chance of rooting. || Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: To divide, carefully separate the root clumps, ensuring each division has healthy roots. Replant them immediately to give them the best chance to thrive in their new homes. — Collection: The best time to divide Nyctaginia capitata is early spring when the plant is just waking up from dormancy. This timing helps minimize stress on the plant.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/nyctaginia-capitata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://greg.app/headed-four-oclock-overview/#:~:text=%F0%9F%8C%B1%20Seed%20Propagation,keep%20an%20eye%20on%20them! | 1) https://greg.app/headed-four-oclock-overview/#:~:text=%F0%9F%8C%B1%20Seed%20Propagation,keep%20an%20eye%20on%20them! 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Nyctaginia_capitata.html#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Devil's%20bouquet?&text=This%20captivating%20ornamental's%20allure%20is,significantly%20improve%20propagation%20success%20rates."}, {"Plant_ID": "Nymphaea odorata", "Scientific Name": "Nymphaea odorata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "White Waterlily", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Rhizome", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Rhizome — Treatment: Division — Method: Cut the rhizomes into sections, ensuring each section has at least one growing point, and plant them in loamy soil submerged in water. — Collection: best done in the spring when the plant begins to grow actively.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/nymphaea-odorata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://earthone.io/plant/nymphaea%20odorata?srsltid=AfmBOooy3H3XurVN-gYEY5W06fbKtx8l02PXxgNHGGlAPQ7nzXC3wAFj"}, {"Plant_ID": "Other common name(s):", "Scientific Name": "Other common name(s):", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Long Flower Beeblossom", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Prepare a well-draining soil mix. A mix of loamy soil with some sand can provide the right texture for longflower beeblossom. Ensure the planting medium is free from weeds and pathogens. Sow the seeds on the soil surface and lightly press them in, ensuring they are in good contact with the soil but not deeply buried. Light is necessary for germination, so do not cover them with soil. Mist the soil lightly to keep it consistently moist but not waterlogged. Use a spray bottle to ensure even moisture without displacing the seeds. Place the sown seeds in a warm area with ample indirect sunlight. Maintain a stable temperature and humidity by covering the seed tray with a clear plastic cover or a plastic bag to create a mini greenhouse effect. — Collection: Choose healthy, mature seeds from longflower beeblossom. Opt for seeds that are visually free of any damage or discoloration.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/oenothera-%ef%ac%81liformis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Oenothera_filiformis.html 2) https://earthone.io/plant/oenothera%20lindheimeri"}, {"Plant_ID": "Oenothera hartwegii", "Scientific Name": "Oenothera hartwegii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Western Primrose", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Prepare a well-draining potting mix with a high content of sand and gravel to mimic the natural growing conditions of hartweg's sundrops. Fill seed trays or pots with the prepared soil mix. Sow seeds on the surface of the soil, pressing them lightly into the substrate without covering them. Hartweg's sundrops seeds require light to germinate, so avoid burying them under the soil. Mist the soil surface lightly with water, ensuring it stays moist but not waterlogged. Cover the seed trays or pots with a clear plastic lid or place them in a greenhouse to maintain humidity. Monitor for germination, which typically occurs within 2-4 weeks. Once seedlings have developed a set of true leaves, carefully transplant them into individual pots or outdoor garden beds, ensuring they are spaced adequately to allow for growth. — Collection: Collect mature seeds from hartweg's sundrops when the seed pods turn brown and begin to split open. Ensure the seeds are completely dry before storing them for propagation.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/oenothera-hartwegii-ssp-hartwegii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Oenothera_hartwegii_subsp._hartwegii.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Oenothera laciniata", "Scientific Name": "Oenothera laciniata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Cutleaf Evening Primrose", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow them at a depth of 1/4 inch for optimal growth. Germination typically takes about 10-14 days under ideal conditions. Keep the soil moist but not soggy to encourage healthy sprouting. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully dig up the root clumps and separate them. To divide, carefully dig up the root clumps and separate them. Replant the divisions immediately to ensure they thrive in their new locations. — Collection: This should be done in early spring or fall for the best results.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/oenothera-laciniata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://greg.app/cutleaf-evening-primrose-overview/#:~:text=%E2%9C%82%EF%B8%8F%20Division%20of%20Established%20Plants,multiple%20areas%20of%20your%20garden. 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Oenothera_laciniata.html | https://greg.app/cutleaf-evening-primrose-overview/#:~:text=%E2%9C%82%EF%B8%8F%20Division%20of%20Established%20Plants,multiple%20areas%20of%20your%20garden."}, {"Plant_ID": "Oenothera macrocarpa", "Scientific Name": "Oenothera macrocarpa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Missouri Primrose", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: The best time to propagate is in the spring. Sow seeds in well-draining soil and keep them moist until germination. — Collection: ` || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Take a healthy stem, dip it in rooting hormone, and plant it in a suitable growing medium.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/oenothera-macrocarpa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://earthone.io/plant/oenothera%20macrocarpa"}, {"Plant_ID": "Oenothera serrulata", "Scientific Name": "Oenothera serrulata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Yellow Evening Primrose", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Best propagated in spring and summer. Rooting hormones can be used to stimulate growth, although yellow sundrops usually roots well without them. It's essential to provide adequate sunlight and protect the cuttings from extreme conditions until they establish. — Collection: To ensure success, select healthy, non-flowering stems and cut just below a node. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: For annual species and warmer climates, sow in early spring or late summer. Biennials should be planted in the early days of fall. Soak the seeds in water for 5-10 hours and remove them once inflated. To prepare the substrate, spread a layer of coarse grain or rubble in the seedling container to ensure smooth drainage and mix with organic fertilizer. Sow the soaked seeds in the substrate using tweezers, and make sure the seeds are evenly distributed. Cover the seeds with a thin layer of soil. Keep the seeding substrate moist at all times and temperatures between 18 to 21 ℃. The seeds should germinate within 10-15 days. Once they've developed 3-5 leaves, transplant.For annual species and warmer climates, sow in early spring or late summer. Biennials should be planted in the early days of fall. Soak the seeds in water for 5-10 hours and remove them once inflated. To prepare the substrate, spread a layer of coarse grain or rubble in the seedling container to ensure smooth drainage and mix with organic fertilizer. Sow the soaked seeds in the substrate using tweezers, and make sure the seeds are evenly distributed. Cover the seeds with a thin layer of soil. Keep the seeding substrate moist at all times and temperatures between 18 to 21 ℃. The seeds should germinate within 10-15 days. Once they've developed 3-5 leaves, transplant.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/oenothera-serrulata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Oenothera_serrulata.html 2) https://davesgarden.com/guides/pf/go/185704 | 1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Oenothera_serrulata.html 2) https://earthone.io/plant/oenothera%20parviflora 3) https://davesgarden.com/guides/pf/go/185704"}, {"Plant_ID": "Oenothera speciosa", "Scientific Name": "Oenothera speciosa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Pink Evening Primrose", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Root | Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Root — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully dig up an established plant and separate the roots into smaller sections, making sure each division has healthy roots and shoots. Replant these divisions in well-draining soil, and they will establish themselves quickly. — Collection: Best done in the spring or fall. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow them in well-draining soil, either indoors 6-8 weeks before the last frost or outdoors, in the fall. Pinkladies prefer cool temperatures for germination. Ensure the seeds are lightly covered with soil and kept moist until they germinate, which usually occurs within a few weeks. Choose a spot with well-draining soil and full sun to partial shade. Be patient they can be slow to germinate. — Collection: Collect seeds from mature plants in late summer or early fall. Seeds are difficult to collect so place a mesh bag over the maturing seed heads. Or collect pods before they split open and scatter. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip stems in rooting hormone and place in a pot of soil covered with clear plastic to retain moisture and encourage rooting. Place the cutting in a bright location, but out of direct sunlight. Rooting usually takes 4-6 weeks. — Collection: In spring or early summer. These seasons offer mild temperatures and optimal light conditions, which enhance root development and growth. Cut non flowering stems in 5” sections and remove leaves to expose nodes.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/oenothera-speciosa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://planetdesert.com/products/pink-ladies-plant-oenothera-speciosa#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Oenothera%20speciosa,of%20new%20pink%20ladies%20plants. 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-oenothera-speciosa/#google_vignette | 1) https://planetdesert.com/products/pink-ladies-plant-oenothera-speciosa#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Oenothera%20speciosa,of%20new%20pink%20ladies%20plants. 2) https://www.greauxnative.org/post/pink-evening-primrose-oenothera-speciosa#:~:text=This%20plant%20can%20be%20propagated,soil%20covered%20with%20clear%20plastic. 3) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-oenothera-speciosa/#google_vignette | 1) https://www.greauxnative.org/post/pink-evening-primrose-oenothera-speciosa#:~:text=This%20plant%20can%20be%20propagated,soil%20covered%20with%20clear%20plastic. 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-oenothera-speciosa/#google_vignette"}, {"Plant_ID": "Onosmodium bejariense var. bejariense", "Scientific Name": "Onosmodium bejariense var. bejariense", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "False Gromwell", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds in spring, after last frost, using sterile seed germinating mix and intermittent misting (about every hour for 6 seconds). Cover the seed with media, about 1/8\" deep. They do benefit from some shade when trying to germinate them. Can be sown as late as July with success (again give them more shade. — Collection: Allow seedheads to dry on plants; remove and collect seeds.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/onosmodium-bejariense-var-bejariense/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/expert/show.php?id=1769 2) https://davesgarden.com/guides/pf/go/68305"}, {"Plant_ID": "Opuntia engelmannii", "Scientific Name": "Opuntia engelmannii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Prickly Pear", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Transplant — Method: Fallen pads are easily transplanted by sticking the base in contact with soil. — Collection: Proper handling is crucial to avoid injury from spines and glochids. Rotting can be a problem if cuttings aren’t properly dried before planting. Use a sharp, clean knife or shears to remove a healthy pad (cladode). Allow the cut end to callous over for a few days to a week in a dry, shaded area. Plant the cutting in well-draining cactus potting mix, ensuring only the base is buried. Avoid overwatering. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Seed germination of Opuntia engelmannii is possible, but it’s known to be challenging and slow. The hard seed coat requires scarification to improve germination rates. This can be achieved through mechanical means (e.g., gently nicking the seed coat with a file) or chemical means (e.g., brief immersion in concentrated sulfuric acid – proceed with extreme caution and follow specific instructions if attempting this method). Sow seeds in a well-draining cactus potting mix, ensuring good drainage. Maintain consistent warmth (around 70-80°F) and avoid overwatering. Consider using a humidity dome to enhance germination. Stratification (a period of cold, moist storage) may not be necessary, but a period of warm storage can have a beneficial effect.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/opuntia-engelmannii-var-lindheimeri/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-opuntia-engelmannii/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Oxalis drummondii", "Scientific Name": "Oxalis drummondii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Drummond's Woodsorrel", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump division | Root", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Once ready, plant the seeds in well-drained soil, covering them lightly to ensure they have the best chance to germinate. — Collection: Start by allowing the seed pods to mature and dry on the plant. || Clump division — Treatment: Division — Method: Replant them immediately to encourage healthy growth. This propagation process not only helps you expand your garden but also ensures the vitality of your existing plants. — Collection: The best time to do this is in early spring or fall; simply dig up the plant carefully, separate the root clumps. || Root — Method: Carefully separate the tubers and plant them in individual pots with well-draining soil. — Collection: Oxalis drummondii can be propagated through division of its tubers. This is best done during the dormancy period.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/oxalis-drummondii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://greg.app/drummonds-woodsorrel-overview/#:~:text=%F0%9F%8C%B1%20Seed%20Propagation,the%20best%20chance%20to%20germinate. | 1) https://greg.app/drummonds-woodsorrel-overview/#:~:text=%F0%9F%8C%B1%20Seed%20Propagation,the%20best%20chance%20to%20germinate. 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Oxalis_drummondii.html#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Drummond's%20woodsorrel?&text=Drummond's%20woodsorrel%20can%20be%20effectively,unique%20characteristics%20of%20drummond's%20woodsorrel. | https://earthone.io/plant/oxalis%20drummondii"}, {"Plant_ID": "Packera obovata", "Scientific Name": "Packera obovata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Golden Groundsel", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Offshoots", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow the seed immediately and it usually germinates within a week or two. Consistent moisture and indirect sunlight are important. — Collection: Harvest and clean seeds in June. || Offshoots — Treatment: Division — Method: YouTube video shows how to gently shake out individual plants from the soil and transfer to a pot until established. — Collection: Dig up clump. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Cold moist stratification (refrigeration) for at least 3 weeks will help ensure germination. — Collection: Harvest and clean seeds in June.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/packera-obovata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://mowildflowers.net/packera-obovata-roundleaf-groundsel/# | https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zDvVug7UBFU"}, {"Plant_ID": "Palafoxia rosea", "Scientific Name": "Palafoxia rosea", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Rosy Palafox", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Winter sow in vented containers, coldframe or unheated greenhouse. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct sow outdoors in the fall.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/palafoxia-rosea/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://davesgarden.com/guides/pf/go/983"}, {"Plant_ID": "Panicum virgatum", "Scientific Name": "Panicum virgatum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Switchgrass", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Outdoors: Plant the seed after the soil is warmed in spring. Seed needs no special treatment to germinate, and typically sprouts after 2-3 weeks in warm conditions. It usually takes about three years for the plants to mature, during which time weeds must be managed for best results. Indoors: No pre-treatment necessary other than cold, dry storage. Start at least 4 weeks before outdoor night temperatures are reliably in the 10 C (50 F) range. Plant seed 0.64 cm (1/4 inch) deep in pots. Keep moist but not soggy and very warm (21 C - 70 F). When seedlings are 5 cm (2 in.) tall, transplant into the garden spaced 30 cm (1 ft.) apart. Outdoors: Sow seed 0.64 cm (1/4 inch) deep outdoors in either late fall or early spring. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Switchgrass should be divided every few years, as the center of the plant may die out. This will also improve plant vigor. Divide in spring to allow roots to establish through the growing season.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/panicum-virgatum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://hort.extension.wisc.edu/articles/switch-grass-panicum-virgatum/#:~:text=Propagating%20Switchgrass&text=The%20species%20can%20be%20grown,fall%20planting%20is%20not%20recommended. 2) https://www.wildflowerfarm.com/panicum-virgatum-switchgrass.html#:~:text=Here's%20some%20information%20about%20growing%20Panicum%20virgatum,for%20creating%20dense%20cover%20for%20wildlife%20habitat. | 1) https://www.gardendesign.com/ornamental-grasses/switchgrass.html#:~:text=Switchgrass%20should%20be%20divided%20every,establish%20through%20the%20growing%20season. 2) https://growingthehomegarden.com/propagating-switchgrass-through/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Pappophorum bicolor", "Scientific Name": "Pappophorum bicolor", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Pink Pappusgrass", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Seed should be planted 1/8 to 1/4 inch deep in early spring or late summer when there is the least weed competition.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/pappophorum-bicolor/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/plantmaterials/stpmcpg9999.pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Parthenocissus heptaphylla", "Scientific Name": "Parthenocissus heptaphylla", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Seven-leaf Creeper", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Semi-harwood | Hardwood | Stem | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end of each cutting into a rooting hormone to encourage root growth. This step is crucial as it significantly increases the chances of successful rooting. Plant in pots with a well-draining soil mix, such as a blend of peat and perlite or sand. Make a hole in the soil with a pencil or similar tool, and insert the treated cutting about 2 inches deep ensuring at least one node is buried where roots can develop. Cover the pots with clear plastic bags or place them in a mini-greenhouse to maintain high humidity and warmth. Ensure the plastic does not directly touch the leaves by supporting it with sticks or a frame. Keep soil consistently moist but not waterlogged. Place the pots in a warm area with bright, indirect light. Remove the cover for a few hours each day to prevent mold growth and check moisture levels, re-covering it afterward. Rooting typically occurs within 4-6 weeks. — Collection: Select healthy shoots in spring or summer from the current or last growing season. Ensure the cuttings are about 4-6 inches long, with several leaves. Use a sharp, clean knife to make cuts just below a leaf node. || Hardwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the bottom inch of the cuttings in rooting hormone. Insert the cuttings into a mix of perlite and peat moss, burying at least two nodes below the surface. Keep the soil moist. In 4-8 weeks, the cuttings should develop roots, and you can transplant them to individual pots or directly into the ground. — Collection: During dormancy, from late fall to early spring, select healthy, pencil-thick stems from the previous year’s growth. Cut 6-8 inch sections, making the top cut just above a bud and the bottom cut below a bud. || Stem — Treatment: Layering — Method: Bury the wounded portion of the stem under a couple of inches of soil and secure it with a rock or landscape pin. Keep the area consistently moist. After a few weeks, gently tug on the stem; if you feel resistance, roots have formed. Then, you can sever the rooted section from the main plant. — Collection: Choose a long, flexible stem and (optional) make a small wound on the underside. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Though not mandatory, a period of cold stratification (about 6-8 weeks) in moist sand in the refrigerator can increase germination rates. In spring, sow the seeds in a well-draining seed starting mix, lightly covering them. Keep the soil consistently moist and warm. Expect germination within 2-4 weeks. — Collection: • Harvest ripe, dark berries in the fall and extract the small seeds. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Next, clean and dry the seeds thoroughly before planting. They thrive in warm temperatures, ideally around 70°F (21°C), and require consistent moisture to kickstart their growth. Seeds typically germinate within 2-4 weeks. This plant takes approximately 2-3 years to reach full maturity. — Collection: Collect seeds from mature berries in late summer.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/parthenocissus-heptaphylla/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Parthenocissus_heptaphylla.html 2) https://plantiary.com/plant/parthenocissus-heptaphylla_40935.html | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-parthenocissus-heptaphylla/ | 1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-parthenocissus-heptaphylla/ 2) https://greg.app/parthenocissus-heptaphylla-overview/ | https://greg.app/parthenocissus-heptaphylla-overview/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Parthenocissus quinquefolia", "Scientific Name": "Parthenocissus quinquefolia", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Virginia Creeper", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow directly in the ground in the fall. — Collection: Collect fruits after they have turned bluish black by hand-stripping from vine. Extract seeds from pulp and air-dry. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratify in moist sand or peat for 60 days at 41 degrees. Sow in the spring. — Collection: Collect fruits after they have turned bluish black by hand-stripping from vine. Extract seeds from pulp and air-dry.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/parthenocissus-quinquefolia/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=PAQU2"}, {"Plant_ID": "Paspalum floridanum", "Scientific Name": "Paspalum floridanum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Florida Paspalum", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Freshly harvested seed has a high degree of dormancy which is reduced as the seed ages. Ambient (room) temperature storage reduces dormancy better than cold stratification treatment, with the best germination attained after 9 months of ambient storage. Cold storage reduces seed dormancy less quickly, requiring a minimum of 3 years of cold storage to reduce seed dormancy. For optimal germination, Florida Paspalum seeds thrive in temperatures ranging from 70°F to 85°F. This warm environment encourages quick sprouting, setting the stage for healthy growth. — Collection: Florida paspalum establishes quite easily from seed compared to many other warm-season grasses. Seedlings are vigorous and compete well with concurrently germinating weeds, establishing well in the first growing season with adequate moisture and fertility. Florida paspalum can be seeded in a pure stand or in a mix of other species with a seeding depth of 1/4” on fine textured soils and up to 3/4” on coarse textured soils. The smooth seed can be planted with most seed drills or broadcast seeded into a prepared firm seedbed. It is recommended to firm the seedbed after seeding with a roller or culti-packer. General seeding recommendations are 6 to 8 pounds PLS per acre for most applications. Seeds are large and light with approximately 91,000 seeds/lb. With adequate moisture, most seeds will germinate within 7 days. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully separate clumps of grass and replant them in prepared soil to ensure they thrive in their new locations. — Collection: Early spring or fall. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Use a rooting medium composed of peat and perlite for the best results. — Collection: Select healthy stems that are 4-6 inches long", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/paspalum-floridanum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/plantguide/pdf/pg_pafl4.pdf 2) https://greg.app/florida-paspalum-overview/#:~:text=Florida%20Paspalum%20supports%20local%20wildlife,growth%2C%20fostering%20a%20thriving%20ecosystem. | https://greg.app/florida-paspalum-overview/#:~:text=Florida%20Paspalum%20supports%20local%20wildlife,growth%2C%20fostering%20a%20thriving%20ecosystem."}, {"Plant_ID": "Paspalum plicatulum", "Scientific Name": "Paspalum plicatulum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Brownseed Paspalum", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Corm", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct sow in the ground. expect germination within 7-14 days, making this a relatively quick process. — Collection: Collect seeds when they turn brown and dry. While dried seeds re-imbibe if stored in humid conditions and rapidly lose viability, seed stored in a dry situation can last for two years. || Corm — Treatment: Division — Method: Simply separate the clumps carefully and replant them immediately to ensure they thrive in their new spots. — Collection: The best time for this is early spring or fall. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: There is little or no post-harvest dormancy, and any dormancy can be broken by chilling seed at 7 ºC for 30 days if necessary. Seed germinates at 20‒35 °C. Seedling vigour is low, so it is best sown into a well-prepared, weed-free seedbed. It should be sown at 2‒3 kg/ha, no more than 10‒15 mm deep, then rolled to provide close contact with the soil.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/paspalum-plicatulum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://greg.app/paspalum-plicatulum-overview/#:~:text=Next%2C%20let's%20explore%20the%20propagation,Seedling%20Development%20%F0%9F%8C%BF | https://tropicalforages.info/text/entities/paspalum_plicatulum.htm#:~:text=It%20is%20normally%20planted%20from,close%20contact%20with%20the%20soil."}, {"Plant_ID": "Passiflora affinis", "Scientific Name": "Passiflora affinis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Bracted Passionflower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Softwood | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Soak the seeds in warm water for a few hours to soften the seed coat. Sow the seeds in a well-draining potting mix, lightly covering them with soil. Keep the soil moist and place the pot in a warm location with indirect light. Germination can take up to several weeks. Once the seedlings develop a few true leaves, they can be transplanted into separate pots. — Collection: Collect seeds from ripe fruits, clean the seeds and remove any remaining pulp from them. || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the leaves from the lower half of the cutting and dip the cut end in a rooting hormone powder to encourage root development. Embed in a light, well-draining, moist potting mix, ensuring at least two nodes are buried in the soil. Provide steady support for the cutting. Maintain dampness and a warm atmosphere to stimulate root formation. A humidity dome or plastic bag helps create a moist environment. Use a spray bottle to mist the cuttings to maintain optimal humidity levels. Keeping cuttings moist but not saturated. Root development typically occurs within 4-6 weeks. — Collection: In spring or summer, harvest a cutting directly beneath a leaf node from recent growth, about 4-6 inches long with at least 3-4 leaf nodes. || Stem — Treatment: Layering — Method: Bury the wounded section of the stem in a shallow trench or pot filled with soil, leaving the tip above the ground. Secure the stem in place using a small stake or wire. Keep the soil moist and provide indirect light. After a few weeks, new roots should form at the wounded section. Once roots are established, the new plant can be separated from the parent plant and potted. — Collection: Identify a low-growing, flexible stem near the base of the plant. Gently bend the selected stem down to the ground and make a small incision or scrape the underside where it will touch the soil. || Stem — Treatment: Grafting — Method: Make a corresponding diagonal cut on the rootstock plant stem. Join the two cut surfaces together and bind them tightly using grafting tape or a rubber band. Keep the graft union covered with a plastic bag or humidity dome to maintain moisture. Place the grafted plant in a warm, well-lit area. After a few weeks, the graft union should heal and new growth will begin to emerge. — Collection: This is an advanced method. Select a healthy rootstock plant, preferably a Passiflora species with strong root system and disease resistance. Take a stem cutting from a desired Passiflora Affinis plant and make a 45-degree diagonal cut at the base to maximize surface contact area.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/passiflora-affinis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://plantiary.com/plant/passiflora-affinis_21195.html | 1) https://www.forwardplant.com/care/propagate/passiflora-affinis/ 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Passiflora_affinis.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Passiflora incarnata", "Scientific Name": "Passiflora incarnata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Purple Passionflower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: To enhance germination, stratify the seeds by placing them in a moist medium (like sand or peat moss) and refrigerate for about 2-3 months. Planting: After stratification, sow the seeds in a well-draining potting mix. Keep the soil moist and place the pots in a warm, sunny location. Germination: Seeds typically germinate within 2-4 weeks. Once seedlings are large enough to handle, transplant them into individual pots. — Collection: Leathery berries develop during a 2-3 month period after flowering. Check seeds when the berry is soft and yellowish. Mature seeds are brown. Seeds should be cleaned (remove the sticky material from seeds) || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the lower leaves from the cutting, leaving a few at the top. Dip the cut end in rooting hormone to encourage root development. Insert the cutting into a pot filled with a well-draining potting mix. Keep the soil moist and cover the pot with a plastic bag to maintain humidity. Place the pot in a warm, bright location but out of direct sunlight. Roots should develop in 4-6 weeks, after which the cutting can be transplanted. — Collection: Choose healthy, non-flowering shoots in late spring or early summer. Cut a 4-6 inch segment just below a node.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/passiflora-incarnata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://thecameronteam.net/passiflora-incarnata-history-propagation-planting-uses/ 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=PAIN6 | https://thecameronteam.net/passiflora-incarnata-history-propagation-planting-uses/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Passiflora lutea", "Scientific Name": "Passiflora lutea", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Yellow Passionflower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the leaves from the lower half of each cutting, being careful not to damage the stem. This will help to prevent rot and will encourage root growth from the nodes. Dip end of stem in rooting hormone. Fill a clean pot with a well-draining potting mix, such as a blend of peat, perlite, and vermiculite or a commercial seed starting mix. Make a hole in the center of the potting mix with a pencil or your finger, and insert the bottom of the cutting, ensuring that at least one node is buried beneath the surface. Keep the cutting in a warm, humid environment until it establishes roots, covering with plastic if needed. Place the pot in an area that receives bright, indirect light. Avoid direct sunlight, as it can cause the cuttings to overheat under the plastic covering. After 4-6 weeks, gently tug on the cutting to check for resistance, which indicates rooting. You can also look for signs of growth, such as new leaves. After roots have developed, acclimate the cutting to the outside environment by gradually removing the plastic covering for a short period each day over a week. Then, transplant the cutting into a larger pot with fresh potting mix or into your garden after ensuring it is well-rooted and showing signs of growth. — Collection: Spring or early summer, select a healthy yellow passionflower with new growth. Choose semi-ripe stems that have not yet become woody and take cuttings about 6-8 inches long, ensuring there are at least 2-3 nodes (where leaves attach) on each cutting. Use a sharp, sterile pair of pruners or scissors to make clean cuts. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Sow seeds after they've been soaked in water for 24 hours to enhance germination rates. For optimal growth, provide yellow passionflower with a trellis or support for climbing and ensure it's placed in a location with adequate sunlight and protection from harsh conditions.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/passiflora-lutea/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://earthone.io/plant/passiflora%20lutea 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Passiflora_lutea.html | https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Passiflora_lutea.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Passiflora tenuiloba", "Scientific Name": "Passiflora tenuiloba", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Birdwing Passionflower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: To propagStart by soaking seeds in water for 24 hours. After soaking, plant the seeds in a seed-starting mix, and expect germination within 2 to 4 weeks. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting, Root — Method: For cutting propagation, select healthy stems that are 4 to 6 inches long. Use a rooting medium made of perlite and peat moss to encourage root development. || Stem — Treatment: Layering — Method: Layering is another effective propagation method. Simply bend a stem to the ground, cover it with soil, and patiently wait for roots to develop.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/passiflora-tenuiloba/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://greg.app/passiflora-tenuiloba-overview/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Pavonia lasiopetala", "Scientific Name": "Pavonia lasiopetala", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Rock Rose", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Softwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Seed coat thickness varies. More uniform germination rates may be achieved by first soaking the seeds in hot water. — Collection: Seeds can be collected from the capsule when it turns brown, but before it becomes dry and splits. || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Take cuttings in spring before plant starts to bloom. Cut a stem three to six inches long, just below the node. Remove all but the top leaves and place in vermiculite.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/pavonia-lasiopetala/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=PALA13"}, {"Plant_ID": "Pectis angustifolia", "Scientific Name": "Pectis angustifolia", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Limoncillo", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sown spring and fall.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/pectis-angustifolia/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=PEAN"}, {"Plant_ID": "Pellaea atropurpurea", "Scientific Name": "Pellaea atropurpurea", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Purple Cliffbrake Fern", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Spores | Bud", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Spores — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Place them on a tray lined with moist peat moss. Cover the tray with plastic wrap and keep it in a warm, well-lit location. After a few weeks, you should see tiny green plants emerging from the spores. Once they are large enough to handle, you can carefully separate them and plant them in small pots filled with a well-draining soil mix. Keep them moist and in a warm, bright location, and they should grow into healthy plants over time. — Collection: Spores are produced June–September on fertile leaves. Fertile (spore-bearing) leaflets are longer and thinner than the sterile ones, and spores are borne in a continuous band along the outer margin of the underside of the leaflets, protected by the recurved edge of the leaflet (the edge of the leaflet curls around the underside edge of the leaflet). To propagate this plant, you will need to wait until the spores are mature and ripe. This usually occurs in late summer or early fall. Once you see the spores on the undersides of the fronds, you can carefully collect them. || Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: Gently dig around the plant's base to expose the roots. Carefully separate the rootball into smaller sections, ensuring each section has healthy fronds and its own set of roots. Plant these divisions into pots or directly into the ground. — Collection: Choose a mature Pellaea atropurpurea plant. During early spring or early fall.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/pellaea-atropurpurea/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://mdc.mo.gov/discover-nature/field-guide/purple-cliff-brake#:~:text=Ferns%20have%20a%20two%2Dpart,the%20typical%20fern%20life%20cycle. | https://plantiary.com/plant/pellaea-atropurpurea_15156.html#:~:text=Propagation%3A%20You%20can%20propagate%20Pellaea,the%20fronds%20with%20spore%20cases."}, {"Plant_ID": "Penstemon baccharifolius", "Scientific Name": "Penstemon baccharifolius", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Rock Penstemon", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds barely covered by soil. Will germinate in approximately 8 wks @ 40ºF (4ºC).", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/penstemon-baccharifolius/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://tomclothier.hort.net/page08.html#b"}, {"Plant_ID": "Penstemon cobaea", "Scientific Name": "Penstemon cobaea", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Wild Foxglove", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Germination is best with cold-moist stratification. Sow the seeds in a well-draining soil mix in the spring. — Collection: Collect seed in summer when capsules are brown and seeds are black. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Take a healthy stem cutting and root it in a moist, well-draining medium. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Dig up plant carefully. Divide making sure there are roots and stems for each division. Plant immediately in the ground. Keep moist until it becomes established.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/penstemon-cobaea/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://earthone.io/plant/penstemon%20cobaea?srsltid=AfmBOor2ypxSJEUcPwhATyZkscT0KAOSg5EGEDFHrL2MfGd67czC4XuT 2) https://plants.ces.ncsu.edu/plants/penstemon/ 3) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=PECO4 | https://earthone.io/plant/penstemon%20cobaea?srsltid=AfmBOor2ypxSJEUcPwhATyZkscT0KAOSg5EGEDFHrL2MfGd67czC4XuT | https://plants.ces.ncsu.edu/plants/penstemon/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Penstemon digitalis", "Scientific Name": "Penstemon digitalis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Smooth White Penstemon", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump | Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Dividing is done by digging up the plant and gently separating the crowns and roots into sections, each with a few shoots and roots attached. Prune back the foliage of each new division. — Collection: Fall or early spring. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Seeds require exposure to sunlight to germinate and a cold/moist stratification period of approximately 4 weeks. Not exposing Penstemon seed to a cold/moist period will significantly reduce the germination rate. Either cold-stratify the seeds in the refrigerator for 30 days, or winter-sow the seeds in order to break the seeds dormancy. Sprinkle seed on top of the soil in a pot, press the seed into the soil with your thumb to ensure good contact with the soil without burying the seed. If direct sowing on bare, disturbed areas, just scatter seed where you would like the plants to grow. Then, walk over the seed to press them into the soil. Keep the soil and seed moist. Seeds will generally germinate within a few weeks in spring and will bloom the second year. — Collection: Collect ripe seeds in the fall || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the bottom leaves of the cutting and dip the cut end into rooting hormone before planting in moist soil. Keep the soil moist and the cutting in a bright but not too hot location until roots begin to form. — Collection: Stem cuttings can be taken the summer or fall from healthy stems that are not flowering, and should be about 4-6 inches long.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/penstemon-digitalis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=PEDI 2) https://plantiary.com/plant/penstemon-digitalis_864.html | 1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=PEDI 2) https://growitbuildit.com/foxglove-beardtongue-guide-penstemon-digitalis/ | https://plantiary.com/plant/penstemon-digitalis_864.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Penstemon laxiflorus", "Scientific Name": "Penstemon laxiflorus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Nodding Beardtongue", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Bud", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: To hIf the pods are not ripe enough it may be necessary to crush the capsules screen them. See can be moist stratified after storage at 33-40 F for 30 days (Philips 1985, Shirley 1994). Penstemons reseed readily in loose soil and the plantlets thus produced may be transplant. There are 3,200,000 seeds/lb and the recommended seeding rate is 1 lb/acre (USDA 1948). — Collection: To harvest seeds, cut the stalk and place into a paper bag upside down. Store the bag in a cool, dry place until the seeds dry and fall from the pods. Shake the bag to remove all the seeds then screen to clean. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: If the pods are not ripe enough it may be necessary to crush the capsules screen them. Seed can be sown fresh. || Bud — Method: Clumps may be divided in fall or early spring.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/penstemon-laxiflorus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://warcapps.usgs.gov/PlantID/Species/Details/4024#:~:text=Beardtongue%20prefers%20full%20to%20a,in%20fall%20or%20early%20spring."}, {"Plant_ID": "Penstemon murrayanus", "Scientific Name": "Penstemon murrayanus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Cupleaf Penstemon", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Getting the seed to germinate is a challenge. Sow the seed at the start of winter to allow them to naturally stratify. They flower the second year after their attractive glaucous green foliage bulks up for the first growing season. — Collection: Collected seed after the seed capsules dried. Bag seedheads to capture ripening seed Allow pods to dry on plant; break open to collect seeds || Seed — Treatment: Scarification, Stratification — Method: Stratifying seed for three months increased germination to 20%. Seeds that had smoke water and three months of stratification had 46% germination! Use of gibberellic acid and liquid smoke to improve seed germination of native perennial seed. Gibberellic acid is a plant hormone that promotes germination. Liquid smoke can contain karrakins, another germination promoting hormone. There’s research that demonstrates after a fire passes through an ecosystem that karrakins are produced and help increase germination of some plant species. While gibberellic acid can be a bit of a challenge for home owners to acquire, smoke water is readily available from grocery stores. — Collection: Collected seed after the seed capsules dried. Bag seedheads to capture ripening seed Allow pods to dry on plant; break open to collect seeds", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/penstemon-murrayanus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://meristemhorticulture.com/planted/scarlet-penstemon#:~:text=These%20plants%20I%20found%20provided,and%20not%20impede%20the%20view. | 1) https://meristemhorticulture.com/planted/scarlet-penstemon#:~:text=These%20plants%20I%20found%20provided,and%20not%20impede%20the%20view. 2) https://davesgarden.com/guides/pf/go/138793"}, {"Plant_ID": "Penstemon triflorus", "Scientific Name": "Penstemon triflorus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Hill Country Penstemon", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow the seeds in spring, covering them lightly with soil to ensure proper germination. — Collection: Collect seeds from mature plants in late summer. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Use a rooting medium composed of perlite and peat moss to encourage root development. Expect the rooting process to take approximately 2-4 weeks. During this time, keep the cuttings in a warm, humid environment to promote successful growth. — Collection: Select healthy stems that are about 4-6 inches long.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/penstemon-triflorus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://greg.app/hill-country-penstemon-overview/#"}, {"Plant_ID": "Phacelia congesta", "Scientific Name": "Phacelia congesta", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Blue Curls", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Cutting", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: You can start the seeds indoors, if you want, but they also start well from direct sowing in late winter to early spring. Lightly cover the seeds with growing medium and keep the area evenly moist until the seeds sprout. (Seeds I direct-sowed on March 26 started sprouting on April 30; your experience may vary.) The winter-sowing method can also work well if you want to sow in late fall to mid winter. Blue curls may self-sow if you allow the seeds to ripen on the plants. I find that some of the dropped seeds sprout in fall, and those plants tend to flower earlier a few weeks earlier the following spring. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: If starting indoors, stratify seeds by placing them in a moist medium (e.g., damp paper towel or sand) inside a plastic bag and refrigerating them at around 40°F (4°C) for 4–6 weeks before sowing. Scarification. || Cutting — Method: Preparation: Remove the lower leaves from the stem, leaving just a few leaves at the top. Rooting Medium: Prepare a pot filled with a sterile rooting medium, such as a mixture of peat moss and perlite. Planting: Insert the cut end of the stem into the rooting medium. Ensure the stem is planted firmly. Humidity: Cover the pot with a plastic dome or wrap to create a humid environment. Lighting: Place the pot in a bright, indirect location. Watering: Keep the rooting medium moist, but avoid overwatering. Timing: Depending on the environment, cuttings can root anywhere from a few weeks to a month or two. — Collection: Select healthy, actively growing stems from your existing Phacelia congesta plants.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/phacelia-congesta/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://hayefield.com/product/phacelia-congesta-blue-curls/#:~:text=Germination%20Information:%20You%20can%20start,weeks%20earlier%20the%20following%20spring. 2) https://www.forwardplant.com/care/propagate/phacelia-congesta/ | https://nativefloraseeds.org/products/blue-curls#:~:text=Spring%20Sowing:%20If%20starting%20indoors%2C%20stratify%20seeds,is%20not%20typically%20necessary%20for%20Phacelia%20congesta. | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-phacelia-congesta/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Philadelphus ernestii", "Scientific Name": "Philadelphus ernestii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Canyon Mock Orange", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Semi-harwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Take semi-hardwood stem cuttings: Using clean and sharp pruning shears, take cuttings from the Philadelphus Ernestii shrub. Cut a 4-6 inch (10-15 cm) section of stem just below a node. Ensure the cut is clean and not jagged. Prepare the cuttings: Remove the lower leaves from the stem, leaving only a few at the top. This helps reduce water loss during the rooting process. Optional: You can also dip the cuttings in a rooting hormone powder to encourage root growth. Prepare the planting medium: Fill a small container with a well-draining soil mix. A combination of peat moss, perlite, and sand can be used. Ensure the medium is moist, but not waterlogged. Plant the cuttings: Make a hole in the planting medium with a pencil or your finger and insert the stem cutting into it. Gently firm the soil around the cutting to provide support. Provide the right environment: Place the container in a warm and bright location, but avoid direct sunlight. The ideal temperature for rooting is between 68-77°F (20-25°C). Mist the cuttings: To maintain humidity around the cuttings, mist them with water using a spray bottle. Ensure that the soil remains moist but not excessively wet. Be patient: It can take several weeks for the cuttings to develop roots. During this time, avoid disturbing or moving the container. Transplanting: After the cuttings have rooted and developed a healthy root system, typically after 6-8 weeks, they can be transplanted into individual pots or directly into the garden. — Collection: The best time to propagate Philadelphus Ernestii is during the early spring or late autumn when the plant is dormant. Look for healthy, disease-free stems to use for propagation. Ideally, choose stems that are about one-year-old, as they have the best chance of rooting successfully.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/philadelphus-ernestii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://plantiary.com/plant/philadelphus-ernestii_23420.html#:~:text=Propagation:%20You%20can%20propagate%20Philadelphus,occasionally%20until%20they%20develop%20roots."}, {"Plant_ID": "Phlox drummondii", "Scientific Name": "Phlox drummondii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Drummond's Phlox", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Select a flat or tray with drainage holes and fill it with a sterile, well-draining seed starting mix. Moisten the mix with water until it is evenly damp but not waterlogged, preparing a suitable environment for annual phlox seeds. Scatter annual phlox seeds sparingly on top of the prepared seed starting mix. Slightly press the seeds into the soil with your hand or a flat object. Do not cover the seeds with soil as annual phlox needs light for germination. Place the sowing container in a location with consistent light and maintain a temperature around 65-70°F (18-21°C). Ensure that the seed starting mix remains damp by misting with water regularly, avoiding over-watering which can cause the seeds of annual phlox to rot. Monitor the sowing container daily for signs of germination. Germination of annual phlox typically occurs within 10-21 days under optimal conditions. Keep the seedlings exposed to strong, indirect light to avoid legginess. Once the seedlings of annual phlox develop their first set of true leaves, thin them to prevent overcrowding. Carefully select and remove the weakest seedlings, leaving the strongest to continue growing. When annual phlox seedlings are large enough to handle and have developed several sets of true leaves, carefully transplant them into individual pots or a prepared garden bed. Handle the delicate roots with care to avoid damage. Water the newly transplanted seedlings deeply but infrequently, allowing the soil to dry out slightly between watering. Protect the young plants from extreme weather and pests. — Collection: Collect seeds from capsules that have turned from green to a light tan color just prior to being released.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/phlox-drummondii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=PHDR 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Phlox_drummondii.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Phlox pilosa", "Scientific Name": "Phlox pilosa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Fragrant Phlox", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Not as reliable. Germination is enhanced by cold stratification one week at 30 degrees. — Collection: Fruits open abruptly, so save the seed by tying a mesh bag around the developing fruits", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/phlox-pilosa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=PHPI"}, {"Plant_ID": "Phyla nodiflora", "Scientific Name": "Phyla nodiflora", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Frogfruit", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Clump | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Root them in a moist, well-draining soil mix. — Collection: Take stem cuttings in the spring or early summer || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Division can be done during repotting by separating the plant into smaller sections. When planting Frog Fruit, it’s essential to ensure the soil is well-drained and to provide regular watering, especially during the initial establishment phase. Once the plant is settled, it requires minimal maintenance, with occasional pruning or mowing as needed to maintain its desired appearance. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sowing the seeds in the spring or fall and providing consistent moisture can result in the successful establishment of new Frog Fruit plants. When planting Frog Fruit, it’s essential to ensure the soil is well-drained and to provide regular watering, especially during the initial establishment phase. Once the plant is settled, it requires minimal maintenance, with occasional pruning or mowing as needed to maintain its desired appearance.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/phyla-nodiflora/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://earthone.io/plant/phyla%20nodiflora 2) https://www.sustainscapeflorida.com/project/phyla-nodiflora-frog-fruit/#:~:text=Seed%20Propagation&text=Sowing%20the%20seeds%20in%20the,of%20new%20Frog%20Fruit%20plants. | https://earthone.io/plant/phyla%20nodiflora | https://www.sustainscapeflorida.com/project/phyla-nodiflora-frog-fruit/#:~:text=Seed%20Propagation&text=Sowing%20the%20seeds%20in%20the,of%20new%20Frog%20Fruit%20plants."}, {"Plant_ID": "Physostegia intermedia", "Scientific Name": "Physostegia intermedia", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Marsh Obedient Plant", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Prepare a seed bed or trays with a mixture of half garden soil and half organic compost. Ensure the soil is well-draining yet retains enough moisture. Sow the seeds evenly over the surface of the soil, lightly pressing them into the soil without covering them completely. The seeds require light to germinate. Gently mist the soil with water to ensure it is evenly moist but not waterlogged. Maintain consistent moisture throughout the germination period. Place the seed bed or trays in a location with plenty of light. Seeds typically germinate within two to three weeks. Continue to water regularly, ensuring the soil remains moist. After germination, thin out seedlings to reduce overcrowding. Transplant seedlings to a prepared garden bed when they are large enough to handle. — Collection: Collect seeds from mature slender false dragonhead plants by allowing the seed heads to dry on the plants. Once dry, gently shake the seeds into a container for collection.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/physostegia-intermedia/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Physostegia_intermedia.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Physostegia virginiana", "Scientific Name": "Physostegia virginiana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Obedient Plant", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump | Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Divide the clump into two to three new clumps. Place clumps in individual pots with potting soil. Put the pots into a shady place for a few days to recover. Transfer the new clumps into their permanent spots in full sun. — Collection: Clumps that form from spreading stolons can be divided in early spring or late fall. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Damp stratify seeds 3 months at 40 degrees. Plant the seeds just below the surface of the soil in groups of about two to three seeds. Space groups of seeds about 18 to 24 inches apart. It will take about a week for seeds to germinate. Once the plants are a few inches tall in pots, they can be transplanted into your garden a few weeks after the last frost. — Collection: Seeds are 1/8\", dull-brown nutlets. Harvest the seeds from the seed heads two months after blooming when the flowers are faded and dried. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the shoot's lower leaves and plant it in a small container filled with potting soil. Keep the soil moTransplant the young plant into the ground or container when new leaves have formed. You can also wait until the early fall to place them in the ground. ist but not soggy. — Collection: Cut off a 5 to 6-inch long young, tender shoot with a sterile cutting tool. Cut below a leaf node.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/physostegia-virginiana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=PHVI8 2) https://www.thespruce.com/obedient-plant-1402852#:~:text=Light,twice%20a%20week%20once%20established. | 1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?https://www.thespruce.com/obedient-plant-1402852#:~:text=Light,twice%20a%20week%20once%20established.id_plant=PHVI8 2) https://farmhouseandblooms.com/how-to-grow-obedient-plant-physostegia-virginiana/#:~:text=sowing%20directly%20into%20the%20garden | https://www.thespruce.com/obedient-plant-1402852#:~:text=Light,twice%20a%20week%20once%20established."}, {"Plant_ID": "Phytolacca americana", "Scientific Name": "Phytolacca americana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "American Pokeweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Root", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: The seeds of pokeberry are germinated successfully by storing them dry over winter and then nicking them with a needle to break the seed coat, followed by germination treatment at about 75ºF. sow autumn or spring in a cold frame[200]. When they are large enough to handle, prick the seedlings out into individual pots and grow them on in the greenhouse for their first winter. Plant them out into their permanent positions in late spring or early summer, after the last expected frosts. If you have sufficient seed, it might be worthwhile trying an outdoor sowing in a seed bed in early spring. Grow the plants on in the seedbed for their first year and plant them out the following spring. — Collection: Gather about a pint of the purple berries, crush them, cover with water, and let ferment for a few days. The good seeds will settle to the bottom and the pulp and skins can be floated off and discarded. The seeds are then spread out to dry and then stored in a cool place. || Root — Treatment: Division — Method: Use a sharp spade or knife to divide the rootstock, making sure that each section has at least one growth bud. Very easy, larger divisions can be planted out direct into their permanent positions. It is better to pot up the smaller divisions and grow them on in light shade in a cold frame until they are well established before planting them out in late spring or early summer. — Collection: Division on March or October", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/phytolacca-americana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=PHAM4 2) https://research.fs.usda.gov/treesearch/19804#:~:text=The%20seeds%20of%20pokeberry%20(Phytolacca,germination%20treatment%20at%20about%2075%C2%BAF. 3) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Phytolacca+americana#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,late%20spring%20or%20early%20summer. 4) https://www.michigangardener.com/growing-pokeweeds/ | 1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=PHAM4 2) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Phytolacca+americana#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,late%20spring%20or%20early%20summer."}, {"Plant_ID": "Pinus taeda", "Scientific Name": "Pinus taeda", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Loblolly Pine", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sown in late fall. — Collection: Collect cones from vigorous trees n late summer and fall just before they completely open to drop seeds. Spread cones on racks to dry so they will release seeds. Cones may be shaken to release seeds.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/pinus-taeda/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=PITA"}, {"Plant_ID": "Platanus occidentalis", "Scientific Name": "Platanus occidentalis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Sycamore", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Seeds which over-winter on tree and are planted in spring germinate quickly. — Collection: Fruit is most easily collected after leaf drop. Dry heads, then place in bags and crush to separate seeds. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stored seeds must be stratified 30 days at 41 degrees before planting.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/platanus-occidentalis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=PLOC"}, {"Plant_ID": "Pluchea odorata", "Scientific Name": "Pluchea odorata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Saltmarsh Fleabane", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Fill seed trays or pots with well-drained soil or a seed starting mix. Scatter the seeds thinly across the surface of the soil and gently press them down for good soil contact, but do not bury them deeply; sweetscent seeds need light to germinate. Water the seeds in gently using a spray bottle or a fine nozzle watering can, ensuring the soil is moistened but not waterlogged. Keep the soil consistently moist throughout the germination period. Place the seed trays or pots in a location with bright light but not direct sunlight. Provide temperatures of about 70°F (21°C), which is typically favorable for sweetscent seed germination. After germination, when seedlings are large enough to handle, thin them out by snipping the weakest seedlings at soil level, allowing sufficient space for the strongest onAfter successfully propagating sweetscent, transition the seedlings to individual pots or their final growing location once they are large enough to handle the conditions. Sweetscent prefers full sun to light shade and tolerates a range of soil types, although it thrives in wetter soils. Water sweetscent regularly but avoid overwatering. Monitor for pests and diseases and manage them as necessary.es to grow. — Collection: Gather ripe seeds from a mature sweetscent once they've developed on the plant. Dry them if they are moist, and remove any chaff or debris to ensure only clean, viable seeds are used for sowing. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: For cuttings, take a healthy stem cutting and place it in moist soil or water until roots develop. Propagation is best done in the spring or early summer.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/pluchea-odorata-var-odorata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Pluchea_odorata.html 2) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/pluchea-odorata | https://earthone.io/plant/pluchea%20odorata?srsltid=AfmBOoq66Ynimj6K5Ds1lDp0-U-UUBCX3N2e2HVCKVTOqQIS-BssyydN"}, {"Plant_ID": "Polanisia dodecandra", "Scientific Name": "Polanisia dodecandra", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Clammyweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seed about 1/4 inch deep outdoors in late fall to early spring, so they get exposed to cold temperatures and can then sprout when they’re ready. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: For the rooting medium, use a mix of peat and perlite. This combination provides excellent drainage while retaining enough moisture for the cuttings to establish roots. — Collection: Select healthy stems that are 4-6 inches long. This length is ideal for rooting, ensuring a robust start for your new plants.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/polanisia-dodecandra/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://hayefield.com/product/polanisia-dodecandra-redwhisker-clammyweed/#:~:text=I%20recommend%20sowing%20(about%201,description%20as%20well%20before%20ordering. 2) https://greg.app/redwhisker-clammyweed-overview/#:~:text=Soil%20Preparation%20%F0%9F%8F%9E%EF%B8%8F,ideally%20between%206.0%20and%207.0. 3) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Polanisia_dodecandra.html#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Redwhisker%20Clammyweed?&text=Redwhisker%20Clammyweed%20is%20effectively%20propagated,to%20partial%20shade%20to%20thrive. | 1) https://greg.app/redwhisker-clammyweed-overview/#:~:text=Soil%20Preparation%20%F0%9F%8F%9E%EF%B8%8F,ideally%20between%206.0%20and%207.0. 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Polanisia_dodecandra.html#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Redwhisker%20Clammyweed?&text=Redwhisker%20Clammyweed%20is%20effectively%20propagated,to%20partial%20shade%20to%20thrive."}, {"Plant_ID": "Polygala alba", "Scientific Name": "Polygala alba", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "White Milkwort", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the lower leaves from the cutting and dip the end of the stem in rooting hormone. Plant the cutting in a pot with well-draining soil and keep it moist. Provide the cutting with bright, indirect light and keep it warm. After a few weeks, the cutting should develop roots and begin to grow. — Collection: Take cuttings from healthy, non-flowering stems during active growth. The cutting should have at least one node.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/polygala-alba/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Polygala_alba.html# 2) https://plantiary.com/plant/polygala-alba_9587.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Polytaenia texana", "Scientific Name": "Polytaenia texana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Prairie Parsley", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow fresh seed outdoors in Fall. — Collection: Allow seedheads to dry on plants then remove and collect seeds", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/polytaenia-texana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://davesgarden.com/guides/pf/go/141172"}, {"Plant_ID": "Pontederia cordata", "Scientific Name": "Pontederia cordata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Pickerelweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Root | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Root — Treatment: Division — Method: Dig up the plant or remove it from its pot. Use a clean sharp soil knife or pruners to cut apart the roots, leaving each piece with several healthy leaves and thick rhizomes. Replant the new clumps and they will take off quickly, increasing your pickerel weed inventory. — Collection: Divide the rhizomes in late winter to early spring. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Start inside in flats in late winter. Seeded plants can take several seasons to produce the bright flowers. Caring for pickerelweeds: once the seeds have germinated just requires consistent moisture and bright sunlight. Plant outside in spring. Alternatively: sown as soon as it is ripe in pots standing in 2cm of water in a cold frame. Cover the seed lightly with silver sand. Submerse in 3cm depth of water after the seedlings emerge[200]. When they are large enough to handle, prick the seedlings out into individual pots and grow them on in water in the greenhouse for their first winter. Plant them out into their permanent positions in late spring or early summer, after the last expected frosts. — Collection: You can save and dry the seeds from the plant Best sown as soon as it is ripe", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/pontederia-cordata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.gardeningknowhow.com/ornamental/water-plants/pickerelweed/growing-pickerel-rush.htm 2) https://www.rhs.org.uk/plants/13502/pontederia-cordata/details 3) https://gardeningsolutions.ifas.ufl.edu/plants/ornamentals/pickerel-weed/#:~:text=Planting%20and%20Care,flag%20iris%20(Iris%20virginica). 4) https://pfaf.org/user/plant.aspx?latinname=Pontederia+cordata#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,Lateral%20shoots. | 1) https://www.gardeningknowhow.com/ornamental/water-plants/pickerelweed/growing-pickerel-rush.htm 2) https://pfaf.org/user/plant.aspx?latinname=Pontederia+cordata#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,Lateral%20shoots."}, {"Plant_ID": "Populus deltoides", "Scientific Name": "Populus deltoides", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Eastern Cottonwood", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Semi-harwood | Seed | Root", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Plant directly into soil immediately, leaving 2-3 nodes above the soil line. Growth hormones can be used to aid in rooting. Ensure the area is well irrigated to allow for ample rooting which takes 3 to 6 weeks. Another method is to plant cuttings in a potting mixture, keeping the soil moist and in indirect sunlight until roots develop. Leaves will begin to emerge when trees normally break dormancy. — Collection: Collect 8-12” length cuttings from established trees either in late fall before dormancy, or in late winter just before breaking dormancy. Use newer branches with multiple nodes, remove any leaves. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow the seeds in a seed tray containing a well-draining soil mixture. Keep the soil moist, and the seeds should germinate within 2-3 weeks. — Collection: Collect mature seeds from the parent plant (not from the ground) and soak them in water for 24 hours. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Place open catkins and seeds in a bucket of water for one to two weeks and change water every other day, and as soon as seedlings appear, press catkins with seeds in a moist sphagnum peat moss in flats, but do not cover and keep under intermittent mist. — Collection: Collect partially opened catkins from trees and avoid collecting catkins that have been on the ground for several days. Place catkins in a closed brown bag in room temperature, until almost 100% of catkins open. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Distribute seeds on moist silt, sand, or fine gravel in full sunlight. Seeds will germinate within 5 days. The fragile seedling grows slowly for about 3 weeks and then should be moved to full sunlight for a substantial part of each day, as it is not shade tolerant. — Collection: Seed dispersal occurs from May through mid-July. Viability improves if the seeds are air-dried before storage. Cottonwood seed should always be stored at below freezing temperature, even for short-term storage. || Root — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Plant cuttings in a potting mixture, keeping the soil moist and in indirect sunlight until roots develop. — Collection: Take a 1-2 inch section of the root from an established plant.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/populus-deltoides/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://courses.washington.edu/esrm412/protocols/2022/PODE3.pdf 2) 2) https://hort.ifas.ufl.edu/database/lppi/sp292.shtml 3) https://plantiary.com/plant/populus-deltoides_3795.html | https://plantiary.com/plant/populus-deltoides_3795.html | https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=salicaceae-populus-495 | 1) https://courses.washington.edu/esrm412/protocols/2022/PODE3.pdf 2) https://hort.ifas.ufl.edu/database/lppi/sp292.shtml"}, {"Plant_ID": "Portulaca pilosa", "Scientific Name": "Portulaca pilosa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Chisme", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end into rooting hormone and stick into moist soil in the garden or a pot. Water enough to keep the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged. The cuttings should root in one to two weeks. Once new growth is visible, cut back to regular watering. — Collection: Using sharp, sterile snips or pruners, take stem cuttings of 2 to 4 inches from the tips. Remove any spent blooms or buds, and remove leaves from the bottom half of the stem. || Seed — Method: catter seeds over moist, well-draining soil, and press lightly to make contact with the soil. The seeds germinate best when exposed to light. Water to keep soil lightly moist until growth is visible. Keep indoor seedlings in a bright window or under grow lights. Seedlings germinate in 10 to 14 days. After the danger of frost has passed, harden off indoor seedlings, gradually exposing them to outdoor temperatures and sunlight. Transplant into the garden or a larger container, being careful not to disturb the roots.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/portulaca-pilosa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.southernliving.com/portulaca-7561541#:~:text=Portulaca%20is%20very%20easy%20to,cut%20back%20to%20regular%20watering."}, {"Plant_ID": "Proboscidea louisianica", "Scientific Name": "Proboscidea louisianica", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Devil's Claw", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Semi-harwood | Rhizome | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: The best time to plant seeds is in the spring, after the last frost has passed, or start them indoors a few weeks before the last frost. The seeds should be planted 1 to 2 inches deep in well-draining soil that has been amended with compost or other organic matter. The seeds should be kept moist but not waterlogged, and they should germinate within 2 to 3 weeks. — Collection: Collect mature pods in the fall after turning brown, just before they begin to split open. The pods should be allowed to dry completely before the seeds are removed. Once separated, the seeds can be planted immediately or stored in a cool, dry place until planting is desired. || Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove any leaves from the bottom inch or two of the cutting and dip the cut end in rooting hormone to encourage root development. Plant your cuttings in a moist, well-draining potting mix. Place them in a bright, indirect light location. Keep the soil consistently moist during the rooting process, which usually takes 4-6 weeks. — Collection: Take semi-hardwood cuttings from actively growing stems. Opt for sections with at least two sets of leaves and make a clean cut just below a leaf node. || Rhizome — Treatment: Cutting — Method: The cuttings should be planted in well-draining soil and kept moist until new growth appears. It is important to keep the cuttings out of direct sunlight until they have rooted and begun to grow, as direct sunlight can dry out the tender new roots. — Collection: Root cuttings should be taken in early spring, just as new growth is beginning. The cuttings should be about 4 to 6 inches long and should include several nodes. Each division should have its own roots and shoots. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: The divided sections should be replanted immediately in well-draining soil and kept moist until new growth appears. — Collection: Best for mature plants that have become woody or unproductive. Division should be done in the fall, just before the plant goes dormant. The plant should be carefully dug up and the root ball divided into several sections, each with its own set of roots and new growth.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/proboscidea-louisianica/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-proboscidea-louisianica/ 2) https://www.botanikks.com/plants/martynia-louisiana-miller/563020/1 | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-proboscidea-louisianica/ | 1 ) https://greg.app/propagate-devils-claw/ 2) https://www.botanikks.com/plants/martynia-louisiana-miller/563020/1 | https://www.botanikks.com/plants/martynia-louisiana-miller/563020/1"}, {"Plant_ID": "Prosopis glandulosa", "Scientific Name": "Prosopis glandulosa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Honey Mesquite", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Stored seed require soaking for 1 minute hot water (200*F). Or mechanical scarification. Sow seeds in a greenhouse in November. Seeds germinated over the following 6 months. Seedlings grow quickly. — Collection: Gather pods as soon as they turn brown. Dry pods and extract their seed.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/prosopis-glandulosa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://publicgarden.ucdavis.edu/tree-database/honey-mesquite-prosopis-glandulosa 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=PRGL2"}, {"Plant_ID": "Prunus caroliniana", "Scientific Name": "Prunus caroliniana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Cherry Laurel", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Remove pulp from seeds and briefly air dry. Moist stratification for 30-60 days in warm area, then cold stratified for 60-90 days. Sow in spring. — Collection: Collect fruit when it is filled out, firm, and its ripe color. Seeds to be sown immediately in fall do not need drying.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/prunus-caroliniana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=PRCA"}, {"Plant_ID": "Prunus mexicana", "Scientific Name": "Prunus mexicana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Mexican Plum", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Clean pulp from seeds. Require a period of after-ripening followed by cold stratification. Stratify seeds for 40-60 days in a moist, warm environment, followed by cold stratification between 35 and 40 degrees, for 60-90 days. — Collection: Collect fruit when it is filled out, firm, and its ripe color. Loses viability rapidly if allowed to dry out after collection and cleaning.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/prunus-mexicana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=PRME"}, {"Plant_ID": "Prunus minutiflora", "Scientific Name": "Prunus minutiflora", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Almond", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Offshoots | Softwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Requires 2 - 3 months cold stratification and is best sown in a cold frame as soon as it is ripe. Sow stored seed in a cold frame as early in the year as possible. Protect the seed from mice etc. The seed can be rather slow, sometimes taking 18 months to germinate. Prick out the seedlings into individual pots when they are large enough to handle. Grow them on in a greenhouse or cold frame for their first winter and plant them out in late spring or early summer of the following year.. — Collection: Unblemished fruit must be significantly overripe before harvesting seed; clean and dry seeds. || Offshoots — Treatment: Division — Method: This method is used when the plant already has an established root system. Divide the plant into halves or smaller sections using a clean and sharp knife, and plant each section in individual containers or directly into the ground. It is recommended to divide the plant in the early spring before new growth emerges. || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the leaves from the bottom half of the cutting. Dip the cut end into a rooting hormone and plant into a well-draining potting mix. Rooting occurs in 4-6 weeks, and the cutting can be transplanted into a bigger container or the ground once it has rooted. — Collection: Softwood cuttings are taken in spring or semi-hardwood cuttings in summer. The cuttings should be taken from the current year's growth and should be 10-15 cm long. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Seeds can be germinated for propagation in the late winter or early spring season. It is recommended to treat the seeds with a fungicide before sowing. The seeds can be sown in pots filled with a well-draining potting mix. They should be kept in a bright, warm and moist location for good germination. Germination can take anywhere from a few weeks to several months. Once the seedlings have grown to a sufficient size, they can be transplanted to individual containers or directly into the ground. — Collection: Unblemished fruit must be significantly overripe before harvesting seed; clean and dry seeds.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/prunus-minutiflora/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.botanikks.com/plants/prunus-minutiflora-engelm/576468/1. 2) https://temperate.theferns.info/plant/Prunus+minutiflora#:~:text=The%20Reference%20Manual%20of%20Woody,M.%20W.&text=A%20very%20detailed%20book%20on,summer%20of%20the%20following%20year.&text=Layering%20in%20spring. 3) https://davesg3rden.com/guides/pf/go/81575 | https://www.botanikks.com/plants/prunus-minutiflora-engelm/576468/1 | 1) https://www.botanikks.com/plants/prunus-minutiflora-engelm/576468/1. 2) https://temperate.theferns.info/plant/Prunus+minutiflora#:~:text=The%20Reference%20Manual%20of%20Woody,M.%20W.&text=A%20very%20detailed%20book%20on,summer%20of%20the%20following%20year.&text=Layering%20in%20spring. | 1) https://www.botanikks.com/plants/prunus-minutiflora-engelm/576468/1. 2) https://davesgarden.com/guides/pf/go/81575"}, {"Plant_ID": "Prunus rivularis", "Scientific Name": "Prunus rivularis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Creek Plum", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Clean pulp from seed and briefly air dry. Seeds sown in fall don't need to be dried. Seeds taken from ripe fruit have a high viability rate. — Collection: Collect fruit when it is filled out, firm, and its ripe color. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Clean pulp from seeds. Require a period of after-ripening followed by cold stratification. Stratify seeds for 40-60 days in a moist, warm environment, followed by cold stratification between 35 and 40 degrees, for 60-90 days.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/prunus-rivularis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=PRRI"}, {"Plant_ID": "Prunus serotina var. eximia", "Scientific Name": "Prunus serotina var. eximia", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Escarpment Black Cherry", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Requires a period of after-ripening followed by a period of warm stratification followed by a period of cold stratification. For spring sowing, after-ripen for a period, then stratify seeds in moist sand for two weeks in a greenhouse, then cold stratify (36-41 degrees) for 60-90 days. Use a light mineral medium for seedlings. Plant well before high temperatures. — Collection: Collect fruit when it is filled out, firm, and its ripe color. Clean seeds from pulp and briefly air dry. (Seeds to be sown immediately in fall do not need drying.) Storage viability is maintained at 31-41 degrees.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/prunus-serotina-var-eximia-2/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=prsee"}, {"Plant_ID": "Prunus serotina var. serotina", "Scientific Name": "Prunus serotina var. serotina", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Eastern Black Cherry", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Clean pulp from seeds. Requires a period of after-ripening followed by cold stratification. Stratify seeds for 40-60 days in a moist, warm environment, followed by cold stratification between 35 and 40 degrees, for 60-90 days.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/prunus-serotina-var-eximia/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=PRSES"}, {"Plant_ID": "Psoralidium tenuiflorum", "Scientific Name": "Psoralidium tenuiflorum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Scurfy Pea", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Pre-soak the seed for 24 hours in warm water and then sow in early to mid spring in a greenhouse. Either sow the seed in individual pots or pot up the young seedlings as soon as possible in order to avoid root disturbance. Grow them on in the pots until planting out in their final positions. It is usually impossible to transplant this species without fatal damage to the root || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Division in spring. With great care since the plant resents root disturbance. It is virtually impossible to divide this species successfully.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/psoralidium-tenuiflorum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Psoralea+tenuiflora#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,this%20species%20successfully%5B200%5D."}, {"Plant_ID": "Ptelea trifoliata", "Scientific Name": "Ptelea trifoliata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Wafer Ash", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratify 3 months at 41 degrees. — Collection: Harvest samaras in late summer and early fall as soon and they turn light yellow-brown.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ptelea-trifoliata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=PTTR"}, {"Plant_ID": "Quercus buckleyi", "Scientific Name": "Quercus buckleyi", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Red Oak", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Semi-harwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Scarification: Soak in water, let stand in water for 24 hours. Plant texas red oak at a depth where the soil covers the acorn to ensure adequate moisture retention and protect young saplings from harsh environmental conditions and wildlife until established. — Collection: Collect healthy, mature acorns. Before sowing, carry out a float test by immersing acorns in water; those that sink are more likely viable and should be chosen for further steps. Stratification is often not required, but ensuring the acorns are free from pests and disease is crucial. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratification: cold stratify for 60 days , or until radicle emergence. Plant texas red oak at a depth where the soil covers the acorn to ensure adequate moisture retention and protect young saplings from harsh environmental conditions and wildlife until established. — Collection: Collect healthy, mature acorns. Before sowing, carry out a float test by immersing acorns in water; those that sink are more likely viable and should be chosen for further steps. Stratification is often not required, but ensuring the acorns are free from pests and disease is crucial. || Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the leaves from the bottom half of each cutting. If present, cut any large remaining leaves in half to reduce moisture loss. Dip the cut end into rooting hormone powder to encourage root growth. Fill a pot with well-draining potting mix, like a mixture of peat, perlite, and sand. Insert the cut end of the cutting into the soil, ensuring a couple of leaf nodes are covered. Water the soil thoroughly so it is moist but not waterlogged. Place the pot in an area that receives bright, indirect light and has a consistent temperature. Cover the pot with a plastic bag or a clear plastic dome to maintain high humidity around the cutting, creating a mini greenhouse effect Check the soil moisture regularly, keeping it consistently moist. Also, check for signs of fungus or disease, and remove the covering periodically to allow for air ventilation. Over a few weeks, roots will begin to form. Gradually acclimate the cutting to normal humidity conditions before planting in a permanent location. — Collection: Harvest semi-hardwood cuttings from a healthy texas red oak during the growing season. Select stems that are mature but still slightly flexible, about pencil-thickness, and 4-6 inches long, with several leaf nodes.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/quercus-buckleyi/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://sheffields.com/seeds/Quercus/buckleyi#:~:text=Growing%20Info,Native%20to:%20Oklahoma%2C%20Texas 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Quercus_buckleyi.html#:~:text=Propagation%20Time:%20Spring,conditions%20and%20wildlife%20until%20established. | https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Quercus_buckleyi.html#:~:text=Texas%20red%20oak%20is%20a,acclimated%20to%20natural%20outdoor%20conditions."}, {"Plant_ID": "Quercus fusiformis", "Scientific Name": "Quercus fusiformis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Escarpment Live Oak", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Softwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Before planting, the seeds must first undergo stratification, a process of exposing them to cool temperatures, typically around 40°F, for a period of several weeks. This step is necessary as it softens the hard outer shell of the seed, allowing water to penetrate and the seed to germinate. After stratification, the seeds are sown in well-prepared soil and covered with a thin layer of mulch. Plant at a shallow depth. Burying acorns too deep can inhibit germination and root growth for texas live oak. Initially, the soil should be kept moist, and as they begin to grow, they require regular watering. — Collection: The seeds are collected from mature trees in the fall, either on the ground, or after shaking the branches. || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip in a rooting hormone before planting in a well-aerated rooting medium such as perlite or vermiculite. Soil can be used, but it should be mixed with coarse sand to improve its drainage. The propagated cuttings should be kept under high humidity with frequent misting to avoid wilting or drying out. After several weeks, roots should begin to grow, and the cuttings can be transplanted to more stable growing conditions. — Collection: Softwood cuttings from new growth are typically collected during the spring or early summer. The cuttings should be 6-8 inches long.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/quercus-fusiformis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.botanikks.com/plants/quercus-fusiformis-small/548392/1 2) https://earthone.io/plant/quercus%20fusiformis?srsltid 3) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Quercus_fusiformis.html | https://www.botanikks.com/plants/quercus-fusiformis-small/548392/1"}, {"Plant_ID": "Quercus havardii", "Scientific Name": "Quercus havardii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Havard Oak", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the bottom end of the cutting in rooting hormone powder and shake off excess. Plant the cutting in a pot of well-draining soil mix and water it thoroughly. Place the pot in a bright but indirect light and keep the soil moist. After several weeks, gently tug on the cutting to see if it has rooted. Once roots have formed, you can transplant the new plant into a larger container or outdoors. — Collection: Take a cutting from a healthy branch that is at least 6 inches long and has several leaves attached. Remove the leaves from the bottom half of the cutting. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Soak the acorns in water for 24 hours to remove any toxins and improve germination. Fill a pot or small container with well-draining soil mix and plant the acorn with the pointed end facing down, around 1-2 inches deep. Water the soil until it is moist but not waterlogged. Keep the pot in a warm location with bright but indirect light. Once the seedling has emerged, you can gradually acclimate it to more sunlight and outdoor conditions. — Collection: Collect ripe acorns from a mature Quercus Havardii tree. || Stem — Treatment: Layering — Method: Wrap the cut section with moist sphagnum moss and cover it with plastic wrap, securing the ends tightly. Check the moisture level of the moss regularly and mist it if needed to keep it damp. After several weeks, roots should have formed at the cut section. Cut the branch below the rooted section and pot it in well-draining soil mix. Keep the new plant in a warm, bright location with moderate humidity, watering it regularly. — Collection: Select a healthy, non-flowering branch and peel off a narrow strip of bark around one-third to one-half of the stem, exposing the inner cambium layer.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/quercus-havardii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://plantiary.com/plant/quercus-havardii_11821.html#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate,with%20bright%20but%20indirect%20light."}, {"Plant_ID": "Quercus laceyi", "Scientific Name": "Quercus laceyi", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Lacey Oak", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Best if sown immediately as acorns lose viability quickly in storage. Plant immediately outdoors or in deep containers to accomodate long initial taproot. They sprout immediately without dormancy period. — Collection: Best quality acorns are picked or shaken from the tree. Collect when color has changed to brown. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Use a clean, sharp knife to make a clean cut just below a leaf node. Remove the lowest leaves to expose 1-2 inches of the stem. If available, dip the cut end in rooting hormone to enhance root development. Fill a pot with a well-draining potting mix, such as a combination of peat and perlite. Insert the cut end of the cutting into the soil, ensuring at least one node is buried, as roots and new shoots will form from these nodes. Cover the pot with a plastic bag or place it in a propagator to maintain high humidity. This is crucial for lacey oak, as it helps prevent the cutting from drying out before it can root. Keep the soil moist but not waterlogged, and place the pot in a location with indirect light. Rooting typically occurs in 4-8 weeks, after which you can gradually acclimatize the new lacey oak plant to less humid conditions. — Collection: Choose healthy, new growth branches from lacey oak in early summer. These cuttings should be approximately 6-8 inches long and have several sets of leaves.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/quercus-laceyi/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=QULA | https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Quercus_laceyi.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Quercus macrocarpa", "Scientific Name": "Quercus macrocarpa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Bur Oak", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Hardwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Best if sown immediately as acorns lose viability quickly in storage. Plant directly in the soil outdoors or in deep containers to accommodate long initial taproot. Keep the soil moist but not waterlogged. Ideal planting depth ranges from 1/2 to 3/4 inches. Acorns to be sown immediately can be soaked in hot water for 15 min. to prevent weevil infestation. Stored seed should be fumigated with methyl bromide. Storage of seed is best in a cooler or refrigerator maintained at a high relative humidity and cool temperatures (33 to 370F). Germination rates decline quickly after 2 years in storage. Partial shade is considered beneficial to germination. Usually seedlings are lifted and transplanted after the first year’s growth. — Collection: Collect acorns in the fall, remove the caps, Collect when color has changed to brown. Best quality acorns are picked or shaken from the tree. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: 30-60 days at 41 degrees may be beneficial. — Collection: Collect acorns in the fall, remove the caps, Collect when color has changed to brown. Best quality acorns are picked or shaken from the tree. || Hardwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end in rooting hormone and plant it in a container filled with potting soil made of peat moss and perlite. Keep the soil moist and the humidity high by wrapping a clear plastic bag loosely over the cutting. Place it in a warm area until roots form, which might take two or three months. Keep in mind that not all cuttings will \"take\" and grow—don't be disappointed if you lose several of them. Once roots grow, put the tree indoors in a sunny, warm spot for the first year. Then, it is ready to be transplanted into the ground. — Collection: With sharp, clean pruners, take several cuttings from hardwood, each at least 6 inches long, from stems at least the diameter of a pencil. The cutting should have at least three or four nodes. Snip the leaves off the bottom, leaving only a few at the top. Make a fresh, sharp cut at a 45-degree angle on the bottom of the cutting,", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/quercus-macrocarpa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=QUMA2 2) https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/plantmaterials/mtpmcrb13122.pdf 3) https://www.thespruce.com/growing-bur-oak-5091583 4) https://earthone.io/plant/quercus%20macrocarpa?srsltid=AfmBOooHHKA7cs44zjozakqm7i_NjUcDqtUw-n_CGi61to53Y6KQRnM- | 1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=QUMA2 2) https://www.thespruce.com/growing-bur-oak-5091583 | 1) https://www.thespruce.com/growing-bur-oak-5091583 2) https://www.eiu.edu/biology/posters/2012-01.pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Quercus marilandica", "Scientific Name": "Quercus marilandica", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Blackjack Oak", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Semi-harwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Seeds quickly lose viability if it is allowed to dry out. It can be stored moist and cool overwinter but is best sown as soon as it is ripe in an outdoor seed bed, though it must be protected from mice, squirrels etc. Small quantities of seed can be sown in deep pots in a cold frame. Plants produce a deep taproot and need to be planted out into their permanent positions as soon as possible, in fact seed sown in situ will produce the best trees[11]. Trees should not be left in a nursery bed for more than 2 growing seasons without being moved or they will transplant very badly. To propagate in pots, prepare a potting mix made of equal parts sand and peat moss. Fill pots with the mixture and plant the acorns about 1 inch deep. Keep the pots in a warm and well-lit area, and keep the soil moist. After 6-8 weeks, the acorns should begin to sprout. Once the seedlings have grown to 2-3 inches in height, they can be carefully transplanted into larger containers or planted in the ground. The newly propagated plants will need to be watered regularly and protected from harsh weather conditions during their early growth stages. With proper care, they will grow into healthy trees over time. — Collection: Seeds (acorns) collected by hand picking or flailing it from tree as soon as acorns can be removed from caps-avoid collecting acorns that have been on the ground for several weeks. collect acorns from mature trees in the fall. Choose healthy acorns that are free of pests and damage. Clean the acorns by removing any debris or foreign objects and soak them in water overnight. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Seeds (acorns) to be stratified in damp sphagnum peat moss for three or four months in 36 to 40 degrees Fahrenheit refrigerator. Acorns planted into individual pots deep enough to accommodate taproot or in flats to start off several seedlings, before transplanting them into individual pots. Do not let acorns dry. || Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Once you've selected your cuttings, it’s time to prepare them for rooting. Begin by trimming the leaves from the lower half of each cutting to reduce moisture loss. Next, make a small cut at the bottom of the cutting. This wounding process encourages rooting by increasing the surface area for water absorption. Using a rooting hormone can significantly enhance your success rate. Opt for a rooting hormone that contains auxins, which are natural plant hormones that promote root development. Before planting, dip the cut end of each cutting into the rooting hormone. This simple step can make a big difference in how well your cuttings take root. Creating the right environment is essential for rooting success. Maintain high humidity levels between 70-80% by using a humidity dome or covering the cuttings with a plastic bag. Temperature also plays a vital role; keep the rooting area at a steady 70-75°F (21-24°C). Additionally, provide indirect sunlight to prevent scorching, ensuring your cuttings receive the light they need without the risk of damage. — Collection: start by selecting semi-hardwood cuttings taken in late summer or earlBlackjack Oakor cuttings that arootstockches long and have at least 2-3 healthy leaf nodes. Choosing healthy stems is crucial; ensure they are free from any signs of disease or pests. This attention to detail will set the foundation for successful rooting.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/quercus-marilandica/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.npsot.org/wp-admin/post.php?post=16793&action=edit 2) https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=fagaceae-quercus-499&referer=wildflower 3) https://plantiary.com/plant/quercus-marilandica_3621.html#:~:text=To%20propagate%20this%20plant%2C%20you,into%20healthy%20trees%20over%20time. 4) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Quercus_marilandica.html#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Blackjack%20oak?&text=Blackjack%20oak%20propagates%20easily%20through,the%20soil%20is%20well%2Ddraining. | 1) https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=fagaceae-quercus-499&referer=wildflower 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Quercus_marilandica.html#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Blackjack%20oak?&text=Blackjack%20oak%20propagates%20easily%20through,the%20soil%20is%20well%2Ddraining. | 1) https://greg.app/propagate-blackjack-oak/#:~:text=%F0%9F%8C%B1%20Selecting%20the%20Right%20Cuttings,is%20essential%20for%20rooting%20success. 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Quercus_marilandica.html#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Blackjack%20oak?&text=Blackjack%20oak%20propagates%20easily%20through,the%20soil%20is%20well%2Ddraining."}, {"Plant_ID": "Quercus muehlenbergii", "Scientific Name": "Quercus muehlenbergii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Chinkapin Oak", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: The best time to plant acorns is immediately after they fall in autumn. Plant the acorns sideways, 3/4 to 1 inch deep, in pots deep enough to accommodate long taproot or directly in their permanent location. Give them at least 1 inch of water weekly if it doesn’t rain. Cover the soil with 2 to 3 inches of mulch or straw to help suppress weeds and protect the seedlings against frost heave. The acorns will soon start germinating; growth will stop during cold weather and restart in the spring. Be careful when pulling weeds so you don’t uproot the tender seed Chinkapin oaks are cold-hardy trees that can tolerate freezing temperatures. Protect young saplings growing outside in containers or newly transplanted outdoors with a layer of mulch or straw over the root zone. A radicle is produced in the fall soon after planting. Top growth is initiated the following spring. Length of Establishment Phase: 4-6months which includes the overwintering period. Active Growth Phase: Plants require little maintenance during active growth other than application of at least 1 inch of water per week during drouth conditions and elimination of weed competition. — Collection: Collect seeds immediately after they drop. Place them in a bowl of cold water; viable seeds will sink to the bottom, while those with low viability will float. Discard those and plant the viable acorns immediately to achieve optimum germination rate. If you store the acorns over the winter, the germination rate can drop from over 90% to less than 50%.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/quercus-muehlenbergii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.thespruce.com/chinkapin-oak-growing-guide-5202085#:~:text=Propagating%20Chinkapin%20Oak,t%20uproot%20the%20tender%20seedlings. 2) chrome-extension://efaidnbmnnnibpcajpcglclefindmkaj/ https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/plantmaterials/wvpmcot12017.pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Quercus shumardii", "Scientific Name": "Quercus shumardii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Shumard Oak", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Best if sown immediately as acorns lose viability quickly in storage. Plant immediately outdoors or in deep containers to accomodate long initial taproot. They sprout immediately without dormancy period. Soaking seeds in hot water for at least 15 minutes helps to prevent weevil infestation. After the soaking plant directly into a large container. The Shumard oak grows best in moist but well-drained loamy soils — Collection: Best quality acorns are picked or shaken from the tree. Collect when color has changed to brown. Seed may be floated in water to help determine viability. Seed that floats is normally poorly filled and has low or no viability. Floaters are discarded, while the seed that sinks is retained for planting. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cuttings in rooting hormone to stimulate root developent and increase the chances of success when propagating. It helps to accelerate the rooting process, which is beneficial for the relatively slow-rooting oak species. Trays are used to hold the potting mix and maintain the cuttings in a controlled environment. They allow for ease of transport during the propagation process. Enrich the planting site with compost and ensure that the soil has good drainage and the appropriate pH level to foster robust growth in shumard oak. Placing a clear plastic dome over the propagation tray creates a greenhouse-like environment with high humidity, which is beneficial for the cuttings of shumard oak to prevent them from drying out before they can establish roots. Maintain consistent moisture, but avoid over-saturation. Allow the soil to dry out slightly between watering to prevent rot. Once the cutting of shumard oak has established roots, gradually introduce it to less humid conditions by opening the plastic bag or humidity dome for increasing periods each day. After a week, remove the cover completely. Transplant the rooted cutting to a larger pot filled with standard potting soil and ensure it receives full sun to partial shade. Water the young shumard oak deeply to encourage deep root growth, allowing the soil to dry slightly between waterings. Protect from extreme weather conditions and pests, and supplement with fertilizer according to shumard oak's growth stages and the soil's nutrient content. — Collection: Select disease-free branches for cutting propagation. Ensure the cuttings are from vigorous and healthy parts of the parent plant to increase the chances of successful propagation.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/quercus-shumardii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://apps.cals.arizona.edu/arboretum/taxon.aspx?id=838#:~:text=Cultivation%20Notes:%20Like%20most%20oaks,a%20low%20toxicity%20(1). 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=QUSH 3) https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/plantmaterials/wvpmcot12018.pdf | 1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Quercus_shumardii.html#:~:text=Shumard%20oak%20can%20be%20propagated,or%20seed%20is%20kept%20moist. 2) https://apps.cals.arizona.edu/arboretum/taxon.aspx?id=838#:~:text=Cultivation%20Notes:%20Like%20most%20oaks,a%20low%20toxicity%20(1)."}, {"Plant_ID": "Quercus stellata", "Scientific Name": "Quercus stellata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Post Oak", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Hardwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Best if sown immediately as acorns lose viability quickly in storage. Plant outdoors or in deep containers to accommodate long initial taproot. Plant in permanent location after a year. Acorns to be sown immediately can be soaked in hot water for 15 min. to prevent weevil infestation. Stored seed should be fumigated with methyl bromide. Gently coaxing post oak into a new location thrives best when done in the warmth of late spring into early summer, providing ample growing time. Choose sites that mimic its native, well-drained soils and offer partial sun. Remember, patience is key with post oak's slow rooting nature. — Collection: Collect when color has changed to brown. Stored seeds have a reduced chance of germination. || Hardwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Sharp pruning shears are essential for taking clean cuts from the parent post oak without crushing or damaging the tissues. Clean cuts help prevent infection and encourage healthy root development. Rooting hormone when applied to the cut end of the post oak cutting, it promotes faster and more reliable root initiation, greatly increasing the chances of successful propagation. Sterile soil mix provides a pathogen-free environment for the post oak cuttings to establish roots, which is crucial for preventing disease and ensuring the cuttings remain healthy. Propagation trays with domes offers a controlled environment with optimal humidity to encourage rooting in post oak cuttings and protect them from external stress factors. A watering can with fine hole delivers gentle, even watering that doesn't disturb the planting medium or newly established roots of the post oak cuttings, promoting steady growth. A mister or spray bottle helps maintain high humidity around the post oak cuttings, which is significant for preventing water loss from the leaves and encouraging root formation. Care for post oak post-propagation involves gradually acclimating the new plant to outside conditions after roots have established, which may take several weeks. Once acclimated, plant post oak in a location with full to partial sun and well-drained soil. Water the young tree deeply to encourage deep root growth, but allow the soil to dry out between watering, as post oak is drought-resistant. Pruning is minimal except to remove dead or diseased wood. Extra care must be taken not to overwater as post oak's native habitat is typically dry, and it is adapted to these conditions. — Collection: The ideal time to propagate post oak by cutting is during autumn, when the tree is entering dormancy and resource allocation shifts from foliage to root development, enhancing rooting potential. Cooler temperatures reduce transpiration stress on cuttings, while autumn's diffused light supports gradual acclimatization. This seasonal timing promotes successful root establishment before spring growth. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratify them by storing in a moist, cool environment for several months, and then plant them in well-drained soil in the spring. — Collection: Collect acorns in the fall. Stored seeds have a reduced chance of germination.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/quercus-stellata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=QUST 2) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Quercus+stellata#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,they%20will%20transplant%20very%20badly. 3) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Quercus_stellata.html#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Post%20oak?&text=Post%20oak%20(Quercus%20stellata)%20propagates,propagating%20using%20cuttings%20or%20layering. 4) https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/plantmaterials/wvpmcot12019.pdf 5) https://treeshepherds.net/post-oak/#:~:text=Propagation,a%20reduced%20chance%20of%20germination. | https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Quercus_stellata.html | 1) https://earthone.io/plant/quercus%20stellata https://treeshepherds.net/post-oak/#:~:text=Propagation,a%20reduced%20chance%20of%20germination."}, {"Plant_ID": "Quercus virginiana", "Scientific Name": "Quercus virginiana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Live Oak", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Semi-harwood | Root", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Best if sown immediately as acorns lose viability quickly in storage. Plant immediately outdoors, with pointed end facing down, or in deep containers to accommodate long initial taproot. Time of year to collect seed: Autumn, Time of year to sow seed: Summer, Seed treatment: none, Time required for germination: 3-5 weeks, Comment: Mulched beds. Wire screens against rodents. — Collection: Best quality acorns are picked or shaken from the tree. Collect when color has changed to brown. || Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Cutting type: stem tip. Time of year to take cuttings: Summer. Cutting maturity: semi-hardwood Rooting hormone: IBA TALC 16000 PPM. Rooting environment: intermittent mist, Soil temperature for best rooting: 70-80 degrees F. Time to rooting: 10-12 weeks. Comment: Juvenile cuttings should be pencil size. || Root — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip cuttings briefly in 1,250, 2,500, 5,000 or 10,000 parts per million (ppm) IBA solution containing 50 percent ethyl alcohol. These cuttings were rooted in a mist propagation bed in a mix of three parts perlite to 1 part peat (by volume). Those dipped in 10,000 ppm IBA had 100 percent rooting in 40 days. All cuttings treated with 2,500 or 5,000 ppm IBA rooted in 70 days, whereas those treated with 1,250 ppm IBA required 100 days to reach completed rooting. Plant rooted cuttings in No. 1 pots two months after cuttings are collected. — Collection: Collect 8inch-long tip cuttings of rhizomic shoots in April.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/quercus-virginiana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://hort.ifas.ufl.edu/database/lppi/sp319.shtml#:~:text=Time%20of%20year%20to%20graft,Scions%20should%20be%20pencil%20size. 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=QUVI 3) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/quercus-virginiana | 1) https://hort.ifas.ufl.edu/database/lppi/sp319.shtml#:~:text=Time%20of%20year%20to%20graft,Scions%20should%20be%20pencil%20size. 2) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/quercus-virginiana | 1) https://agrilife.org/elpaso/files/2011/10/Cloning-live-oak.pdf 2) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/quercus-virginiana"}, {"Plant_ID": "Quincula lobata", "Scientific Name": "Quincula lobata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Purple Groundcherry", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Propagate through cuttings from healthy stems with leaves, planted in well-draining soil. Maintain moisture without waterlogging, and provide indirect light for optimal root development, leading to robust new plants.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/quincula-lobata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Quincula_lobata.html#:~:text=Water:%20Originating%20from%20arid%20regions,leading%20to%20robust%20new%20plants."}, {"Plant_ID": "Ranunculus macranthus", "Scientific Name": "Ranunculus macranthus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Big Buttercup", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Tuber | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Begin by soaking the seeds for 24 hours. This simple step helps to enhance germination, which thrives in moist and warm conditions, ideally between 20-25°C. The germination of Ranunculus macranthus typically takes about 10-14 days under optimal conditions. Providing warmth and moisture is key to kickstarting this processe. || Tuber — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully separate the tubers and replant them immediately to ensure they establish well. — Collection: Aim to do this every 2-3 years during early spring or fall. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Use a rooting medium that consists of a mix of perlite and peat moss to encourage robust root development. — Collection: Select healthy stems that have at least 2-3 nodes.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ranunculs-macranthus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://greg.app/ranunculus-macranthus-overview/ 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Ranunculus_macranthus.html 3) https://www.forwardplant.com/plant-info/ranunculus-macranthus/ | 1) https://greg.app/ranunculus-macranthus-overview/ 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Ranunculus_macranthus.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Ranunculus hispidus var. nitidus", "Scientific Name": "Ranunculus hispidus var. nitidus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Bristly Buttercup", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump division | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow them directly in the soil at a depth of 1/4 inch. Under optimal conditions, expect germination within 14 to 30 days. || Clump division — Treatment: Division — Method: Dividing established plants is best done in early spring or fall. Carefully separate the clumps and replant them immediately to ensure their health and vitality. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: For the cuttings method, select healthy stems that are 4-6 inches long. Use a rooting medium composed of peat and perlite to encourage successful root development. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Buttercup seeds need some cold stratification for germination, at least 30 days and some species require 60 days.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ranunculus-hispidus-var-nitidus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://greg.app/hispid-buttercup-overview/ | https://www.friendsofeloisebutler.org/pages/plants/swampbuttercup.html#:~:text=Seed:%20Fertile%20receptacles%20elongate%20and,some%20species%20require%2060%20days."}, {"Plant_ID": "Ratibida columnifera", "Scientific Name": "Ratibida columnifera", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Mexican Hat", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seed directly in the soil in the fall. Usually blooms the second year. — Collection: Seed is available commercially or can be collected in late summer. Collect seed from several plants to increase the spectrum of color. If possible, collect seed from plants with solid yellow ray petals to contrast with plants with reddish-brown ray plants. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Place the seeds in a moistened paper towel, seal them in a plastic bag, and store them in a refrigerator for 30-60 days to mimic winter conditions and break seed dormancy. Fill seed trays or pots with well-draining seed starting mix, leaving some space at the top. Sow the stratified prairie coneflower seeds on the surface of the pre-moistened starting mix, as light aids germination. Gently press them into the soil without covering them with additional soil. Water the seeds gently with a fine mist to moisten the soil without disturbing the seeds. Cover the pots or trays with a clear plastic dome or wrap to maintain humidity and warmth, which aids in germination. Position the pots or trays in a location that receives bright, indirect light and maintains a consistent temperature, ideally between 70-75°F (21-24°C). Check the soil moisture daily, ensuring it remains damp but not waterlogged. Watch for germination, which should occur in 2-3 weeks for prairie coneflower. Once seedlings appear, gradually remove the humidity cover to acclimate them to lower humidity levels. When seedlings develop a couple of true leaves and are easily handled, thin them out, leaving the strongest ones with enough space to grow. After the seedlings have grown strong enough and there is no danger of frost, transplant each prairie coneflower seedling into individual pots or a prepared garden spot with full sun exposure and well-draining soil. Gradually acclimate the prairie coneflower seedlings to outdoor conditions over a period of 7-10 days before planting them out in their final location. Provide consistent watering, particularly during the first growing season, to establish a strong root system. As prairie coneflower is drought-tolerant, reduce watering frequency once established. — Collection: Choose healthy, mature seeds from a reputable supplier or collect them from an existing prairie coneflower plant after the blooms have dried and seed heads have formed.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ratibida-columnifera/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=RACO3 | 1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=RACO3 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Ratibida_columnifera.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Rhus aromatica", "Scientific Name": "Rhus aromatica", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Aromatic Sumac", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Acid scarification for one hour followed by stratification at 41 degrees for 30-60 days. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Acid scarification for one hour followed by stratification at 41 degrees for 30-60 days.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/rhus-aromatica-2/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=RHAR4"}, {"Plant_ID": "Rhus glabra", "Scientific Name": "Rhus glabra", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Smooth Sumac", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Acid scarify one to three hours, then stratify immediately for 30 days at 41 degrees. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: After scarification, then stratify immediately for 30 days at 41 degrees.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/rhus-glabra/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=RHGL"}, {"Plant_ID": "Rhus copallinum var. lanceolata", "Scientific Name": "Rhus copallinum var. lanceolata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Flameleaf Sumac", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Suckers | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Suckers — Treatment: Division — Method: Cut suckers and keep soil moist and in the shade until established. Another way is to cut the suckers, cover up and leave in the ground until they have formed roots. Keep them moist until established. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Remove pulp from seed. Soaking the seed in water then removing and planting plump seeds. Or 30-55 minutes of acid scarification needed, treat with boiling water, or use rock tumbler to scarify seed. — Collection: Collect September to October from plump, red fruit. Remove pulp from seed.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/rhus-lanceolata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=RHLA3"}, {"Plant_ID": "Rhus microphylla", "Scientific Name": "Rhus microphylla", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Little Leaf Sumac", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Acid scarification for one hour followed by stratification at 41 degrees for 30-60 days. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Acid scarification for one hour followed by stratification at 41 degrees for 30-60 days.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/rhus-microphylla/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=RHMI3"}, {"Plant_ID": "Rhus virens", "Scientific Name": "Rhus virens", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Evergreen Sumac", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Remove the seeds from the fruit and soak them in water for 24 hours (scarification). Some sources specify soaking in hot water starting at a temperature of 80 - 90c and allowing it to cool, prior to sowing in order to leach out any germination inhibitors. Rhus virens seeds also require a period of cold stratification. (see below) After stratification, sow the seeds in pots filled with well-draining potting mix. Place the pots in a sunny location and keep the soil consistently moist. Germination can take up to 6-8 weeks. — Collection: Gather mature, red fruit clusters during the fall. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Place the soaked seeds in a moist mix of peat moss and sand and store them in a refrigerator for 60-90 days. sow the seeds in pots filled with well-draining potting mix. Place the pots in a sunny location and keep the soil consistently moist. Germination can take up to 6-8 weeks.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/rhus-virens/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-rhus-virens/ 2) https://pfaf.org/User/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Rhus+virens"}, {"Plant_ID": "Rhynchospora colorata", "Scientific Name": "Rhynchospora colorata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Whitetop Sedge", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Ensure each division has a healthy root system. Proper soil fertility and drainage are essential for successful establishment after replanting, while careful handling protects the roots during the division process. — Collection: Divide when clumps get too large or crowded.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/rhynchospora-colorata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.shootgardening.com/plants/rhynchospora-colorata 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Rhynchospora_colorata.html#:~:text=Water:%20Starrush%20Whitetop%20thrives%20in,roots%20during%20the%20division%20process. 3) https://earthone.io/plant/rhynchospora%20colorata?srsltid=AfmBOorCsilkabyIg4GF09DSeg3HZ6qva7P8AZirZ2GbmKnMNV98UvRc"}, {"Plant_ID": "Rhynchospora nivea", "Scientific Name": "Rhynchospora nivea", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Showy Whitetop", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds in a seed starting mix, barely covering them. Keep the soil consistently moist and provide bright, indirect light. Germination can be erratic, ranging from a few weeks to a couple of months. — Collection: Collect seeds in late summer or early fall when the flower heads have matured and turned brown. Gently rub the heads to release the tiny, brown seeds. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Gently tease apart the clump into smaller sections, each with a good portion of roots and shoots. Replant the divisions at the same depth they were originally growing. Water thoroughly and keep the soil consistently moist until new growth emerges. — Collection: Spring is the ideal time to divide established clumps. Carefully dig up a healthy clump, ensuring you get a good root mass.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/rhynchospora-nivea/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-rhynchospora-nivea/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Rivina humilis", "Scientific Name": "Rivina humilis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Pigeonberry", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: It is easiest to clean the fruit while fresh because once dried the pulp sticks to the seed, making it more difficult to remove. Sow seeds in a well-draining soil mix and keep them moist until germination. — Collection: When collecting the berries with the intent saving seeds, one should always make sure the berry is completely ripe. If the berries are deep red and come off the plant easily, they are ripe. Pink berries are not ripe and may not be viable. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Pigeonberry is best propagated from cuttings during the warm seasons of spring and summer. This plant's propagation is moderately easy. Ensure a well-draining soil mix for optimal results. For stem cuttings, take a healthy cutting with several nodes, remove the lower leaves, and place it in moist soil or water until roots develop. Look for new growth as a sign of successful propagation.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/rivina-humilis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://earthone.io/plant/rivina%20humilis 2) https://sharonsflorida.com/plants-page/native-shrubs/rouge-plant/#:~:text=Propagation,it%20more%20difficult%20to%20remove. | 1) https://earthone.io/plant/rivina%20humilis 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Rivina_humilis.html#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Pigeonberry?,acclimatizes%20to%20its%20new%20abode."}, {"Plant_ID": "Rosa foliolosa", "Scientific Name": "Rosa foliolosa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "White Prairie Rose", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Root | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Root — Treatment: Division — Method: It can be planted deeper and filled with soil to the roots so that new roots can grow at the bottom of each branch. At the same time, prune the branches on the ground to reduce the evaporation of water and improve the survival rate of transplanting. — Collection: In the early spring or late autumn, the whole plant can be dug out with soil to be divided into ramets. Select a stem with 1-2 branches and some fibrous roots, and then separate it from the whole plant || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: The substrate for cutting can be a mix of river sand, rice chaff ash, or vermiculite, etc. Insert the branches into the substrate, shade it properly, and spray to maintain humidity. The branches will take root 20-30 days after cutting, and the survival rate is 70-80%. If the branches are dipped in rooting powder and then inserted into the substrate, the survival rate will be higher. Additionally, the cuttings can be immersed in water for cutting; the cutting temperature is 20 to 25 ℃, and new roots will grow after 20 days. — Collection: Take cutting in spring and autumn. Branches with 3-4 buds can be cut off to use.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/rosa-foliolosa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Rosa_foliolosa.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Rubus trivialis", "Scientific Name": "Rubus trivialis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Southern Dewberry", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: equires stratiRfication and is best sown in early autumn in a cold frame. Stored seed requires one month stratification at about 3°c and is best sown as early as possible in the year. Prick out the seedlings when they are large enough to handle and grow on in a cold frame. Plant them out into their permanent positions in late spring of the following year. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Cuttings of half-ripe wood, July/August in a frame. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: If there are multiple plants growing, unpot the plant and gently tug the plants apart, being careful not to disturb too many of the roots. They may be connected by large root segments which you may need to break to free the plantlet. Pot up the new plant in well-draining soil Repot the parent plant back into its original pot — Collection: Check to see if there is more than one plant. In some cases they may still be beneath the soil surface. If you feel confident, you may remove the soil to check for baby plantlets below!", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/rubus-trivialis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://temperate.theferns.info/plant/Rubus+trivialis 2) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Rubus+trivialis#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,in%20the%20autumn%5B200%5D. | 1) https://greg.app/plant-care/rubus-trivialis-southern-dewberry 2) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Rubus+trivialis#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,in%20the%20autumn%5B200%5D."}, {"Plant_ID": "Rudbeckia amplexicaulis", "Scientific Name": "Rudbeckia amplexicaulis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Clasping Coneflower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct sow in late fall, pressing into the surface of the soil since this plant needs light to germinate. Keep the soil lightly moist until germination, which usually takes 2-3 weeks. The Rudbeckia Amplexicaulis seeds can also be started indoors 6-8 weeks before planting in spring. Keep seedlings lightly moist, and transplant them as soon as they have developed several leaves. — Collection: After the flower petals fall from the head, the center cone will begin to develop seed. Remove the seed heads as soon as the stem beneath the cone begins to turn dry and brown. Spread the seed heads out to dry away from direct sunlight, then separate the small seeds from the stems by rubbing them lightly. Store the cleaned clasping coneflower seed in a dry, cool place. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Rudbeckia can be divided every 3–4 years in early spring or fall to prevent overcrowding. For more specific information on how to divide Rudbeckia, see fact sheet HGIC 1150, Dividing Perennials.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/rudbeckia-amplexicaulis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.everwilde.com/store/Rudbeckia-amplexicaulis-WildFlower-Seed.html 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=dram 3) https://hgic.clemson.edu/factsheet/rudbeckia/#:~:text=Rudbeckia%20can%20be%20propagated%20by,months%20at%2040%C2%B0F. 4) https://www.outsidepride.com/resources/planting/rudbeckia-planting/#:~:text=How%20to%20Plant%20Rudbeckia%20*%20Prepare%20the,surface%20and%20press%20them%20into%20the%20soil. | https://hgic.clemson.edu/factsheet/rudbeckia/#:~:text=Rudbeckia%20can%20be%20propagated%20by,months%20at%2040%C2%B0F."}, {"Plant_ID": "Rudbeckia fulgida", "Scientific Name": "Rudbeckia fulgida", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Perennial Black-eyed Susan", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sown in the fall directly in the ground. — Collection: Seeds can be allowed to dry out before sowing.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/rudbeckia-fulgida/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=RUFU2"}, {"Plant_ID": "Rudbeckia hirta", "Scientific Name": "Rudbeckia hirta", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Black-eyed Susan", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow directlul in soil in the fall — Collection: The nutlets turn charcoal-gray at maturity, usually 3-4 weeks after the bloom period. Seeds are mature at this time, but they are easier to collect after cones lose their tight compact stucture. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratify for 3 months at 40 degrees. Sow in the spring.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/rudbeckia-hirta/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=RUHI2"}, {"Plant_ID": "Ruellia drummondiana", "Scientific Name": "Ruellia drummondiana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Drummond's Wild Petunia", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Fill a seed tray with a well-draining potting mix. Sow the seeds on the surface and lightly press them into the soil, but do not cover them with too much soil, as they need light to germinate. Moisten the soil gently using a fine spray of water. Keep the soil consistently damp but not waterlogged until germination occurs. Once the seedlings have developed a few true leaves and are strong enough to handle, transplant them into individual pots or a prepared garden bed, ensuring adequate spacing for growth. — Collection: Harvest mature seeds from drummond's wild petunia once the seed pods turn brown and start to open on their own. Clean the seeds by gently removing any pod remnants or debris. Allow them to dry for a few days in a cool, dry place.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ruellia-drummondiana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Ruellia_drummondiana.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Ruellia humilis", "Scientific Name": "Ruellia humilis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Prairie Petunia", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the stem ends in rooting hormone. Hold the rooted cuttings in a cold frame until spring. — Collection: Cuttings can be taken in late spring or early summer. For cuttings, use a sharp knife to take a 4-6 inch cutting, || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct sow in late fall, planting just below the surface of the soil. Keep the soil lightly moist until germination, which usually takes 4-6 weeks. Water seedlings regularly until they become established. — Collection: After the flowers fade, small seed pods will form. When ripe, the seed pods will begin to turn brown; remove them and spread them out to dry away from direct sunlight. Keep in mind that the pods often explode and expel their seed as they dry, and may need a light covering to contain the seed. Separate the wild petunia seed from the pods and store the seed in a cool, dry place. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: For spring planting, mix the wild petunia seeds with moist sand and store in the refrigerator for 60 days before planting The Ruellia Humilis seeds can also be started indoors 6-8 weeks before planting in spring. Keep seedlings lightly moist, and transplant them as soon as they have developed several leaves. Water seedlings regularly until they become established. — Collection: After the flowers fade, small seed pods will form. When ripe, the seed pods will begin to turn brown; remove them and spread them out to dry away from direct sunlight. Keep in mind that the pods often explode and expel their seed as they dry, and may need a light covering to contain the seed. Separate the wild petunia seed from the pods and store the seed in a cool, dry place.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ruellia-humilis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=RUHU 2) https://earthone.io/plant/ruellia%20humilis?srsltid=AfmBOooliDNHvvRWDcKQaFIAaShQF16MlYcNKyzgjqGslmlO_CDgoXNJ | 1) https://www.everwilde.com/store/Ruellia-humilis-WildFlower-Seed.html#:~:text=HOW%20TO%20GROW,addition%20to%20a%20rock%20garden. 2) https://noddingoniongardens.com/ruellia-humilis/#:~:text=Propagation%20Notes%20Ruellia%20humilis&text=Seed%20%2D%20Collect%20late%20in%20fall,high%20February%202016%20germination%20rate. 3) https://www.wildflowerfarm.com/ruellia-humilis-wild-petunia.html | 1) https://www.everwilde.com/store/Ruellia-humilis-WildFlower-Seed.html#:~:text=HOW%20TO%20GROW,addition%20to%20a%20rock%20garden. 2) https://noddingoniongardens.com/ruellia-humilis/#:~:text=Propagation%20Notes%20Ruellia%20humilis&text=Seed%20%2D%20Collect%20late%20in%20fall,high%20February%202016%20germination%20rate."}, {"Plant_ID": "Ruellia metzae", "Scientific Name": "Ruellia metzae", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Metz's Wild Petunia", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct sow outdoors in fall or spring after last frost.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ruellia-metzae/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://davesgarden.com/guides/pf/go/38218"}, {"Plant_ID": "Ruellia nudiflora", "Scientific Name": "Ruellia nudiflora", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Wild Petunia", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Plant these in a mix of peat and perlite to strike roots quickly. Keep the soil consistently moist and provide bright, indirect light for optimum growth. Rooting hormone can encourage faster root development, but isn't strictly necessary. Once roots establish, transfer violet wild petunia to individual pots to continue thriving. — Collection: Using healthy, non-flowering stems, ensure each cutting has a set of leaves.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ruellia-nudiflora/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Ruellia_nudiflora.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Sabal minor", "Scientific Name": "Sabal minor", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Dwarf Palmetto", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratify 30 days at 38 degrees.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/sabal-minor/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=SAMI8"}, {"Plant_ID": "Sabatia campestris", "Scientific Name": "Sabatia campestris", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Meadow Pink", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow the seeds in well-draining soil in the spring after the last frost. Lightly rake the surface to loosen it and create small indentations or “dibbles” where you will place the seeds. Sprinkle the tiny seeds into the dibbles, covering them lightly with about 1/4 inch of soil. Gently firm the soil around the seeds to ensure good contact. Water the seeds gently and ensure the soil is consistently moist but not waterlogged. Germination can take 2 to 4 weeks. — Collection: Collect mature seed heads from the plant and allow them to dry out completely. Once dry, remove the seeds from the seed heads. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Plant the divisions in prepared beds, ensuring they are spaced appropriately and water well to encourage root development. — Collection: Division is best attempted in the spring or fall when the plant is dormant. Carefully dig up the entire plant and gently separate it into several smaller divisions, each with their own roots and foliage. A sharp knife or garden shears may be used to cut the root ball into separate sections. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Fill a flat or tray to about an inch deep with seed starting mix. The substrate should be moist but not waterlogged to facilitate ideal germination conditions for Meadow Pink. Evenly distribute the seeds across the surface of the starting mix and lightly press the seeds into the soil. Place the seed tray in bright, indirect light. Keep the temperature around 68-72°F. Ensure the soil remains consistently moist by misting with water. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: It's important to scarify the seeds to ensure proper germination. To do this, the seeds should be rubbed with sandpaper or nicked with a knife before planting. Seeds can be planted directly in the ground in a well-draining soil and should be kept moist until they germinate. Alternatively, seeds can be started inside in pots and transplanted outside after the last frost. — Collection: Small, brown seeds should be collected in the fall after the plant has finished flowering, then stored in a cool, dry place until spring. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the lower leaves and any flower buds from the cutting. Root in a container filled with a well-draining soil mix. Keep the soil moist and provide the cutting with bright, indirect light. Once the cutting has rooted, it can be transplanted outside. — Collection: The best time to take cuttings is in the spring or early summer. Select a healthy stem and make a clean cut with a sharp knife just below a node.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/sabatia-campestris/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://earthone.io/plant/sabatia%20campestris 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-sabatia-campestris/ 3) https://plantiary.com/plant/sabatia-campestris_20748.html | 1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-sabatia-campestris/ 2) https://plantiary.com/plant/sabatia-campestris_20748.html | https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Sabatia_campestris.html | https://www.botanikks.com/plants/sabatia-campestris/586872/1"}, {"Plant_ID": "Sagittaria platyphylla", "Scientific Name": "Sagittaria platyphylla", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Delta Arrowhead", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Plant immediately in the soil. — Collection: Spreads by runners. Allow the new plant to develop a root system and leaves before separating it from the mother plant with very sharp, sterilized scissors.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/sagittaria-platyphylla/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.npsot.org/wp-admin/post.php?post=15966&action=edit 2) https://en.aqua-fish.net/plants/sagittaria-platyphylla"}, {"Plant_ID": "Salix nigra", "Scientific Name": "Salix nigra", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Black Willow", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Separate from capsule and plant immediately. — Collection: Collect seeds as soon as the capsules begin to dry and turn yellow-brown.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/salix-nigra/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=SANI"}, {"Plant_ID": "Salvia azurea", "Scientific Name": "Salvia azurea", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Azure Sage", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Clump division", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Soak the seeds in water for 24 hours before planting. Sow them about 1/4 inch deep in seed trays or pots filled with a quality seed-starting mix. Germination usually occurs within 14-30 days, provided you maintain optimal conditions. Keep an eye on them during this period to ensure they’re thriving. Opt for a light, well-draining mix. A combination of peat moss, vermiculite, and perlite works wonders. Aim for a pH level between 6.0 and 7.0 for the best results. Avoid heavy soils, as they can retain too much moisture and lead to damping-off disease. Your seedlings will need 12-16 hours of bright, indirect light each day. Utilize grow lights or place them in a sunny window to meet this requirement. Keep the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged. A spray bottle is perfect for gentle watering. As your seedlings grow, thin them out to prevent overcrowding once they develop their first true leaves. — Collection: Wait until the flower heads turn brown and dry, then collect the seeds for storage. Store these seeds in a cool, dry place within an airtight container to maintain their viability. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Prepare your cuttings by removing the lower leaves. This step prevents rot and directs energy toward root development. Cut the stems at a 45-degree angle to maximize moisture absorption. Allow the cuttings to callous for 1-2 hours before planting; this helps prevent rot when they go into the soil. Applying rooting hormone can significantly enhance root development. Choose either a powder or gel form and follow the manufacturer's instructions for application. Using rooting hormone increases your chances of successful sage propagation. Use a well-draining potting mix, such as a blend of perlite and peat moss. Maintaining humidity levels around 70% is crucial, so consider using a humidity dome or a plastic bag to create a mini greenhouse effect. Provide indirect sunlight and keep temperatures between 70°F to 75°F (21°C to 24°C) for optimal rooting conditions. This environment will help your cuttings thrive and establish roots effectively. — Collection: Select stems that are 4-6 inches long from healthy, mature plants. Aim for semi-hardwood stems, ideally taken in late spring or early summer, and ensure each cutting has at least 2-3 leaf nodes for optimal rooting. || Clump division — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully dig around the base of the plant to lift it from the soil. Shake off excess soil and inspect the root system. Use a knife to divide the root ball into sections, ensuring each section has roots and shoots. Replant divisions immediately in well-draining soil, spacing them 1-2 feet apart. — Collection: The best times to divide your Big Blue Sage are early spring or fall. During these seasons, the plant is actively growing, making it easier for the divisions to establish. Look for signs of overcrowding or reduced flowering as indicators that it's time to divide. If your sage seems cramped or isn't blooming as vibrantly, it’s a good signal to take action. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct sow in late fall, pressing into the surface of the soil since this plant needs light to germinate. For spring planting, mix Azure Blue Sage seeds with moist sand and store in the refrigerator for 30 days before planting. Keep the soil lightly moist until germination, which usually takes 1-2 weeks.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/salvia-azurea/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://greg.app/propagate-big-blue-sage/ | https://www.everwilde.com/store/Salvia-azurea-WildFlower-Seed.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Salvia ballotiflora", "Scientific Name": "Salvia ballotiflora", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Shrubby Blue Sage", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the lower leaves and trim each cutting just below a node. You can either start propagating by placing them in water or by putting them in soil. For propagation in water, just put the cuttings in a vase and add a few inches of water. When rooting cuttings in soil, dip the cut end in rooting hormone, then plant it in moist potting medium. It’s crucial to use a well-draining soil mix. This helps prevent water retention and supports better root growth without the risk of fungal diseases. After three weeks, cuttings should be ready to pot. — Collection: Pruning shrubby blue sage before propagation encourages healthier new growth. Take cuttings in August or September, from vegetative (non-flowering) branches that are about 3 inches long. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow the seeds indoors 10-12 weeks before the last frost and keep evenly moist. Seedlings will emerge in 15-21 days at 21-24 °C.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/salvia-ballotiflora/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://travaldo.blogspot.com/2021/07/salvia-ballotiflora-shrubby-blue-sage-mejorana-care-and-culture.html 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Salvia_ballotiflora.html | https://travaldo.blogspot.com/2021/07/salvia-ballotiflora-shrubby-blue-sage-mejorana-care-and-culture.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Salvia coccinea", "Scientific Name": "Salvia coccinea", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Scarlet Sage", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds outdoors in a well-draining soil and keep them moist until germination. They can also be started indoors. Start transplants from seed indoors 6-8 weeks before the average last frost. Sow seeds shallowly, as they require light to germinate. It takes 2-3 weeks for the seeds to germinate — Collection: Bag the flowering heads to capture seeds. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the lower leaves, and place it in water or moist soil until roots develop. — Collection: Take a 4-6 inch cutting from a healthy plant, || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Older plants can be divided in spring, or cuttings taken during the growing season.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/salvia-coccinea/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://earthone.io/plant/salvia%20coccinea 2) https://www.fnps.org/assets/pdf/pubs/salvia_coccinea_tropicalsage_3_1.pdf | https://earthone.io/plant/salvia%20coccinea | https://hort.extension.wisc.edu/articles/scarlet-sage-salvia-coccinea/#:~:text=Scarlet%20sage%20is%20propagated%20by,pulled%20or%20transplanted%20when%20small)."}, {"Plant_ID": "Salvia farinacea", "Scientific Name": "Salvia farinacea", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Mealy Blue Sage", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Light is required for germination, so just press the seed into the growing medium rather than covering it. Seeds should germinate in 10-30 days. Sow indoors 8-10 weeks before the average last frost date, Bottom water or mist to avoid covering seed. Harden by setting out plants after the last frost. Plants sown outdoors after last frost may not bloom before the first frost in fall. — Collection: Seeds can be collected by bagging the old flower spikes to capture ripening seed.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/salvia-farinacea/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://hort.extension.wisc.edu/articles/mealycup-sage-salvia-farinacea/#:~:text=Grow%20mealycup%20sage%20in%20full,bright%20but%20cool%20sunny%20window. 2) https://www.johnnyseeds.com/growers-library/flowers/salvia/salvia-farinacea-key-growing-information.html#:~:text=DAYS%20TO%20GERMINATION:,USES: 3) https://sowrightseeds.com/blogs/planters-library/growing-mealycup-blue-sage-salvia-farinacea?srsltid=AfmBOortMfFdw7uxZUaUinbd7DLWORIH39dXq-0b36B2uHJmhOxiDEqt"}, {"Plant_ID": "Salvia greggii", "Scientific Name": "Salvia greggii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Autumn Sage", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Semi-harwood | Clump | Cutting", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds indoors in early spring or directly in the garden after frost. — Collection: Collect the seeds as the capsules begin to dry but before they have dropped the seeds. Allow them to dry before storing. || Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Root in moist, well-draining soil. Rooting should occur in three weeks — Collection: Take 4-6 inch cuttings from healthy non-flowering stems in late spring or summer || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Insure each section has healthy roots and stems. — Collection: Split mature clumps in early spring or fall. || Cutting — Treatment: Layering — Method: In the spring, pull it back and snip/separate all the rooted branches. — Collection: Put down fresh mulch for the fall and make sure the lower branches are in contact with the soil.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/salvia-greggii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=SAGR4 2) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/salvia-greggii#:~:text=Plant%20Salvia%20greggii%20in%20well,seeds%2C%20cuttings%2C%20or%20division: | https://www.gardenia.net/plant/salvia-greggii#:~:text=Plant%20Salvia%20greggii%20in%20well,seeds%2C%20cuttings%2C%20or%20division: | https://www.facebook.com/groups/npsotaustin/posts/3393903137598155"}, {"Plant_ID": "Salvia lyrata", "Scientific Name": "Salvia lyrata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Lyre Leaf Sage", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump | Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: To divide, carefully separate the plant into smaller sections, ensuring each section has roots attached, and replant them in suitable soil. — Collection: Division is best done in early spring or fall. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Cold-moist stratification period is required for germination of Salvia seed. This species does require light for germination so should not be covered with more than 1/8 of an inch. — Collection: Collect the seeds as the capsules begin to dry but before they have dropped the seeds. Spread seeds in thin layers to dry a few days before storing in sealed, refrigerated containers. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Using a clean, sharp pair of scissors or pruning shears, cut just below a leaf node. Remove the leaves from the lower half of the cutting to prevent rot. Although optional, applying rooting hormone to the cut end can enhance root development. Dip the end of the cutting into a small amount of rooting hormone powder or liquid. Fill a planting container with a well-draining potting mix suitable for lyreleaf sage. Make a hole in the soil with a pencil or your finger, and insert the cutting about 1 to 2 inches deep, ensuring at least one leaf node is below the surface. Water the cuttings gently but thoroughly to settle the soil around them. Make sure the soil is consistently moist, but not waterlogged, to promote root growth. Cover the container with a plastic bag or place it in a propagator to create a humid atmosphere. This mimics a greenhouse effect and helps prevent the cuttings from drying out. Place the container in a bright location with indirect sunlight. Avoid full sun exposure as it can cause the cuttings to overheat and wilt. Check the cuttings every few days for soil moisture and to aerate by briefly removing the cover. Look out for new growth as a sign of rooting, typically within 2-6 weeks. Once the cuttings have developed a good root system, transplant them into individual pots or directly into the garden. Be gentle to avoid damaging the delicate roots. Gradually acclimate the new lyreleaf sage plants to outdoor conditions if they were rooted indoors. This process should take place over 7-10 days before planting in their final location. — Collection: Choose healthy, non-flowering stems from an established lyreleaf sage plant. Look for stems with new growth that are about 6 to 8 inches long.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/salvia-lyrata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=SALY2 2) https://earthone.io/plant/salvia%20lyrata | 1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=SALY2 2) https://earthone.io/plant/salvia%20lyrata 3) https://sharonsflorida.com/plants-page/native-wildflowers/lyreleaf-sage/#:~:text=Propagation,watered%20until%20it%20becomes%20established. | https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Salvia_lyrata.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Salvia penstemonoides", "Scientific Name": "Salvia penstemonoides", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Big Red Sage", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Cutting | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: In the spring, sow the seeds on the surface of a well-draining seed-starting mix, lightly pressing them into the soil without covering them too deeply to allow light to assist in germination. Place the pots in a warm, brightly lit location but out of direct sunlight and keep the soil consistently damp. Germination typically occurs within a few weeks. — Collection: Collect seeds from the mature flowers after the flowers have wilted and the seed pods have dried. Allow the seeds to dry. || Cutting — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Cuttings taken from the mother plant in early summer are planted in moist soil and covered with plastic to maintain humidity. Roots will form in 2-4 weeks, after which the plastic cover can be removed. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: The divided sections can be planted in separate pots or directly in the soil. — Collection: As the plant grows, it forms a clump which can be carefully dug up, and the clump is divided into 2 or 3 sections each containing a portion of the root system.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/salvia-pentstemonoides/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Salvia_pentstemonoides.html | https://www.botanikks.com/plants/salvia-penstemonoides-kunth-bouch/504495/1"}, {"Plant_ID": "Salvia roemeriana", "Scientific Name": "Salvia roemeriana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Cedar Sage", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip it in rooting hormone, and plant it in well-draining soil. Keep the soil moist until roots develop. — Collection: Take a healthy stem cutting in late spring or early summer. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Make sure large fallen leaves are kept cleared away from the area where seeds are sown, as seedlings can't emerge otherwise. — Collection: Collect seed in late spring and summer when seeds are black. They fall soon after maturing so watch closely.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/salvia-roemeriana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://earthone.io/plant/salvia%20roemeriana? | https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=saro3"}, {"Plant_ID": "Salvia texana", "Scientific Name": "Salvia texana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Sage", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Soak texas sage seeds in warm water for 24 hours prior to sowing. This helps to break the dormancy of the seeds, increasing the germination rate. Plant the pre-treated seeds in the prepared soil mix. Place the seeds on the soil surface and lightly cover with a thin layer of soil no more than 1/4 inch deep. This will allow for optimal exposure to light, which is necessary for germination. Maintain the soil evenly moist but not waterlogged. Keep the sowing area at a consistent temperature ideally between 65-75°F. — Collection: Collect seeds from mature plants after they’ve finished flowering. Once harvested, let the seeds dry completely before storing them away for future planting. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the lower leaves but leave 2-3 leaves at the top to support photosynthesis. Apply a rooting hormone to the cut end and plant in a well-draining propagation medium. Provide bright, indirect light and maintain consistent moisture in the propagation medium, but avoid waterlogging. — Collection: Take cuttings in late spring to early summer when the new growth is soft and pliable. Look for those that are green, flexible, and non-flowering, and take cuttings that are 4-6 inches long, ensuring each has at least two leaf nodes for optimal growth. || Stem — Treatment: Layering — Method: Create a 1-inch long incision about one-third through the stem. This cut will encourage root development. Dust the cut area with rooting hormone. This step boosts the chances of successful rooting. Cover the cut area with sphagnum moss and secure it with plastic wrap to help retain moisture for root growth. Ensure the air layering site receives indirect sunlight to keep the moss moist until roots develop. After 4-6 weeks, look for visible roots. Once roots are established, cut below the new roots and transplant your new Texas Sage. — Collection: Look for a flexible stem that is at least one year old. This ensures that the stem has enough vigor to support new growth.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/salvia-texana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Salvia_texana.html 2) https://greg.app/propagate-texas-sage/ | https://greg.app/propagate-texas-sage/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Sambucus nigra ssp. canadensis", "Scientific Name": "Sambucus nigra ssp. canadensis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Common Elderberry", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct sow in the fall, will not geminate until the following year. — Collection: Collect seeds as soon as the fruits ripen and turn dark blue. Clean seeds to avoid fermentation. Air dry two days before storing || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Scarify in sulfuric acid for 10-20 minutes followed immediately by stratification in moist peat at 36-40 degrees for two months. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Scarify in sulfuric acid for 10-20 minutes followed immediately by stratification in moist peat at 36-40 degrees for two months.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/sambucus-nigra-ssp-canadensis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=SANIC4"}, {"Plant_ID": "Sapindus saponaria var. drummondii", "Scientific Name": "Sapindus saponaria var. drummondii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Soapberry", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Scarify seeds in sulfuric acid for one to three hours and then stratify at 35-45 degrees for 40-60 days. — Collection: Collect seeds in late fall or early winter. Seeds may be cleaned or dried with the pulp on. Store in sealed, refrigerated containers.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/sapindus-saponaria-var-drummondii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=SASAD"}, {"Plant_ID": "Saururus cernuus", "Scientific Name": "Saururus cernuus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Lizard Tail", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Offshoots | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Offshoots — Treatment: Division — Method: The bare stem can then be planted into the substrate, ensuring the stem remains intact. Over a few weeks, the cutting will develop its own root system and begin to establish itself. In the wild, this plant can also spread by sending out runners, allowing it to colonize small areas of shallow water or wetlands. — Collection: Take side shoots from the mother plant and carefully remove the lower two pairs of leaves to expose the stem. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Seeds are stored cold and dry in sealed, airtight plastic bags through the winter in a refrigerator at 2 C (35 F). In January, about 4 weeks prior to seeding, remove seeds from cold storage and soak them in containers of water for 2 weeks. Seeds are covered with twice their volume in water and remain in the same water for the duration of the soaking period. Seeds are then mixed with damp, sterile sand, at a ratio of 1 part seed to 5 parts sand by volume, and subjected to cold, moist stratification (refrigeration at 2 to 4 C [35 to 40 F) for 2 weeks. Stratified seeds are surface sown in open flats (approximately 25 cm wide X 50 cm long X 6 cm deep (10 X 20 X 2.5 in) containing a soilless mix (55% sphagnum, 30% vermiculite, 15% perlite by volume); a variable amount of fine sand is added to the mix to provide aeration. Two hundred to 400 seeds are sown per flat, and covered with a dusting of the germinating mix (applied by sieve over the seeds). Seeded flats are then placed into solid bottom flats filled with water to allow saturation of the planting medium. The flat-in-flats are arranged on bottom-heated greenhouse benches. Medium temperature is maintained at approximately 21 to 23 C (70 to 74 F) during germination. Greenhouse air temperature ranges from a low of 4 C (40 F) to a high of 27 C (80 F). Germination usually occurs within 3 weeks, at which time the flats in their solid-bottom watering trays are moved to a mist bench. The mist cycle is set at 2 to 8 s every 10 min, and the flats continue to be bottom heated. Trays remain under mist for about 2 weeks, or until seedlings have 2 sets of true leaves and are about 2.5 cm (1 in) tall. Seedlings are transplanted from the open flats to 50-cell plug trays, 1 seedling to each cell. Once lizard's tail seedlings have been transplanted, the plug trays are moved outdoors to 4.5 X 30 m (15 X 100 ft) unheated, uncovered huts with overhead irrigation, where they receive 15 min of watering per day to saturate the growing medium. — Collection: Seedheads are held over paper bags andthe 1-seeded achenes (about 3 mm (0.125 in) in diameter) are stripped into the bags by hand.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/saururus-cernuus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://en.aqua-fish.net/plants/saururus-cernuus#:~:text=Saururus%20cernuus%20is%20propagated%20primarily,beauty%20of%20the%20water's%20edge. | https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=saururaceae-saururus-460&referer=wildflower#:~:text=Seeds%20are%20stored%20cold%20and,%C3%B8F%5D)%20for%202%20wk."}, {"Plant_ID": "Schizachyrium scoparium", "Scientific Name": "Schizachyrium scoparium", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Little Bluestem", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Little bluestem is easy to propagate by dividing healthy, established clumps in the spring. Doing it early in the year allows the roots of the division plenty of time to establish before winter. Space the divisions around 1 1/2 feet apart. — Collection: This species and most other grasses are best divided and planted in the spring, to allow the full season for their roots to develop. Grasses planted or transplanted in the fall may not establish well enough to survive winter. It should be seeded as early in the spring as possible. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment, Stratification — Method: Little bluestem is easy to grow from seed, and it's best to do this as early in the spring as possible. That way, the extensive root system will have a chance to establish before winter arrives. It will germinate within one to three weeks with the right temperatures (around 80°F). Using 3 to almost 5 pounds of seeds per acre produces good results.1 Little Bluestem Grass. USDA.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/schizachyrium-scoparium/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://hort.extension.wisc.edu/articles/little-bluestem-schizachyrium-scoparium/#:~:text=Propagation%20of%20Little%20Bluestem,to%20be%20divided%20very%20often. 2) https://www.thespruce.com/little-bluestem-growing-guide-5214474#:~:text=Propagating%20Little%20Bluestem,Does%20little%20bluestem%20spread%20fast? | https://www.thespruce.com/little-bluestem-growing-guide-5214474#:~:text=Propagating%20Little%20Bluestem,Does%20little%20bluestem%20spread%20fast?"}, {"Plant_ID": "Schoenocaulon texanum", "Scientific Name": "Schoenocaulon texanum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Feathershank", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Texas feather-shank is propagated by division, where the mature plant is separated into smaller, root-bearing sections and planted directly in the ground.. This method ensures healthy replanting and produces genetically identical plants, maintaining consistent growth and appearance across cultivations.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/schoenocaulon-texanum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Schoenocaulon_texanum.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Scutellaria ovata", "Scientific Name": "Scutellaria ovata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Heartleaf Skullcap", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Prepare a well-draining potting mix and moisten it. Sow the seeds on the surface of the soil, lightly pressing them into the mix. Cover the pot with a plastic or glass lid to create a humid environment for the seeds. Place the pot in a bright location, but avoid direct sunlight as it may overheat and damage the seeds. Keep the soil moist and wait for the seeds to germinate. Once the seedlings have developed, you can transplant them into larger containers or outdoor garden beds. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end into rooting hormone to stimulate root growth. Prepare a potting mix that's moist and well-draining. Make a hole in the soil and insert the cutting, gently pressing the soil around the base to support it. Cover the pot with a plastic bag to create a humid environment that encourages the cutting to take root. Place the pot in bright, indirect light. Check on the cutting regularly, and keep the soil moist but not overly wet. Once the cutting has rooted, you can transplant it into a larger pot or an outdoor garden bed. — Collection: Choose a healthy stem from the plant and cut a piece that's around 4-6 inches long. Remove the leaves from the bottom 2 inches of the cutting.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/scutellaria-ovata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://plantiary.com/plant/scutellaria-ovata_17490.html#:~:text=Cultivation,landscaping%20to%20promote%20local%20biodiversity."}, {"Plant_ID": "Muhlenbergia reverchonii", "Scientific Name": "Muhlenbergia reverchonii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Seep Muhly", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Examine the root system and identify natural divisions or sections. Use your hands, a sharp knife, or gardening tools to divide the clump into smaller sections. Each section should have its own roots and shoots or stems. Inspect the divided sections for damage, pests, or diseases and treat them as necessary. Prepare the planting site or containers for the divided sections. Ensure that the soil or potting mix is suitable for the plant's needs. Plant each division in its designated spot, ensuring the roots are adequately covered with soil or planting medium. After planting the divisions, water them thoroughly to promote root establishment. Provide regular care, including watering and sunlight, according to plant requirements. Monitor the divisions for any signs of stress or problems and address them accordingly. — Collection: It is generally advisable to divide in the early spring or fall when the plant is not actively growing or flowering. This allows the divided sections to establish new roots before vigorous growth. Carefully dig up the entire plant, preserving the root system and minimizing damage to the plant. Use a garden fork or shovel to loosen the soil around the plant before lifting it out of the ground. Three or four blades supported by a root system is sufficient to start a new plant. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Germinates best with a very light scarification. It is recommended that the seed be rubbed between a fine grain sandpaper to scar the seed coat, not completely remove. Prepare a suitable soil mix, such as potting soil or a seed tray filled with a seed-starting mix. Lightly cover the seeds with soil and gently firm the soil to ensure proper seed-to-soil contact. Provide adequate moisture, suitable temperature, and sufficient light. Once the seeds germinate and the seedlings emerge, provide regular watering, protection from pests and diseases, and adjust environmental conditions as needed to promote healthy growth. As the seedlings grow and develop, they will eventually outgrow their initial containers or seed trays. At this stage, they can be carefully transplanted into larger pots or directly into the ground, ensuring proper spacing and soil preparation. Greenouse conditions: M. reverchonii can tolerate temperature swings from 45F to 90F in pots and it has low water requirements. Garden conitions: M. reverchonii can tolerate a wide range of soils and temperatures including cold hardiness. — Collection: Collect mature and healthy seeds from a parent plant. This can be done by harvesting seeds directly from the plant or by obtaining seeds from other sources such as seed catalogs or nurseries. Seed must be collected very ripe in order to be viable; check for a darker gray/brown embryo when deciding when to collect. In some climates, M. reverchonii will not bloom until late September-October; this may not provide enough time for fully-formed seed to develop.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/seep-muhly/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://plantselect.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Muhlenbergia-reverchonii-_Prop-Protocol.pdf 2) https://www.perenual.com/plant-propagation-methods/method/13 | 1) https://plantselect.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Muhlenbergia-reverchonii-_Prop-Protocol.pdf 2) https://www.perenual.com/plant-propagation-methods/method/32"}, {"Plant_ID": "Senegalia greggii", "Scientific Name": "Senegalia greggii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Gregg Catclaw Acacia", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow the seed in Spring in a greenhouse. As soon as the seedlings are large enough to handle, prick them out into individual pots and grow them on in a sunny position in the greenhouse for their first winter. Plant them out in late spring or early summer, after the last expected frosts, and consider giving them some protection from the cold for their first winter outdoors. — Collection: Late summer to early fall when seeds are firm, filled out, and dark brown || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Seeds are scarified by clipping prior to 4 to 5 hour water soak. Germinants are sown in open nursery flats using a growing medium of 2 parts sand, 1 part mulch and 2 parts perlite. Seedlings are ready for transplanting into larger containers at 8 to 12 weeks. Irrigation frequency and duration is gradually reduced for 4 to 8 weeks prior to out-planting. — Collection: Seeds are hand collected in when pods have matured and begin to split open. Seeds and pods are allowed to dry for 4 to 6 weeks in paper bags in a warm, dry room. After seeds have been cleaned, they are stored under refrigeration in air tight containers at 7C.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/senegalia-greggii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://temperate.theferns.info/plant/Senegalia+greggii#:~:text=Sow%20the%20seed%20in%20Spring%20in%20a,the%20cold%20for%20their%20first%20winter%20outdoors. 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=SEGR4 | https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=fabaceae-acacia-2543"}, {"Plant_ID": "Senegalia roemeriana", "Scientific Name": "Senegalia roemeriana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Catclaw Acacia", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: start by soaking them in water for 24 hours. This simple step kickstarts the germination process, ensuring your seeds are primed for growth. For the best results, maintain warm temperatures between 70°F to 85°F and keep the soil consistently moist. These conditions create an ideal environment for your seeds to sprout and thrive. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Take 4-6 inch cuttings from healthy, vigorous plants to ensure a strong start. Timing is crucial; aim to do this in late spring or early summer when the plant is actively growing.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/senegalia-roemeriana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://greg.app/roemers-acacia-overview/#:~:text=Fertilize%20in%20early%20spring%20and,the%20plant%20is%20actively%20growing."}, {"Plant_ID": "Senna lindheimeriana", "Scientific Name": "Senna lindheimeriana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Lindheimer's Senna", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sowing seeds directly into a well-draining soil mixture ensures robust development. The soil should be kept moist but not waterlogged to prevent rot. Seedlings require adequate sunlight for vigorous growth. — Collection: Collect pods in late summer when they have turned brown and begun to dry. Air-dry seeds after they have been removed.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/senna-lindheimeriana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=SELI4 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Senna_lindheimeriana.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Senna roemeriana", "Scientific Name": "Senna roemeriana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Two Leaved Senna", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump | Semi-harwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Successful propagation involves ensuring good seed-to-soil contact by lightly covering the seeds with soil, as twoleaf senna seeds have a hard coating that benefits from scarification to enhance germination rates. Germination rates can be low, so plant more seeds than necessary. Generally, it takes three to four years for the plant to bloom after propagation by seed. — Collection: Collect pods in late summer when they have turned brown and begun to dry, but before they split open. Air dry before storing. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Replant the sections in new pots or areas in the garden. It usually takes about a year for the plant to recover and bloom after division. — Collection: In early spring, before new growth, gently lift the plant from the soil, and use a sharp knife to divide the plant into sections. Ensure that each section has sufficient roots and rinse them with water. || Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the leaves from the lower half of the cutting and dip the cut end of the stem into a rooting hormone powder or gel. Insert the treated cutting into a pot filled with well-draining potting mix, such as a combination of perlite and peat moss. Make a hole in the mix using a stick or your finger, and then place the cutting into the hole, firming the soil around it gently. Place the potted cutting in a warm, bright location with indirect sunlight. Maintain humidity by covering the cutting with a plastic bag, then water the soil lightly, keeping it moist but not waterlogged. — Collection: The optimal time to propagate through cuttings is during late spring to early summer, to take advantage of ideal temperature and light conditions and natural growth cycles. Cut a 4-6 inch long stem section from the plant with at least one node and some leaves.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/senna-roemeriana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=SERO8 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Senna_roemeriana.html 3) https://www.botanikks.com/plants/cassia-roemeriana-scheele/545069/1 | https://www.botanikks.com/plants/cassia-roemeriana-scheele/545069/1 | https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Senna_roemeriana.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Setaria scheelei", "Scientific Name": "Setaria scheelei", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Southwestern Bristlegrass", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow the seeds directly into the garden after the last frost. For a head start, you can start them indoors 6-8 weeks before the last frost date. Choose a well-draining soil with a pH between 6.0 and 7.0. Sow the seeds ¼ inch deep and space them 6-12 inches apart. Keep the soil consistently moist until germination, which typically takes 10-14 days. Once seedlings have a few true leaves, thin them out to the desired spacing. — Collection: Collect seeds when at the \"ripe dough\" stage, usually just as the color has changed from green to brown. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Gently lift the plant from the ground and use the spade to divide the clump into smaller sections, ensuring each section has a healthy set of roots and shoots. Plant the divided sections into prepared soil beds or pots with good drainage. Space the sections adequately to allow for growth, and cover the roots with soil, pressing lightly to remove air pockets. Water the newly planted divisions thoroughly to help settle the soil and establish roots. Continue to keep the soil moist but not waterlogged. After propagation, place southwestern bristlegrass in a location where it receives ample sunlight, as it prefers full sun to partial shade. Water regularly, especially during dry periods, but ensure proper drainage to avoid waterlogging. Mulch around the base to retain soil moisture and control weeds. Monitor for pests and diseases, treating them promptly if any issues arise. — Collection: Water the plant a day before dividing to ensure the soil is moist and the roots are hydrated, making them easier to separate. Carefully dig around the base of southwestern bristlegrass to expose the root system.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/setaria-scheelei/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-setaria-scheelei/ 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=SESC2 3) https://seedsource.com/southwestern-bristlegrass/ | 1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Setaria_scheelei.html#:~:text=Southwestern%20bristlegrass%20is%20a%20resilient%20bunchgrass%20found,and%20are%20re%2Dplanted%20promptly%20in%20well%2Ddrained%20soil. 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-setaria-scheelei/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Sida lindheimeri", "Scientific Name": "Sida lindheimeri", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Showy Fanpetals", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Scarify the seeds lightly using sandpaper to enhance germination rates. Choose a well-draining seed-starting mix. Fill seed trays or small pots with the mix, ensuring it's evenly moist but not waterlogged. Place the seeds on the surface of the prepared soil and lightly press them down. Cover the seeds with a thin layer of soil, about 1/8 inch deep, as they need light for germination. Gently water the soil to settle it around the seeds. Keep the soil consistently moist but avoid overwatering, which can cause seed rot. Place the trays or pots in a warm area with indirect sunlight. Seeds should germinate within 2-4 weeks. Once seedlings have developed a few true leaves and are sturdy enough, transplant them into larger pots or directly into the garden. — Collection: Gather seeds from mature plants. Remove any remaining seed pod material to ensure clean seeds.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/sida-lindheimeri/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Sida_lindheimeri.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Sideroxylon lanuginosum", "Scientific Name": "Sideroxylon lanuginosum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Gum Bumelia", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Softwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: The seeds need to be scarified before planting to encourage germination. One method of scarification is to rub the seeds with sandpaper until the outer seed coat is visibly scratched. Another method is to soak the seeds in hot water for 24 hours. This will soften the hard seed coat. Plant the seeds in a well-draining seed-starting mix at a depth of about ¼ inch and gently cover them with soil. Water generously and place in a bright, warm location. Depending on conditions, germination can take anywhere from a few weeks to several months. — Collection: Allow the fruits to ripen fully and then carefully extract the seeds. Or during the fall collect from the tree fresh seeds that have not dried out. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Apply a rooting hormone to the cut end of the stem to encourage root growth. Fill small pots with a well-draining cactus or succulent potting mix. Insert the cutting into the soil, planting it about a third of the way down. Gently firm the soil around the base of the cutting. Place the pot in a warm, bright location, but avoid direct sunlight. Keep the soil moist but not soggy. Roots should appear within several weeks. — Collection: Stem cuttings should be taken in the late spring or early summer, when the new growth is still green and flexible. The cuttings should be 4-6 inches in length and contain at least two nodes. Cut just below a node, which is the point where a leaf or branch grows from the stem. Remove any leaves at the base of the cutting || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: The cutting should then be dipped in rooting hormone powder and placed into a well-draining soil mix. It is recommended to use a rooting hormone powder that is specifically designed for softwood cuttings. The soil mix should be kept moist but not waterlogged, and the cutting should be placed in a warm and bright location but not exposed to direct sunlight. — Collection: Take softwood cuttings from the parent plant during the early growing season. The cuttings should be about 5-6 inches long and should be taken from the tip of the branch. The leaves on the bottom half of the cutting should be removed.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/sideroxylon-lanuginosum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-sideroxylon-lanuginosum/ 2) https://www.botanikks.com/plants/sideroxylon-lanuginosum-michx/507422/1 | 1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-sideroxylon-lanuginosum/ 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Sideroxylon_lanuginosum.html 3) https://www.botanikks.com/plants/sideroxylon-lanuginosum-michx/507422/1 | https://plantiary.com/plant/sideroxylon-lanuginosum_3292.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Silphium albiflorum", "Scientific Name": "Silphium albiflorum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "White Rosinweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Root | Stem | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Root — Treatment: Division — Method: Replant each section into well-draining soil. The divided sections can then be planted in their own pots or directly into the soil, and water thoroughly. — Collection: This method should be done in the spring or early fall when the plant is still dormant. Carefully dig up the plant and separate the roots into smaller sections with a sharp, sterile tool. Each section should have at least a few healthy roots and some green growth. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove any leaves from the lower third of the stem and dip the cut end into rooting hormone. Plant the stem into well-draining soil and keep it moist in a warm and humid environment. — Collection: Propagation should be done in the spring or fall when the plant is actively growing. Choose a healthy stem and cut it at an angle into 6-inch sections with clean, sharp scissors. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow the collected seeds on the surface of the soil in early spring. Lightly press them into the soil but do not cover them as white rosinweed seeds require light to germinate. Ensure the seeds are kept moist until germination. It can take up to two years for the seedlings to reach maturity. — Collection: Collect seeds from mature white rosinweed flower heads once they have dried out. Ensure seeds are fully dried for better viability.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/silphium-albiflorum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.botanikks.com/plants/silphium-albiflorum-gray/507678/1 2) https://plantiary.com/plant/silphium-albiflorum_33773.html | 1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Silphium_albiflorum.html 2) https://www.selinawamucii.com/plants/asteraceae/silphium-albiflorum/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Silphium laciniatum", "Scientific Name": "Silphium laciniatum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Compassplant", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: To break dormancy expose seeds to cold, moist stratification. Start at least 5 weeks before outdoor night temperatures are reliably in the 10 C (50 F) range. Mix the seed with a slightly moistened, sterile, soil-less growing mix. Put this in a labelled, sealed plastic bag and store in a refrigerator for one day. The next day place this in the freezer for one day. Repeat this for one week, alternating between the fridge and the freezer. After stratifying, plant seed 0.64 cm (1/4 inch) deep in pots. Keep moist but not soggy and very warm (21 C - 70 F). When seedlings are 5 cm (2 inches) tall or more, transplant into the garden spaced 30 cm (1 foot) apart. Seedlings take 2-3 years to flower. — Collection: Collect seeds of compassplant from mature plants. The seeds are typically ready when the flower heads dry out and turn brown. Gently cut the heads and store them in a cool, dry place until you are ready to plant. Prepare the seeds by breaking them free from the dried flower heads. Be careful to keep as much of the seed intact as possible. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: In late fall through to mid-winter fill plastic pots with a slightly moistened, sterile, soil-less growing mix. Plant seed 0.64 cm (1/4 inch) deep in pots and label the pots. Place them outdoors in an area where they will experience the cold of winter. The seed will germinate in the pots in spring as the weather warms up. Be sure to water the pots regularly in spring and once the plants are 5 cm (2 inches) tall, transplant them into your garden. Seedlings take 2-3 years to flower. — Collection: Collect seeds of compassplant from mature plants. The seeds are typically ready when the flower heads dry out and turn brown. Gently cut the heads and store them in a cool, dry place until you are ready to plant. Prepare the seeds by breaking them free from the dried flower heads. Be careful to keep as much of the seed intact as possible.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/silphium-laciniatum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://illinoispollinators.org/plant/compass-plant/#:~:text=Establishment%20and%20Propagation,2%20inch)%20in%20the%20spring. 2) https://www.wildflowerfarm.com/silphium-laciniatum-compass-plant.html#:~:text=Here's%20some%20information%20about%20growing%20compass%20plant,deeply%20divided%20leaves%20that%20orient%20themselves%20north%2Dsouth. 3) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Silphium+laciniatum#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,deep%20and%20extensive%20root%20system. 4) https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/plantguide/pdf/pg_sila3.pdf 5) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Silphium_laciniatum.html 6) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/silphium-laciniatum | 1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Silphium_laciniatum.html 2) https://www.wildflowerfarm.com/silphium-laciniatum-compass-plant.html#:~:text=Here's%20some%20information%20about%20growing%20compass%20plant,deeply%20divided%20leaves%20that%20orient%20themselves%20north%2Dsouth. 3) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/silphium-laciniatum"}, {"Plant_ID": "Simsia calva", "Scientific Name": "Simsia calva", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Bush Sunflower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Ensure a well-draining soil medium, and lightly cover the seeds as they need some light to germinate. Providing consistent moisture aids in germination, without causing waterlogged conditions that may lead to rot. Germination is generally straightforward and, once seedlings establish, they can be transplanted to their final growing locations. Regular care during the early growth stages will promote healthy and robust plants.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/simsia-calva/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Simsia_calva.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Sisyrinchium angustifolium", "Scientific Name": "Sisyrinchium angustifolium", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Narrowleaf Blue-eyed Grass", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: When transplanting seedlings, individual plants should be spaced 6 to 8 inches apart to allow plants to grow into each other to form a single mass. — Collection: Collect seed capsule when they have darkened to brown and become wrinkled. Seed is black, globular, pitted. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Use a sharp edged tool to cut clumps into smaller pieces, then move the pieces to a moist location until the roots redevelop. — Collection: Division is recommended in early spring or fall every two to three years. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Seal the seeds in a Ziploc-style bag or a Rubbermaid-style container in equal amounts of seeds to perlite or vermiculite and add just enough water to moisten the entire mixture. Store in a refrigerator or cold garage (42 degrees F or colder) for at least three months. Cold store until planted (up to 3 years).", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/sisyrinchium-angustifolium/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://edis.ifas.ufl.edu/publication/AG401 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=SIAN3 3) https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=iridaceae-sisyrinchium-1877#:~:text=Propagation%20Environment:%20Greenhouse%20film%20is,about%2010%25%20of%20seeds%20germinating. 4) https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=iridaceae-sisyrinchium-1877 | https://edis.ifas.ufl.edu/publication/AG401 | https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=iridaceae-sisyrinchium-1877"}, {"Plant_ID": "Solanum triquetrum", "Scientific Name": "Solanum triquetrum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Nightshade", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Prepare a pot filled with a well-draining soil mixture, ideally a blend of peat and perlite or sand. This will help provide the right moisture balance for rooting. Insert the cut end of the stem into the prepared potting mix. Make sure it's deep enough to support itself. Water gently yet thoroughly, ensuring that the soil is moist but not waterlogged. Cover the pot with a plastic bag to create a greenhouse effect, which maintains humidity and warmth to promote rooting. — Collection: Sterilize a sharp pair of scissors or pruning shears using rubbing alcohol. This is to prevent the spread of diseases. Carefully select a healthy stem. Look for a stem that is around 4-6 inches long, with at least a few leaves. Make sure the stem appears vigorous and disease-free. Make a clean, angled cut just below a leaf node. The angle increases the surface area for rooting and helps in absorbing moisture. Remove the leaves from the lower half of the cutting to prevent excess moisture loss.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/solanum-triquetrum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Solanum_triquetrum.html 2) https://davesgarden.com/guides/pf/go/114899#:~:text=Solanaceae%20(so%2Dlan%2DAY,protect%20hands%20when%20handling%20seeds"}, {"Plant_ID": "Solidago altissima", "Scientific Name": "Solidago altissima", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Tall Goldenrod", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Clump | Root", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow the seeds directly in the garden in early spring or fall. Plants grown from seed will usually bloom in their second or third year. — Collection: After the flowers have dried, collect the seeds from the seed heads and store the seeds in a cool, dry location. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the leaves from the bottom inch or two of the stem. Dip the cut end of the stem in a rooting hormone to encourage root growth. Plant the cuttings in a well-drained soil mixture and water thoroughly, then keep them consistently moist and shaded. — Collection: This is best done in the late spring or early summer. Select healthy stems that are about 6 inches long. Cut the stems at a 45-degree angle just below a node (the point where leaves grow from the stem). || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Plant the divisions in a well-drained location with plenty of sunlight. — Collection: This is one of the easiest ways to propagate Solidago altissima and works best in the spring or early fall when the plant is actively growing. Carefully dig a trench around a well-established plant with multiple stems, being mindful of the roots. Using a sharp spade or garden knife, carefully divide the root ball into smaller sections, ensuring each division has healthy roots and shoots. || Root — Treatment: Division — Method: The divided sections are then planted in soil that has been amended with compost or organic matter. — Collection: The plant is dug up in the early spring or late fall and the roots carefully separated into smaller sections, each section being at least 4 inches long with at least one growth bud.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/solidago-altissima/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-solidago-altissima/ 2) https://plantiary.com/plant/solidago-altissima_4181.html | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-solidago-altissima/ | https://plantiary.com/plant/solidago-altissima_4181.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Solidago nemoralis", "Scientific Name": "Solidago nemoralis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Prairie Goldenrod", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Cold Stratification: Gray Goldenrod seeds need a period of cold treatment to germinate best. Mix the seeds with damp vermiculite or sand and store them in the refrigerator (around 40°F) for 6-8 weeks. Sowing Time: Once the cold treatment is complete, sow the seeds in seed trays filled with a well-draining seed starting mix. Don’t bury them deep; just press them lightly on the surface. Light and Warmth: Place the seed trays in a bright location, out of direct sunlight. Maintain a temperature of around 70°F. Germination Patience: It may take 2-4 weeks for the seeds to germinate. Keep the soil consistently moist but not soggy. Transplant Time: When the seedlings have developed a few sets of true leaves, they are ready to be transplanted into individual pots or directly into the garden after the last frost. — Collection: If planting untreated seed, be sure it is fresh. In the fall, collect seed heads from your existing plants, when the heads are brown and become fluffy. Allow them to dry thoroughly before storing in a cool, dry place. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Replant your divisions immediately in well-drained soil, spacing them 12-18 inches apart. Water thoroughly. — Collection: Early spring or fall, when the plant is dormant, are ideal times for division. Divide mature plants, making sure each section has a bud and a root. Carefully loosen the soil around the clump using a garden fork, ensuring you don’t damage the roots.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/solidago-nemoralis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-solidago-nemoralis/ 2) https://plants.ces.ncsu.edu/plants/solidago-nemoralis/#:~:text=Attributes:%20Genus:%20Solidago%20Species:,Wildlife%20Value: 3) https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/factsheet/pdf/fs_sone.pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Dermatophyllum secundiflorum", "Scientific Name": "Dermatophyllum secundiflorum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Mountain Laurel", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump | Semi-harwood | Stem | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Plant the divisions in individual pots with well-draining soil. Water sparingly initially to allow the roots to recover. — Collection: Divide the plant during its active growing season (spring or summer). Gently remove the plant from its pot and carefully separate the root ball into several sections, each with its own established root system and sufficient foliage. || Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the leaves from the lower half of the cutting to prevent them from rotting. Allow the cut ends to callous over for several days in a dry, well-ventilated area. Dip the cut end of the cutting in rooting hormone. Use a well-draining rooting medium such as a succulent potting mix or mix of perlite and vermiculite. Insert the cuttings into the rooting medium, making sure that the nodes where the leaves were removed are buried. Water thoroughly and cover with a plastic bag or humidity dome. Place in a warm, bright location, but avoid direct sunlight. Avoid overwatering; allow the soil to dry completely between waterings. Use a fungicide as a preventative measure. Root development can take several weeks or even months. Dermatophyllum secundiflorum cuttings are susceptible to fungal infections if not allowed to dry properly before planting. — Collection: The best time to take cuttings is in the late spring or early summer when the plant is actively growing. Choose semi-hardwood cuttings, which are new growth that has begun to harden off. The cuttings should be about 4-6 inches long and have several leaves. Avoid taking cuttings from flowering stems. || Stem — Treatment: Layering — Method: For ground layering, wound the stem by making a shallow cut or scraping off a small section of bark where it will be buried. For air layering, make a similar wound on the stem. For ground layering, bury the wounded portion of the stem in the soil and secure it with a rock or stake. For air layering, wrap the wounded area with moist sphagnum moss and secure it with plastic wrap or tape. Keep the soil or sphagnum moss consistently moist. Root development can take several weeks or months. Once the stem has developed a strong root system, it can be separated from the parent plant and transplanted into its own pot. — Collection: Layering involves rooting a stem while it is still attached to the parent plant. Ground Layering involves bending a low-growing stem to the ground and burying a portion of it in soil. Choose a low-growing, flexible stem that can be easily bent to the ground. Air Layering involves wounding a stem and wrapping it with moist sphagnum moss to encourage root development. Select a healthy stem that is accessible. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: The seed coat is extremely hard and needs to be scarified to allow water to penetrate and initiate germination. One method is to gently rub the seeds with sandpaper or carefully nick the seed coat with a knife. Be careful not to damage the inner seed. Another method is to hold the seed with a pliers and with a file, rub one spot on the outer coat (at the larger cotyledon end) until the thin light-colored (tan) inner coat is visible - being careful not to scratch into the inner coat itself nor into the cotyledons of the embryo. Soak the scarified seeds several hours to several days and then plant them only if swelling has occurred. Otherwise repeat the scarification and soaking. A third option is to soak the seeds in hot (not boiling) water for 24 hours to help soften the seed coat. Sow the scarified seeds about ½ inch deep in individual pots or a seed tray using a well-draining potting mix specifically formulated for seeds. Keep the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged. Maintain a warm temperature (around 70-75°F or 21-24°C) to encourage germination. A heat mat can be helpful. Germination can be slow and erratic, taking anywhere from several weeks to several months. — Collection: Seeds should be gathered when the pods are still green and the seeds a pale pink color (they later turn red). Soak pods in water if they're difficult to open. Or gather seeds from mature pods in late summer or early fall. The pods will turn brown and begin to split open, revealing the bright red seeds. Carefully remove the seeds from the pods, wearing gloves to avoid skin contact with the potentially irritating seed covering. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Plant the seeds about 1/2 inch deep in well-drained soil, watering well initially and later only sparingly. Initial growth seems to focus on creating a deep root, a shallow container thus being unsuitable. The first visible sign of germination is a slender shoot with the beginnings of the first true leaves, at which point the root is likely to have reached a depth of 6-8 inches. Mountain laurel is a slow grower, and it may be years before flowers are produced. In our hill-country environment it has taken at least 10 years for untended plants started from seed to bloom. — Collection: Seeds germinate readily and with no need for scarifying if collected and planted in late spring when the seed pods begin to turn greyish/pinkish, but before the red seed shell hardens. Seeds with only a pink tint or a red blotch virtually all germinate. Several weeks after the 'pink' stage noted above the familiar deep red seed covering will harden and the seed will rapidly shrink and rattle inside the pod. At this stage the pods will be very tough, requiring a sharp knife to cut through to remove seeds.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/sophora-secundiflora/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-dermatophyllum-secundiflorum/ | 1) https://unitedsounds.org/how-to-propagate-texas-mountain-laurel-pl866 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-dermatophyllum-secundiflorum/ | https://unitedsounds.org/how-to-propagate-texas-mountain-laurel-pl866 | 1) https://www.thespruce.com/texas-mountain-laurel-growing-guide-5215169#toc-propagating 2) https://unitedsounds.org/how-to-propagate-texas-mountain-laurel-pl866 | https://w3.biosci.utexas.edu/prc/DigFlora/SOSE3/MtL-propagation.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Sphaeralcea angustifolia", "Scientific Name": "Sphaeralcea angustifolia", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Narrowleaf Globemallow", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: The seed has a hard seed coat and benefits from either autumn sowing or scarification of stored seed. This can usually be done by pouring a small amount of nearly boiling water on the seeds (being careful not to cook them!) and then soaking them for 12 - 24 hours in warm water. By this time they should have imbibed moisture and swollen - if they have not, then carefully make a nick in the seedcoat (being careful not to damage the embryo) and soak for a further 12 hours before sowing. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Cold stratify the seeds for 30 days before planting to enhance germination rates. Plant the seeds 1/4 inch deep in well-draining soil, ensuring they have enough space to thrive. — Collection: Harvest seeds from mature plants in late summer when they are fully developed. Mature seed is typically dry and will easily separate from the seed head. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Use a mix of perlite and peat moss to create an ideal environment for rooting. Expect rooting to take 2-4 weeks in a humid environment, so keep the cuttings moist but not soggy. — Collection: Selecting cuttings: In early spring, take 4-6 inch stem cuttings from healthy plants. Hand strip mature seed by grasping the bottom of the seed head, then gently pulling away from the base of the plant. Deposit seed in a brown paper bag or seed envelope. a. Please do not use a plastic bag b. Moisture will collect and mold seed.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/sphaeralcea-incan/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://pfaf.org/User/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Sphaeralcea+angustifolia#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,Division%5B200%20%5D. | 1) https://greg.app/narrowleaf-globemallow-overview/#:~:text=%F0%9F%8C%B1%20Seed%20Propagation,have%20enough%20space%20to%20thrive. 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-sphaeralcea-angustifolia/ 3) https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/plantmaterials/txpmcbr13181.pdf | 1) https://greg.app/narrowleaf-globemallow-overview/#:~:text=%F0%9F%8C%B1%20Seed%20Propagation,have%20enough%20space%20to%20thrive. 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-sphaeralcea-angustifolia/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Sphenopholis obtusata", "Scientific Name": "Sphenopholis obtusata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Prairie Wedgescale", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Can be sown directly in the soil outdoors. Seeds germinate after sowing in a warm location. When direct sowing, space the seeds 6-12 inches apart and lightly cover them with soil. If starting indoors, use seed starting trays and place them in a sunny window or under grow lights. Keep the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged. Germination typically takes 1-2 weeks, but can vary depending on temperature and soil conditions. Once your seedlings emerge, thin them to allow for proper spacing. — Collection: The seeds mature in late summer or early fall. Look for the seed heads turning brown and ready to shed their seeds. Carefully collect these seed heads and store them in a cool, dry place until you’re ready to plant. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: You can scarify your seeds by gently rubbing them against coarse sandpaper or placing them in a bowl of boiling water for a few minutes, followed by an immediate ice water bath. Keep the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged. Germination typically takes 1-2 weeks, but can vary depending on temperature and soil conditions. Once your seedlings emerge, thin them to allow for proper spacing. — Collection: The seeds mature in late summer or early fall. Look for the seed heads turning brown and ready to shed their seeds. Carefully collect these seed heads and store them in a cool, dry place until you’re ready to plant.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/sphenopholis-obtusata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.prairiemoon.com/sphenopholis-obtusata-prairie-wedgegrass#panel-planting 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-sphenopholis-obtusata/ | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-sphenopholis-obtusata/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Sporobolus airoides", "Scientific Name": "Sporobolus airoides", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Alkali Sacaton", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow spring in a greenhouse and only just cover the seed. Germination should take place within 2 weeks. Prick out the seedlings into individual pots when they are large enough to handle and plant them out in the summer if they have grown sufficiently. Otherwise, grow them on in a greenhouse for their first winter and plant them out in late spring of the following year. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Division in spring. Larger divisions can be planted out direct into their permanent positions. We have found it best to pot up the smaller divisions and grow them on in a lightly shaded position in a cold frame, planting them out once they are well established in the summer.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/sporobolus-airoides/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Sporobolus+airoides#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,well%20established%20in%20the%20summer."}, {"Plant_ID": "Sporobolus cryptandrus", "Scientific Name": "Sporobolus cryptandrus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Sand Dropseed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Seeds have high viability but a high proportion of them can become dormant, which means that dormancy breaking in the form of stratification, moist conditions and/or scarification is necessary for successful germination (Holub and Jehlík, 1987, Sartor and Malone, 2010). Substituting 28 days cold stratification for the acid treatment gives an average of 81.8% versus 90.8% for the acid (Toole 1941). || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: For propagating by seed: Soak in 71% H2S04 for 2 mins., then soak in 1% potassium nitrate 24 hrs., and germinate at high diurnal fluctua.tion, room temperature (60.8° to 75.2°) and 95°F, 17 and 7 hrs. respectively with light. This treatment is the best overall. Omitting the acid may give good results; substituting 68°F constant for room temperature gives slightly less germination. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: No treatment. if sown outdoors during July or August may give good germinatio. Can also sow in spring in a greenhouse and only just cover the seed. Germination should take place within 2 weeks. Prick out the seedlings into individual pots when they are large enough to handle and plant them out in the summer if they have grown sufficiently. Otherwise, grow them on in a greenhouse for their first winter and plant them out in late spring of the following year. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Division in spring. Larger divisions can be planted out direct into their permanent positions. We have found it best to pot up the smaller divisions and grow them on in a lightly shaded position in a cold frame, planting them out once they are well established in the summer.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/sporobolus-cryptandrus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2351989421004923#:~:text=The%20thousand%2Dseed%20weight%20of,Rasmussen%20and%20Rice%2C%201971).&text=Fig.,T%C3%B6lgyesi). 2) https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/plantmaterials/stpmcpg12942.pdf | https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Sporobolus+cryptandrus#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,well%20established%20in%20the%20summer."}, {"Plant_ID": "Stenaria nigricans", "Scientific Name": "Stenaria nigricans", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Prairie Bluet", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Cold/moist stratification", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/stenaria-nigricans/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://warcapps.usgs.gov/PlantID/Species/Details/3123"}, {"Plant_ID": "Styphnolobium affine", "Scientific Name": "Styphnolobium affine", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Eve’s Necklace", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Seeds can be extracted by macerating the fruits in water. Seeds must be filed or mechanically scarified with a knife. — Collection: Collect seeds when the pod begins to dry and the seeds turn red.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/styphnolobium-affine/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=STAF4"}, {"Plant_ID": "Symphoricarpos orbiculatus", "Scientific Name": "Symphoricarpos orbiculatus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Coralberry", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Softwood | Seed | Semi-harwood | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Cuttings taken in late spring or early summer. Dip the cuttings in rooting hormone and plant them in a well-draining soil mix. Keep the soil moist and provide indirect light until roots develop. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Nutlets are difficult to germinate because of hard seed coats and immature embryos. Warm stratification for 3-4 months followed by cold for 4-6 months is necessary. — Collection: Fruits can be collected anytime during the fall and winter by stripping or flailing onto drop cloths. Seeds can be extracted by macerating the fruits in water. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Coralberry is not typically grown from seed because it requires a lengthy process to get the seeds to germinate. It is recommended to scarify the seeds (nick the seeds with a knife or rub them against sandpaper to break open or soften the seed coat). After scarification, subject the seeds to 2 cold, moist periods. This period is called cold stratification. || Semi-harwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: To take a semi-hardwood cutting, ensure your snips are sharp and clean. Select a section of the stem that’s healthy and beginning to thicken and darken, ensuring you have at least 4 to 6 inches of this semi-hardwood section. Snip off any fresh green growth at the top if the top of the stem is still soft. Cut the remaining leaves in half. Pull the leaves off the bottom 1 to 2 nodes (where the leaves grow from the stem; this is where your new roots will grow). You can choose to use a rooting hormone or not. If so, dip the end of the stem in the rooting hormone. Use a dibbler (or pencil) to poke a hole in your well-draining, loose potting mix for your cutting. Place the cutting in the hole so the bottom nodes are buried. Press the potting mix firmly around the cutting. Keep the cutting moist with high humidity for a few weeks. Cover the pot with a plastic milk jug or plastic wrap to keep moisture high. You don’t want the cutting to be soggy wet–just evenly moist. Mist the plant to keep humidity high instead of watering the potting mix in the beginning. — Collection: Propagate coralberry with semi-hardwood cuttings. Semi-hardwood cuttings are those taken when the plant stem becomes slightly darker and thicker. Collect these cuttings between mid-July and early fall. || Stem — Treatment: Layering — Method: If coralberry “suckers” are already present, using a spade, dig out a section of the plant that has rooted and move it to a new location. There is no need to amend the soil. Just make sure there is enough to cover the plant’s crown so none of the roots are above the soil line. If you do not notice any stems already rooted to the ground, artificially create this by laying a stem along the ground and securing it by mounding soil up around nodes (where the leaves join the stem). Once you see new growth emerging from the soil mound, you can separate these plantlets from the main stem and transplant them accordingly. — Collection: Collect in the fall or early spring. Coralberry propagates itself in the wild by rooting at the nodes where its stems meet the ground. However, the cultivated varieties of coralberry are not as ambitious as the wild coralberry.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/symphoricarpos-orbiculatus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://earthone.io/plant/symphoricarpos%20orbiculatus | 1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=SYOR 2) https://www.epicgardening.com/coralberry/ | https://www.epicgardening.com/coralberry/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Symphyotrichum drummondii var. texanum", "Scientific Name": "Symphyotrichum drummondii var. texanum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Aster", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Use a well-draining seed-starting mix and fill seed trays or small pots. Place seeds in the prepared soil, spacing them about an inch apart, and lightly cover with a thin layer of soil. Moisten the soil carefully using a misting spray to avoid displacing seeds, keeping it consistently moist but not waterlogged. Place the trays or pots in a warm, sunny location, ensuring they receive at least 6 hours of sunlight daily. Once seedlings have two sets of true leaves, transplant them to their final location, ensuring they are spaced about 12-18 inches apart.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/symphyotrichum-drummondii-var-texanum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Symphyotrichum_drummondii_var._texanum.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Symphyotrichum ericoides", "Scientific Name": "Symphyotrichum ericoides", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Heath Aster", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Start seeds indoors four weeks before the last spring frost date. Fill biodegradable seed-starter cells three-quarters full with a potting medium that contains fertilizer. Place two seeds in each cell. Cover the seeds with one-eighth of an inch of soil. Place in a sunny location. Keep the soil evenly moist. When the seedlings have two sets of true leaves, thin them to one per cell. After the danger of frost passes, acclimate the seedlings to the outdoors for a few hours each day, increasing the time spent outside over about four days. Choose a sunny location. Prepare the garden soil by working it to a depth of eight to 12 inches to aerate it and make it crumbly. Space at intervals of 12 to 18 inches to allow for ample airflow and inhibit fungal growth. Set the biodegradable cells in the soil so the top of each cell is at ground level. Tamp the soil around the cells to hold them firmly in place. — Collection: Sowing indoors || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: To direct sow seeds: Prepare the soil in a sunny prepared garden bed. Sow one to two seeds every 12 to 18 inches. Cover the seeds with one-eighth of an inch of soil. Maintain even moisture. When the second set of true leaves sprouts, thin to one seedling per interval — Collection: Sowing outdoors || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Place the stem in four inches of water. Change the water daily. When roots grow, transplant the rooted stem cutting into the garden per the instructions below. Another way to root a soft stem cutting is to dip the cut bare stem in rooting hormone powder and plant it in soil. Select a biodegradable six-inch seed starter pot. Fill it three-quarters full of potting soil that contains fertilizer. Bury the dipped stem two inches deep in the soil and tamp to secure it. Maintain even moisture. When you see new leaves, you’ll know the stem has rooted. Transplant it into prepared garden soil in a sunny location. You can settle the entire seed-starter pot into the soil with the top rim even with the soil surface. Tamp the soil firmly around it. — Collection: In late spring to early summer, cut about six inches from the growing tip of a fresh, soft stem. Remove the leaves from the bottom four inches of the stem. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: As plants mature, they form an expanding network of roots, increasing their presence in the landscape year by year. After three to five years, thinning helps to improve airflow, inhibit fungal disease, and invigorate blooming. To divide, dig as soon as you see new shoots in early spring. Place a long-handled shovel four to six inches out from the center of a clump of shoots. Work around the clump, digging and lifting, until you can unearth it. Lift the entire mound of roots and soil from the ground and lay it on its side. Use your shovel or a sharp garden knife to slice through the roots and soil, and separate the mound into two or more individual sections. Transplant the sections or divisions into prepared soil in sunny locations. Apply a slow-release, all-purpose granular fertilizer around – but not touching – the divisions. Water well and provide an inch of water per week, including rain. — Collection: After three to five years, thinning helps to improve airflow, inhibit fungal disease, and invigorate blooming.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/symphyotrichum-ericoides/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://gardenerspath.com/plants/flowers/grow-heath-asters/#:~:text=By%20early%20summer%2C%20you%20can,the%20last%20spring%20frost%20date."}, {"Plant_ID": "Symphyotrichum lanceolatum", "Scientific Name": "Symphyotrichum lanceolatum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Lanceleaf Aster", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully separate the root clumps and replant them. Large divisions can be planted into their permanent positions whereas smaller clumps should be kept in a cold frame until they are growing well. — Collection: Take divisions in early spring or fall || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Pre-chill spring sown seeds to improve germination. — Collection: Fertile flowers mature to a dry cypsela, 0.5 to 1.6 mm long, with a whitish pappus attached for wind dispersion. These seed heads are rounded and look like small dandelion seed heads. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Seeds can be sown fresh in the fall or spring.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/symphyotrichum-lanceolatum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://earthone.io/plant/symphyotrichum%20lanceolatum 2) https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/plantguide/pdf/pg_sylal4.pdf | 1) https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/plantguide/pdf/pg_sylal4.pdf 2) https://friendsofeloisebutler.org/pages/plants/whitepanicleaster.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Symphyotrichum lateriflorum", "Scientific Name": "Symphyotrichum lateriflorum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Calico Aster", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Bud | Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: Water the Plant: Thoroughly water the plant the day before you plan to divide it. This helps reduce stress on the roots. Dig Carefully: Use a spade or garden fork to dig around the plant, being cautious not to damage the roots. Lift the Clump: Gently lift the clump from the ground, taking care to keep the root ball intact. Separate Sections: Divide the clump into smaller sections, ideally with 3-4 stems each. Replant Immediately: Place the divisions back into the soil at the same depth they were originally growing. This ensures they adapt quickly to their new home. — Collection: Timing is crucial for successful division. Aim for early spring or fall when your calico aster plants are not actively blooming. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Weather conditions play a significant role in propagation success. Avoid extreme heat or frost, as these can hinder growth and damage delicate seedlings or cuttings. Soil temperature is another critical factor. Ensure the soil is warm enough to promote seed germination and rooting. A consistent, suitable temperature creates an environment where your Calico Aster can thrive. — Collection: For seeds, aim to collect them in late summer to early fall, then sow them during winter for optimal growth. When seedlings have two sets of true leaves, harden off to gradually acclimate them to the outdoors. Set them outside for a few hours a day for three or four days. Then transplant seedlings to the garden. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the stem in powdered rooting hormone, and place it two to three inches deep in potting medium, in a container with good drainage. Keep the rooting stem out of direct sunlight, and maintain even moisture. You can make a mini greenhouse by covering the container with a plastic bag. This promotes condensation and keeps the growing environment moist. — Collection: To take a stem cutting, use clean, sharp pruners to cut a 6 to 7-inch stem of soft, new growth in the spring or summer. Remove the leaves from the bottom three or four inches.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/symphyotrichum-lateriflorum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://greg.app/propagate-calico-aster/#:~:text=Best%20Time%20to%20Propagate%20%F0%9F%8C%B1,summer%20is%20your%20best%20bet. | 1) https://greg.app/propagate-calico-aster/#:~:text=Best%20Time%20to%20Propagate%20%F0%9F%8C%B1,summer%20is%20your%20best%20bet. 2) https://gardenerspath.com/plants/flowers/grow-calico-aster/#Propagation 3) https://www.fellabees.com/shop/p/56c8zhm059g5gdos0p21ee3kxs5sqj | https://gardenerspath.com/plants/flowers/grow-calico-aster/#Propagation"}, {"Plant_ID": "Symphyotrichum oblongifolium", "Scientific Name": "Symphyotrichum oblongifolium", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Fall Aster", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Rhizome", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: If seeds are sown directly, sow them five-eighths of an inch deep in the fall and sow thickly. Plant a cover crop of a cool-season annual grass over the seedbed to protect seed over the winter. — Collection: Seeds can be collected from wild plants in late fall when the achenes (dry fruits) separate easily from the receptacle. Seeds should be collected in paper bags and allowed to dry for 1–2 weeks. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: If seeds are to be propagated in a container, they should be stored for 1–3 months at 30–40 degrees Fahrenheit before sowing. Many species of Aster benefit from moisture during the cold storage (stratification) period. Use a perlite/vermiculite mix for stratification. The seed will germinate in 10 to 15 days at 72 degrees Fahrenheit. Germination to true leaf stage is 7 to 15 days. Seedlings should be thinned at this stage. — Collection: Seeds can be collected from wild plants in late fall when the achenes (dry fruits) separate easily from the receptacle. Seeds should be collected in paper bags and allowed to dry for 1–2 weeks. || Rhizome — Treatment: Division — Method: Given this plant spreads by rhizomes and division is a great way to propagate. It can be formally divided every 3-5 years. But in reality, if one wants to propagate new plants you only need to cut and plant the newly emerging shoots in Spring. If a stalk has at least a few roots, then planting it in the cool Spring soil is all that is needed to give birth to a new colonizing plant.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/symphyotrichum-oblongifolium/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/factsheet/pdf/fs_syob.pdf 2) https://growitbuildit.com/aromatic-aster-symphyotrichum-oblongifolium/#:~:text=Aromatic%20Aster%20can%20also%20be,to%20a%20new%20colonizing%20plant. | https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/factsheet/pdf/fs_syob.pdf | https://growitbuildit.com/aromatic-aster-symphyotrichum-oblongifolium/#:~:text=Aromatic%20Aster%20can%20also%20be,to%20a%20new%20colonizing%20plant."}, {"Plant_ID": "Symphyotrichum patens", "Scientific Name": "Symphyotrichum patens", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Late Purple Aster", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Clump division | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the leaves from the lower half of the cutting to prevent rot and dip the cut end into rooting hormone to enhance root growth. Insert into a pot filled with moist, well-draining potting mix. Make sure at least two leaf nodes are buried in the soil. Cover the pot with plastic to retain humidity and place it in indirect light. Keep the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged. — Collection: The best time to propagate late purple aster is during early spring through mid-summer, using stem cuttings. Choose a healthy, non-flowering stem from late purple aster that is about 4-6 inches long. Make sure the stem has several sets of leaves. Cut the stem Using your prepared tools, cut the selected stem at a 45-degree angle just below a leaf node. || Clump division — Treatment: Division — Method: Replant these divisions at the same depth they were originally growing to foster healthy new growth. — Collection: Carefully separate the root clumps in the dormant period, ensuring each new section has ample roots. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: To sprout seeds indoors, begin four weeks before your region’s last average spring frost date. Keep the soil moist but not soggy. Provide ample sunlight. Once the frost danger passes, set the seedlings outdoors in a sheltered area for a few hours each day for about four days, increasing the amount of time spent out each day. To direct sow seeds, wait until the danger of frost passes and prepare the soil the garden soil by working it to a depth of 8 to 12 inches until it is crumbly. Sow one to two seeds every 8 to 36 inches. When the seedlings have two sets of true leaves, thin them to one seedling per interval. — Collection: Knowing when to harvest is easy. You’ll see them starting to dry out as the first frost date approaches. The first method is to cut entire stalks bearing clusters of blossoms. The fresh ones continue to dry on the harvested stalks. The second is to collect individual flower heads by holding a paper grocery bag beneath a plant with one hand, and snipping off individual dry flower heads with the other. Or rub the dry heads between thumb and fingers until they loosen and fall in. For harvested stalks, simply bind them together with twine, like bouquets, and suspend them upside-down. For snipped flower heads and crumbled heads, lay out newspaper and spread the contents of your bag(s) over it in a single layer. Allow to dry for about a week. Then Rub the seed heads between your thumbs and fingers, removing as much debris as possible as you go along. Gently blow across the paper to remove remaining fluff. Store in airtight containers in a cool, dry location until ready to use.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/symphyotrichum-patens/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Symphyotrichum_patens.html# | https://gardenerspath.com/plants/flowers/save-aster-seeds/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Symphyotrichum praealtum", "Scientific Name": "Symphyotrichum praealtum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Willowleaf Aster", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: 30 Days Cold Stratification increases germination. Seeds are small and requires light to germinate. Surface sow and bottom water. Willowleaf aster should be propagated in early spring, particularly through sowing seeds. Ideal conditions include temperatures between 65-75°F and ample sunlight. Springtime offers optimal soil moisture and increasing daylight, which supports strong root development and vigorous growth. Once the seedlings have developed a few sets of true leaves and are strong enough to handle, carefully transplant them into individual pots or directly into the garden space, ensuring proper spacing for growth. — Collection: Harvest mature seeds from dried flower heads of willowleaf aster. Gently shake or tap the flower heads to collect seeds on a clean surface.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/symphyotrichum-praealtum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.fellabees.com/shop/p/iey7qnrv7w75xf6a1k0etlc6df6my1 2) https://www.prairiemoon.com/symphyotrichum-praealtum-willow-aster#panel-planting 3) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Symphyotrichum_praealtum.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Taxodium distichum", "Scientific Name": "Taxodium distichum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Bald Cypress", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Seed sowing is generally recommended in spring. Soak the seeds in hot water for 24 hours beforehand – this helps speed up germination. The seedlings grow a long taproot and therefore need to be planted in a deep container to avoid root deformation. The seedlings have 3 to 9 (most often 6) cotyledons and are capable of very rapid growth usually reaching 75 to 100 cm (30 to 40 in) in height during their first full growing season. Plants should be moved to their permanent positions during the dormant season. — Collection: Seeds should be collected in the fall. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Cuttings root quite easily. It’s important to provide suitable conditions: a warm and humid environment is ideal. — Collection: Choose fresh shoots in early summer. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Store the seed cold and moist over winter - best mixed in damp sand and kept at +1 or +2°C. Then sow in spring, either indoors in a pot, or outdoors after the risk of frost is over. They are not too fussy over soil type, silty is perhaps best but it won't make a lot of difference. No fertilizer needed. The seedlings grow a long taproot and therefore need to be planted in a deep container to avoid root deformation. The seedlings have three to 9 (most often six) cotyledons and are capable of very rapid growth, usually reaching 75 to 100 cm (30 to 40 in) in height during their first full growing season. Plants should be moved to their permanent positions during the dormant season. — Collection: Seeds should be collected in the fall.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/taxodium-distichum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://gardentask.uk/bald-cypress-taxodium-distichum/#:~:text=Learn%20How%20to%20Propagate%20the,and%20humid%20environment%20is%20ideal. 2) https://earthone.io/plant/taxodium%20distichum 3) https://www.treeseedonline.com/store/p105/Swamp_Cypress_%28taxodium_distichum%29.html#:~:text=Several%20different%20methods%20are%20possible,positions%20during%20the%20dormant%20season. | 1) https://gardentask.uk/bald-cypress-taxodium-distichum/#:~:text=Learn%20How%20to%20Propagate%20the,and%20humid%20environment%20is%20ideal. 2) https://earthone.io/plant/taxodium%20distichum | 1) https://forums.botanicalgarden.ubc.ca/threads/bald-cypress-taxodium-distichum-seeds.46370/ 2) https://earthone.io/plant/taxodium%20distichum 3) https://www.treeseedonline.com/store/p105/Swamp_Cypress_%28taxodium_distichum%29.html#:~:text=Several%20different%20methods%20are%20possible,positions%20during%20the%20dormant%20season."}, {"Plant_ID": "Tetragonotheca texana", "Scientific Name": "Tetragonotheca texana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Squarebud Daisy", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Use a well-draining sandy soil mix. Surface-sow seeds and lightly cover, ensuring they receive ample sunlight for germination. Keep soil just moist until seedlings appear, then provide full sun and avoid waterlogged conditions for healthy root development.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/tetragonotheca-texana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Tetragonotheca_texana.html#:~:text=Propagation:%20To%20propagate%20nerve%2Dray,%2C%20and%20disease%20info%2C%20etc."}, {"Plant_ID": "Tetraneuris scaposa", "Scientific Name": "Tetraneuris scaposa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Four-nerve Daisy", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Fresh seed may germinate better. Direct sow outdoors in fall. Sprinkle the seeds on the soil surface and lightly press them in, ensuring they are not buried deeply as they require light for optimal seed germination. Place the seed tray in a bright location, but out of direct sunlight. Keep warm and keep the soil consistently moist, but avoid overwatering. Slow growing. — Collection: Allow seedheads to dry on plants; remove and collect seeds. Or collect seed when it falls off easily, year-round. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Strip the lower leaves to expose the nodes and dip in a rooting hormone before planting in a well-draining soil mix, ensuring that at least two leaf nodes are buried in the soil. Provide consistent moisture and warmth to support root establishment. When ready to transplant, they require shallow planting for cuttings to take root. — Collection: Take cuttings in spring and early summer to provide the best light levels and temperatures that support the rooting process and new growth. Select a healthy non-flowering stem 4-6 inches long and make a clean cut below a leaf node. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Replant the divisions immediately in well-prepared soil at the same depth as they were originally growing. Keep the soil consistently moist until they are established. — Collection: Clump division should be done in early spring or fall. Carefully dig up the plant, ensuring you get a good root mass. Divide the plant into smaller sections, each with a healthy set of roots and shoots.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/tetraneuris-scaposa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=TESC2 2) https://davesgarden.com/guides/pf/go/53549 3) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Tetraneuris_scaposa.html#:~:text=Propagation%20Time:%20Spring%2C%20Summer,to%20allow%20for%20optimal%20growth. 4) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-tetraneuris-scaposa/ | https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Tetraneuris_scaposa.html | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-tetraneuris-scaposa/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Teucrium canadense", "Scientific Name": "Teucrium canadense", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "American Germander", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow spring in a cold frame and only just cover the seed. Prick out the seedlings into individual pots when they are large enough to handle and plant them out in the summer if they are large enough. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Divisions can be planted out direct into their permanent positions. We have found that it is best to pot up smaller divisions and grow them on in light shade in a greenhouse or cold frame until they are growing away well. Plant them out in the summer or the following spring.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/teucrium-canadense/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Teucrium+canadense#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,summer%20or%20the%20following%20spring."}, {"Plant_ID": "Thelesperma filifolium", "Scientific Name": "Thelesperma filifolium", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Greenthread", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct sow in late fall, planting just below the surface of the soil. For spring planting, mix the Thelesperma Filifolium seeds with moist sand and store in the refrigerator for 30 days before planting. Keep the soil lightly moist until germination. Water seedlings occasionally until they become established; since they need good drainage, mature plants grow well in drought and poor soil as well as rocky soil or gravel. Occasional watering in especially dry weather will improve its blooming. This greenthread plant will self-seed occasionally in good growing conditions. It makes an excellent choice for rock gardens, and attracts butterflies. — Collection: After the flower petals fall from the head, the center cone will begin to develop seed. Remove the seed heads as soon as the stem beneath the cone begins to turn dry and brown. Spread the seed heads out to dry away from direct sunlight, then separate the Thelesperma Filifolium seeds from the stems by rubbing them lightly. Store the cleaned greenthread seed in a dry, cool place. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Cold stratify for 15-45 days. Sow in early spring at 15 60 - 75 degrees F. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end in a rooting hormone and plant it in a well-draining soil mix. Keep the soil moist but not waterlogged and place the cutting in a warm, bright area. After a few weeks, the cutting should start to develop roots. Once the roots have developed, the new plant can be transplanted into its own pot or into the garden. — Collection: Take a 3-4 inch cutting from healthy stem tips, avoiding any flowers or flower buds.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/thelesperma-filifolium/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.everwilde.com/store/Greenthread-Wildflower-Seeds.html 2) https://plantiary.com/plant/thelesperma-filifolium_4424.html#:~:text=The%20propagation%20of%20this%20plant,pot%20or%20into%20the%20garden. | https://www.gardenia.net/plant/thelesperma-filifolium | https://plantiary.com/plant/thelesperma-filifolium_4424.html#:~:text=The%20propagation%20of%20this%20plant,pot%20or%20into%20the%20garden."}, {"Plant_ID": "Thelesperma simplicifolium", "Scientific Name": "Thelesperma simplicifolium", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Navajo Tea", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Direct sow. For germination, aim for optimal conditions: temperatures between 70°F and 85°F and consistent moisture. This will help your seeds sprout within 7 to 14 days. — Collection: Timing is crucial; harvest seeds when they are fully mature, typically in late summer or early fall. o collect seeds, gently shake the plant or use a paper bag to catch any that fall. Ensure you store them in a cool, dry place until you're ready to plant. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Once you've chosen your cuttings, prepare a rooting medium. A mix of well-draining soil or perlite works best to encourage root development. Place the cuttings in the medium, ensuring they are secure but not overly compacted. Keep the soil moist and provide indirect sunlight to promote healthy growth. — Collection: Start by selecting healthy stems that are free from disease or damage.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/thelesperma-simplicifolium/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://greg.app/slender-greenthread-overview/#:~:text=%F0%9F%8C%B1%20Seed%20Propagation%20Methods,to%20catch%20any%20that%20fall."}, {"Plant_ID": "Pelazoneuron kunthii", "Scientific Name": "Pelazoneuron kunthii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Wood Fern", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Rhizome | Spores", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Rhizome — Treatment: Division — Method: Plant each division immediately in a moist well-draining potting mix, ensuring the crown (where the fronds emerge) is level with the soil surface. Place the divided section in a shaded area, water well, and mulch. — Collection: This fern spreads slowly by underground rhizomes and can be divided every 3–4 years, ideally during its active growing season, preferably in spring. Carefully lift the plant and gently tease apart the rhizomes (underground stems). Each division should have a healthy set of roots and fronds. || Spores — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Prepare a seed tray or small pots with a sterile seed-starting mix. Sprinkle the collected spores thinly over the dampened surface. Do not bury them as light is essential for germination. Cover the container with a clear lid or plastic wrap to maintain humidity. Place the container in a warm, indirectly lit location. Germination can take several weeks to months. Once the spores germinate, tiny heart-shaped structures will appear. These produce both male and female organs, leading to fertilization and the development of new fern plants. Once the fernlets are large enough to handle, gently separate them and transplant them into individual pots filled with well-draining potting mix. — Collection: Begin by identifying mature fronds with darkened sori (cluster of spore-producing receptacles on the underside of a frond). Carefully snip off a frond and place it in a paper bag, spore-side down. Leave it in a dry, warm location for a few days to allow the spores to release.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/thelypteris-kunthii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-thelypteris-kunthii/ 2) https://www.chestateefarms.com/post/southern-shield-fern-thelypteris-kunthii-a-tough-elegant-native-for-atlanta-s-zone-7# | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-thelypteris-kunthii/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Thymophylla pentachaeta", "Scientific Name": "Thymophylla pentachaeta", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Parralena", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds directly in the garden in early spring after the last frost. The seeds require light to germinate, so do not cover them with soil. Keep the soil lightly moist until germination occurs. — Collection: Allow the seed heads to dry out on the plants and then remove and collect the seed.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/thymophylla-pentachaeta/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://earthone.io/plant/thymophylla%20pentachaeta 2) https://horticultureunlimited.com/thymophylla-pentahaeta/#:~:text=Thymophylla%20pentachaeta%20%2D%20Horticulture%20Unlimited,remove%20and%20collect%20the%20seed."}, {"Plant_ID": "Tinantia anomala", "Scientific Name": "Tinantia anomala", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "False Dayflower", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Use well-draining, fertile soil. Lightly cover seeds and maintain consistent moisture. Ensure proper spacing for growth. Regular care and moisture adjustments are essential for healthy development after sowing.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/tinantia-anomala/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Tinantia_anomala.html 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=TIAN"}, {"Plant_ID": "Tradescantia gigantea", "Scientific Name": "Tradescantia gigantea", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Giant Spiderwort", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Layering — Method: Drape long stems over a separate pot of compost and secure the stem with a stone or pin. Over time this stem will develop roots where it makes contact with the soil. To test if roots have formed gently tug on the stem, if you feel resistance then roots are laying foundations in their new home but if the stem moves easily then leave well alone for another week or so. Once established you can cut the stem off from the parent plant and you have a completely independent baby plant. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: You can root your cuttings in water or soil. Place the cutting in a jar or glass of water, ensuring the node is submerged. Change the water every few days. Plant the cutting in a pot with a well-draining potting mix, burying the node slightly in the soil. Keep the soil consistently moist. Roots typically develop in a few weeks. You’ll know they’re ready when new growth appears on the cutting. — Collection: Using clean, sharp scissors or a knife, cut a 4-6 inch stem just below a node. Remove the bottom leaves to reveal the node.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/tradescantia-gigantea/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://plantsmith.co.uk/how-to-propagate-tradescantia/#:~:text=Propagate%20in%20soil,to%20keep%20the%20cuttings%20hydrated. | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-tradescantia-gigantea/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Tradescantia hirsutiflora", "Scientific Name": "Tradescantia hirsutiflora", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Hairyflower Spiderwort", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: The seeds may be sown fresh or stored dry at 10 degrees F. Fresh seed germinates in two weeks but Steffen (1997) recommendes cold/moist stratification for stored seed. — Collection: The capsules should be collected when mature (two to three weeks after flowering). || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end of the stem into a rooting hormone (optional), then plant it in a pot filled with moist potting soil. Keep the soil evenly moist and place the pot in a location with bright, indirect light. In a few weeks, the cutting should start to produce new roots and begin growing. — Collection: choose a healthy stem with at least two nodes (the points where leaves attach to the stem). Using clean, sharp scissors or a knife, cut the stem just below a node. Remove any leaves from the lower half of the cutting, leaving a few leaves at the top.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/tradescantia-hirsutiflora/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://warcapps.usgs.gov/PlantID/Species/Details/804#:~:text=Tradescantia%20is%20easily%20propagated%20by,be%20aggressive%20in%20disturbed%20ground. | https://plantiary.com/plant/tradescantia-hirsutiflora_4412.html#:~:text=Propagation:%20Tradescantia%20hirsutiflora%20can%20be,roots%20within%20a%20few%20weeks."}, {"Plant_ID": "Tradescantia occidentalis", "Scientific Name": "Tradescantia occidentalis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Prairie Spiderwort", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Ensure you have clean, sharp scissors or pruning shears. Sterilize the blades with rubbing alcohol or a 10% bleach solution to prevent the spread of diseases. Make a clean cut just below a node. Remove the lower leaves to expose the nodes, leaving at least two or three leaves on the upper part of the stem for photosynthesis. Place the cutting in a glass of water or a moist potting mix. Ensure the nodes are submerged in water or buried in the potting mix. Place the setup in a location that receives bright, indirect light. Change the water every few days or keep the soil lightly moist. Roots should begin to form in 1-3 weeks. Once substantial roots have developed, transplant the cutting into a suitable pot with well-draining soil. After propagating western Spiderwort, position the new plant in a location that receives bright, indirect light. Water the plant consistently, allowing the top inch of soil to dry between watering. Western Spiderwort enjoys high humidity, so consider using a humidity tray or misting the leaves. — Collection: Choose a healthy stem from western Spiderwort that is at least 4-6 inches long. Make sure the stem has several nodes, as these will help in root development. The optimal periods for propagating western Spiderwort are spring and summer, using cutting methods. These seasons offer favorable conditions with mild temperatures and increased daylight, which are critical for root generation and growth. The longer daylight periods in these months also provide sufficient light for photosynthesis, important for the successful establishment of new plants.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/tradescantia-occidentalis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Tradescantia_occidentalis.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Trichloris crinita", "Scientific Name": "Trichloris crinita", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Two-flowered Trichloris", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Plant in early fall (August) in south Texas. Plant seed ⅛ to ¼ inch deep. It is better to plant too shallow than too deep. This corresponds to planting 20 live seeds per square foot. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Once you have the clump out of the ground, use a sharp, clean knife or garden spade to divide the root mass into smaller sections. Each section should have several stems and a portion of the root system attached. Prepare the new planting site by loosening the soil and removing any weeds. Plant each divided section of false rhodes grass into the prepared soil at the same depth it was previously growing. Firm the soil around the base to eliminate air pockets. Water the newly planted divisions thoroughly after planting to help settle the soil and encourage root establishment. Maintain consistent soil moisture for the first few weeks to ensure successful rooting. — Collection: The optimal periods for propagating false rhodes grass are spring and autumn. During these seasons, the temperature is moderate, and the plant is in active growth, facilitating successful division. These periods provide sufficient light and encourage root development, leading to robust new plants. Avoid extreme temperatures of summer and winter for best results. Begin by selecting a healthy, mature clump of false rhodes grass that is well established in your garden or environment. Ensure the chosen clump shows vigorous growth with multiple stems and a healthy root system. Carefully dig around the perimeter of the false rhodes grass clump with a spade or garden fork, digging deep enough to lift the entire root mass without damaging it. Gently lift the clump from the soil.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/trichloris-crinita/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/plantmaterials/stpmcrb13709.pdf | https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Trichloris_crinita.html#:~:text=False%20rhodes%20grass%20enjoys%20warm%20climates%20and,rhodes%20grass%20requires%20minimal%20maintenance%20once%20established."}, {"Plant_ID": "Trichostema brachiatum", "Scientific Name": "Trichostema brachiatum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "False Pennyroyal", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Spring, sow seeds directly outdoors. You can also start them indoors 4-6 weeks before the last frost date in your region. Choose a sunny spot with well-draining soil. For indoor sowing, use seed trays with a good seed-starting mix. Scatter the seeds thinly on the surface and lightly cover them with soil. Keep the soil consistently moist but not soggy. Blue Curls seeds typically germinate within 7-21 days at temperatures between 65-75 degrees Fahrenheit. Once seedlings have a few true leaves, thin them out to ensure adequate space for healthy growth. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Propagation via stem cuttings is best done in early summer when the plant is actively growing. Choose healthy, young stems with no signs of disease or pests. Cut them just below a node (the point where a leaf grows). Dip the base of the cutting in rooting hormone, which encourages root development. Use a well-draining potting mix. Insert the cuttings into moist soil, leaving 1-2 leaves above the soil line. Cover the cuttings with a clear plastic dome or bag to maintain high humidity and encourage rooting. Place them in a bright, indirect light location. Rooting can take anywhere from 4 to 6 weeks. Monitor the cuttings and ensure the soil remains moist. Once roots have formed, transplant the cuttings into individual pots or directly into the garden.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/trichostema-brachiatum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-trichostema-brachiatum/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Tridens albescens", "Scientific Name": "Tridens albescens", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "White Tridens", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Clump | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Water the clump thoroughly the day before dividing. Carefully dig around the entire clump, lifting it from the ground. Separate mature clumps with minimal root disturbance. ensuring each division has a good amount of roots and shoots. Plant divisions at the same depth. Water immediately and maintain consistent moisture. Choose an appropriate location based on white tridens's light and soil preferences for optimal growth. — Collection: Early spring, just as new growth emerges, is the ideal time for division. This allows ample time for the divisions to establish themselves before the heat of summer. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: For a head start, sow seeds indoors 6-8 weeks before the last expected frost. Use a seed starting mix, sow seeds shallowly, and keep the soil consistently moist. Once the soil warms in spring, you can directly sow seeds into prepared garden beds. Choose a location with well-drained soil and full sun to partial shade. Germination can take anywhere from 10 days to several weeks. Keep the soil consistently moist until seedlings are established. — Collection: Purchase seeds from reputable suppliers or collect your own from mature plants in late summer or fall.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/tridens-albescens/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Tridens_albescens.html 2) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-tridens-albescens/ | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-tridens-albescens/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Tridens congestus", "Scientific Name": "Tridens congestus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Pink Tridens", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Plant them in a well-draining soil mix, covering lightly. Water gently: Keep the soil moist but not soggy. Seeds typically germinate within a few weeks. — Collection: Collect seeds from mature plants in late summer or early fall. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Replant immediately in prepared soil, watering them well. — Collection: Best done in early spring or fall. Dig up the clump: Carefully lift the plant from the ground. Gently pull apart the clumps, ensuring each division has healthy roots. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end in rooting hormone to encourage growth. Place the cutting in a pot with moist soil and cover it with a plastic bag to maintain humidity. After a few weeks, roots should develop, and you can transplant them into larger pots or your garden. — Collection: Choose vigorous stems and cut them just below a node.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/tridens-congestus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://greg.app/tridens-congestus-overview/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Tridens strictus", "Scientific Name": "Tridens strictus", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Longspike Tridens", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Bud", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Plant seeds in well-draining soil. Cover the seeds lightly with soil and keep the soil moist. The seedlings should appear in a few weeks. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: To propagate via stem cuttings, take a 3- to 4-inch stem cutting from a healthy plant. Remove the leaves from the bottom half of the stem and dip the cut end in rooting hormone. Plant the stem cutting in well-draining soil and keep the soil moist. The cutting should root in a few weeks. || Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: It is also possible to propagate Tridens Strictus via division, where the plant is dug up and separated into multiple smaller plants. However, this method can be more difficult and is typically reserved for more mature plants.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/tridens-strictus/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://plantiary.com/plant/tridens-strictus_27992.html#:~:text=Tridens%20Strictus%20plant%20can%20be,reserved%20for%20more%20mature%20plants."}, {"Plant_ID": "Typha domingensis", "Scientific Name": "Typha domingensis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Southern Cattail", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Surface sow in a pot and stand it in 3cm of water. Pot up the young seedlings as soon as possible and, as the plants develop, increase the depth of water. Plant out when large enough. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Plant them out into their permanent positions. — Collection: Harvest the young shoots when they are about 10 - 30cm tall, making sure there is at least some root attached.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/typha-domingensis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://tropical.theferns.info/viewtropical.php?id=typha+domingensis#:~:text=tolerating%206%20%2D%208%5B-,Title%20Ecocrop%20Publication%20Author%20Website%20http://ecocrop.fao.org,Title%20Flora%20of%20N. | 1) https://tropical.theferns.info/viewtropical.php?id=typha+domingensis#:~:text=tolerating%206%20%2D%208%5B-,Title%20Ecocrop%20Publication%20Author%20Website%20http://ecocrop.fao.org,Title%20Flora%20of%20N. 2) https://earthone.io/plant/typha%20domingensis"}, {"Plant_ID": "Ulmus alata", "Scientific Name": "Ulmus alata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Winged Elm", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Collection: Collect seeds by raking from the ground soon after they fall or by stripping them from the branches. Air-dry a few days before storing. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Fall-ripened seeds may be stratified for 30-60 days at 36-40 degrees.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ulmus-alata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ULAL"}, {"Plant_ID": "Ulmus americana", "Scientific Name": "Ulmus americana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "American Elm", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Softwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratify seeds for 2-3 months to boost germination success. Transplant in dormancy with a robust root system and moist soil. Plant your stratified seeds shallowly, about 1/16 inch deep, and tamp the soil gently. Keeping the bed moist is non-negotiable until germination wraps up. If you're in a semiarid region, consider transferring year-old seedlings to containers for a better survival rate. — Collection: Collect samaras, the elm's winged seeds, right after they hit the ground in spring. Look for seeds that are undamaged and free from disease. Remember, proximity matters; American Elm seeds typically fall within a 300-foot radius of the parent tree. || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: First, identify a branch that’s got new growth on it. Inspect closely to see the difference between old growth and new growth. Find a piece of branch that’s not firm, brown old growth, it’ll be green but by now it will have gone semi hard. Snip a cutting just below a node, make sure the width of the cutting is not too thin, 1/4 inch width is fine, and they should be 6-8 inches long. Remove leaves except for 1-2 at the top, if they are too big cut the leaves in half. Pruning blades must be sharp and clean to ensure a clean cut that reduces the risk of infection and damage to the parent plant. Pruning shears must be sterilized between cuts to prevent the spread of disease. Treat with indolebutyric acid or by leaf bud cuttings. In a test, greenhouse-grown stock rooted easier than field-grown stock. Dip the cut end into rooting hormone, to enhance root growth for a stronger establishment. Maintaining high humidity is crucial for cuttings to prevent desiccation. A dome or plastic bag placed over the containers creates a humid environment that supports the initial growth of american elm's cuttings. Once the american elm cutting has rooted and shows new growth, gradually acclimate it to less humid conditions by removing the plastic cover for longer periods each day. After a few weeks, transplant the young american elm into a larger pot or directly into a prepared site in the garden with well-draining soil. Continue to water regularly to keep the soil evenly moist, and protect the tree from strong winds. As american elm grows, provide support if necessary, and monitor for pests and diseases. Pruning to develop a strong branch structure can begin after the first year of growth. — Collection: Take in June. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Scarify the seeds to improve germination rates.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ulmus-americana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=ulmaceae-ulmus-2026&referer=wildflower 2) https://greg.app/propagate-american-elm/ | 1) https://www.srs.fs.usda.gov/pubs/misc/ag_654/volume_2/ulmus/americana.htm#:~:text=American%20elm%20can%20be%20propagated,cuttings%20has%20not%20been%20effective. 2_ https://meridian.allenpress.com/jeh/article/30/2/73/79821/Vegetative-Propagation-of-American-Elm-Ulmus 3) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Ulmus_americana.html 3) https://www.ecofriendlyincome.com/blog/how-to-propagate-white-elm-ulmus-americana | https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Ulmus_americana.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Ulmus crassifolia", "Scientific Name": "Ulmus crassifolia", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Cedar Elm", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Fall-ripened seeds may be stratified for 30-60 days at 36-40 degrees. — Collection: Collect seeds by raking from the ground soon after they fall or by stripping them from the branches. Air-dry a few days before storing.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ulmus-crassifolia/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=ULCR"}, {"Plant_ID": "Ungnadia speciosa", "Scientific Name": "Ungnadia speciosa", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Mexican Buckeye", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Best sown fresh. Untreated seed will germinate in three weeks. Germination is best in warm soil. Field plant or use deep containers to accommodate a long initial root. Do not allow the soil to dry out. — Collection: Gather seed in August through October when capsules turn dark reddish brown and begin to open. Seeds should be shiny black and hard. Remove seeds from pods and air dry a few days before storing in bags or ventilated containers at room temperature. For longer storage, place paper bags in the refrigerator. They do not store well for long periods of time. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut end of the stem in a rooting hormone powder to encourage root growth. Tap off any excess powder to prevent over-application. Fill a pot with well-draining potting mix. Insert the cut end of the stem into the soil, making sure at least two leaf nodes are buried for potential root growth. Water the soil gently to settle it around the cutting. Place the pot in a warm location with indirect sunlight. Mexican buckeye cuttings benefit from high humidity, so consider placing a clear plastic bag over the pot to create a mini-greenhouse effect. Make sure the bag does not touch the leaves. Check the cutting regularly to ensure the soil remains moist but not waterlogged. Roots typically form within 4-8 weeks. After roots have established, gradually acclimatize the cutting to less humid conditions by removing the plastic bag for extended periods. — Collection: Gather a pair of clean, sharp pruning shears. Select a healthy, non-flowering stem from mexican buckeye ensuring it is at least 6 inches long and has multiple leaves. Cut the stem at a 45-degree angle just below a leaf node.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/ungnadia-speciosa/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=UNSP 2) https://gardenoracle.com/images/ungnadia-speciosa.html | https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Ungnadia_speciosa.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Vaccinium arboreum", "Scientific Name": "Vaccinium arboreum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Farkleberry", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratify for 60-90 days at 41 degrees. Sow in sligthly acid soil mix.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/vaccinium-arboreum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=VAAR"}, {"Plant_ID": "Vachellia farnesiana", "Scientific Name": "Vachellia farnesiana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Huisache", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Before planting, the tough seed coats will need to be loosened. This will improve the seeds’ chances of germinating. The process of loosening a seed coat is called scarification. To do this, remove the seeds and soak them in hot water overnight, allowing them to slowly cool. If you are in a hurry, rub them lightly with sandpaper instead. New plants will sprout in less than two weeks. — Collection: Wait until the green pods turn brown to collect fruit. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Cuttings can be taken from semi-hardwood branches and rooted in a well-draining soil mix. Propagation is best done in the spring or early summer.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/vachellia-farnesiana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://gardeningsolutions.ifas.ufl.edu/plants/trees-and-shrubs/trees/sweet-acacia/#:~:text=It%20is%20multi%2Dstemmed%20with,contact%20your%20county%20Extension%20office. 2) https://irrecenvhort.ifas.ufl.edu/Native%20Plants/Publications/propagation%20of%20sweet%20acacia-Smith%20et%20al.pdf#:~:text=Results%20confirm%20that%20asexual%20propagation%20of%20sweet,scarification%20treatment%20to%20alleviate%20physical%20seed%20dormancy. | https://earthone.io/plant/vachellia%20farnesiana?srsltid=AfmBOooqTBuOXlajNus9UVl9LfhbQkq_ZHaG1TK09WWeQIoRznbFpuXk"}, {"Plant_ID": "Vallisneria americana", "Scientific Name": "Vallisneria americana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "American Eelgrass", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stolon", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Allow seeds to sit in pods for 1-2 months until pods break down; it is easier to remove seeds from the gel matrix that surrounds them in the pods. It appears that seeds can be stored in tap water at 4 C for up to a year with no loss in viability; after 2 years in germination decreased over 50%.. — Collection: Collect green seed pods from plants in early fall (Sept-Oct) from stock plants maintained in our greenhouse or in outdoor tanks because of state restrictions on harvesting material in the wild; seeds for stock plants were originally collected from wild plants prior to implementation of a permitting process. Seed pods are ready if we can break them open and observe that many of the seeds inside are dark brown and hard. || Stolon — Treatment: Division — Method: Cut any excess lengths of stolon from plantlets or turions, and plant immediately in greenhouse tanks. Do not store these materials in 4 C cooler. Plantlets stored moist (in a moistened paper towel inside a plastic bag) tend to dry out rapidly and those in water still lose color and die; turions stored moist or wet turn black and soft. Replanting. In late fall, dig turions (overwintering structures) that also form at the end of stolons from the soil around our stock plants maintained in outdoor tanks. — Collection: Break small plantlets/rosettes off the end of stock plant stolons at any time of the year", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/vallisneria-americana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=VAAM3 2) https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=hydrocharitaceae-vallisneria-2355#:~:text=Seed:%20We%20collect%20green%20seed,plants%20maintained%20in%20outdoor%20tanks. | https://npn.rngr.net/renderNPNProtocolDetails?selectedProtocolIds=hydrocharitaceae-vallisneria-2355#:~:text=Seed:%20We%20collect%20green%20seed,plants%20maintained%20in%20outdoor%20tanks."}, {"Plant_ID": "Verbena halei", "Scientific Name": "Verbena halei", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Texas Verbena", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Verbena halei appears to exhibit recalcitrant seed behavior, meaning its seeds have a very short viability window and are difficult to germinate under typical conditions. Sow indoors 8-10 weeks before the last frost or outdoors directly into the ground after the danger of frost has passed. Place seeds on the surface lightly covered with soil. — Collection: Allow seedheads to dry on plants; remove and collect seeds. Store them in a cool, dry place until you're ready to sow. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Replant the divisions immediately in well-prepared soil, maintaining adequate moisture until they establish themselves. — Collection: Older, well-established plants divide more easily. The best time for division is during spring or early autumn, after flowering has subsided but before the onset of winter. Water the plant thoroughly a day before to ease division and reduce stress. Carefully dig up the plant, gently separate the root crown into smaller divisions, ensuring each division contains sufficient roots and healthy stems. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip the cut ends in rooting hormone powder to encourage root development. Plant the cuttings in moist soil or a well-draining propagating mix (e.g., a blend of perlite and peat moss) and kept consistently moist but not soggy, or place directly in water. Cover the cuttings with a humidity dome or plastic bag to maintain high humidity levels. Provide bright, indirect light. Rooting typically takes several weeks. — Collection: Taking cuttings during the active growing season (spring or early summer) is crucial. Using semi-hardwood cuttings (partially matured stems) generally yields better results. Take cuttings approximately 4-6 inches long, removing the lower leaves to prevent rot. Make a clean cut below a leaf node.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/verbena-halei/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-verbena-halei/ 2) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=VEHA 3) https://greg.app/propagate-verbena-halei/ | 1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-verbena-halei/ 2) https://greg.app/propagate-verbena-halei/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Verbena xutha", "Scientific Name": "Verbena xutha", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Gulf Vervain", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Stem | Clump", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: The best time to propagate gulf vervain is in spring, ideally through sowing. Spring offers optimal growing conditions with increasing temperatures and longer daylight hours, facilitating germination and growth. This period aligns with the natural growth cycle of gulf vervain, ensuring higher success rates and robust plant development. Sow seeds in a well-draining mix, lightly pressing them into the soil. Keep soil moist but not waterlogged; maintain moderate humidity and warmth. Once seedlings establish, thinning may be needed for optimal growth. — Collection: Collect seeds from mature gulf vervain plants. Ensure that the seeds are fully developed and dry before collection for best results. Clean the seeds gently to remove any attached floral debris. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stratify the seeds to enhance germination rates. This involves storing the seeds wrapped in moist paper towels inside a sealed plastic bag, and then placing them in a refrigerator for about 2 to 4 weeks. Remove the seeds from stratification and sow them in a tray filled with a well-draining seed starting mix. Lightly cover the seeds with soil as gulf vervain seeds require light for optimal germination. Keep the tray in a spot that receives bright, indirect sunlight. Keep the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged. Use a spray bottle to gently mist the soil surface if it begins to dry out. Maintain an ambient temperature around 65-75°F, which is ideal for gulf vervain's seed germination. Once the seedlings are several weeks old and have developed a set of true leaves, transplant them to individual pots or directly into the garden. Ensure that the transplantation is done carefully to avoid damaging the fragile roots. — Collection: Collect seeds from mature gulf vervain plants. Ensure that the seeds are fully developed and dry before collection for best results. Clean the seeds gently to remove any attached floral debris. || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Soak the Verbena xutha seeds in water for 24 hours before planting. This helps soften the seed coat and encourages faster germination. Plant them about 1/4 inch deep in moist, well-draining soil. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the lower leaves, dip the cut end in rooting hormone, and plant in a potting mix. — Collection: elect healthy, non-flowering stems and cut 4-6 inch segments just below a node. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully separate the root clumps, ensuring each division has roots and shoots. Replant the divisions immediately in a prepared bed or pot. — Collection: Dig up a mature Verbena xutha plant in early spring.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/verbena-xutha/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Verbena_xutha.html 2) https://www.forwardplant.com/plant-info/verbena-xutha/ | 1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Verbena_xutha.html 2) https://www.forwardplant.com/plant-info/verbena-xutha/ | https://www.forwardplant.com/plant-info/verbena-xutha/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Verbesina encelioides", "Scientific Name": "Verbesina encelioides", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Cowpen Daisy", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Plant five Cowpen Daisy seeds per one-gallon pot. The seeds require light to germinate, so do not cover them with soil. Water regularly, and when they get about two inches tall, she cuts back two of the plants, leaving a set of three per one-gallon pot. “That gives them plenty of room. Wait for the plants to sprout their true leaves. These are the leaves that follow the initial baby leaves. — Collection: Allow seedheads to dry on plants; remove and collect seeds", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/verbesina-encelioides/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=VEEN 2) https://texasbutterflyranch.com/2019/02/13/cowpen-daisy-how-to-grow-verbesina-encelioides-from-seed/#:~:text=Drake%20White%20of%20the%20Nectar,leaves%20inherent%20in%20the%20seed. 3) https://earthone.io/plant/verbesina%20encelioides?srsltid=AfmBOopXzkCIzTpSIax4pcmtUR-Zz5KHx90bybR6n6rbsb_W820gZf3c"}, {"Plant_ID": "Verbesina lindheimeri", "Scientific Name": "Verbesina lindheimeri", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Lindheimer's Crownbeard", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Prepare a well-draining soil mix, ideally a combination of potting soil and sand. Fill seed trays or pots with the soil mix. Sow the seeds on the surface of the soil mix. Lightly press them into the soil but do not cover them completely as they require light to germinate. Gently water the soil to keep it moist but not waterlogged. Use a spray bottle to avoid disturbing the seeds. Place the seed trays or pots in a location with plenty of indirect sunlight. Maintain a consistent temperature around 70°F (21°C) for optimal germination. Once seedlings have developed a few sets of true leaves, they can be transplanted to their permanent location. Ensure they are planted in well-draining soil with full sun exposure. Water them regularly until established, then reduce watering as lindheimer's crownbeard is drought-tolerant. Monitor for pests and diseases and address any issues promptly. Mulch around the base to retain moisture and suppress weeds. — Collection: Collect mature seeds from lindheimer's crownbeard after the flowering period. Ensure seeds are dry and free from any mold or pests.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/verbesina-lindheimeri/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Verbesina_lindheimeri.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Verbesina virginica", "Scientific Name": "Verbesina virginica", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Frostweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Root | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Root — Treatment: Division — Method: Ensure each division has sufficient roots and foliage for successful growth. — Collection: Divide while dormant in winter. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Seeds germinate readily and can be sown directly in the garden. — Collection: Allow seedheads to dry on plants and turned a brownish-black color; remove and collect seeds, then allow them to dry fully.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/verbesina-virginica/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=VEVI3 2) https://monsteraholic.com/verbesina-virginica/ | 1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=VEVI3 2) https://plantiary.com/plant/verbesina-virginica_4137.html 3) https://monsteraholic.com/verbesina-virginica/"}, {"Plant_ID": "Vernonia baldwinii", "Scientific Name": "Vernonia baldwinii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Western Ironweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: In the spring once the ground has warmed up, scatter seeds directly onto the soil surface in a well-prepared bed. Lightly rake the soil to cover the seeds and water them thoroughly. Ironweed seeds need sunlight to germinate, so don’t cover them deeply. They generally germinate within 2-4 weeks. Another method is to fill a seed starting tray or pots with a well-draining seed-starting mix. Moisten the mix with water until it is damp but not waterlogged. Sow the seeds on the surface and press them gently into the soil for good seed-to-soil contact, but do not bury them, as they need light to germinate. Cover the tray or pots with a clear plastic lid or plastic wrap to maintain humidity around the seeds, then ensure the soil stays moist. Place the seed tray or pots in a bright, indirect light or use grow lights to provide the appropriate light levels for germination. — Collection: Collect the seed once the flowers have fluffed out and produced a white “pappus” – the fluffy parachute-like appendage that helps a seed fly. Usually this happens around October. Allow the seed heads to dry completely before storing in a paper envelope in a cool, dry location.The sooner you sow your seeds, the better their chance at germinating. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Separate the plant into smaller divisions, each having a healthy root system and several shoots. Dividing the roots too small can impede their ability to establish themselves after transplanting, which may lead to a poor survival rate. Larger divisions tend to recover and grow more vigorously. Plant the divisions into well-prepared soil, spacing them according to the mature size of the plant. Water well and provide adequate sunlight. — Collection: The best time to divide Ironweed is in early spring or late summer, while the plant is actively growing. Dig up the plant carefully, being sure to loosen the soil around the root ball. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove the leaves from the bottom 2 inches of the stem. Next, dip the cut end of the stem into rooting hormone powder, which will encourage the development of roots. Place the stem cutting into a pot filled with a well-draining soil mix, such as a mixture of peat moss and perlite. Water the cutting thoroughly and place it in a warm and bright location, but not in direct sunlight. Keep the soil moist but not waterlogged. After about 4-6 weeks, you should start to see roots developing from the cutting. Once roots have formed, you can transplant the new plant into a larger pot or into your garden, taking care not to disturb the roots too much. — Collection: Take a stem cutting from a healthy and mature plant approximately 4-6 inches in length and taken from the top of the plant.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/vernonia-baldwinii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-vernonia-baldwinii/ 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Vernonia_baldwinii.html 3) https://gardenerspath.com/plants/flowers/grow-ironweed/ | 1) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-vernonia-baldwinii/ 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Vernonia_baldwinii.html | https://plantiary.com/plant/vernonia-baldwinii_19381.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Vernonia lindheimeri", "Scientific Name": "Vernonia lindheimeri", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Woolly Ironweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: The best time to propagate woolly ironweed is in early spring. During this period, temperatures and light conditions are favorable for seed germination. Sowing seeds in spring ensures they benefit from the increasing sunlight and warmth, which promotes healthy growth. This season also allows the plants to establish themselves before the harsher summer conditions. Prepare a well-draining seed starting mix. Fill seed trays or pots with this mix, ensuring it is lightly moistened but not waterlogged. Sow the woolly ironweed seeds on the surface of the soil. Lightly press the seeds into the soil but do not cover them with soil as they require light for germination. Mist the soil lightly to keep it moist. Cover the seed trays with a clear plastic lid or plastic wrap to increase humidity, but ensure there is some ventilation to prevent mold growth. Place trays in a warm location with indirect sunlight. Once seedlings are large enough to handle and have developed true leaves, transplant them into individual pots or directly into the garden, maintaining a spacing of about 12-18 inches apart. — Collection: Collect seeds from mature woolly ironweed plants. Ensure the seeds are dry and free of any moisture to prevent mold or rot during storage or sowing. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: Separate the clumps: Using a sharp knife or garden trowel, divide the root ball into smaller clumps, each with at least a few healthy stems. Plant the divisions: Replant the divisions in a sunny spot with well-draining soil. Water them thoroughly. Plant the divisions: Replant the divisions in a sunny spot with well-draining soil. Water them thoroughly. — Collection: Carefully dig up the plant, making sure to preserve as much of the root system as possible. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove lower leaves: Strip off the leaves below the soil line. Dip in rooting hormone: Optional, but beneficial, dip the cut end in rooting hormone. Plant in rooting medium: Fill a pot with a rooting mix and insert the cutting, ensuring it’s firmly in place. Keep it moist: Maintain a consistently moist environment and place the pot in a bright, indirect light spot. Wait patiently: Depending on conditions, cuttings might take weeks or months to root. — Collection: Select a healthy stem that’s not flowering, ideally with some new growth. Use a sharp knife or scissors to make a clean cut at a 45-degree angle just below a leaf node.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/vernonia-lindheimeri/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Vernonia_lindheimeri.html 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Vernonia_lindheimeri.html 3) https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-vernonia-lindheimeri/?print=print | https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-vernonia-lindheimeri/?print=print"}, {"Plant_ID": "Vernonia missurica", "Scientific Name": "Vernonia missurica", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Missouri ironweed", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump division", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds in a well-draining seed starting mix in early spring. Keep the soil moist and provide bright, indirect light. Once seedlings develop true leaves, transplant them into a sunny location outdoors. Space the plants 1-2 feet apart. Showy Ironweed seeds can be slow to germinate, taking several weeks or even months. — Collection: Collect seeds from mature flower heads after they’ve turned brown and dry. These will have a fuzzy appearance and contain the tiny seeds. Let the seed heads dry further in a paper bag or container. || Clump division — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully dig up the plant and gently separate the root ball into smaller sections, each with healthy roots and shoots. Replant each division in a well-prepared bed, ensuring they have sufficient space to grow. Be sure to water them well. — Collection: Divide Vernonia missurica in early spring or fall, when the plant is dormant. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Sow just under the surface of the soil and water in. Then cover them with plastic and place in a fridge for 90 days. Be sure they stay moist. After the cold stratification they are then brought back to room temperature 20-22°C (68-72°F) for them to germinate. Germination is irregular over a long period of time, generally 60-90 days, but some can take longer.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/vernonia-missurica/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://propagate.one/how-to-propagate-vernonia-missurica/ | https://ferriseeds.com/products/vernonia-missurica-br-missouri-ironweed?srsltid=AfmBOoqB__U3EucQVlsxyR4YL6JO1Zx3iemFi-PiytpOYV_10ouKHV1x"}, {"Plant_ID": "Viburnum rufidulum", "Scientific Name": "Viburnum rufidulum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Rusty Blackhaw Viburnum", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Softwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Best sown in a cold frame as soon as it is ripe. Germination can be slow, sometimes taking more than 18 months. If the seed is harvested 'green' (when it has fully developed but before it has fully ripened) and sown immediately in a cold frame, it should germinate in the spring. || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Take cuttings in July-August of half-ripe wood, 5 - 8 cm long with a heel if possible. Use a rooting hormone and a well-draining potting mix to enhance root development. Keep the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged and provide indirect light. Patience is needed as this shrub can be slow to propagate. These cuttings can be difficult to overwinter. It is best to keep them in a greenhouse or cold frame until the following spring before planting them out. Pot up into individual pots once they start to root and plant them out in late spring or early summer of the following year. Gradually acclimate to outdoor conditions before planting in the final location. — Collection: Cuttings should be from healthy, non-flowering shoots. Ensure the cuttings have at least two nodes and plant them in a well-draining soil mix. || Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Stored seed will require 2 months warm then 3 months cold stratification and can still take 18 months to germinate. Prick out the seedlings into individual pots when they are large enough to handle and grow them in a cold frame or greenhouse. Plant out into their permanent positions in late spring or early summer of the following year.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/viburnum-rufidulum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://pfaf.org/USER/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Viburnum+rufidulum#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,wood%2C%20winter%20in%20a%20frame. | 1) https://pfaf.org/USER/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Viburnum+rufidulum#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,wood%2C%20winter%20in%20a%20frame. 2) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/Viburnum_rufidulum.html#:~:text=How%20to%20Propagate%20Rusty%20blackhaw?&text=Rusty%20blackhaw%20is%20a%20deciduous,to%20outdoor%20conditions%20before%20planting. 3) https://earthone.io/plant/viburnum%20rufidulum"}, {"Plant_ID": "Viguiera dentata", "Scientific Name": "Viguiera dentata", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Plateau Goldeneye", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sown in the fall or early spring.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/viguiera-dentata/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=VIDE3"}, {"Plant_ID": "Viguiera stenoloba", "Scientific Name": "Viguiera stenoloba", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Skeletonleaf Goldeneye", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Softwood", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds in spring and fall. Scatter seed on prepared well-drained soil. Keep lightly moist until seedlings emerge. Then transition gradually to deeper less frequent watering. If volunteers appear near parent plants, transplant them while small to fill gaps. — Collection: Gather seeds as they turn brown and begin to shatter. Air-dry before storing || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Dip in rooting hormone and place soil. — Collection: Take cuttings in late spring.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/viguiera-stenoloba/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=VIST 2) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/viguiera-stenoloba-skeleton-leaf-goldeneye#:~:text=Skeleton%2Dleaf%20goldeneye%20grows%20as,Foliage%20and%20Texture | 1) https://legacyblog.stbctmn.org/2019/12/27/skeleton-leaf-golden-eye-and-mistflower-are-must-have-plants-for-october/ 2) https://www.gardenia.net/plant/viguiera-stenoloba-skeleton-leaf-goldeneye"}, {"Plant_ID": "Viola sororia", "Scientific Name": "Viola sororia", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Common Blue Violet", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Bud", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds in a tray or small pot filled with well draining seed compost mix. Press the seeds gently into the soil. But do not burry them, they need light to germinate. Cover the containers with clear plastic to maintain humidity. Place the containers in a bright location, but out of direct sunlight. Keep the soil evenly moist, but not soggy. Germination can take 10 days to several weeks. Once seedlings have developed their first set of true leaves. Carefully transplant them into individual pots. Gradually acclimate the young plants to outdoor conditions before transplanting them in their final location — Collection: Collect seeds from mature violet plants, or purchase commercially. || Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully dig up the clump of violets you wish to divide, trying not to damage the roots. Gently tease apart the roots with your fingers or a knife to separate the clump into individual plantsmaking sure eachclum has a good root system and some foliage. Replant the divisons in prepared soil with plenty of room to grow. Water the transplants well and keep consistently moist until plants are established. — Collection: The best time to divide violets is early spring or fall when the plants are not inf full bloom.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/viola-sororia-2/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.gardenia.net/guide/violets-viola-how-to-grow-and-care 2) https://earthone.io/plant/viola%20sororia"}, {"Plant_ID": "Viola sororia var. missouriensis", "Scientific Name": "Viola sororia var. missouriensis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Missouri Violet", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Bud", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow seeds in a tray or small pot filled with well draining seed compost mix. Press the seeds gently into the soil. But do not burry them, they need light to germinate. Cover the containers with clear plastic to maintain humidity. Place the containers in a bright location, but out of direct sunlight. Keep the soil evenly moist, but not soggy. Germination can take 10 days to several weeks. Once seedlings have developed their first set of true leaves. Carefully transplant them into individual pots. Gradually acclimate the young plants to outdoor conditions before transplanting them in their final location — Collection: Collect seeds from mature violet plants, or purchase commercially. || Bud — Treatment: Division — Method: Carefully dig up the clump of violets you wish to divide, trying not to damage the roots. Gently tease apart the roots with your fingers or a knife to separate the clump into individual plantsmaking sure eachclum has a good root system and some foliage. Replant the divisons in prepared soil with plenty of room to grow. Water the transplants well and keep consistently moist until plants are established. — Collection: The best time to divide violets is early spring or fall when the plants are not inf full bloom.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/viola-sororia/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.gardenia.net/guide/violets-viola-how-to-grow-and-care 2) https://earthone.io/plant/viola%20sororia"}, {"Plant_ID": "Vitis mustangensis", "Scientific Name": "Vitis mustangensis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Mustang Grape", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Softwood | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: best sown in a cold frame as soon as it is ripe[K]. Six weeks cold stratification improves the germination rate, and so stored seed is best sown in a cold frame as soon as it is obtained. Germination should take place in the first spring, but sometimes takes another 12 months. Prick out the seedlings into individual pots when they are large enough to handle and grow them on in a cold frame for their first winter. Plant out in early summer. || Softwood — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Take cuttings of mature wood of the current seasons growth, December/January in a frame. These cuttings can be of wood 15 - 30cm long or they can be of short sections of the stem about 5cm long with just one bud at the top of the section. In this case a thin, narrow strip of the bark about 3cm long is removed from the bottom half of the side of the stem. This will encourage callusing and the formation of roots. Due to the size of these cuttings they need to be kept in a more protected environment than the longer cuttings. Layering. || Stem — Treatment: Layering — Method: Layering can be done by bending a low-growing stem to the ground and covering it with soil until it roots. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Remove leaves from the lower half of the cutting to prevent excess moisture loss, leaving a few leaves at the top to support photosynthesis. It's advisable to dip the cut end in a rooting hormone to enhance root development. Fill a pot with a well-draining potting mix. Plant the cutting about 2-3 inches deep in the soil, ensuring at least one node is buried as roots will develop from these nodes. Water lightly to settle the soil around the cutting. Place the pot in a location that receives indirect light and maintains a consistent temperature. Keep the soil lightly moist but not waterlogged to prevent rot. Covering the pot with a plastic bag can create a greenhouse effect, encouraging humidity and warmth, which aids in rooting. After about 4-6 weeks, gently tug on the cutting. A slight resistance usually indicates that roots have begun to form. Once confirmed, you can gradually acclimate the cutting to less humid conditions before transplanting. — Collection: Choose a healthy, disease-free cane from a mature mustang grape vine. The cutting should be about 6-8 inches long with at least 2-3 nodes. Make sure the cut is made just below a node using a clean, sharp tool to ensure a clean cut.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/vitis-mustangensis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Vitis+mustangensis#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,Layering. | https://earthone.io/plant/vitis%20mustangensis | https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Vitis_mustangensis.html"}, {"Plant_ID": "Wedelia acapulcensis var. hispida", "Scientific Name": "Wedelia acapulcensis var. hispida", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Zexmenia", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Stem | Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Propagate hairy wedelia via cuttings with healthy nodes for successful rooting. Use well-draining medium and maintain high humidity. After root growth, transplant into fertile, loamy soil. Water regularly and provide partial sunlight until established, then gradually acclimate to final conditions. || Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: For direct seeding, broadcast seed in the late winter or early spring into a clean, weed free seedbed. Seeds should be covered from ¼ to ½” depth to ensure good soil to seed contact. Transplants should be planted in early to mid-spring, to ensure good root establishment before the summer heat arrives. For greenhouse seeding, it is important not to over water, because the small seedlings are prone to damping off. New plants can be transplanted into their permanent locations after three months.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/wedelia-acapulcensis-var-hispida/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Wedelia_acapulcensis_var._hispida.html | https://plants.usda.gov/DocumentLibrary/factsheet/pdf/fs_wete.pdf"}, {"Plant_ID": "Xanthisma texanum", "Scientific Name": "Xanthisma texanum", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Sleepy Daisy", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Seed sown in late winter or early spring requires rain or supplemental water to initiate germination.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/xanthisma-texanum/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=XATE"}, {"Plant_ID": "Yucca arkansana", "Scientific Name": "Yucca arkansana", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Arkansas Yucca", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Yuccas will germinate quickly from fresh seed held over winter. Seeds germinate best in 60-70 degree temperatures. — Collection: Gather capsules as they begin to dry but before they split. Allow to dry, then crush to remove seeds.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/yucca-arkansana/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=YUAR2"}, {"Plant_ID": "Yucca constricta", "Scientific Name": "Yucca constricta", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Buckley’s Yucca", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Root", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Soak the seeds in warm water for 24 hours to soften the seed coats, which enhances the germination process by breaking the dormancy period. Sow the seeds in a well-draining cactus or succulent soil mix, lightly covering them with a thin layer of soil. Use a container with drainage holes to prevent water logging. Place the container in a warm, well-lit area but out of direct sunlight. Maintain a consistent temperature, preferably between 15-21 degrees Celsius (60-70 degrees Fahrenheit). Water the seeds lightly and keep the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged. Monitor the soil moisture frequently, especially in warmer conditions, to ensure it does not dry out completely. It usually germinates within 1 - 12 months if kept at a temperature of 20°c. Prick out the seedlings into individual pots when they are large enough to handle and grow them on in the greenhouse or cold frame for at least their first two winters. — Collection: Collect seeds from mature fruit of buckley's yucca after they have fully ripened and dried on the plant. Ensure the seeds are clean and free from any pulp or residue. || Root — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Root cuttings in late winter or early spring. Lift in April/May and remove small buds from base of stem and rhizomes. Dip in dry wood ashes to stop any bleeding and plant in a sandy soil in pots in a greenhouse until established", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/yucca-constricta/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.picturethisai.com/care/propagate/Yucca_constricta.html 2) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Yucca+constricta#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,greenhouse%20until%20established%5B78%5D. | https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Yucca+constricta#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,greenhouse%20until%20established%5B78%5D."}, {"Plant_ID": "Yucca louisianensis", "Scientific Name": "Yucca louisianensis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Louisiana Yucca", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Clump | Stem", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: The seeds should be sown in well-draining soil and moistened with water. It is recommended to plant the seeds during a season with warm temperatures to facilitate their germination. The seeds should be kept moist, and the soil should not dry out until germination occurs. Requires patience since this species has a slow growth rate. || Clump — Treatment: Division — Method: This technique involves separating the plant into smaller sections and replanting each one separately. It is important to ensure that each section has adequate roots and leaves, which will increase its chances of survival after replanting. The best time to divide the plant is in early spring before new growth appears. || Stem — Treatment: Cutting — Method: After taking the cuttings, they should be allowed to callus for a few days before planting them in a well-draining soil mixture. The cuttings should be kept moist, and the soil should not dry out until roots have established. — Collection: The cuttings should be taken from the mother plant during the growing season, preferably in late spring or early summer. The cuttings should be 20 to 25 cm long and should have several leaves.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/yucca-louisianensis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.botanikks.com/plants/yucca-louisianensis-trel/517275/1"}, {"Plant_ID": "Yucca rupicola", "Scientific Name": "Yucca rupicola", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Twistleaf Yucca", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Root | Offshoots", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Sow in well-draining soil, requiring shallow placement for sunlight exposure. Consistent moisture without waterlogging is crucial for root development, || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Pre-soaking the seed for 24 hours in warm water may reduce the germination time. Sow seed spring in a greenhouse. It usually germinates within 1 - 12 months if kept at a temperature of 20°c. Prick out the seedlings into individual pots when they are large enough to handle and grow them on in the greenhouse or cold frame for at least their first two winters. Plant them out into their permanent positions in early summer and consider giving them some winter protection for at least their first winter outdoors. || Root — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Lift in April/May and remove small buds from base of stem and rhizomes. Dip in dry wood ashes to stop any bleeding and plant in a sandy soil in pots in a greenhouse until established — Collection: Take root cuttings in late winter or early spring. || Offshoots — Treatment: Cutting — Method: Allow cuttings to callous over before planting them in well-draining soil. — Collection: The best time to propagate is during the spring or early summer.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/yucca-rupicola-2/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Yucca_rupicola.html | 1) https://pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Yucca+rupicola#:~:text=Plant%20Propagation,greenhouse%20until%20established%5B78%5D. 2) https://temperate.theferns.info/plant/Yucca+rupicola | https://earthone.io/en/plant/yucca%20rupicola?srsltid=AfmBOoqq6OSt-Wcd2lQdcNQzpGvqhXfiiuvQEKVjGLItJeyKXTYLkiE-"}, {"Plant_ID": "Zanthoxylum clava-herculis", "Scientific Name": "Zanthoxylum clava-herculis", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Hercules Club", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: Stratification — Method: Cold stratify for 120 days || Seed — Treatment: Scarification — Method: Soak in hot tap water, let stand in water for 24 hours. If boiling water treatment does not allow seed to imbibe, sulfuric acid treatment is required, fall sowing in mulched beds is prefered to artificial stratification", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/zanthoxylum-clava-herculis/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://sheffields.com/inventory/view/1524"}, {"Plant_ID": "Zeltnera beyrichii", "Scientific Name": "Zeltnera beyrichii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Mountain Pinks", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: To propagate mountain pink, use fresh seeds in well-draining soil that mimics its native habitat. Sow shallowly for light-assisted germination, keep soil moist but not waterlogged, and provide ample sunlight for seedlings. Gradually acclimatize to outdoor conditions, minimizing transplant shock by handling roots carefully.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/zeltnera-beyrichii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Zeltnera_beyrichii.html#:~:text=Propagation:%20To%20propagate%20mountain%20pink,shock%20by%20handling%20roots%20carefully."}, {"Plant_ID": "Zephyranthes drummondii", "Scientific Name": "Zephyranthes drummondii", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Prairie Lily", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed | Bulb", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Method: Seed is not viable for too long after collection. Do not store long before planting. — Collection: Collect seed several weeks after strong rains mainly in spring when they are near dry stage. || Bulb — Treatment: Division — Method: Ensure each division has a root system and replant immediately in well-draining soil with adequate sunlight. Regular, careful watering supports healthy growth for vibrant blooms.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/zephyranthes-drummondii/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=COPE 2) https://plants.ces.ncsu.edu/plants/zephyranthes-drummondii/#:~:text=Attributes:%20Genus:%20Zephyranthes%20Species:,Medium%20Maintenance:%20Low%20Texture:%20Fine | 1) https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=COPE 2) https://plants.ces.ncsu.edu/plants/zephyranthes-drummondii/#:~:text=Attributes:%20Genus:%20Zephyranthes%20Species:,Medium%20Maintenance:%20Low%20Texture:%20Fine 3) https://www.picturethisai.com/wiki/Zephyranthes_drummondii.html#:~:text=Rain%20lily%20%2D%20Zephyranthes%20drummondii%20(Care,%2C%20Characteristics%2C%20Flower%2C%20Images)&text=Rain%20lily%20(Zephyranthes%20drummondii)%20is,and%20attract%20bees%20and%20butterflies.&text=Monocotyledons-,Snap%20a%20photo%20for%20instant%20plant%20ID%2C%20gaining%20quick%20insights,uses%2C%20and%20symbolism%2C%20etc."}, {"Plant_ID": "Zinnia grandiflora", "Scientific Name": "Zinnia grandiflora", "NPSOT Propagation Common Name": "Plains Zinnia", "NPSOT Propagation Materials": "Seed", "NPSOT Propagation Instructions": "Seed — Treatment: No Treatment — Method: Rapidly germinating, keep seed in constant moisture (not wet) with temperatures of about +20°C [68°F]. Seeds must be covered thinly. Do not cover very small seeds, but tightly press into the earth. Keep in cooler conditions after germination occurs.", "NPSOT Propagation Source URL": "https://www.npsot.org/posts/native-plant/zinnia-grandiflora/", "NPSOT Propagation References": "https://www.jelitto.com/Seed/Perennials/ZINNIA+grandiflora+Portion+s.html"}];
